<HEADLINE>
RANGERS' BALKY LOSS COSTLY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ The Texas Rangers lost a game Friday night because
of a balk as well as their slow-footed cleanup hitter because he
was successful in stealing a base.
</P>
<P>
   A slide that has seen the Rangers lose nine of their past 11
games has perhaps reached the ridiculous stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Unbelievable,'' catcher Ivan Rodriguez said, shaking his head
after Jeff Zimmerman's balk brought in the final run in the
Rangers' 4-3 loss to the Baltimore Orioles at Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like this is getting worse and worse,'' said Rafael
Palmeiro, who left the game in the fifth with tightness in his left
hamstring and was unavailable in a crucial situation. ``We've got
to find a way to get this thing turned around.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers were headed that way when Esteban Loaiza cruised
into the sixth with a 3-0 lead. But Jeff Conine homered off him in
that inning, and Mike Bordick smacked a two-run home run in the
seventh. That made it a 3-3 game and set up the ending in the ninth
that had the Rangers fighting off new levels of overall
frustration.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you lose, everything you do is magnified,'' Rangers
manager Johnny Oates said. ``Everything becomes more important.''
</P>
<P>
   Such as stepping off the pitching rubber properly with the
winning run at third base.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never seen anything like that in my life,'' said Loaiza,
who gave way to Zimmerman after eight innings.
</P>
<P>
   Zimmerman got in trouble in the ninth when Cal Ripken led off
with a single to left and Will Clark doubled to right, moving
pinch-runner Mark Lewis to third.
</P>
<P>
   That brought up Greg Myers, but he never got a chance to swing
the bat. Zimmerman was looking in for the sign from Rodriguez but
tried to step off the rubber and was called for a balk by both home
plate umpire Ian Lamplugh and third base umpire Brian O'Nora.
</P>
<P>
   ``Zimmerman started his motion, stopped, then stepped back off
the rubber,'' Lamplugh said.
</P>
<P>
   Oates didn't argue.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no doubt in my mind,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Zimmerman, ``Nobody came out to argue, so it must have been
pretty blatant. I didn't see the signs from Pudge, so I wanted to
step off the rubber and have him go through them again.''
</P>
<P>
   That was the deciding play, but losing Palmeiro could be much
more painful. He is listed as day-to-day but so was Rusty Greer
when he was scratched from the lineup in New York with a tight
hamstring. Two days later he was on the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll know more (Saturday), but it's going to take something
really severe for me not to play,'' Palmeiro said.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro injured himself by stealing second base without a throw
in the fifth. He said the hamstring ``grabbed'' him as he took his
last step and slipped. Scott Sheldon went in to run for him.
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro's absence might have cost the Rangers in the seventh
after Chad Curtis reached with a one-out single off Orioles starter
Jason Johnson and Rodriguez drew a walk. Palmeiro should have been
up but instead it was Sheldon, who was 0-for-3 for the season
before that at-bat.
</P>
<P>
   Trying to manufacture a run, Curtis broke for third on a 1-1
pitch and was thrown out easily by Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just trying to get to third base with one out,'' Curtis
said. ``(Johnson) had been kind of slow to the plate, and Myers
didn't look like he was throwing the ball well. I just didn't get a
good jump. I should have stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates, whose team led 3-1 at the time, approved of Curtis'
aggressiveness, especially since the Rangers had already stolen
twice off Johnson and Myers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey, you might as well get used to it,'' Oates said. ``We're
going to do some things. We're not going sit back and wait for a
three-run homer because it's not coming.''
</P>
<P>
   A well-timed balk might help, but those plays are going against
the Rangers right now. nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
