</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-SNOWMOBILE-BAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL: A BROAD BAN ON SNOWMOBILES 
</HEADLINE>
   c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times said in an editorial on Saturday, April 29:  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday Donald J. Barry, the assistant secretary of the
interior for fish and wildlife and parks, announced the effective
end of recreational snowmobiling in all but a handful of America's
national parks. The ban is not the result of new legislation or new
regulations. It is the result of a new commitment to laws and rules
that have been on the books for years, including executive orders
that prohibit the use of off-road vehicles except where authorized.
Barry's announcement represents one of those moments, so vital to
the health of our national parks, when the Park Service stands back
and compares its public mission with the status quo. Without such
moments from time to time, we would still be feeding black bears
along the roads in Yellowstone.
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, this announcement does nothing more than urge park
superintendents across the national park system to bring their
parks into compliance with the law, and particularly with the laws
that regulate the enforcement of environmental standards. It
exempts Voyageurs National Park in Minnesota and some parks in
Alaska, which have slightly different legal standing with regard to
snowmobile use. It also exempts Yellowstone and Grand Teton, but
only because those parks are in the midst of drafting a
court-ordered environmental impact statement concerning winter use,
a process that is likely to lead in mid-autumn to a ban on
snowmobiling there as well.
</P>
<P>
   What Barry's announcement underscores is the simple principle
that America's national parks should lead the nation in adherence
to environmental law. Recreation is not incompatible with strict
adherence. It is enhanced. For years snowmobiling has been
tolerated even though it violated the law, and its environmental
impact had scarcely been monitored until recently. But now that the
impact of snowmobiling is clearly understood and the extent of its
pollution clearly documented, overlooking the law has become
intolerable.
</P>
<P>
   There will be sharp debate as the effects of Barry's
announcement are felt and as Yellowstone and Grand Teton approach
snowmobiling bans. The  &UR; c &LR; ongressional delegations from Wyoming,
Montana and Idaho have promised oversight hearings late in May to
challenge the order. But an end to snowmobiling is the right step,
the only one consistent with the ethic, and the laws, governing the
National Park Service.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
