<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THEOLOGIANS WARY OF SIMPLIFICATION OF VIEWS ON GAYS AND CHURCH 
</HEADLINE>
   By PETER STEINFELS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scholar A, Scholar B and Scholar C _ the reasons for anonymity
will be obvious _ have four things in common. First, they are all
respected Protestant theologians well known for their work on
religion and ethics.
</P>
<P>
   Second, they have all articulated carefully modulated arguments
for why Christian churches should not revise their teachings to
bless same-sex unions or ordain gay men and lesbians who do not
intend to live by their church's existing sexual standards.
</P>
<P>
   Third, they were all asked on Thursday to tape interviews for a
televised discussion of these questions.
</P>
<P>
   Fourth, they all said no.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, man, I hate this issue,'' Scholar B said. ``I've been
burned on it before.'' An hour earlier, Scholar A had used
strikingly similar language in begging off. An hour later, so would
Scholar C.
</P>
<P>
   None of these theologians absolutely ruled out being interviewed
at some undetermined time in the future. They just sounded like
Jesus in the garden of Gethsemane: Please, God, let this cup pass
from me.
</P>
<P>
   ``In principle, I'd be willing to think about it,'' Scholar B
said, which was just about as far as any of the three would go.
Part of their hesitation _ but only part of it _ stemmed from the
wariness, ingrained in almost every scholarly psyche, of what the
news media, especially television, can do with complicated views.
</P>
<P>
   And their views are complicated. ``I'm basically in support of
the Vermont law,'' Scholar C said, for example, referring to that
state's new law creating a form of civil union that extends to gay
and lesbian couples many of the rights and benefits attached to
marriage. But for reasons it would be interesting to hear, he
opposed approximating those same-sex civil unions to Christian
marriage, with its biblical and sacramental dimensions.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks ago, Scholar A had turned down a request for a
sound-bite comment on the controversy over homosexuality within the
United Methodist Church, which, along with the Presbyterians (USA)
and the Episcopal Church, will be debating homosexuality-related
questions at national meetings over the next three months. (And in
the background, of course, is the Supreme Court, which heard oral
arguments on whether the Boy Scouts have a right to exclude gay
members, some of them touching on religion and morality, the day
before the theologians were contacted.)
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not sure my views could be condensed,'' Scholar A said.
The three theologians' concerns clearly went beyond the normal
resistance of academics to the simplification of the news media.
Scholar B worried about the way these issues were typically forced
into a debate format: ``Here's Mr. Compassion,'' he said, ``and
here's me.''
</P>
<P>
   It was evidently not the theologians alone who risked being
pegged as anti-gay and anti-compassion. Scholar B mentioned how
family members had felt the ``heat'' for his previous public
statements; he could not agree to an interview without consulting
them first.
</P>
<P>
   Scholar A recalled the last-minute withdrawal of an invitation
to speak at a Midwestern church; his views, the pastor said, would
be offensive to some people.
</P>
<P>
   But more than anything else, the three theologians expressed the
fear that taking a conservative position on issues involving
homosexuality seemed to eclipse almost everything else they wanted
to address as scholars and church leaders.
</P>
<P>
   For Scholar C, these issues are a recent and relatively minor
part of a large body of work long seen as more liberal than
conservative. Yet ``in some circles, I've been typecast,'' he said,
as though homosexuality, rather than a wide range of other topics,
including economic justice and dialogue with other religions, were
``my issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Scholar A said much the same thing. ``I've not wanted to be so
prominently identified with my position on this issue,'' he said.
It is not that he doubts the importance or cogency of the case he
tries to make, he explained, nor does he want to back away from it.
</P>
<P>
   Yet, ``this seems to be an issue where the church has things out
of proportion,'' he said, lamenting the fact that the same kind of
energies are not mobilized around other issues close to his heart
and his scholarship, like the distribution of material goods and
the search for nonviolent ways of living.
</P>
<P>
   Three scholars are hardly a national sample. Other theologians
of measured, complex views will no doubt be found to take their
places. But three strikeouts in a row inevitably leaves one mulling
over the dynamics that reduce society's differences about
sexuality, morality, religion and law to shouting matches and
bumper stickers.
</P>
<P>
   As thoughtful conservatives _ at least on this topic _ these
three theologians confront not only simplification but also the
ideological intolerance and labeling rampant in university
environments and the polarized atmosphere within the churches.
Measured liberals may well face similar pressures: condemnations
from angry conservatives on the other side and criticism from
dissatisfied militants on their own.
</P>
<P>
   American culture is hypersensitive to censorship. What truly
constrains full and open public discussion, however, may be far
more subtle but no less effective.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
