<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0800 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-BAHAMAS-HAITIANS-1STL     04-29 0938
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BAHAMAS-HAITIANS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SURVIVORS OF SHIPWRECK OFF BAHAMAS FLED MOUNTING VIOLENCE IN
HAITI 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS name and removed time element in 2nd graf) 
 (ART ADV: Photos NYT27,28 are being sent to NYT photo clients. Map
is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can purchase
one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By DAVID GONZALEZ   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASSAU, Bahamas _ Survivors of a shipwreck that stranded more
than 250 Haitians on a barren island of the Bahamas 200 miles
southeast of here said Friday that they had fled Haiti aboard a
stolen boat in a desperate attempt to escape the mounting violence
that has swept through their homeland as elections approach.
</P>
<P>
   Their journey, which some said was motivated by the recent
murder of a prominent radio commentator and government critic, Jean
Domi- nique, became a doomed within days of leaving Haiti, the
survivors said.
</P>
<P>
   They quickly ran out of gas, food and water. Some were forced to
drink sea water, they said, making them even weaker. Finally their
drifting, 50-foot sailboat sank off Flamingo Cay, a small island
where they were discovered on Wednesday night.
</P>
<P>
   Although several of the 222 survivors who arrived here Friday
aboard a Bahamian naval vessel said that as many as 18 of their
comrades died during the journey, the figure could not be
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   Bahamian authorities said only two deaths could be verified and
that several dozen others had been already been hospitalized and
treated for dehydration and kidney failure.
</P>
<P>
   But it was the everyday deaths back in Haiti that still
preoccupied the survivors.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in misery,'' said Francisco Martinez, a Haitian whose
parents were from the Dominican Republic. ``The chiefs in Haiti are
killing people. They burn down houses.''
</P>
<P>
   Wednesday night's discovery of hundreds of stranded Haitians
comes after more than 300 other Haitians were rescued by Bahamian
authorities in two previous incidents in the last week. The surge
in boats packed with illegal immigrants coursing through Bahamian
waters on their way to Florida has led local officials to increase
aerial surveillance, but they are alarmed because they cannot
handle a continued, large influx on their own.
</P>
<P>
   ``They come in every year, but it has been some time since we
have seen the amount we are seeing now,'' said Senior Cmdr. Raymond
Farquharson of the Royal Bahamas Defense Force. ``We know
conditions in Haiti are deteriorating. People are trying to get
out. It is a big problem for the Bahamas. We do not have the
resources to get them here, feed them and make arrangements to
repatriate them.''
</P>
<P>
   A Bahamian immigration official said his government would
repatriate the latest group ``as soon as possible.'' Joseph
Etienne, a Haitian diplomat in Nassau said his government was
taking steps to discourage any further illegal immigration, a
difficult promise to keep, given the Haitian authorities' inability
to stem the wave of election-related violence that has wracked the
capital.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the survivors said they were active in electoral
campaigns and had received death threats and had gone into hiding.
Others said the increasing instability was too much to bear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We ran,'' said Jonas Louis, a fisherman from Arcahaie. ``We
hid in places before we robbed the boat.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that he and five others spotted a boat whose crew had
gone ashore to eat. Quickly, they stole it and took off to herd
dozens of passengers on board. The boat, which had a small outboard
motor as well as a sail, ran out of fuel within two days of
leaving. The seas were rough, and water was leaking into the boat,
which drifted towards Flamingo Cay. Without water or food, the
situation grew desperate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We drank water from the sea,'' Louis said. ``Some people died
because they could not stand it. I cannot say how many.''
</P>
<P>
   Bahamian officials who interviewed the Haitians, said they waded
ashore from their crippled boat. There, they were spotted on
Wednesday night by several passing sailboats. In quick order, a
joint U.S.-Bahamian rescue effort was underway. Brian Dudas, a
Coast Guard medical corpsman, flew into Flamingo Cay on Wednesday
night to find a sole Bahamian Defense Force member dressed in
camouflage standing watch on the beach.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was just trying to keep order,'' Dudas said. ``From what I
saw, everybody was just laid out on the beach, just pretty much
crashed out.''
</P>
<P>
   He helped load the most seriously ill Haitians onto a
helicopter, but he said that the scene quickly grew unruly as more
healthy people tried to climb on board.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was like pushing people out of the helo just before we took
off,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   By Thursday, more than 200 dazed and desperate Haitians were
still on the island, clearly visible as Coast Guard Lt. Chuck Bell
maneuvered his Jayhawk helicopter over the white sands. Clothes and
people were scattered among the rocks and shrubs, while others
huddled under a makeshift tent rescuers had built from tarpaulins,
sticks and branches.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was unreal,'' Bell said. ``You flew over, and you could see
the boat they came in on. The water here is crystal clear, and you
could see the boat submerged with its mast sticking out. On the
beach, there were massive amounts of people with clothes and
blankets everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   More rescue crews arrived on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were a lot of emotionally distraught people,'' said
Coast Guard Ensign Breck Smith. ``A lot were looking at photos,
which I assume were of the people who were lost the day before.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Smith, who is stationed in Clearwater, Fla., said a Bahamian
doctor had already set aside five Haitians to be stabilized and
evacuated as quickly as possible, since there were few medical
supplies at hand.
</P>
<P>
   ``The patients were in a serious degree of shock,'' he said.
There was no way to treat them. We showed up with 25 liters of IV
fluid and started plugging people into IVs and getting them out
when an aircraft arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Crew members of one cutter quickly had to secure the area when
they began to distribute food and water to the remaining Haitians,
who had survived for some time with neither.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were getting overrun,'' said Bell.
</P>
<P>
   The same could be said for the Bahamas. Wednesday's discovery
was the third such interception of Haitians in less than a week.
Last Saturday, 200 Haitians were rescued after their boat ran
aground near Harbour Island. On Tuesday, 123 Haitians were plucked
from their sinking ship off the coast of Great Inagua island. Even
as rescue efforts were underway on Flamingo Cay on Thursday,
Bahamian authorities sent two charter planes to the Haitian capital
with most of the Haitians rescued in the previous incidents, said
Farquharson.
</P>
<P>
   Bahamians fear that the influx may continue. In recent years,
Haiti has been paralyzed by a political standoff that has left the
nation without a parliament or constitutionally appointed prime
minister. Millions of dollars in much-needed foreign aid has been
blocked because of the legislative impasse, while efforts to have
elections to establish a new parliament have been marked by delays,
accusations and violence.
</P>
<P>
   Many of the survivors said they did not want to return to Haiti,
adding that they preferred to die here if they could not continue
on to the United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Too many have died already,'' said Louis. ``To Miami. We want
to go to Miami.''
</P>
<P>
   That is not possible. Yet the desperation of these Haitians to
reach the United States touched one Simeon Hall, who wondered why
their cause was not championed the way that keeping Elian Gonzalez
in the United States was championed by Miami's Cuban exile
community.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we should get an Elian Gonzalez here,'' said the
president of the Bahamas Christian Council. ``That would change
things. The policy of the Americans would change. The duplicitous
approach America has taken towards Cubans and Haitians is
obvious.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Still, the pastor of a Haitian congregation in Nassau said he
did not wish to see more of his countrymen attempt the dangerous
voyage that often ends in death.
</P>
<P>
   ``The big problem in Haiti is they have no jobs,'' said Henri
Cher-Amie, the pastor of the Calvary Haitian Baptist Church. ``I
talk to some guys who have the boats, and I tell them to be careful
not to give people hope, that when they come to the Bahamas it will
be wonderful.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday afternoon, as the last of the Haitians slowly walked off
the ship to buses and vans that would take them to detention
centers, the scene at dockside had a surreal flavor. As the
Haitians filed silently down the gangplank, a party boat filled
with wobbly revelers drinking and dancing to ``La Bamba'' bobbed in
the nearby waters. Elsewhere, in the shadow of the huge cruise
ships, tourists went about buying trinkets, taking pictures and
having their hair braided. Hardly any of them noticed the Haitians
boarding the buses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you enjoy your cruise?'' echoed the voice of a DJ as the
party boat pulled in behind the vessel that had brought the
Haitians to Nassau. ``Did you have a good time?''
</P>
<P>
   A few Haitians craned their necks to look. But most stared
straight ahead as the buses began to leave the dockside. Though
they did not understand English, they understood the question was
not meant for them.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
