<HEADLINE>
SCHOENEWEIS KEEPS PRIORITIES IN FOCUS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calilf. _ Scott Schoeneweis is in a groove, so please,
please, don't disrupt him.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed pitcher doesn't want to know that he's tied for
the American League lead in victories with four, or that he ranks
eighth in the league in ERA (3.15), or that he's fourth in innings
pitched (34 innings).
</P>
<P>
   Opposing batters are hitting .222 against Schoeneweis this
season, and he wants to keep it that way. And the only way he feels
he can remains on this roll is to look straight ahead and don't get
distracted. Don't change a thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to stay focused and not get carried away,'' he said.
``I don't read the sports section. I read the money section and the
front page.''
</P>
<P>
   Schoeneweis' attitude is the same when he's on the mound _ look
straight ahead, focus, execute.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is really impressing me with his ability to stick
with his game plan,'' manager Mike Scioscia said. ``He's not afraid
to throw his fastball in, he uses both sides of the plate real
well, he changes speeds and he uses his slider effectively. He has
tunnel vision.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe Schoeneweis is afraid this is a dream, and he doesn't want
to wake up.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Angels) put a lot of faith in me,'' he said. ``They went
out on the line for me. I'm glad I could return the favor.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Then again: On the other end of the spectrum is Ramon Ortiz.
</P>
<P>
   Ortiz has better stuff than Schoeneweis but is more likely to
lose focus on the mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's got to let his emotins be his ally,'' Scioscia said.
``When he does that, he'll take huge steps quickly. He's shown
better stuff than the results (1-2, 5.06 ERA) would indicate. But
he's not going to reach the level we all want him to reach until he
can bottle those emotions.''
</P>
<P>
   Tim Belcher is expected to join the rotation in less than two
weeks, and someone will have to go to make room for him. If Ortiz
is the odd man out, he'll be headed back to the minors, not to the
bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The bullpen) is not an option,'' Scioscia said. ``He's been
trained as a starter, and we don't want to mess with his shoulder
(small cartilage tear).''
</P>
<P>
   __ Controlled arguing: So far, Scioscia has not been shy about
leaving the dugout to argue with umpires. However, the discussions
have been tame. Scioscia hasn't gone nose-to-nose with an ump yet,
like his former manager Tommy Lasorda often did.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are going to be times when it's more heated than others,
it depends on how bad the play was,'' Scioscia said. ``For the most
part, you want to be rational. Certainly, you're going to have
flare ups with umps, that's inevitable. But the nature of my
position is to fight for the 25 guys. I can't worry about the
feelings of an umpire.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Numbers game: Darin Erstad's 44 hits in April (going into
Friday's game) are an American League record. The previous record
of 43 hits was set in 1998 by Kansas City's Hal Morris. The
major-league record for hits in April is 47, set in 1998 by
Colorado's Dante Bichette.
</P>
</TEXT>
