<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SHAKRS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS DOMINATE SHARKS BEHIND ZUBOV
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Sharks forward Vincent Damphousse didn't know what to
say.
</P>
<P>
   What exactly does one say after being absolutely flattened?
</P>
<P>
   Damphousse decided to go with your generic: ``We know we played
poorly. It was our worst effort in the playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars didn't merely win the first game of their second-round
series against San Jose last night at Reunion Arena. They took the
fight right out of the Sharks' mouths with a 4-0 victory that put
them up 1-0 in their best-of-seven series, with Game 2 not coming
near fast enough.
</P>
<P>
   After you play a game as the Stars did in Game 1, you want to
get back on the ice as soon as possible. Especially with defenseman
Sergei Zubov back.
</P>
<P>
   The return of Zubov, who didn't play in the first round because
of a knee injury, helped turn what had been a pretty good Stars
bunch in the first round to the group that looks as though a return
trip to the Western Conference Finals might be only a sweep away.
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' 2-for-26 power play of the first round contributed
two goals last night. Welcome back, Sergei. The Stars held the
Sharks scoreless, and basically shotless, on their six power plays.
Welcome back, Sergei.
</P>
<P>
   ``He really seems to make the real easy play,'' Stars center
Mike Modano said of Zubov, who assisted on both Stars power-play
goals. ``We weren't going to sit and wait to see if they were going
to play or not. We wanted to get our game out and dictate the
play.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars, playing their first game since closing out Edmonton a
week ago, did exactly that.
</P>
<P>
   What worked for them against Edmonton _ Modano, the defensive
pair of Derian Hatcher and Richard Matvichuk and goalie Ed Belfour
_ worked once again in Game 1. What didn't work against Edmonton _
the power play and Joe Nieuwendyk _ started working in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing I was happy about is we got some good efforts from
all 12 forwards,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``That's what
gave us good play today. We didn't have any weak players up
front.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk, the playoff MVP a year ago, scored his first goal of
this year's playoffs at 2:48 of the third period. The Stars have
scored 18 goals in the playoffs. They've had 13 goal scorers.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been spread out, which is good,'' Nieuwendyk said. ``I
think that's a big key for our club.''
</P>
<P>
   Nieuwendyk's goal, which was followed not too long after by
another from Brenden Morrow, put the stamp on a result that was
sealed early in the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Goals by Aaron Gavey (his first this playoffs) and Modano (his
third) gave the Stars a 2-0 lead after the first period. The Sharks
started out bad only to watch it get worse. The one flurry of
honest-to-goodness chances San Jose had at the beginning of the
second period amounted to nothing but frustration.
</P>
<P>
   What Belfour didn't stop, the Sharks flat-out missed.
</P>
<P>
   There were blown two-on-ones. There were missed empty nets. And,
yes, there were Belfour saves. He finished with 18 in all for his
ninth career playoff shutout, his second this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, that was the difference there,'' Sharks winger Todd
Harvey said of the failed beginning to the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Said Stars defenseman Darryl Sydor: ``We gave them life, and we
had to try to take it back again.''
</P>
<P>
   They did. What does it say for the Sharks when their best play
of the night came from defenseman Bryan Marchment. He made an
diving save on a Guy Carbonneau shot at an empty net at 15:27 of
the second period, but Marchment should never outshine players such
as Sharks captain Owen Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   He did. Nolan was not a factor, in large part because Hatcher
and Matvichuk wouldn't let him be.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever life the Sharks had left, the Stars' penalty-killing
unit sucked out. The Sharks were 0-for-6.
</P>
<P>
   ``I definitely think that disheartened them,'' Hatcher said
before adding a big but ... ``I don't think either team played
their best game. I don't think they played their best game. And I
know we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars say they can get better.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks know they have to or they can forget another Game 7,
like they won against St. Louis on Tuesday. They won't make it to
No. 5.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wish we had put up a little bit more tonight,'' Sharks coach
Darryl Sutter said after the game, ``but I know we will.''
</P>
<P>
   He took the words right out of the Stars' mouths. They all saw
the St. Louis series, and those who didn't have been reminded. The
Sharks looked like the worst team in the world losing to the Blues
in Game 6 only to win Game 7.
</P>
<P>
   ``We all realize it is going to get tougher,'' Nieuwendyk said.
``They are going to be a better team in Game 2.'' nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
