<SLUG> BC-OLY-CYCLING-TRIALS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHSTEIN GETS WIN IN HEATED MEN'S MATCH SPRINTS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOHNNY PAUL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRISCO, Texas _ Tempers flared during the best-of-three men's
match sprint semifinal between Marty Nothstein and Jeff Labauve at
last night's U.S. Olympic Team Trials for Track Cycling.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my semifinal ride, I rode the first one real aggressive _
easily beat Labauve,'' Nothstein said. ``In the second one, I was
just basically saving energy and made it close. He made a few
comments, and a little bit of rage took over. I wanted it take it
out in the final ride and make a statement, and I did.''
</P>
<P>
   Memo to Labauve: Don't expect any favors from Jeff Solt in the
near future.
</P>
<P>
   Solt endured Nothstein's wrath later during the evening's
best-of-three final, and the United States' elite sprinter swept
his opponent in dominating fashion.
</P>
<P>
   Nothstein extended his hand toward Labauve after his semifinal
victory while the two circled the 250-meter oval. Labauve refused
to part with a handshake, and the two exchanged words while on the
track.
</P>
<P>
   Nothstein declined to reveal Labauve's choice of words, but he
remained peeved after his triumph against Solt in the final.
</P>
<P>
   ``He made one \Rstatement\S that was pretty bad, and I remember
for a long time,'' said Nothstein, who won the silver medal in the
event during the 1996 Atlanta Games. ``It happens, though. You try
to win like a champion and lose like a champion. I've been racing
at the highest level for the last seven years, and he's yet to even
reach that level.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just basically treaded on some thin ice at that point, but
I was mad at myself for falling into it and wasting the energy
doing it, to be honest with you. I shouldn't even do that. I'm
above that. I've got bigger things to come, but you guys are all
loving this.''
</P>
<P>
   No such fireworks erupted during the women's match sprints.
</P>
<P>
   Tanya Lindenmuth swept the best-of-three final from Jennie Reed
in methodical fashion as they head toward the July 7 selection
date.
</P>
<P>
   Only three Olympic Team berths exist for the four women's track
cycling events at the 2000 Sydney Games. Most expect Chris Witty to
represent the United States in the 500-meter time trial, and Erin
Veenstra-Mirabella _ probably this country's best track endurance
rider _ remains the favorite to compete in the individual
3,000-meter pursuit and points race.
</P>
<P>
   That leaves Lindenmuth and Reed jockeying for what likely will
be the one sprint position.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is definitely an important win,'' Lindenmuth said. ``It's
2000. My goal was that I needed to make the top two here. I
accomplished that, but I wanted to race well and prove to myself
that I could race well, be patient and be confident. I did that in
all of my events. I was patient, and I was alert.''
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, their battle remains far from over. Their
performances during upcoming World Cup events in Moscow; Cali,
Columbia; and Mexico City will bear significance and should ensure
a fight to the finish.
</P>
<P>
   ``As long as we're both here, I think it definitely will be,''
Lindenmuth said. ``We're 1 and 2 right now. We're right where we're
supposed to be, and on any given day, it could be her or it could
be me. This might sound stupid, but it could just depend on how the
sun or moon is.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
