<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-LEBRETON-CYCLING-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NOTHSTEIN GOING FOR THE GOLD AND NOTHING LESS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GIL LEBRETON 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   FRISCO, Texas _ He has changed his workout routine. He has
juggled his coaches. He has altered his diet.
</P>
<P>
   He has taken a little from his old coaches, plus something from
his new ones, and hammered together the golden game plan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to go into Sydney with no excuses,'' Marty Nothstein,
America's best sprint cyclist, said yesterday under the Frisco sun.
``That's the bottom line.''
</P>
<P>
   He has been to the Olympics. Second place, match sprint, 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Though his wife, Christi, has the silver medal proudly displayed
in the family foyer, you get the feeling that Nothstein grimaces
every time he passes it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty does not like to lose,'' said Des Dickie, who will coach
the U.S. sprint cyclists in the Sydney Games.
</P>
<P>
   And so Nothstein trains. He shows up in Texas in the middle of
April to spend time with Dickie, the new U.S. coach, to learn his
methods, to learn about himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is the year,'' said Nothstein, who is 29. ``I don't know
how many more chances I'll get after this.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think I can make the Olympic team in 2004, but I don't want
to just make teams. I want to win medals.''
</P>
<P>
   Medals, he has by the dozens. But first, the rock story.
</P>
<P>
   When he was 14, growing up in Trexlertown, Pa., Nothstein and
his kid brother were nabbed throwing stones at a neighbor's house.
The neighbor, a gentleman named Heinz Walter, whose name is now
part of cycling folklore, issued young Marty a challenge.
</P>
<P>
   Why don't you take all that energy down to the local velodrome
and make something of yourself?
</P>
<P>
   Well, how's he doing, Heinz?
</P>
<P>
   In Italy in 1994, Nothstein became the first male American
sprint cyclist in 82 years to win a world championship. Two days
later, he added a gold medal in the Keirin event and became the
only U.S. cyclist ever to win two world titles in the same year.
</P>
<P>
   In all, Nothstein has won three golds and seven overall medals
in the world championships, plus a record 19 U.S. titles on the
track.
</P>
<P>
   ``Marty,'' Dickie noted, ``is motivated by success. If he is
there, he wants to succeed. He will not put his bike on the line if
he doesn't think he is ready.''
</P>
<P>
   The plan is to be ready in Sydney not once, but twice. In
addition to the match sprint, Nothstein will be among the favorites
in the Keirin, a mass-start sprint where the cyclists are paced by
a motorcycle until the final two laps.
</P>
<P>
   ``My goal all along has been to go down to Sydney and win a gold
medal,'' Nothstein said. ``I plan on going down there and
accomplishing my goal.''
</P>
<P>
   He talks the same way that he rides a bicycle, riding the thin
edge between arrogance and self-assurance.
</P>
<P>
   After a less-than-bountiful medal harvest by the U.S. cyclists
at the Atlanta Olympics, Nothstein will be one of the ones on all
the magazine covers and at the head of all the medal-hopefuls
lists.
</P>
<P>
   ``No problem,'' he said at yesterday's U.S. Olympic Trials at
the Superdrome. ``I like that.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want the load. I want to be the guy who's expected to win. I
can race well under pressure. I wouldn't even call it pressure. I
know what I can do, and I know I can win. And as long as you guys
think I can, too, well, we're all on the same page.''
</P>
<P>
   At 6-foot-2 and 215 pounds, Nothstein has the prototype modern
body for his side of the sport. But his racing savvy, born of 11
years of racing at a world-class level, makes him unlikely to lose
on a U.S. track.
</P>
<P>
   With first place in yesterday's match sprint under his belt,
Nothstein will ride today in a special Trials event designed only
to see him break the Superdrome record for one lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``I plan on demolishing it, to put it bluntly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   In the weeks ahead, Nothstein plans to compete at World Cup
events in Colombia, Mexico and Italy, before shifting into one
final gear for Sydney.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's the guy _ we know that, everyone knows that,'' U.S. coach
Dickie said. ``He's won the worlds, and he's kept in the top five
riders in the world. And at that level, on any given day, any of
those guys can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Soon, Nothstein knows, the magazines will be calling. Soon,
he'll be branded as America's great golden cycling hope.
</P>
<P>
   Bring it on, said Marty Nothstein, who was in a league of his
own at these Olympic Trials.
</P>
<P>
   Stay tuned, Mr. Heinz Walter.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 0113EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 01:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0809 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX     04-29 0880
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-REEVES-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS REMAIN WARY OF TOOTHLESS SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JIM REEVES 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Derian Hatcher stood in a corner of the Dallas Stars'
locker room and, being a proper gentleman and a professional
athlete, wise in the ways of bulletin board fodder, did everything
he could not to state the obvious after Friday night's shockingly
easy 4-0 victory over San Jose at Reunion Arena to open the second
round of the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   So allow me to do the honors: The Sharks have turned into
guppies.
</P>
<P>
   Past experience and the Sharks' stunning seven-game upset of the
No. 1 seeded Blues, had us expecting the reincarnation of ``Jaws'',
complete with double rows of dagger-like teeth, and renowned ax
murderer Bryan Marchment as an added bonus.
</P>
<P>
   What we got instead was ``Flipper'' and friends.
</P>
<P>
   Would you guys like to drop back by Sunday for more punch and
cookies?
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher, asked if he was surprised by how unphysical this game
was, frowned and sidestepped the question as neatly as he did most
of the Sharks' would-be hits Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really don't want to answer that right now,'' Hatcher all
but whispered after most of the media crowd around his locker had
thinned out. ``Honestly, I thought both teams were flat tonight. I
look for both teams to get better and I can just about guarantee
it's going to get more physical.''
</P>
<P>
   Like I said, a wise man. Because these certainly weren't the
Sharks we've come to know and hate.
</P>
<P>
   ``We know that we didn't get their best game tonight,'' Hatcher
added, ``but we're ready for it when it comes.''
</P>
<P>
   Oh, the Sharks were chippy, as usual. There was the normal
amount of post-play slaps and shoves, sniping and insults. But the
Stars kept their composure and the Sharks never unleashed the
physical game we were absolutely sure they'd put on the ice.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think at times they really tried to run around and finish
hits,'' Stars forward Scott Thornton said, ``but ...''
</P>
<P>
   Exactly.
</P>
<P>
   All you need to know about this game is that the Stars outhit
the Sharks, 38-27.
</P>
<P>
   ``We looked a little hesitant,'' Sharks center Vincent
Damphousse admitted. ``We didn't do what we did against St.
Louis.''
</P>
<P>
   Not even close.
</P>
<P>
   With Sergei Zubov back leading the power play, the Stars got
first-period goals from Aaron Gavey and Mike Modano and two more in
the third from Joe Nieuwendyk and linemate Thornton; but strangely,
the game actually turned in the second period, when neither team
scored.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had five great chances in the second period and missed
them,'' Stars coach Ken Hitchcock pointed out. ``And they failed on
three odd-man rushes that could have turned the game around.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, with Eddie Belfour playing perhaps his finest game ever
against the Sharks _ which isn't necessarily saying much, because
he has never played particularly well either for or against them _
the Stars held their 2-0 advantage and then blew the listless
Sharks out in the final period.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our missed chances were more important than anything to do
with their 2-0 lead,'' San Jose coach Darryl Sutter said. ``We had
four quality chances we didn't hit the net on. We were emotionally
flat and it probably showed up in the execution part of those
chances.''
</P>
<P>
   Execution isn't the Sharks' trademark, though. They're not known
for precision passing, or a great offense or a shutdown defense,
though they can do all those things well enough. But their game is
beating the hell out of the other team.
</P>
<P>
   That never came close to happening Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't play as physical as we wanted to,'' Sharks center
Mike Ricci said, ``and that's why we didn't win.''
</P>
<P>
   Nor did their occasional cheap shot _ Marchment, being
Marchment, took a stupid penalty by cross-checking Brenden Morrow
in the back late in the third period _ lure the Stars into
retaliation, which was the key to the Sharks' upset of St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we've learned a lot the last two years,'' Guy
Carbonneau said. ``You look at two years ago when we lost to
Detroit in the playoffs, we kind of got rattled a little bit and
took bad penalties. Last year we really made a commitment to play
aggressive in trying to keep our cool. I think we learned really
well from that and you're seeing the same thing this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edmonton came really hard at us (in the first round). We gave
our hits and we took our hits but we didn't lose our cool. You look
at what St. Louis did and they took bad penalties at bad times.''
</P>
<P>
   That, Sutter said, is why it's one thing to beat the
regular-season champs, a distinction the Blues earned this year,
and another to go up against the defending Stanley Cup champs,
especially when that team has had a full week to rest.
</P>
<P>
   ``It had to do with the team that was fresher than the other,''
Sutter said, a lame excuse, since the Sharks themselves had almost
three full days to rest after wrapping up their series with the
Blues on Tuesday. But that's Sutter, a man known for his fine
whines.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks showed up as the all-you-can eat catfish special
Friday night, but they've been on that platter before and lived to
tell about it. Hatcher's right.
</P>
<P>
   From this point, it's going to get worse before it gets better.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
