<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-ZUBOV-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS' ZUBOV MAKES PRESENCE FELT ON POWER PLAY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MAC ENGEL 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ It took the Stars about 15 seconds to feel the
difference on their power play between Sergei Zubov playing or
watching.
</P>
<P>
   With San Jose's Todd Harvey serving a penalty in the first
period, Zubov settled the puck behind the net and moved up ice,
where he zipped a pass to Brett Hull into the San Jose zone and
left Sharks winger Jeff Friesen frozen.
</P>
<P>
   Hull slapped a pass to an open Zubov near the goal line, where
his shot was deflected by Sharks goalie Steve Shields to a even
more open Mike Modano, who promptly pumped in the shot for a
two-goal lead at 14:01.
</P>
<P>
   Good night, San Jose. Hello, power play and hello Sergei Zubov.
</P>
<P>
   In their 4-0 victory against the Sharks in Game 1 of their
second-round series last night at Reunion Arena, the Stars' special
teams were indeed special with their quarterback at the helm after
missing the past 10 games.
</P>
<P>
   ``He just looked like the same guy who left us in Florida,''
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock said. ``The wilder the game gets the
better he plays.''
</P>
<P>
   Zubov, who last month signed a five-year, $25 million contract
and was having one of his best seasons, had been teetering on the
day-to-day routine after suffering a collateral]partially torn
ligament in his right knee at Florida on March 29.
</P>
<P>
   ``For one, he's a great defenseman, and any time you get a
player of his caliber it's going to help,'' Stars defenseman Derian
Hatcher said. ``There's not many guys in the league who can do what
he did with the puck.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars' power play last night matched the number of goals it
scored in the entire first-round series against Edmonton. The Stars
were 2-for-26 against the Oilers. They are 2-for-7 against the
Sharks.
</P>
<P>
   ``For a guy who has been out as long as he's been, I thought he
stepped in and did a great job for us,'' said Stars center Joe
Nieuwendyk, who scored his first goal of this year's playoffs on a
Zubov-led power play. ``He moves the puck very nicely and really
opens up a lot on the power play. He's probably a big reason why we
had a couple goals on the power play.''
</P>
<P>
   Probably?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's pretty much their power play,'' Sharks defenseman Mike
Rathje said.
</P>
<P>
   After the Stars grabbed a 2-0 lead in the first period thank to
Zubov's set up, they stretched their lead to 3-0 on Nieuwendyk's
power-play backhander past Shields. The assists? Jamie
Langenbrunner and Zubov.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, he was huge in the power play,'' Sharks coach
Darryl Sutter said. ``He's a part of their transition game, moving
the puck. You're talking about one of the top puck movers in the
game; you put him back in the lineup, it makes a huge difference.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't just the power play where his difference was felt.
</P>
<P>
   With Hitchcock remaining true to his word that Zubov would play
as much as needed, Hatcher and Darryl Sydor saw their load decrease
with Zubov's return. He played 17 minutes and 22 seconds in 22
shifts.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's definitely nice,'' Hatcher said. ``I have no idea what I
played tonight, but it's definitely nice not playing so much. \RMy
body\S feels like I played way less tonight.''
</P>
<P>
   He did. After averaging nearly 29 minutes of ice time against
the Oilers in Round 1, Hatcher played 25:35 last night.
</P>
<P>
   Zubov also saw some action on the Stars' penalty kill that shut
down the Sharks unit to 0-for-6.
</P>
<P>
   So, now the Sharks are faced with the question of trying to
contain Zubov, who probably isn't in his top playing condition.
</P>
<P>
   What should they do?
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess all you have to do is to try to keep the puck away
from him,'' Stars center Scott Thornton said. ``That's the best you
can do.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
