<HEADLINE>
SHARKS LOOKING FOR HITS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN and JESSE SANCHEZ 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Sharks captain Owen Nolan didn't make an appearance for
the media after last night's 4-0 loss. Maybe because he spent much
of the game wearing a bullseye on his sweater.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were keying on Nolan, no question. That was expected,''
said Vincent Damphousse, Sharks center and Nolan's linemate. ``Now,
we have to bump some of their players.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first period, Nolan ran face first into a Scott Thornton
elbow that sent him sprawling to the ice spilling blood. Early in
the second period, Nolan was swatted on the wrists with a stick. He
dropped his stick and headed to the bench slumped over.
</P>
<P>
   Neither occurrence kept Nolan, who had four shots, out of the
game. Nolan didn't practice Thursday and was smarting from blocking
an Al MacInnis slap shot in Game 7 against St. Louis, said Sharks
coach Darryl Sutter. Sutter said Nolan was a game-time decision and
that Nolan made the call to play. So, is Nolan hurting?
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it was obvious,'' Sutter said. \Nsubheds:Special teams
The Sharks entered Game 1 with the worst penalty-killing unit of
the eight remaining playoff teams at 79.5 percent. After giving up
two last night, they have allowed 10 goals on 46 power plays.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to do better on the power play,'' Mike Ricci said.
``We lost that battle along with a lot of other battles.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks were 0-for-6 on their power play and managed only two
shots through the first four power plays. \Nsubheds:That first goal
The Sharks know how important getting the first goal is. In their
past five games against the Blues, the team that scored first won.
Against Dallas, the point of scoring first is magnified.
</P>
<P>
   Last night, the Sharks spotted the Stars a 2-0 first-period lead
and never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They get a lead and they just literally frustrate you and kill
you in the neutral \Rzone\S,'' Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said.
``And then after \Rthe game\S people wonder what's wrong or what
happened. Well, that's what happened, they literally shut you
down.'' \Nsubheds:Little battles Thursday, coach Darryl Sutter said
you hope to learn how important winning the battle of the
intangibles, such as faceoffs, is in the playoffs. Last night, the
Stars won 60 percent of their faceoffs and seemed to win every big
faceoff in their own zone. \Nsubheds:Light night for Marchment The
Sharks' Bryant Marchment logged nearly 22 minutes of ice time but
landed only two hits. In the second period, he dived toward the
crease and deflected a Guy Carbonneau puck that was headed for the
back of an open net.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just diving for the puck,'' Marchment said. ``I was
trying to protect the goal. I didn't know where I was.''
\Nsubheds:Time to step up Coach Darryl Sutter called a 15-minute
meeting after the game. Afterward, several Sharks admitted they did
not appear ready to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to refocus,'' defenseman Mike Rathje said. ``Our
second and third lines have to step up and do like they do.''
</P>
<P>
   Bryan Marchment agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are a great hockey club, but we didn't play with any
sense of urgency,'' he said. ``But we have to be ready to play
teams like them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no excuses. This is the playoffs, so if we have to
come ready to play well.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
