<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-THIEL-COLUMN-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG LAYOFF, BUT NEVER A DULL MOMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By ART THIEL  
 c.2000 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Has this been fun, or what?
</P>
<P>
   I take back any criticism about the NBA's craven pandering to TV
interests with its postseason scheduling.
</P>
<P>
   By putting almost an entire off-season between the second and
third games of the playoff series between the Jazz and Sonics to
help boost pathetic ratings, the NBA inadvertently exposed us in
Seattle to some delightful hijinks.
</P>
<P>
   Some think the source of the sillies was a sort of tribute to a
TV movie Monday about the Three Stooges. The last few days around
the Sonics have often seemed like one giant shouting match, wherein
each participant began with Moe's favorite threat: ``Why, I oughta
... ''
</P>
<P>
   But, really, this is the same old Sonics in the spring. It just
that when George Karl, Gary Payton and Shawn Kemp were going
haywire before our eyes, there was only one off-day between games.
</P>
<P>
   Now with so much free time _ the U.S. took Panama, Grenada,
Kuwait and Elian Gonzalez combined in less time than the NBA took
to get to Game 3 _ the spilling of bile, venting of gas and
wringing of hands has become an Oprah mini-series.
</P>
<P>
   For those of you old enough to remember, the Sonics lost the
first two games of this series _ not atypical for a seventh seed
against a second seed _ in a sufficiently desultory fashion that we
journalists have been inspired to tell basketball players and
coaches how to do basketball.
</P>
<P>
   In kind, basketball players and coaches have been inspired to
tell journalists how to do journalism.
</P>
<P>
   This has been great stuff, because both sides know so much about
what they are talking about.
</P>
<P>
   The pinnacle was reached earlier this week, when coach Paul
Westphal was in print and on radio and TV berating media members
for what they were saying. At the same time, the NBA was fining
Payton and the Sonics a combined $35,000 for what he (begin italic)
didn't (end italic) say, and reserve Chuck Person was blaming the
media exclusively for the defeats in Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Thanks to the mini-off-season, words, not jump shots, have
become the coin of this wonderfully absurd new NBA realm. That's
bad news for the jocks, because in this game, we hacks finally can
post them up and deal on them.
</P>
<P>
   As you may have read this week, Payton has demanded control of
the ball while abdicating his responsibilities as leader and
captain.
</P>
<P>
   After practice Wednesday, he said in regards to motivating
teammates that he ``ain't talking to nobody ... tell (Westphal and
Wally Walker) to talk to Vin (Baker). I'm going to talk to myself.
And that's it.''
</P>
<P>
   Contrast those selfless remarks with Payton's words in the P-I
Nov. 4, when he talked about how much more he liked his new
teammates than his old ones:
</P>
<P>
   ``When you've got guys who don't want to communicate with you
and walk off to the side, you think he's got an attitude about
something because you didn't pass the ball to him, or he didn't get
enough playing time,'' Payton said. ``It's crazy. You go into the
locker room and you feel that. A lot of us didn't get along. We
weren't hanging out. Now, about eight or nine of us hang out every
day. We like each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Dunno if these guys are still hanging out, but there's no doubt
it's Payton who has walked into the corner with an attitude.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Simon described it best: Still crazy after all these years.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the momentary state of Payton's affections, it matters
less Saturday because the NBA plans to interrupt this rhetorical
gluttony with an actual game. And if the Sonics win, there will be
only three off-days to discuss it until Game 4 here Wednesday. With
time so tight, the Sonics and the media will be in the market to
hire that speed talker from the old Federal Express TV commercials.
</P>
<P>
   It isn't fashionable to entertain a notion of a Sonics triumph,
not with the prospective hiring of Lenny Wilkens to replace
Westphal and/or Walker and/or both as Topic A at the water cooler.
</P>
<P>
   But the facts are that the Jazz historically have been lame on
the postseason road _ 23-58, or .283, including a 3-6 record in
Seattle _ and the fury in the Sonics camp could burn an entire
container ship's worth of adrenaline.
</P>
<P>
   Whether those factors are sufficient for a team that has lost 13
of its past 18 games and wrenched through two new starting lineups
is dubious. But since that makes no sense for the Sonics, it would
seem likely to happen.
</P>
<P>
   And if it happens Saturday, it can happen Wednesday. Two home
victories won't mean that the franchise is any less screwed up
long-term, but they will add greatly to the confusion and
controversy.
</P>
<P>
   Logic, linear thinking and enlightenment have never been parts
of this Sonics team, nor any Sonics team in the past several years.
Those characteristics are the property of the Jazz.
</P>
<P>
   But because this stretched-out series has way more time for talk
than walk, the wise money says to doom the broom.
</P>
<P>
   Never has an NBA team been better equipped to chat its way out
of an 0-2 hole.
</P>
<P>
   P-I columnist Art Thiel can be reached at 206-448-8135
</P>
<P>
   or artthiel &LR; seattle-pi.com
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 0115EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
