<HEADLINE>
SKINNER CAPTURES POLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ Forgive Mike Skinner if he's not too excited
about taking his third career NASCAR Winston Cup pole Friday. It's
just that the Ontario native, who has yet to win a race, has been
here before.
</P>
<P>
   ``If omens mean anything, then maybe our chances are getting
better of winning our first race,'' Skinner said after qualifying
No. 1 Friday for Sunday's NAPA Auto Parts 500 at California
Speedway. ``But the biggest thing we've got to work on is getting
this car to drive good (in the race). That's going to better our
chances (of winning) more then a good qualifying spot.''
</P>
<P>
   Skinner, who finished second in the DieHard 500 at Talladega,
Ala., two weeks ago, circled the two-mile oval at a track-record
186.061 mph. Jimmy Spencer was second at 185.979 mph with Ricky
Rudd third at 185.830.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lap was good, but it wasn't a perfect lap,'' Skinner said.
``The car pushed a little bit (at the start of the lap). If I had
got good and straight off the corners, I would say it was an
awesome lap.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just tried to focus on hitting our marks. I really didn't
have a lot of confidence in that lap standing up. I was a little
surprised that it held up, but I will take it.''
</P>
<P>
   Spencer, whose last pole came in 1994, nearly slipped by
Spencer, but the veteran scrubbed off too much speed heading into
the tri-oval.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you get that close to the pole, you're a little upset
because naturally you want to be on the pole,'' Spencer said. ``We
got a little bit too loose in (turns) three and four, so that hurt
us a little bit. That little bit cost us the pole, but man, this
year we've been worrying about if we were gonna make the races, so
to start second is a pretty big accomplishment for (our) team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our goals were to try to be in the top 25. That's very
important for practice and for the race, so being second is pretty
special.''
</P>
<P>
   Former CART veteran Scott Pruett, who qualified second at Las
Vegas and third at Texas, topped the rookie qualifiers with a
185.204 mph circuit, which was good enough for sixth.
</P>
<P>
   ``The . . . car ran well,'' said Pruett, who hasn't finished
higher then 19th this season. ``We weren't sure if we were headed
in the right direction, but as it turned out, it looks like
everything worked out all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Veteran Darrell Waltrip, who is retiring at the end of the 2000
season, had his best qualifying attempt of the season. The former
Winston Cup champion will start seventh following a lap of 185.014
mph.
</P>
<P>
   ``They give me those provisional (starts) and it seems every
time we use them up, that's when we go to work,'' Waltrip said.
``That was a great run for us. I think this team is coming around.
Now I've got to put the `V' in our Victory Tour somehow.''
</P>
<P>
   Notables who failed to qualify were Jeff Gordon (26th), Tony
Stewart (31st) and Dale Earnhardt (36th). They can either make an
attempt during second-round qualifying this morning or stand on
their time.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
