<HEADLINE>
SHENG, DOUBLES TEAM ADVANCE TO SEMIS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANEL LAJ  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   OJAI, Calif. _ Only three are left standing.
</P>
<P>
   Thousand Oaks' Phil Sheng and the Harvard-Westlake doubles team
of Prakash Amritraj and David Frankel survived tough competition to
advance to the semifinals of the 100th Ojai Tournament today at the
Thacher School.
</P>
<P>
   The finals are scheduled for 2 p.m. at Libbey Park.
</P>
<P>
   Sheng, the No. 1 seed, won a tough three-set match over Rio
Mesa's Quinn Borchard 2-6, 6-2, 6-4 and will be playing Claremont's
Daniel Clemens at 8 a.m. today.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had a huge first serve, then he just wins the game just
like that. I had to work twice as hard to win this game and that
was the difference of the first set,'' Sheng said of the only set
he's lost in the tournament.
</P>
<P>
   ``He reads (the shot) so well and is really quick at the net. I
give him credit. He made me have to go for the bigger passing shot.
I returned it really well when he served and volleyed to me, but I
give him credit. He had some unbelievable volleys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Wolverines gave up only four games in their quarterfinal
match, in which they beat Beverly Hills' Raymond Hekmat and David
Nguyen 6-4, 6-0.
</P>
<P>
   They face Bakersfield's Bryan Mercado and Jordan Widelock at
Thacher today at 9:30 a.m.
</P>
<P>
   __ Tough losses: Harvard-Westlake's Andrew Rosenfeld led 5-1 in
the first set against Daniel Clemens of Claremont. After that, it
was all Clemens.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenfeld hit a couple of double faults and Clemens gained
enough momentum to break Rosenfeld's next serve to turn the match
around and beat him 7-6 (9-7), 3-6, 6-1.
</P>
<P>
   Crespi's Stephen Amritraj lost to Rio Mesa's Borchard 6-7 (7-0),
7-5, 6-3 in the quarters, and Burbank's Tigran Martiroysan lost to
Jason Kao 7-5, 7-5 of Sunny Hills.
</P>
</TEXT>
