<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RED </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS EDGE RED SOX
</HEADLINE>
 SOX-INDIANS-BOS (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ Apres le deluge last weekend in Boston, the Red
Sox-Indians rivalry was revived Friday night at Jacobs Field, where
the Sox were last seen drenched not by rain, but by champagne.
</P>
<P>
   But unlike Game 5 of the American League division series, which
became the stuff of legend, Jimy Williams could not wave in Pedro
Martinez from the bullpen to silence Cleveland bats, and this time,
when Troy O'Leary came up against Indians reliever Paul Shuey with
the game still hanging in the balance, his drive died in David
Justice's glove.
</P>
<P>
   With much less at stake than the last time they met, the Indians
defeated the Sox, 4-3, before a crowd of 42,885 relieved that the
Cleveland bullpen threw three shutout innings after being so
pitiful in the last three games of the postseason last October,
when the Sox outscored the Tribe, 44-18.
</P>
<P>
   Message game? ``No,'' said Indians starter Dave Burba, who was
trailing, 3-1, until the Indians rallied for three runs in the
bottom of the sixth against Sox lefthanders Pete Schourek and Rheal
Cormier. ``A message game would be 20-2, like they did to us last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Burba was referring to the 23-7 beating the Sox laid on the
Indians in Game 4 last October, the night before O'Leary hit a
three-run home run off Shuey to break an 8-all tie and send the Sox
to a 12-8 clinching win in Game 5.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night, with the Indians clinging to a one-run lead,
Shuey, the fourth Indians pitcher, faced O'Leary leading off the
eighth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh yeah, I thought about the last pitch I threw him,'' Shuey
said. ``This was a real similar deal. I almost threw the same
pitch. This one was a little higher and farther out, and he just
wasn't able to pull it.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary was able, however, to put a good swing on the ball,
launching a deep drive into the left-center-field gap. But Justice,
never breaking stride and ignoring center fielder Jacob Cruz as he
arrived on the scene, made a tough backhanded catch just before the
ball reached the wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``He killed me there,'' O'Leary said. ``He made a great play.
But that's what he's out there for.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Leary's sense of recall Friday night needed a little prodding.
Asked if he was thinking about the last time he faced Shuey, his
face went blank and he said, ``What did I do?'' A split-second
later, when it came back to him, he shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``Last year was last year,'' he said. ``This year, you forget it
and try to win a ballgame.
</P>
<P>
   ``But that's a great team over there. My God, every time you
look up, there's (Jim) Thome, (Robbie and Sandy) Alomar, Justice.
And (Travis) Fryman, he's not as big a name, but he's dangerous,
too.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sox had taken a 1-0 lead on Trot Nixon's double and a single
by Nomar Garciaparra, who all but threw his bat at a low and
outside pitch and golfed the ball into left field, extending his
hitting streak to 14 games.
</P>
<P>
   But after Fryman's leadoff home run in the fourth tied the
score, the Sox took the lead in the fifth when Burba walked Nixon
and Brian Daubach, and Garciaparra beat out a chopper to short to
load the bases for O'Leary, who in Game 5 a year ago hit a grand
slam off Charles Nagy.
</P>
<P>
   Against Burba, O'Leary hit a drive to the right-field track for
a sacrifice fly that brought home one run, and Carl Everett's bloop
single to center scored another.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wind was blowing in,'' O'Leary said. ``Later on in the
summer, that ball might have gone out.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians broke through in the sixth against Schourek and
Cormier to seize the lead. Schourek, who had allowed just three
hits in the first five innings, gave up a ground-rule double to
Fryman and singles by Robbie Alomar and Manny Ramirez to make it
3-2.
</P>
<P>
   Williams summoned lefthander Cormier to face Justice, who
whacked a single to right, tying the score, and sending Ramirez to
third when Nixon's throw to the plate bounced away from catcher
Scott Hatteberg for an error. Richie Sexson flied to shallow center
for the second out, but Thome, who came into the game 0 for 13
against lefthanders, lined a single to right against his ex-hunting
buddy for the go-ahead run.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel like this was one I let slip away,'' said Schourek, who
has now made four starts in which he has allowed three runs or
fewer but has only a 1-2 record.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lead halfway through the game,'' he said, ``and didn't
do enough stuff to hold them down.''
</P>
<P>
   Cormier had not allowed a hit to a lefthanded batter until
Justice and Thome delivered.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have some tough hitters over there,'' Williams said.
``They put some good at-bats on us that one inning.''
</P>
<P>
   And so the rivalry returns. It'll be Ramon Martinez vs. Chuck
Finley Saturday, with Pedro waiting in the wings for Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's emotion there,'' Shuey said. ``We want to beat those
guys. They embarrassed us last year.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
