<SLUG> BC-BBA-ANGELS-LADN-(SLANG) </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD A HIT, BUT ...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calilf. _ The way the Anaheim Angels have pitched
lately, they'd need nine Darin Erstads in the lineup to be
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, they still have only one, which would explain their
11-2 loss to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays Friday night before 31,888 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Even Erstad, who has established an American League record for
hits in the month of April (45), has an off-night now and then.
Friday he went 1 for 4, his league-leading average dipping to .459.
The 45 hits are the most in any month by any player in Angels
history, breaking Garret Anderson's record of 44 set in July 1998.
</P>
<P>
   But even four homers by Erstad would have made little difference
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jason Dickson, coming off his best start of the
season (0 earned runs in 7 innings against the same Devil Rays),
didn't make it out of the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   He was shelled for six runs and seven hits in 1 innings, leaving
the game because of a strained left hip-flexor. There was no word
on how he sustained the injury, other than the possibility he hurt
it dodging line drives that whizzed past his head during the game.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson's performance and more shoddy work from the bullpen shed
light on what is starting to become more rule than exception. In
the first 12 games of the season, the Angels had allowed a total of
48 runs, or 4.0 runs per game. In their last 12, they've allowed 86
runs, or 7.2 per game. Of those 12, the Angels' opposition has
scored in double figures five times.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Angels have fallen to 11-13, the first time
they've been two games below .500 since they were 0-2 on April 4.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson and the Angels were finished Friday before the stadium
lights warmed up. He gave up three runs and five hits in the first
inning, and it would have been worse if not for the hard-hit double
play ball he got out of Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn more than made up for it, though, hitting a three-run
homer off Dickson in the second inning, before adding a single in
the third, another homer in the sixth and a single in the seventh.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn had four of the Devil Rays' 19 hits, which are the most
ever in club history in a nine-inning game. Dave Martinez had three
hits, and Fred McGriff, Vinny Castilla and John Flaherty had two
each in support of starter Esteban Yan (1-1), who allowed only a
two-run homer to Garret Anderson (No. 4) in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays are certainly happy to see the Angels on their
schedule today and Sunday _ they are 4-1 vs. the Angels this
season; 5-12 against the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Down, 8-2, after four innings, the Angels offense appeared to
pack it in for the night. They got only two hits hit in the final
five innings _ Erstad's eighth-inning single and Troy Glaus'
ninth-inning double.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
