<HEADLINE>
CHURCHILL DOWNS CEO OPTIMISTIC ABOUT HOLLYWOOD PARK
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By KEVIN MODESTI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   INGLEWOOD, Calif. _ The waitress at a Laguna Beach sandwich shop
greeted Churchill Downs Inc. CEO Tom Meeker with a friendly ``Hey,
baby!'' one afternoon this week.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, `Go Baby Go!' '' Meeker recalled. ``She said, `No,
that's a horse-racing term.'''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe she just happened to have watched the National
Thoroughbred Racing Association's TV commercials and remembered the
slogan. Or maybe she's one of a legion of Southern Californians who
are horse-racing-aware. Meeker prefers to believe the latter.
</P>
<P>
   In meetings with employees and horsemen on opening night at
Hollywood Park _ which Churchill Downs Inc. purchased for $140
million in September _ Meeker delivered a refreshingly optimistic
message about the sport's future. He rejected what he called
``Chicken Little talk.''
</P>
<P>
   ``As horsemen and track operators, we should have a smile from
ear to ear,'' he said. ``We are at the cusp of something big.''
</P>
<P>
   Meeker's mere presence Friday, the first of Hollywood Park's 65
days and nights of racing, sent the message that the 62-year-old
track is a cornerstone of Churchill Downs Inc.'s burgeoning
simulcast network. He planned an early morning flight home to
Louisville to attend Churchill Downs' own season-opening card this
afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, a relaxed Meeker:
</P>
<P>
   __ Endorsed cutting back racing dates but said that alone won't
solve California's problem of small fields.
</P>
<P>
   __ Smiled at Santa Anita boss Frank Stronach's repeated calls
for extra racing dates and direct competition between the wanting
to roll grenades across the floor at one another. We're not going
to get into that,'' Meeker said. ``We haven't yet found a way to
work together. That doesn't mean we're fighting.''
</P>
<P>
   __ Acknowledged that Churchill executives are still learning the
L.A. market, noting that ethnicities are different, the racetrack
isn't the civic institution that it is in Kentucky, and horse
culture is less prevalent here. ``But I wouldn't sell California
too short,'' Meeker said. ``There are a lot of racing fans here.''
</P>
<P>
   The 23,000 fans (a mid-card estimate) who showed up on a
pleasant Friday night watched David Flores rally Islay Mist ($18)
to victory on the turf in the $100,000 Senorita Stakes for
3-year-old fillies; Kent Desormeaux ride two of the first three
winners; and Laffit Pincay pick up No. 9,008 aboard No Wager in the
fourth race. Pincay's record-breaking No. 8,834 was the highlight
of Hollywood's fall meet.
</P>
<P>
   Opening weekend begins with today's Fastness Handicap on turf;
Bonapartiste tries to give trainer Ron McAnally his 100th Hollywood
stakes win (McAnally's total is second to Charlie Whittingham's
California Gold Rush card of California-bred races drew an average
of 11 horses for the events in a guaranteed $1 million pick-six.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 0155EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
