<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 02:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0849 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-NUANGELS-LADN-(SL     04-29 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-NUANGELS-LADN-(SLANG)WRITETHRU </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ERSTAD A HIT, BUT...
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. The way the Anaheim Angels have pitched lately,
they'd need nine Darin Erstads in the lineup just to be
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   As it is, they have only one Erstad, which would explain their
11-2 loss to the Tampa Bay Devil Rays Friday night before 31,888 at
Edison Field.
</P>
<P>
   Even Erstad, who established an American League record for hits
in the month of April (45), has an off-night now and then. He had
only one hit in four at-bats on Friday, as his league-leading
average dipped to .459.
</P>
<P>
   However, the 45 hits are the most in any month by any player in
Angels history, breaking Garret Anderson's record of 44 set in July
1998.
</P>
<P>
   Then again, not even four home runs by Erstad would have made
little difference.
</P>
<P>
   Angels starter Jason Dickson, coming off his best start of the
season (0 earned runs in 7 innings against the same Devil Rays),
didn't make it out of the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   He was shelled for six runs and seven hits in 1 innings, leaving
the game because of a strained left hip. Dickson said he's felt a
nagging pain for a couple days but thought he could get through the
game. That's why he didn't tell manager Mike Scioscia of his injury
until the Angels were in a 6-0 hole.
</P>
<P>
   ``You'd rather get a little heads up,'' Scioscia said. ``But
it's not something you'd be able to hide. It's Jason's makeup not
to alibi, not to look for ways out of games. His makeup is not to
make excuses.''
</P>
<P>
   There is no excuse for the way the Angels have pitched lately,
particularly out of the bullpen.
</P>
<P>
   Dickson's performance and more shoddy work from the bullpen shed
light on what is starting to become more rule than exception.
</P>
<P>
   In the first 12 games of the season, the Angels had allowed a
total of 48 runs, or 4.0 runs per game. In their last 12, they've
allowed 86 runs, or 7.2 per game. Of those 12, the Angels'
opposition has scored in double figures five times.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, the Angels have fallen to 11-13, the first time
they've been two games below .500 since they were 0-2 on April 4.
</P>
<P>
   After the game, Scioscia held his first post-game team meeting
of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We just talked about a couple things, nothing big,'' Scioscia
said. ``We haven't done a lot of things well the last couple games.
It's not about effort. If anything, they're trying a little too
hard. Particularly the pitching staff. They're not executing the
way they can.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows when it's necessary,'' Angels first baseman Mo Vaughn
said of the meeting. ``He had what he had to say. That's why we got
him, for these situations. He knows the difference between getting
beat and beating ourselves. He said it's not effort, it's a mental
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Dickson and the Angels were finished Friday before the stadium
lights warmed up. He gave up three runs and five hits in the first
inning, and it would have been worse if not for the hard-hit
double-play ball he got out of Greg Vaughn.
</P>
<P>
   Vaughn more than made up for it, though, hitting a three-run
homer off Dickson in the second inning, before adding a single in
the third, another homer in the sixth and a single in the seventh
off Angels relievers.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do you do?'' Dickson said. ``On one hand, you want to
tough it out. But six runs in two innings doesn't give your team a
chance to win. Live and learn. . . I guess I should have given them
a heads-up ahead of time. Next time I will.''
</P>
<P>
   Greg Vaughn had four of the Devil Rays' 19 hits, which were the
most ever in club history in a nine-inning game. Dave Martinez had
three hits, and Fred McGriff, Vinny Castilla and John Flaherty had
two each in support of starter Esteban Yan (1-1), who allowed only
a two-run homer to Garret Anderson (No. 4) in seven innings.
</P>
<P>
   The Devil Rays are certainly happy to see the Angels on their
schedule today and Sunday _ they are 4-1 vs. the Angels this
season; 5-12 against the rest of the league.
</P>
<P>
   Down, 8-2, after four innings, the Angels offense appeared to
pack it in for the night. They got only two hits hit in the final
five innings _ Erstad's eighth-inning single and Troy Glaus'
ninth-inning double.
</P>
</TEXT>
