<SLUG> BC-ELLISON-RICHEST-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 ELLISON ECLIPSES GATES IN STOCK  &HT;     By TODD WALLACK 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Oracle Chairman Larry Ellison, the swashbuckling
executive who built a career out of tweaking Microsoft, passed
Microsoft co-founder Bill Gates on Friday as the world's richest
man.
</P>
<P>
   Almost.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison's 24 percent stake in Oracle of Redwood Shores inched up
to $53 billion Friday, compared with $51.7 billion for Gates' stake
in Microsoft of Redmond, Wash.
</P>
<P>
   Ellison, 55, who lives in Atherton, passed Gates, 44, earlier
this week, if you ask Oracle how many shares he holds: 689 million.
But documents filed with the federal Securities and Exchange
Commission in April indicate that Ellison had options to sell 27
million of those shares within 60 days _ meaning he may not
actually own them today.
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, Gates probably still officially holds the Midas
title, according to Forbes magazine, which estimates that Gates
also has $10 billion in outside investments versus $200 million in
real estate holdings for Ellison.
</P>
<P>
   But it's no less stunning that the flamboyant Ellison, who is
known for buzzing Silicon Valley at all hours in his corporate jet
and racing his yacht around the world, has come so close to
eclipsing the nerdier Gates, who prefers to go off on retreats with
a stack of research papers and technical reports.
</P>
<P>
   Just a year ago, Forbes estimated that Gates was the richest man
with $85 billion compared with $13 billion for Ellison. Gates has
become such a fixture at the head of the list that there is even a
Web site _ the Bill Gates Personal Wealth Clock
( &LR; www.webho.com/WealthClock &LR; ) _ that purports to calculate Gates'
current wealth based on the price of Microsoft stock. (The numbers
differ, incidentally, because the Web site operator uses the number
of Microsoft shares Gates held in 1995.)
</P>
<P>
   One of the prime reasons Ellison has come so close to passing
Gates is that Microsoft's shares have tumbled 15 percent this past
year over concerns about the landmark U.S. antitrust trial against
Microsoft. Government antitrust lawyers recommended yesterday that
Microsoft be split in two.
</P>
<P>
   Oracle shares, meanwhile, have surged 485 percent over the past
12 months, partly fueled by the growth in the Internet and
technology as a whole. Some critics say that Oracle has nearly as
much dominance in database software as Microsoft has in PC
software.
</P>
<P>
   That's a little ironic, because Ellison has lambasted Gates for
racking up his fortune by using Microsoft's monopoly hold on
personal computer software. Ellison once said ``Gates should be
jailed'' for trying to drive rivals out of business.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Todd Wallack at  &LR; todd(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
