<HEADER>
A0852 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-MICROSOFT-BREAKUP-SFC     04-29 1452
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-BREAKUP-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 MICROSOFT SPLIT URGED  &HT;     By Kelly Zito 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Microsoft should pay the ultimate price for its
dominance in the software industry and be cleaved into two distinct
companies, according to a proposal filed Friday with the federal
judge overseeing the landmark antitrust case.
</P>
<P>
   The document, filed jointly by the Department of Justice and
attorneys general of 17 states, proposes splitting the software
behemoth into two pieces: one that sells applications like Word and
another centered on the Windows operating system. The plan is aimed
at breaking Microsoft's stranglehold on the desktop and
jumpstarting competition in the software market.
</P>
<P>
   On April 3, U.S. District Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson ruled
that Microsoft broke state and federal antitrust laws designed to
promote a level playing field by using its monopoly in the
operating systems market to pulverize rivals. That, in turn, hurt
consumers by limiting choices, the ruling said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This decree will not limit Microsoft's ability to add new
features to its products or otherwise to innovate,'' said Joel
Klein, the Justice Department's antitrust chief. ``But by turning
loose the power of competition in the operating systems business,
this decree will stimulate innovation throughout the software
industry.''
</P>
<P>
   Friday's development is just the latest salvo in a battle that
has already lasted two years and could drag on for several more.
And many legal, software and consumer experts are divided whether a
breakup would encourage real competition. Some even say the move
could backfire for consumers by driving up software prices and
handcuffing other high-tech companies that fear similar reprisals
from an emboldened Department of Justice.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup of Microsoft would be the first of a U.S. monopoly
in 16 years _ since American Telephone &AMP; Telegraph's split into the
eight regional ``Baby Bells.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This breakup is nonsensical,'' said Helen Chaney, a public
policy fellow at the Pacific Research Institute for Public Policy,
a free market think tank. ``People keep talking about (the) AT&AMP;T
breakup, but this is different. This is not going to change the
dynamics in the market and it's going to create a lot of needless
regulation and cost taxpayers a bundle because the government will
have to continually monitor the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft Chairman Bill Gates derided the proposal as
``disturbing'' and reiterated confidence that the appeals court
will overturn Jackson's ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``These remedies would not allow us to deliver new software
products like we have in the past,'' Gates said. ``These
regulations do not help the software industry. They retard the
speed at which it will move ahead.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft stock, which has fallen 25 percent since Jackson's
April 3 ruling, fell 6 cents in regular trading, closing at $69.75.
In after-hours trading the stock edged up to around $70.44.
</P>
<P>
   Under the proposal, Microsoft's various Windows operating
systems would comprise one company; the other would be made up of
the rest, including the extremely popular Office suite of products
and the company's Web navigation tool, Internet Explorer. The
operating systems company would receive a one-time license to
integrate Internet Explorer into its software, but would eventually
have to develop its own. Only one company could retain the
Microsoft name; and the company's two or three largest shareholders
_ including Gates _ would have to choose stock in one company. The
two entities could not combine for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the structural remedies _ which would not be
enacted until the appeals process is concluded _ the proposal
includes conduct curbs. Those would go into effect immediately
after the completion of the remedies phase of the trial and stay in
place until three years after the structural remedies went into
affect.
</P>
<P>
   Those measures include restricting Microsoft from retaliating
against any computer maker that decided to use a competing product
or offering discounts on the Windows operating system to selected
computer makers.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft could not insist that computer makers agree to license
other Microsoft software in order to receive a license for Windows.
</P>
<P>
   Computer makers would also be free to modify the Windows startup
sequence to remove icons for Microsoft products or display
competitors' products. Microsoft would make available the technical
information that competing software makers use to make their
products compatible with Windows, and it could not interfere with
the performance of such software.
</P>
<P>
   Two states, Ohio and Illinois, filed a separate remedy statement
supporting only behavioral restrictions on the company for several
years. If those didn't achieve the stated goals, a structural
remedy would then be imposed.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft has until May 10 to file its response to the
government's remedies _ though the company has signaled it will ask
for an extension. The Justice Department and states have a week to
respond. On May 24, Jackson is scheduled to hold hearings on the
proposals; he could make his final ruling on Microsoft's fate as
soon as June.
</P>
<P>
   Many anti-Microsoft groups hailed the final proposal, after
several weeks in which other remedies ranging from behavioral curbs
to splitting the company into several smaller ``clones'' were
suggested, according to reports.
</P>
<P>
   ``The price of software overall will come down when the
competitive pressures are unleashed here,'' said Mike Pettit,
executive director of ProComp, an anti-Microsoft trade group based
in Washington, D.C. ``When you look at AT&AMP;T, the net effect was the
prices in all areas went down in both local and long-distance
service.''
</P>
<P>
   However, many questions remain.
</P>
<P>
   Namely, whether the government's proposal _ if actually enacted
_ will restore competition in a marketplace that has changed
drastically in the two years since the case was filed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It may be that Windows holds a high market share now, but
other technologies are threatening to unseat Microsoft,'' Chaney
said. ``The government should ask itself what it's planning to
achieve in this case. Already, the market is moving away from the
Windows platform and into other platforms like Web-based
software.''
</P>
<P>
   If the company is broken up, the most obvious winners are the
makers and distributors of Linux, the increasingly popular
alternative operating system based on Unix.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linux and open source is going to win against Microsoft no
matter what happens _ this accelerates that,'' said Larry Augustin,
chief executive of VA Linux, a Sunnyvale company that provides
servers and workstations based on Linux.
</P>
<P>
   In the broader applications market, Augustin believes a breakup
``will create more excitement, because there will be less fear that
Microsoft will enter a potential market.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Augustin worries about the legal fallout.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a saying that Microsoft may get what it deserves, but
everyone else may get what Microsoft deserves as well,'' he said.
``It could lead to the breakup of other companies where it doesn't
make as much sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Others postulate that Microsoft could become like the Hydra
monster of Greek myth, which could sprout heads almost as quickly
as a swordsman cut one off.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this breakup plan were to make it all the way through
appeals, it could create a lot of confusion in the marketplace,''
said Rob Enderle, an analyst with the Giga Information Group.
``Long term, we'd find a lot more benefit, but it might be with two
very dominant companies instead of one.''
</P>
<P>
   Analysts seem to think Microsoft shareholders could be a winner
because investors could own stock in two extremely powerful
entities, instead of just one.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you split a pretty dynamic company like that in half, it
dilutes overall value,'' said William Welch, managing director of
Fiduciary Asset Management, with $155 million in assets. ``Still,
Microsoft split in two is still going to be Microsoft, and I think
it should be bought for long-term growth potential.''
</P>
<P>
   And finally there's the question of whether the idea of a pair
of Microsofts will ever become a reality. Silicon Valley antitrust
attorney Rich Gray thinks the Justice Department proved its case
that Microsoft illegally protected its Windows monopoly.
</P>
<P>
   But he concedes that a breakup of the world's biggest software
company is far from certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``Microsoft will have some good arguments'' on appeal, he said.
``They may even have a better than a 50-50 chance'' of overturning
Jackson's decision. ``But nothing is a sure thing.''
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Kelly Zito at  &LR; kzito(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
