r f BC-ONLINE-BROKERS-SFCHRO     04-29 0729
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ONLINE-BROKERS-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FIDELITY, SCHWAB SCORE BEST IN CUSTOMER SURVEY OF ONLINE
BROKERS  BY SAM ZUCKERMAN
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ A hush-hush study by J.D. Power, one of the
nation's leading market research firms, shows sharp differences in
customer satisfaction at the major online brokerage firms. The news
is good for Charles Schwab Corp. and bad for E-Trade Group. The two
Bay Area companies dominate the fast-growing industry.
</P>
<P>
   The survey covering 13 Internet brokerage services showed
Fidelity Investments did the top job of keeping its customers
happy, followed closely by San Francisco's Schwab. Menlo Park,
Calif.'s E-Trade had the second-worst customer satisfaction record,
barely beating out Citibank, the industry laggard.
</P>
<P>
   Power, widely known for its auto industry customer satisfaction
surveys, issued the confidential brokerage report to clients in
March based on questionnaires submitted to 6,706 online investors
at the beginning of the year. The Chronicle obtained a copy.
</P>
<P>
   The popularity of online stock trading is soaring in the Bay
Area and nationwide. The industry added more than 3 million
accounts in the first three months of 2000, bringing total U.S.
accounts to more than 15 million, according to the brokerage firm
Solomon Smith Barney.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Gap Viewed as Significant
</P>
<P>
   Power, based in Agoura Hills , Calif., declined to discuss the
performance of specific companies. But Nancy Salk, research
director at the firm's Connecticut office, said researchers found a
significant gap between brokers at the top of the survey and those
at the bottom.
</P>
<P>
   ``We saw very distinct strengths and weaknesses among them,''
Salk said.
</P>
<P>
   Overall, Salk said, the industry is doing better at satisfying
customers. From May 1999, when Power conducted its first brokerage
survey, to January, the industry's average customer-satisfaction
score increased 6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The rising tide lifted all boats, including Citibank and
E-Trade, which improved their satisfaction scores a few notches.
The better scores in part reflect improved reliability of company
Web sites, which were notoriously prone to slowdowns and outages
early last year.
</P>
<P>
   Power's scores are an index based on six measures of customer
satisfaction, including customer service, company integrity and
reputation, information and education and reliability of brokerage
Web sites. Among the questions investors were asked were how easy
it was to get through to their broker, how reliable was the firm's
Web site, how well questions were answered and whether orders were
executed accurately.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; sh1  &LR; Tradition of Service
</P>
<P>
   Wall Street analysts said it is not surprising to see a gap
between Fidelity and Schwab, which were in the brokerage business
before online investing took off, and E-Trade, which came of age in
the Internet era.
</P>
<P>
   ``Schwab and Fidelity have a long tradition of high-quality
customer service and support,'' said Stephen Franco of U.S. Bancorp
Piper Jaffray. ``E-Trade is a more technology-controlled firm as
opposed to a customer-controlled firm.''
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade has had phenomenal success in attracting customers and
has had to scramble to build an infrastructure to support its
booming business.
</P>
<P>
   High Marks for Fidelity
</P>
<P>
   Top marks for Fidelity, which recently adopted the name
Powerstreet for its Internet business, reflect its history as a
brokerage and mutual fund company that invested heavily in
telephone and branch support. ``We take customer support very
seriously and built the infrastructure for it,'' said Tracey
Curvey, chief of the company's brokerage business.
</P>
<P>
   For its part, E-Trade stressed its push to build its customer
support operations, including hiring more than 300 new service
employees in recent months. ``We are making incredible strides in
customer service,'' said spokesman Patrick di Chiro.
</P>
<P>
   E-Trade has also come out on top in rankings that emphasize
reliability and ease of use of Internet sites, he said.
</P>
<P>
   Citibank, meanwhile, said it had not seen the Power report and
could not comment on it directly. Citibank's online banking and
brokerage services continue to rank very high in surveys of
respected publications, such as Forbes, Worth, Smart Money and
Money magazines, said spokesman Mark Rodgers.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Sam Zuckerman at  &LR; szuckerman(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
