r f BC-MP3-COPYRIGHT-SFCHRON     04-29 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MP3-COPYRIGHT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MP3.COM RULED IN VIOLATION OF COPYRIGHTS  &HT;     BY BENNY EVANGELISTA
</HEADLINE>
   &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ The nation's biggest record labels scored a key
victory Friday when a federal judge ruled that Internet music
portal MP3.com Inc. infringed on copyright laws by running a
virtual online jukebox service called MyMP3.com
</P>
<P>
   The decision by U.S. District Judge Jed Rakoff in New York means
MP3.com of San Diego is liable for a huge civil penalty amounting
to billions of dollars in damages sought by the Recording Industry
Association of America.
</P>
<P>
   The one-page ruling is the first in a number of copyright
infringement suits filed by record companies or artists against
high-tech companies that are rewriting the rules for distributing
music for free online.
</P>
<P>
   But legal experts say the ruling by itself only affects the
portal's MyMP3.com service and shouldn't set new legal precedents
that would affect other lawsuits against San Mateo, Calif.'s
Napster Inc. or stall the growing use of MP3 and other formats to
swap songs via the Internet. MyMP3.com was launched in January by
the pioneering online music portal as a jukebox service that would
allow members to listen to any song they own from any computer
linked to the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com copied songs from about 45,000 CDs into the
MP3-compression format and stored them on audio files accessible
through the Web. All MyMP3.com members had to do was prove they
already owned the song to gain access to the Internet version.
MP3.com argued its customers were legally entitled to listen to
their music in any form they chose.
</P>
<P>
   But the major record companies represented by the recording
industry trade group said MP3.com violated copyright law because
it, and not the individual music fan, made unauthorized copies.
</P>
<P>
   Current laws allow music fans to make copies of songs or albums
for their own use, but not for broad distribution or resale.
</P>
<P>
   Neil Rosini, a copyright law attorney with Franklin, Weinrib,
Rudell &AMP; Vassallo of New York, said yesterday's ruling reaffirmed
``a very long-rooted, old media maxim that people own copyrights.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't surprise me,'' he said. ``If they (the record
companies) had not won, it would have set back copyright laws as we
know it a couple of hundred years.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I like the concept of what MP3.com is doing, but I don't know
that the law supports it, and I'm not surprised by the judge's
decision,'' said Jim Burger, a computer and software licensing
attorney with Dow, Lohnes &AMP; Albertson law firm of Washington, D.C.
</P>
<P>
   MP3.com executives said they would appeal the ruling and had no
plans to shut down their MyMP3.com service unless ordered by the
judge.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a victory for the record labels, it's a loss,''
MP3.com chief executive Michael Robertson said in a statement after
the ruling.
</P>
<P>
   ``New technologies for delivering music are here to stay, and
the technology trend is moving in only one direction, forward,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Robertson said his company's system was superior to those of
Napster and other software programs that swap music over the
Internet because MP3.com requires users to purchase CD's before
accessing the music on the Net.
</P>
<P>
   A Redwood City, Calif., company, called MyPlay Inc., offers a
similar service. MyPlay has the record industry's support because
the customers do the work of uploading songs into ``virtual
lockers,'' said co-founder David Pakman.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear just how much the recording association can
collect. Theoretically, the damage award could be in the billions
because the suit against MP3.com originally asked for $150,000 in
damages for each unauthorized copy of a song.
</P>
<P>
   However, legal experts say it is doubtful the judge would assess
anywhere near the full amount against a company that has never
showed a profit and as recently as the first quarter of this year
lost $8.4 million.
</P>
<P>
   Rakoff's ruling did not provide details about how he arrived at
his decision, but he told attorneys for both sides to expect a
full, written ruling in a week or two. The next step will include
court hearings on penalties.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Benny Evangelista at  &LR; bennye(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
