<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 04:26 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0855 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-ANALYSIS-JUSTICE-SFCH     04-29 0855
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ANALYSIS-JUSTICE-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 NEWS ANALYSIS: MICROSOFT BREAKUP SCHEME MAY ASSUME TOO MUCH  &HT;     By HENRY NORR 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ When and if the Justice Department gets its way
and Microsoft is divided into separate operating-system and
application companies, the immediate result will simply be to
replace one monopoly with two.
</P>
<P>
   The company that gets Windows will still hold a position of
overwhelming dominance in the market for PC operating system
software. The other company _ the one that gets Microsoft Office
and the rest of the current company's products _ will have an
equally tight grip in business productivity software, still the
heart of the whole desktop software market.
</P>
<P>
   The plan creates no new competitors in either arena. It gives no
direct assistance to existing alternatives _ Mac OS, BeOS, Linux
and other Unix derivatives in the OS market, Corel, Lotus, Sun and
others in the applications arena.
</P>
<P>
   So why do the Justice Department and the 17 state attorneys
general who joined it in submitting this plan think it will revive
competition?
</P>
<P>
   Their argument depends on a series of assumptions about the
likely  &LR; indirect  &LR; consequences of the proposed breakup. Though not
implausible, these assumptions are by no means proven.
</P>
<P>
   The key assumptions:
</P>
<P>
   -- The new applications company, once cut loose from the entity
that markets Windows, will choose to offer versions of its
programs, especially Office, for other operating systems.
</P>
<P>
   -- The availability of such programs for other operating systems
will make customers more willing to adopt those systems in
preference to Windows. That in turn will make PC manufacturers more
willing to offer non-Windows operating systems preinstalled on
their hardware, either in place of or alongside a Microsoft system.
</P>
<P>
   The government's proposal, however, won't  &LR; require  &LR; the
applications company to develop products for non-Windows systems.
Instead, the government is apparently convinced the invisible hand
of capitalism _ the existence of a market opportunity from which
the new company could profit _ will induce it to move its
applications to other operating platforms.
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft already offers a version of Office, with most of the
features of its standard Windows version, for one other operating
system, Apple's Mac OS. That product has helped keep the Apple
alternative afloat; indeed, many industry watchers doubt that
Apple's revival in recent years, under the tutelage of CEO Steve
Jobs, could have occurred if Jobs hadn't managed in 1997 to
persuade Bill Gates to pledge publicly to keep developing Office
for the Mac for at least five more years.
</P>
<P>
   But because the Mac OS (in its current form, anyway) doesn't run
on the Intel and Intel-compatible chips that power roughly 95
percent of the world's personal computers, the availability of
Office for the Mac doesn't do much to bring competition into the
computing mainstream.
</P>
<P>
   There are, of course, several non-Windows operating systems
already available for Intel-based PCs: IBM still maintains its OS/2
product; Menlo Park, Calif.'s Be Inc. continues to improve its
multimedia-oriented BeOS; and several versions of Unix, an
industrial-strength OS mainly used for servers and high-end
workstations, have been adapted to run on PCs.
</P>
<P>
   For the future, though, all eyes are on Linux, the Unix
derivative that's distributed free and maintained by a worldwide
community of volunteer programmers. It has already proved its
mettle as an alternative to Microsoft's Windows NT and 2000 in
parts of the marketplace, chiefly for use on Internet servers.
</P>
<P>
   But servers are one market and the mainstream desktop quite
another, and so far, Linux has made only limited inroads into the
latter. Though it works with most up-to-date PCs, it still lacks
software ``drivers'' needed for compatibility with many older and
less-popular graphics cards, network adapters and the like.
Installing it can still be complicated, though Linux developers are
working hard to alleviate that problem.
</P>
<P>
   And the selection of applications, utilities, plug-ins and games
available for it, though growing, remains far more limited than the
options for Windows PCs.
</P>
<P>
   In other words, it's not obvious that enough users are likely to
adopt Linux in the near term to create a market large enough to
induce the new Microsoft-descended applications company to develop
Office for that platform _ even if the company makes its decisions
strictly on the basis of its own economic self-interest, without
regard to its former OS colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   And even if Office were to become available, it's not clear how
soon, if ever, the other obstacles would be overcome enough to
attract masses of home and business users.
</P>
<P>
   The arrival of Office on Linux could actually choke off the
competition that's emerging in the Linux applications market, where
Sun Microsystems is promoting its StarOffice package, Corel is
trying to revive its WordPerfect Office suite and several smaller
companies also have strong offerings.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail Henry Norr at  &LR; hnorr(AT)sfgate.com. &LR;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
