<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0050 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 04:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0856 &Cx1f; ttd-z
r f BC-REACT-MICROSOFT-SFCHR     04-29 0810
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REACT-MICROSOFT-SFCHRON </SLUG>
  
 IT'S BUSINESS AS USUAL FOR MICROSOFT  &HT;     By DAVID LAZARUS 
 &HT;     c. 2000 The San Francisco Chronicle 
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ As antitrust officials sought a breakup of
Microsoft Corp. Friday, workers at the software giant's spiffy new
Mountain View, Calif., campus were enjoying barbecued chicken and
bags of popcorn.
</P>
<P>
   As they ate, the Microsofties were volunteering their time at
tables set up by about a dozen local charities and community
groups.
</P>
<P>
   The event almost seemed scientifically designed to place the
company in a good light and counter the perception that Microsoft
is in fact an evil corporation that desires nothing less than total
world domination.
</P>
<P>
   ``It might seem kind of fishy,'' Microsoft spokeswoman Nikki
Wiebe said of the timing of the charity get-together. ``But
actually this had been planned for months.''
</P>
<P>
   In a sense, the picnic in Mountain View summed up the general
reaction to news of a potential breakup of Microsoft: business as
usual.
</P>
<P>
   From consumers in stores to members of computer support groups,
the consensus was that since the case still has a long way to go,
it's too early to mourn or celebrate, depending on where you stand
on the issue.
</P>
<P>
   Not surprisingly, Microsoft's Bay Area employees are toeing the
company's line that a breakup is unwarranted and that it should be
fought in court.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's anyone working here who thinks there's
much validity to the case,'' said Dick Craddock, manager of
Microsoft's Mac Internet Explorer group. ``That may be the party
line, but it's also the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an expected thing,'' said Jon DeVaan, senior vice
president of the company's consumer group. ``The mood here is
actually pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft received a vote of support from the 150 or so members
of the Windows-loving San Francisco PC Users Group.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any reason to break up the company,'' said Butler
Crittenden, the group's president. ``I don't see that they're using
any competitive strategies that are different from other
companies.''
</P>
<P>
   While agreeing that consumers in general do need protection from
the greedy clutches of big business, he said antitrust officials
chose the wrong target in going after Microsoft.
</P>
<P>
   ``I personally need to be protected from the pharmaceutical
industry,'' Crittenden said. ``I'm diabetic and the price of
insulin keeps going up.''
</P>
<P>
   At the CompUSA outlet in downtown San Francisco, restaurant
consultant Lance Feldman was unfazed by word of the Justice
Department's tactics as he added a $229.99 copy of Microsoft's
Office 2000 to his shopping basket.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems like they're hitting Microsoft with a lot,'' he said.
``Instead of regulating them over the years, they're going for a
quick fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Feldman, like others interviewed, said he was more worried about
the impact this would have on Microsoft's share price than on the
company itself.
</P>
<P>
   Shoppers at the Microsoft retail outlet in San Francisco's
Metreon center were amusing themselves with all the cool gadgets on
display. Uncertainty about the company's future wasn't much of a
consideration.
</P>
<P>
   Shari Wildschutte of Concord, Calif., was one of the few with a
strong position on the breakup question. ``There need to be
sanctions,'' she said. ``Too few people own too much of
everything.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Wildschutte said she has no particular beef
with Microsoft. She feels pretty much the same about all big
corporations.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Tyde, founder of the Bay Area Linux Users Group, which
promotes use of the Linux operating system, said that ``it's about
time'' government authorities moved to curb Microsoft's predatory
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it doesn't matter whether the government busts up
Microsoft,'' he said. ``Linux will overtake Windows in the long run
anyway.''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, this is pretty much what Bill Gates has been saying,
that the tech market is competitive because there's always going to
be someone coming along with a new idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't necessarily disagree with that,'' Tyde said.
</P>
<P>
   Raines Cohen, co-founder of the Berkeley, Calif., Mac Users
Group, offered a similarly contradictory perspective.
</P>
<P>
   He said a breakup of Microsoft will punish the company ``for its
past behavior.'' But at the same time, he observed that development
of new applications for the Macintosh operating system has never
been stronger.
</P>
<P>
   ``In my heart, I support the breakup,'' Cohen said. ``But as a
consumer advocate, I'm cautious about introducing any change into a
dynamic market.''
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps 5-year-old Adam Lundblad summed it up best. While
playing a computer game at Metreon's Microsoft store, he only shook
his head when asked what would be gained by the Justice
Department's proposed action.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   E-mail David Lazarus at  &LR; davidlaz(AT)sfgate.com &LR; .
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
