<BODY>
 AM-NYT-BUDGET  
(lh) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR SUNDAY AMs &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, April 30:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-VILLAGES (Khanh Hau, Vietnam) _ Vietnamese villages are
insular places. They absorb the pressures of history, adapt to them
and go on very much as before. In an often-repeated saying, the
mandate of the emperor stops at the village gate. ``Rural
communities have always been the real areas of negotiation,'' said
Shaun K. Malarney, a scholar of Vietnamese village life. The
history of Vietnam is not just the history of great national
events, he said; it is thousands of histories of individual
villages. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   SOUTHASIA-TERROR (Undated) _ The State Department has for the
first time identified South Asia as a major hub of international
terrorism, accusing Pakistan, a traditional U.S. ally, and
especially Afghanistan of providing safe haven and support to
international terrorist groups. By Judith Miller.
</P>
<P>
   CAMBODIA-TRIBUNAL (Ho Chi Minh City, Vietnam) _ Sen. John Kerry
said Saturday that Cambodia and the United Nations had reached a
compromise that would allow the creation of an international court
to try former leaders of the Khmer Rouge. By Seth Mydans.
</P>
<P>
   NKOREA-ECON (Seoul, South Korea) _ For a decade, experts have
watched North Korea suffer through one of the worst economic slides
of recent history and wondered when the country would finally
collapse. In the last year or so, though, as North Korea's
still-small modern sector has risen impressively, the question
seems to have shifted. Now people wonder who will win the horse
race between a dying Stalinist economy and a sprouting new one that
represents the country's first tentative steps into global
capitalism. By Howard W. French.
</P>
<P>
   HUMAN-RIGHTS-FORUM (Geneva) _ After six weeks of review, debate
and bargaining at the annual session of the main U.N. human rights
forum, which ended on Friday, China emerged free of condemnation of
its human rights record while Russia and others were chastised. By
Elizabeth Olson.
</P>
<P>
   MOZAMBIQUE-REBUILD (Durban, South Africa) _ The angry waters
have receded in Mozambique but thousands of people remain homeless.
The floods swept away schools and clinics, crops and cattle. And
nearly two months after the torrential rains ravaged the country,
the painful work of rebuilding is only just beginning. By Rachel L.
Swarns.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-JAPAN (St. Petersburg, Russia) _ In their first meeting
as the new leaders of Russia and Japan, President Vladimir Putin
and Prime Minister Yoshiro Mori pledged Saturday to meet often,
call each other by their nicknames and to try to conclude a
long-sought peace treaty by the end of the year. Such a treaty
would formally end decades of antagonism between the two countries
over a group of islands seized by Russia at the end of World War
II. By Patrick E. Tyler.
</P>
<P>
   KOSOVO-U.N. (Pristina, Kosovo) _ The eight-member delegation
from the U.N. Security Council, which came to Kosovo to give a
stern message to all sides to stop the violence and to urge on the
U.N. mission here, wound up its visit Saturday somewhat muted by
the complexities on the ground. By Carlotta Gall.
</P>
<P>
   RUBIN-PROFILE (Washington) _ During nearly eight years at the
side of the first woman to serve as secretary of state, James Rubin
fulfilled a number of roles: friend, adviser, protege, gossip
buddy, fashion consultant and self-described ``intellectual mate.''
Now, at 40, he is leaving Washington behind to move to London with
another high-powered woman, his wife, Christiane Amanpour, the CNN
foreign correspondent, who gave birth to their son a month ago. By
Christopher Marquis.
</P>
<P>
   CHECHNYA-GROZNY (Grozny, Russia) _ Now that the Russian
authorities have captured Grozny, they do not seem to know what to
do with it. The cost of rebuilding the ravaged city appears to be
more than the Kremlin is prepared to bear, especially since it
still faces a formidable task of restoring the rest of the battered
republic. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS (San Francisco) _ While lawyers and
regulators in Washington ponder the fate of Microsoft Corp.,
Anthony Troy stands in a computer store here, struggling with the
conflict the case inspires in ordinary consumers. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT-ASSESS (Undated) _ An analysis of the economic
arguments in support of the Justice Department's case.
</P>
<P>
   CALIF-RACIAL-PROFILING (Los Angeles) _ Gov. Gray Davis of
California has agreed to support legislation outlawing racial
profiling by police officers, though the bill no longer contains
what critics say is a crucial component for determining the extent
of the problem.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-ADVISER (Washington) _ Donald L. Evans has almost always
been present at the pivotal junctures in George W. Bush's life, an
important witness to the evolution of both the man and the
candidate and an integral part of his political campaigns. But
while Evans has attracted public notice over the last year solely
for his work as Bush's national finance chairman, his role is much
broader, deeper and less tidily defined than that. By Frank Bruni.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-GORE-SURPLUS (Washington) _ This is the first presidential
election in memory where the candidates have a budget surplus to
discuss, not a deficit, and their sharply contradictory approaches
on how to use it are perhaps the biggest differences between Vice
President Al Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas. By Adam Clymer.
</P>
<P>
   NC-REPUBS (Asheboro, N.C.) _ As is so often the case in
Republican politics these days, the race for this state's
Republican nomination for governor has become a charge toward the
right, with candidates showing little restraint _ and often little
concern for the facts _ in painting each other as closet liberals.
By Kevin Sack.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS (Undated) _ For Illinois governor, an
explanatory tour; Dust swirls in battle for a key House seat;
Oregon initiatives torment governor; Adding up the score: Bush 308,
Gore 160. B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   PRIVACY-LEGISLATION (Washington) _ The Clinton administration is
preparing legislation to protect the financial privacy of consumers
by limiting how banks, insurers and other companies share sensitive
consumer information. By Stephen Labaton.
</P>
<P>
   MEDICAL-RESEARCH (Washington) _ Medical researchers who receive
federal money often flout a federal law that requires them to
analyze the effects of new drugs and treatments on women, three new
studies have found. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; COLUMNS &LR;  (Moving in ``k'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   DOWD-COLUMN (Washington) _ McCain can't get no satisfaction. By
Maureen Dowd.
</P>
<P>
   KRUGMAN-COLUMN (Undated) _ A clean break or none at all. By Paul
Krugman.
</P>
