<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 11:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0893 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT &LR;      04-29 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS OF THE WEEK IN SUMMARY 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Monopoly Medicine
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's future? Split in two, if the government gets its
way. The Justice Department and states suing Microsoft told a
federal judge those are the appropriate remedies for a company the
court has ruled is a ``predatory'' monopolist.
</P>
<P>
   The government proposal calls for Microsoft's Windows operating
system to be placed in one company, while the other company would
get the rest including the Word word processor, Excel spreadsheet
and the MSN Internet service. There are also a smorgasbord of curbs
on Microsoft's conduct that would last three years. And the two
companies cannot get back together for a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The issue is now in the lap of Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson.
But appeals could take years. Microsoft calls the plan ``extreme,
reckless and not justified by the evidence in the case.'' Two of
the 19 states in the suit apparently agreed, declining to support
the breakup proposal.
</P>
<P>
   The Never-Ending Argument
</P>
<P>
   The abortion debate has lately been dominated by efforts to ban
``dilation and extraction,'' a late-term procedure that abortion
opponents call ``partial-birth abortion.'' Nebraska and two dozen
other states have banned it, but a Supreme Court argument last week
on the Nebraska law produced strong hints that all such bans may be
unconstitutional.
</P>
<P>
   Most justices appeared to agree with a lower court that the ban
is so vaguely worded as to put doctors at risk of prosecution for
performing any sort of late-term abortions, even constitutionally
protected second-trimester ones, which occur well before the point
of fetal viability.
</P>
<P>
   That Whining Sound Of Lost Money and Lives
</P>
<P>
   Responding to a study showing malaria is a major impediment to
African development, the World Bank announced that it would pledge
$500 million toward the eradication of the disease. The
announcement came in Abuja, Nigeria, at the first international
summit on the disease, which kills 3,000 Africans a day, most of
them children.
</P>
<P>
   The study of 27 African economies from 1965 to 1990, done by
Harvard's Center for International Development and the London
School of Hygiene and Tropical Medicine, concluded that sub-Saharan
Africa's gross domestic product would now be $400 billion instead
of $300 billion if malaria had been eliminated in 1965.
</P>
<P>
   The first line of defense is mosquito nets dipped in
insecticide, a fact which Jeffrey Sachs of the Harvard Center for
International Development, said might induce Americans to
contribute more money to cure the disease. ``Bed nets,'' he pointed
out, ``aren't going to end up in bank accounts in Switzerland.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington Whispers
</P>
<P>
   Secretary of State Madeleine Albright ordered an overhaul of
security measures at the State Department after a laptop computer
containing sensitive files on arms proliferation vanished from her
intelligence bureau.
</P>
<P>
   Republican lawmakers scheduled hearings into a series of
security lapses at the department, including the discovery of an
eavesdropping device in a conference room _ which resulted in the
expulsion of a Russian diplomat _ and the 1998 theft of documents
by a man in a tweed coat within view of Albright's office.
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to protecting government secrets, she said, ``99
percent is a failing grade.''
</P>
<P>
   (MORE)  &QL; 
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1143EDT &QL; 
