<TEXT>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, April 30, have moved.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   KEY-STATES-REVIEW (Undated) _ Every presidential candidate at
this stage of the game swears he will fight for every state and
every vote in this richly diverse country. But the ugly little
truth in presidential politics, which no candidate dares
acknowledge, is that some states are more important than others,
not just because they are big (with a lot of electoral votes) but
because they are up for grabs. As the primary season was dominated
by New Hampshire, the general election campaign will likely be
ruled by an arc of big industrial states, including Pennsylvania,
Ohio, Michigan, Illinois and Missouri. By Robin Toner.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `p' category)
</P>
<P>
   FALUN-GONG-REVIEW (Shanghai) _ Surely one of the more unlikely
foreign policy problems ever to have afflicted the ruling Chinese
Communist Party must be the one caused by its brutal suppression of
Falun Gong, a spiritual movement that now claims millions of
adherents. Amidst the moral revulsion against the Chinese
government's actions, however, little has been written that might
help anyone understand why so many people feel Falun Gong is worth
fighting and dying for, and little is understood in the West about
those aspects of the movement, or cult, that might suggest that its
followers are misled and their leader deluded, or even a fraud. By
Craig S. Smith.
</P>
<P>
   (Moved in `i' category)
</P>
<P>
   Moving in `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-REFERENCES-REVIEW (Undated) _ The latest skirmish over
the separation of church and state has its roots in 1959, when the
Ohio legislature approved ``With God, all things are possible,' as
the state's official motto. It had been the idea of a 12-year-old
Cincinnati boy who was concerned that Ohio was the only state
without a motto. By Jane Fritsch.
</P>
<P>
   AUTO-ADS-REVIEW (Detroit) _ The Auto industry's spending on ads
is enormous _ $1 in every $7 of all advertising spending in this
country. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   GAMBLING-REVIEW (Undated) _ By now the argument over gambling
has become academic; its appeal shows no sign of abating. Granted,
gambling may not be the most edifying of pastimes; gamblers could
assuredly broaden themselves by reading best sellers and watching
wrestling instead of whiling away the hours in clockless rooms. On
the other hand, whose business is it if adults find pleasure in
throwing away their money? By Walter Goodman.
</P>
<P>
   NIXON-VIETNAM-REVIEW (Undated) _ Last Thursday the National
Archives, as part of its routine declassification of government
records, released thousands of secret documents from President
Richard Nixon's National Security Council, which was led by his
national security adviser, Henry Kissinger. Many deal with the war
in Vietnam, which ended 25 years ago Sunday. The records capture
the sulfurous scent of anger and desperation at the White House and
the U.S. Embassy in Saigon as the war went wrong, at home and
abroad. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ The news of the week in review.
</P>
<P>
   Moving in `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   YUGOSLAVIA-REVIEW (Belgrade) _ Twenty years after the death of
Tito, Yugo-nostalgia wafts through the remnant of the Yugoslavia he
created. And everywhere here, despite the continuing sway of
Slobodan Milosevic, there is a strong feeling of fin-de-regime,
that another era of personal rule is coming to a close. Today, in
this incredibly shrinking country, when even tiny Montenegro talks
of independence, there is a continuing sense of bewilderment,
poverty and farce, of helplessness as the Milosevic era goes
through its lengthy death throes. By Steven Erlanger.
</P>
<P>
   WORLD-TRAVEL-REVIEW (Undated) _ So-called special interest
travel, encompassing adventure travel, ecotourism and journeys to
exotic locales, is the fastest-growing segment of the $519 billion
U.S. travel market, according to industry estimates. By Joe
Sharkey.
</P>
<P>
   ZIMBABWE-REVIEW (Durban, South Africa) _ Over radio waves and on
television screens, the conflict often appears stark and simple:
The battle in Zimbabwe, it seems, is a battle between blacks and
whites. The truth is that the struggle in Zimbabwe is less about
race and land than it is about one governing party's struggle to
keep its virtual monopoly of power. For while President Mugabe
rages about the white enemy, his supporters have quietly recognized
that ordinary blacks pose the more potent political threat. By
Rachel L. Swarns.
</P>
</TEXT>
