<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WEATHER-MAP-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER 
</HEADLINE>
  (Editors: The following text accompanies the weather map for
Sunday, April 30, sent to computer graphics clients of The New York
Times News Service. For information call: 888-603-1036.) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
<TEXT>
<P>
   NATIONAL FORECAST
</P>
<P>
   Clusters of thunderstorms and areas of torrential rain will
plague a large part of the central and southern Plains Sunday and
Monday. A slow disturbance moving east from the southern Rockies
will draw abundant moisture north from central Texas to Kansas and
western Missouri. Rain amounts of 1 to 3 inches will be common by
early Monday, resulting in local flooding. Severe thunderstorms and
a few tornadoes will form later Sunday from the Texas panhandle to
Kansas where a cold front will lift the humid air. In the wake of
the front, showers and some mountain snow will linger in the
central Rockies.
</P>
<P>
   Clouds and a few sprinkles will linger over northern New
England, but increasing northerly breezes will deliver dry, cool
air to most of the Northeast. Farther west, sprawling high pressure
will promote mild and dry conditions with light winds from the Ohio
Valley to the Southeast.
</P>
<P>
   FOCUS: FIRE AND WIND
</P>
<P>
   Gusty winds have been hampering firefighters battling a major
blaze that is sweeping across the Tonto National Forest in Arizona.
The pressure difference between high pressure over the Northwest
and a developing storm system over the Southwest has been
responsible for the strong breezes blowing across much of the
interior West. But, fires also generate wind. The contrast between
the hot air near the flames and the surrounding cooler air results
in complex, turbulent wind flows that can further fan the flames.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1153EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 12:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0900 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-BONANNO-MAFIA-ART-110     04-29 1166
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BONANNO-MAFIA-ART-1100-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A MAFIA FAMILY'S SECOND WIND 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By SELWYN RAAB    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than a decade ago, the Bonanno crime family _ once one of
the nation's most feared Mafia organizations _ was galloping toward
extinction. Undermined by deadly rivalries and by federal
investigations, the family was shunned by the other New York Mafia
families as a fractious, unreliable partner.
</P>
<P>
   The Bonannos' ranks and power declined so sharply in the late
1980s and early 1990s that the Federal Bureau of Investigation
disbanded a squad whose sole job had been to focus on the family's
leaders and criminal operations.
</P>
<P>
   But aided by the FBI's inattention, the Bonanno mob has revived
to become one of the most potent and dangerous Mafia groups in the
New York region, organized crime experts say.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement officials grudgingly attribute the recovery to
Joseph C. Massino, who they say gained control of the family in
1993 after serving a prison term for racketeering and extortion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Joe Massino learned from the mistakes of other bosses who
unwisely attracted attention to themselves,'' said Lewis D.
Schiliro, who retired this month as assistant FBI director in
charge of the New York office. ``He is the undisputed leader of the
family, a low-key guy who avoids the spotlight, who has brought
back discipline and order.''
</P>
<P>
   The man law enforcement officials contend is responsible for the
Bonannos' comeback says his accusers have it all wrong. ``I did my
time; I paid my dues,'' Massino, 57, said in a telephone interview.
``They can claim whatever they want, but it's not true.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't believe there is such a thing as the Mafia,'' he
added. ``A bunch of Italian guys go out to eat, and they say it's
Mafia.''
</P>
<P>
   According to New York Police Department intelligence reports,
Massino's success in rebuilding the empire inspired other mobsters
to nickname him the Ear. Dennis R. Hawkins, chief of investigations
for the Brooklyn district attorney's office, said detectives
believe the nickname attests to Massino's gift for keeping his ear
to the ground to detect possible danger.
</P>
<P>
   And his hearing seems to be acute. Massino is described by
investigators as an electronic wizard keenly aware of the most
advanced listening devices used by agents to eavesdrop on Mafia
figures.
</P>
<P>
   Based on electronic eavesdropping and Mafia informers, federal
and state investigators say that although the Genovese family
remains the largest and most dangerous mob organization in the
region and the country, the Bonannos have replaced the Gambino
family as the second most powerful of the five Mafia groups in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   A heavyset man, 5 feet 10 inches tall and weighing about 200
pounds, Massino lives with his wife, Josephine, in a modest home in
Howard Beach, Queens. It is about a block from where his close
friend John J. Gotti, the boss of the Gambino family, lived before
he was sentenced to life imprisonment in 1992 for murder and
racketeering.
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say Massino is often at King Caterers, a company
at 60 Smith St. in suburban Farmingdale, Long Island, that provides
sandwiches, hot dishes and snacks for street vendors, and at the
Casablanca Restaurant at 62-15 60th Lane in Maspeth, in the borough
of Queens. Investigators suspect that these businesses are his main
spots for discreet meetings with Bonanno lieutenants.
</P>
<P>
   Reached by telephone at King Caterers, Massino said he was a
legitimate businessman, working both as a consultant for that
company and, in his spare time, as a manager of real estate
properties, including the Casablanca building.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on the street for seven years and on parole for
five,'' he said. ``If I did anything, wouldn't I have been
pinched?''
</P>
<P>
   Investigators say that Massino has tried to insulate himself
from possible indictments by meeting with only a few top aides who
relay his orders and through careful screening of new members.
Under his leadership, no defectors have implicated him in crimes,
even as mob turncoats have provided crucial testimony in the
convictions of the leaders and numerous soldiers in other families,
especially in the Gambino, Colombo and Lucchese groups.
</P>
<P>
   As the power of other Mafia families withered in the late 1990s,
Massino increased the Bonanno ranks of active ``made'' soldiers and
capos, or captains, to about 110 from a low of 80 in the early
1990s, investigators said. A ``made'' or inducted soldier takes the
blood oath of ``omerta,'' swearing loyalty and obedience to the
Mafia under penalty of death for betrayal.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and police investigators maintain that Salvatore Vitale,
52, of Dix Hills, N.Y., the brother-in-law of Massino, is the
family underboss and his closest confidant.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Spero, 71, of Brooklyn, who law enforcement officials
say is the Bonanno consigliere or counselor _ the
third-highest-ranking leader _ is facing federal racketeering and
murder charges. But the officials think that even if Spero is found
guilty, his conviction will probably not be a significant blow to
Massino. The investigators said that Spero, who has pleaded not
guilty, had already been replaced by Anthony Urso, 63, of Franklin
Square, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel J. Castleman, who is in charge of organized crime
investigations for the Manhattan district attorney's office, said
that the Bonannos were very strong right now. ``They are the only
family with an undisputed leadership and without serious internal
struggles,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Bonanno gangsters have long been the area's premier mob
traffickers in narcotics, according to the authorities. One crew is
composed mainly of Sicilian-born members, known as Zips, Sicilian
slang for rural residents and farmers. Investigators say the crew
maintains close ties with Mafia clans in its homeland and that it
is believed to handle much of the family's heroin deals.
</P>
<P>
   But the family's largest booty, law enforcement officials said,
comes from illegal bookmaking on sports and numbers gambling and
from loan-sharking in Brooklyn and in Queens, where most of its
operations are centered.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's their bread and butter,'' said Schiliro, the former FBI
official. FBI and police investigators estimate that gambling and
loan-sharking rings net the family more than $20 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mob relies on bookmaking and loan-sharking because it's
low risk and the public thinks these are victimless crimes,'' said
Frederick Martens, former executive director of the Pennsylvania
Crime Commission, who teaches criminology at the College of New
Jersey in Trenton. ``It's easy money and inevitably will be used as
feeder money to set up fronts and to buy into legitimate
businesses, especially in the construction and the garbage-removal
industries.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   For decades, the crime family reaped millions of dollars a year
from extortion, fraud, phantom jobs and other corrupt alliances
with union officials, but convictions of Bonanno leaders in the
late 1980s and early 1990' are thought to have shattered most of
those labor rackets.
</P>
<P>
   With that income gone, the Bonannos were one of the first Mafia
crime families to cash in on the Wall Street bull market in the
late 1990s, the authorities said. In the last three years, Frank
Coppa and Frank Lino, who the authorities say are Bonanno capos,
have been indicted in multimillion-dollar stock market swindles;
Lino has been convicted, and Coppa, who has pleaded not guilty, is
awaiting trial in Brooklyn.
</P>
<P>
   The family's roots and its name date back to 1931, when Joseph
C. Bonanno was anointed boss of one of the five Mafia families
established that year. Bonanno ruled for 30 years until he was
forced into retirement in 1966 after a power struggle with bosses
in other families.
</P>
<P>
   A later Bonanno kingpin, Carmine Galante, who had been convicted
of heroin trafficking, was gunned down in Joe and Mary's Restaurant
in Bushwick, Brooklyn, in 1979 on orders from rival bosses who
feared he wanted to move in on their rackets.
</P>
<P>
   Galante's murder ignited a bloody purge in the early 1980s.
Massino was then a capo who sided with the winning faction led by
Philip Rastelli, investigators and federal prosecutors say.
Rastelli's reign ended with his conviction in 1986 for labor
racketeering, and the gang was left rudderless for seven years.
</P>
<P>
   The Bonanno fortunes were further crippled by a celebrated
undercover investigation. An FBI agent, Joseph D. Pistone, using
the name Donnie Brasco, was accepted into a Bonanno crew. The agent
surfaced in 1981, and his investigation led to a dozen convictions.
</P>
<P>
   Police and FBI intelligence reports say the other major mob
families became alarmed by the Bonannos' bloody feuds and the
family's infiltration by the FBI; those groups branded the Bonannos
as reckless outlaws, or Mafia pariahs. Until the mid-1990s, the
other families banned criminal collaborations with Bonanno members.
The family was ousted from the Commission, the New York mob's
version of a board of directors, which resolves disputes among
families and sets policies, the investigators said.
</P>
<P>
   Massino's only conviction was in 1986, in the middle of the
Bonanno family's decline. He was found guilty on federal charges in
Brooklyn that he had extorted payoffs from moving and storage
companies.
</P>
<P>
   Schiliro and other Mafia experts say the family is now welcomed
as a partner by other mobsters. Investigators say that Massino took
two measures that bolstered the family's security and discipline:
he reined in ``cowboys,'' younger members who commit violent crimes
like drug-related murders and robberies that attract scrutiny, and
he prohibited capos from using small storefront clubs as regular
meeting places because they invite easy surveillance.
</P>
<P>
   Current and former FBI officials said monitoring of the Bonanno
family was minimized in the late 1980s because the gang's decline
seemed irreversible. Instead, they said, agents concentrated on the
formidable Gambino and Genovese families.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can't blame the FBI,'' Martens, the former head of the
Pennsylvania Crime Commission, said. ``Every law enforcement agency
has limited resources, and you have to react to the most serious
problems.''
</P>
<P>
   In fact, crackdowns by federal and state agencies in the
mid-1990s are credited with weakening the Gambino and Genovese
families, culminating in the convictions of Gotti, the Gambino
boss, and Vincent Gigante, the Genovese chief.
</P>
<P>
   Current and former FBI officials acknowledged that it was a
mistake in 1988 to merge the Bonanno squad with a unit responsible
for investigating the Colombo family. Separate squads for each
family were re-established in 1996, and officials say the Bonanno
family is now being actively investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The lesson to be learned is that you cannot de-emphasize
vigilance on any of the families,'' said J. Bruce Mouw, a former
FBI agent who was in charge of the Gambino and Bonanno squads in
New York. ``All are capable of comebacks.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
