<HEADER>
A0902 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-29 0750
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: POLITICAL DIVAS 2000 
</HEADLINE>
   By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Diva is driven by wants and whims. The Diva
hoards the spotlight. The Diva lets loose when something is Not
Pleasing. The Diva Will Survive.
</P>
<P>
   Diana Ross or John McCain?
</P>
<P>
   You decide.
</P>
<P>
   Senator McCain said he was going to drop out of the presidential
race. But he hasn't quite gotten around to it yet. He's still
clutching the microphone and waiting for his closeup. And he's
still scuffling with W., trying to out-macho, out-patriot and
out-moralize the man who beat him.
</P>
<P>
   There was John McCain on Thursday on the front page of The New
York Times, shown on a tour of the Hanoi Hilton with his son
(trailed by a brace of Washington pundits), while poor W.
languished on A24 with his big speech calling for civility.
</P>
<P>
   There was John McCain on Friday on ``The Today Show,'' telling
Matt Lauer what it felt like to be beaten with bamboo sticks and
bayoneted by his captors. He, his wife, Cindy, and their
13-year-old, Jack, were treated to the trip to Vietnam by NBC.
Whass-uppp with that? Taking freebies from a broadcaster he helps
regulate as Commerce Committee chairman doesn't exactly square with
his McClean image, even if the Senate Ethics Committee did OK the
trip.
</P>
<P>
   There he was again this weekend, volunteering to help out his
pal Rudy Giuliani by taking over his gigs on the Sunday talk shows.
</P>
<P>
   In Vietnam for the 25th anniversary of the fall of Saigon, he
got embroiled in two diplomatic kerfuffles.
</P>
<P>
   He fell into an escalating war of words with the Vietnamese
Foreign Ministry, after he said ``I think the wrong guys won,''
trashed his captors for killing some of his comrades, and
criticized the Vietnamese for carrying hammer-and-sickle banners.
</P>
<P>
   He also got involved at Ho Chi Minh airport when the Vietnamese
_ perhaps in retaliation _ refused to let a member of his
entourage, Tucker Carlson of The Weekly Standard and Talk magazine,
leave the country, claiming his exit visa was not in order.
</P>
<P>
   McCain, who stayed behind for five years the first time the
Vietnamese would not let his comrades leave with him, argued for
two hours this time before leaving Tucker in the hands of the U.S.
Embassy and flying off with the rest of his group. (Tucker was
sprung later that day.) ``Straight Talk Express'' becomes
``Midnight Express''?
</P>
<P>
   The senator seems to have Sudden Attention Withdrawal Disorder.
In 1960, Thomas Dewey wrote to Richard Nixon, telling him, if he
lost, not to make important decisions for six months because his
thinking would be so distorted. Nixon passed along the advice to
George Bush in '92. But McDiva didn't get the advice.
</P>
<P>
   Ten days ago, the senator offered a melodramatic mea culpa on
the Confederate flag, confessing he really did think it should come
down. It was a slap at W., who is still stuck with the old
mealy-mouthed, pandering position that it is best if the state
decides.
</P>
<P>
   W. said last week he wanted to ``end the arms race of anger''
between the two parties. But he can't even stop it in his own.
McCain threw a hissy fit when he thought W. was maneuvering him
into a position where he'd have to say _ eyeball to eyeball _
whether he wants to be considered for VP. He doesn't want to seem
selfish if he refuses, or a supplicant if he agrees.
</P>
<P>
   He resents feeling manipulated or patronized _ especially by the
princeling. ``It's not a character trait of John's to say `yes,
sir, no, sir' to anybody,'' says a McCain adviser.
</P>
<P>
   Even away from the pressures of the campaign, he is too quickly
prickly. In Vietnam, when he heard about a Robert Novak column that
began ``Gov. George W. Bush's advisers consider his May 9 meeting
in Pittsburgh with Sen. John McCain to be like a visit to an
incompetent dentist: all pain and little satisfaction,'' he
threatened to cancel the summit, insisting the Bushies treat him
like an equal and bargain on policy issues.
</P>
<P>
   As in other respects, the Republicans are becoming like
Democrats. Republicans used to just fall into line behind their
leader after the primaries. Now they have those Who Dissed Whom,
Who Gets What, psyche-stroking reconciliation sessions, which
reached a hilarious apogee with Jesse Jackson and Michael Dukakis
in 1988.
</P>
<P>
   John McCain hasn't turned into Jesse Jackson yet. But if he
remains prickly and unassuageable, the question may begin to
ricochet, with greater and greater impatience: ``What does John
want?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
