<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: STRIP THE ALPHABET FROM THE SOUP 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Fight is expected to begin about 11:30 p.m. EDT; story may be
updated.) 
 By DAVE ANDERSON    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   As soon as Lennox Lewis steps into the ring at Madison Square
Garden on Saturday night against Michael Grant, what has been his
undisputed world heavyweight championship will suddenly be
disputed.
</P>
<P>
   Because Lewis has not defended the title against the World
Boxing Association's No. 1 contender, the uncelebrated John Ruiz,
Lewis will be automatically stripped of the WBA crown.
</P>
<P>
   Against the 6-foot-7 Grant, the 6-5 Lewis will be defending only
two-thirds of boxing's wacky world, those areas governed, however
immodestly or improperly, by the World Boxing Council and the
International Boxing Federation.
</P>
<P>
   But boxers should no longer let themselves be subject to these
three self-styled sanctioning bodies, which exist primarily because
their usually different champions and rankings provide fake
credibility for promoters and television networks.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of letting the alphabet-soup organizations strip the
title from boxers, the boxers should strip the alphabet from the
soup.
</P>
<P>
   Boxers, managers and promoters should just ignore the
proclamations of the WBA, the WBC, the IBF and any of the lesser
alphabetic sanctioning bodies that create ``championship'' fights
out of paper pronouncements instead of out of punches in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   The line of succession could define the true champion in each
weight division, not the WBA, WBC or IBF edicts. Especially an IBF
edict.
</P>
<P>
   In all the Lewis-Grant hype last week, maybe you haven't noticed
that on the other side of the Lincoln Tunnel, a much more important
bout has begun. The IBF is on trial on bribery, racketeering,
conspiracy and tax evasion charges in federal court in Newark,
N.J., where C. Douglas Beavers, the IBF's ratings chairman from
1983 to 1998, is singing.
</P>
<P>
   Threatened with prosecution, Beavers began cooperating with
federal agents in 1997; he secretly recorded more than a hundred
conversations with Robert W. Lee Sr., the IBF president, and other
officials regarding bribes for higher rankings. Among the alleged
$338,000 in payoffs, according to Beavers, were several from the
promoter Don King.
</P>
<P>
   King, one of 14 unindicted co-conspirators, has denied paying
bribes to the IBF, but on the witness stand, Beavers recalled the
time he refused Lee's order to return Beavers' $5,000 share of a
King payoff.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Don King's a street guy and wouldn't ask for the money
back,'' Beavers testified last Tuesday. ``If you're running an
illegal business, you don't ask for bribes back. What's he going to
do, sue me?''
</P>
<P>
   Beavers, who said one reason he didn't return the $5,000 was
that he had already spent it, also told of collecting $100,000 from
the promoter Cedric Kushner, an unindicted co-conspirator who has
declined comment.
</P>
<P>
   If the IBF, meaning primarily Lee and his son Robby, is found
guilty of corruption, its credibility and authority will be gone.
Boxers, managers and promoters would no longer need to abide by its
ratings, no longer need to pay sanctioning fees.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, boxers, managers and promoters never needed to do
that. The IBF (based in East Orange, N.J.), as well as the WBA
(based in Venezuela) and the WBC (based in Mexico) have ruled the
boxing rankings only because nobody else has bothered with them.
</P>
<P>
   That's why boxing has always been so corruptible. Nobody is
really in charge except, ostensibly, the WBA, the WBC and the IBF,
all of which simply assumed their authority, like dictators do. And
until this IBF trial, nobody has challenged their authority.
</P>
<P>
   By its nature, boxing has never attracted seminarians. In a
sense, nobody can break any laws in boxing because, to a great
extent, there are no laws except for the jungle law: survival of
the fittest.
</P>
<P>
   But if the IBF is found to have broken the nation's laws
regarding bribery and racketeering, then boxers, as well as
managers and promoters, will no longer need to abide by the IBF
edicts. Maybe they will also realize that they no longer need to
abide by the WBA or WBC edicts.
</P>
<P>
   At least financially, the Home Box Office promoters have begun
to ignore those edicts in some of its contracts.
</P>
<P>
   ``We told each of our elite champions,'' said Seth Abraham of
HBO, alluding to Lewis, Oscar De La Hoya, Roy Jones Jr. and Prince
Naseem Hamed, ``that you're bigger than any of the governing
bodies' belts, that as long as you do not lose in the ring, we will
not pay you one penny, one shilling, one farthing less. If you're
stripped of a title, your HBO contract will not be affected.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the `championship' belts,'' he added, ``the `jewels' in
them are glass and the belt is plastic.''
</P>
<P>
   In other words, the belts are as fake as all the alphabet-soup
sanctioning bodies. And as unnecessary.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
