<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 12:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0911 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-CHECHNYA-GROZNY-ART-8     04-29 1193
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CHECHNYA-GROZNY-ART-860&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GROZNY REMAINS A MASS OF RUBBLE WHERE NOTHING WORKS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Map is being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   GROZNY, Russia _ Galina Kuzmichova endured the battle of Grozny.
And now that the fighting is over she has done her bit to restore
the Russian Orthodox church here, one of the city's foremost
symbols of Russian culture.
</P>
<P>
   She has cleaned the icons and swept away the debris. But the
church is still a ruin, and the Russian authorities have yet to
take any steps to rebuild it.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin billed the capture of Grozny as a psychological and
military turning point in its battle with Islamic rebels seeking an
independent state in Chechnya. And President-elect Vladimir Putin
vowed to rebuild the Chechen capital when he made a surprise visit
here during the election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   But Grozny appears to have been left on its own.
</P>
<P>
   The laborers who toil in the spring sun to repair the train
station have not been paid for two months. Teachers have
refurbished a school without government support. The pace of the
reconstruction is so glacial that those who fled the city during
the war complain that there is still not much to return to. Those
who hid in their basements and waited for the shooting to stop have
discovered that there was little reward for staying.
</P>
<P>
   Viseet Vakhayev, 36, escaped with his wife and three children
during the fighting. Since the Russian flag was hoisted over
Grozny, he has repeatedly visited the city to see if it is feasible
for his family to come back. And Friday he turned away with
disappointment.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have cleaned up the streets a bit, but there is no effort
to restore the city,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Street after street remains lined by rubble and bombed-out
buildings. Many people are still living in their basements or
temporary shelters. Water is trucked in, and there is no
electricity.
</P>
<P>
   With a population of more than 400,000, Grozny was once the
largest Soviet city in the northern Caucasus. It was established in
1818 as a Russian fortress. In February, the Russians suffered
enormous casualties to seize the city, which has a large ethnic
Russian population.
</P>
<P>
   But now that the Russian authorities have captured Grozny, they
do not seem to know what to do with it. Russian authorities have
required residents to register, but many are still in the process
of doing so. Thousands of people live in the city, though nobody
seems to know exactly how many, and the streets are largely empty.
</P>
<P>
   So far, the cost of rebuilding the ravaged city appear to be
more than the Kremlin is prepared to bear, especially since it
still faces a formidable task of restoring the rest of the battered
republic.
</P>
<P>
   Even keeping order in Grozny is not easy. The city is ringed by
Russian checkpoints, and only residents with Grozny credentials are
allowed to pass. Fifteen miles to the northwest, a base is being
prepared for the 42nd Army Division, part of the Kremlin's plan to
set up a permanent garrison to control the republic.
</P>
<P>
   Despite these precautions, however, rebel fighters have begun to
sneak back into Grozny. Russian military officials say there are as
many as 400 militants, including 50 snipers, in the city. Shooting
often erupts at night. And Russian militia keep their guns trained
on the city's rooftops when they escort journalists through the
city.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stay at our command posts much of the time, and when we go
into the city we never go without our armored personnel carriers,''
said Roman, a 19-year-old member of the Russian militia from the
Krasnodar. His unit was dispatched to Grozny to police the city.
</P>
<P>
   Putin and Nikolai Koshman, Russia's senior representative in the
region, met in Moscow Friday to discuss the situation in Grozny.
Koshman has been wary of pouring huge sums into Grozny for fear
that it will take money from the reconstruction of the rest of the
republic. But Putin has been loath to write the city off and
promised in March to restore it gradually.
</P>
<P>
   After Friday's meeting, however, it was announced that Grozny
was still too unsafe to open up access to it.
</P>
<P>
   While Russian officials debate what to do, Grozny's residents
have tried to restore a semblance of city life, but they are
getting little support. The streets are still largely deserted, and
a hazy smog hangs over the city, the result of oil wells that have
been set on fire during the war and are still aflame.
</P>
<P>
   Russia's Emergency Ministry has cut back on its food
distributions. It used to provide bowls of kasha to Grozny
residents; now only pensioners and veterans qualify. Children 16
and under get a small ration of bread.
</P>
<P>
   ``Things have not gotten any better,'' said Natalaya Fuznetsova,
13, who was standing near the food lines.
</P>
<P>
   The main city project is to restore train service to Moscow next
month. Russian troops are fixing the railroad tracks. But city
residents rebuilding the station are toiling without pay in the
hope that the train will be an economic lifeline for their city.
</P>
<P>
   ``The railroad is the life of the city,'' said Lisa Batayeva,
the 47-year-old director of the planned Grozny-to-Moscow train.
``So far, the workers have not received anything, but they have
been promised that they will be paid.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The authorities have turned a deaf ear to attempts by some
residents to put the war behind them. Galina Grebtsova, 64, an
ethnic Russian, was fetching firewood in January when a Russian
missile slammed into her house, burying her 24-year-old daughter
under a mound of debris. She is still trying to recover the body.
She has sent several letters to the Emergency Service asking them
to help _ to no avail.
</P>
<P>
   Now that Grozny is in Russian hands, the authorities have sought
to create new symbols of their victory. A Grozny thoroughfare has
been renamed Bislan Gantamirov Street in honor of the former Grozny
mayor who was jailed for embezzlement but released by the Russians
so he could fight with them during the war.
</P>
<P>
   But the Russian authorities seem curiously indifferent to the
old symbols. At the Church of St. Michael, a group of elderly
Russian women were busy preparing for Orthodox Easter, which is to
be celebrated Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   For the believers, it has been a long wait. Before the latest
war, the city was lawless and some Islamic militants had little
tolerance for the Russian clergy. Two of its priests were kidnapped
and one was murdered. A small grave lies in the center of the
church, the tomb of an elderly Russian woman who was stabbed in the
chapel by a marauder.
</P>
<P>
   The roof of the church has been bashed in and its walls have
crumbled. Still, the faithful are hoping the Russian Orthodox
Church officials will dispatch a priest to Grozny so they can hold
an Easter service. And while they wait they are cleaning what they
can.
</P>
<P>
   ``We expect a priest will come, and we have cleaned the icons,''
Kuzmichova said. ``But we have no construction materials.''
</P>
</TEXT>
