<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 12:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0918 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-BIGBUCK-MOVIES-2Takes     04-29 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BIGBUCK-MOVIES-2Takes-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUMMER BLOCKBUSTERS BEGIN ROLLING OUT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
(Also moving in the ``n'' California news file.) &HT;    By DAVID BLOOM 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
 &LR;
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With his new film ``Gladiator'' about to open,
director Ridley Scott has a promise for moviegoers: ``Audiences
ain't seen anything like this before.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a boast heard all around Hollywood these days.
</P>
<P>
   The summer season arrives next weekend with the debut of
``Gladiator,'' the first in a legion of blockbuster pictures, many
of them animated and effects-filled extravaganzas, that will march
into theaters weekend after weekend through Labor Day.
</P>
<P>
   Most of these big films cost more than $100 million to make and
market. But they can bring in several times that, financing a big
portion of the studios' operations for the year.
</P>
<P>
   Special effects are a big reason for the steep costs of many of
these films. Not only do they have to be good; in order to really
be competitive, they have to look better than last year's wonders.
And that puts added pressure on studios to create more imaginative
worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``The audience expects, demands, the latest state of the art in
special effects,'' said Art Rockwell, entertainment analyst and
president of Rockwell Capital in Burbank. ``If you're going to have
a credible picture, you can't have teens saying this is no better
than a few years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Summer films have become the equivalent of a theme park's hot
new ride. If they don't provide new thrills, fans won't show up for
the show.
</P>
<P>
   ``People want to see perfect images these days,'' said Wolfgang
Petersen, who directed ``The Perfect Storm,'' a state-of-the-art
seagoing disaster flick based on the nonfiction best seller. ``I
mean, 50 years ago, they would have made this movie in a bathtub
with people using a piece of wood to stir the models in the
water.''
</P>
<P>
   But making images wondrous enough to impress an ever-more
visually sophisticated audience can be an expensive risk. As
DreamWorks production executive Walter Parkes points out: ``CG
(computer-generated special effects) is a double-edged sword. It
also can be the reason why a film goes over budget.''
</P>
<P>
   There (italics on)are(italics off) ways to save some money on
your blockbuster, though, even if it looks like you're doing just
the opposite.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Disney's latest animated effort, ``Dinosaur'' -
which merges 3-D, computer-generated dinosaurs with live-action
backgrounds - has been the subject of a great deal of speculation
over its costs, with some reports as high as $280 million.
</P>
<P>
   Dick Cook, chairman of the Walt Disney Motion Pictures Group,
declined to say exactly how much the studio had spent, but said it
was considerably less than that. Other estimates have placed the
film's cost at $125 million.
</P>
<P>
   Cook said the high-end estimates were inflated because the movie
had been in development for so long, about 10 years, while the
studio tried to create computer animation software that would make
realistic-looking dinosaurs - and who knows what else in the
future.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of (the cost) is time and labor,'' Cook said. ``Any time
you're dealing with new technology and doing breakthrough work,
it's going to be more expensive. But in a lot of regards, we were
laying a foundation for the next group of films we do.''
</P>
<P>
   Another approach: New Line Pictures is spending $130 million to
$160 million, according to reports, to film an adaptation of J.R.R.
Tolkein's ``The Lord of the Rings.''
</P>
<P>
   But the executive overseeing the project, Fine Line Features
President Mark Ordesky, figures he's getting a bargain. Not only is
director Peter Jackson shooting in his native New Zealand, which
saves a hefty percent on labor and materials, he's actually
shooting three features at once, one for each of the three books of
the Ring trilogy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we had shot these in traditional fashion (producing and
releasing one, then repeating the process twice), it would have
taken a decade to finish,'' Ordesky said. ``We'll have all three
films in the can, shot, a year before the first one hits movie
screens.''
</P>
<P>
   And he has good reason to suspect there'll be some interest in
the resulting films, the first of which will be released in 2001: A
trailer for the trilogy posted on the Internet recently was
downloaded more than 6.6 million times in its first five days.
</P>
<P>
   New Line may be unique in getting three probable blockbusters
for what others may spend on one. No other studio is so fortunate,
though Fox with its ``Star Wars'' sequels and Warner Bros.' with
the back-to-back shooting of two ``Matrix'' sequels can come close.
</P>
<P>
   In realty, though, few studios enjoy the comfort of having a
virtual sure thing at the box office, despite the sums being
committed. Still, psychologically, the higher the ante the safer
the bet feels, as far as studio executives are concerned.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL 2ND TAKE FOLLOWS.)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The reason they're doing it is because the expected return is
quite high,'' said financial analyst Rockwell. ``If you're going to
compete for a major summer attraction, you have to be willing to
put big bucks behind it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Summer is still endless kids on vacation looking for something
to do,'' added Dave Davis, senior vice president of the Los Angeles
investment bankers Houlihan Lokay Howard &AMP; Zukin. ``And even though
the movie business tries and tries to become a 52-week business,
it's still basically a summer, the Christmas holidays and a couple
of other holiday weekends kind of business.''
</P>
<P>
   And big films can corner a big chunk of that business.
</P>
<P>
   If a studio has a good year, said Brad Ball, Warner Bros.
Pictures president of domestic theatrical marketing, it'll sell $1
billion worth of tickets in the United States. A single summer
blockbuster could easily generate 15 percent of that total by
itself.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, given the moneymaking possibilities, a nine-figure
price tag can look like a bargain these days. And there will be a
bunch of profitable movies this summer, it appears.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lot of quality, a lot of films from everybody,``
said Tom Sherak, chairman of the 20th Century Fox Domestic Picture
Group. ``Every studio looks healthy. I'm hearing a lot of good buzz
on a lot of films. There's no 800-pound gorilla.''
</P>
<P>
   That's a marked contrast from last summer, when Sherak and Fox
were riding what was more like a 1,000-pound gorilla: ``Star Wars
Episode I: The Phantom Menace.'' Studios scurried to release their
films on dates far from the prequel's mid-May debut, and for good
reason: It went on to become the second-highest grossing film of
all time, behind ``Titanic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no `Star Wars' this year,'' said DreamWorks marketing
executive Terry Press. ``I find it a much healthier environment.
The only problem with the summer is the movies stack up like planes
(about to land) at Kennedy Airport on a Friday afternoon. That is
expensive because then it's who screams loudest (with
advertising).''
</P>
<P>
   And that, Press said, is the reason marketing budgets can jump
to $50 million or more for some films, most of it for television
advertising, spent at a time of year when fewer people are inside
watching TV.
</P>
<P>
   Film expenditures have shot up and profit margins have plummeted
in recent years, in part because of those rising marketing costs,
according to analyst Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Part of the reason why marketing got so expensive is you have
to protect your film's production expenses,'' he says. ``But you're
going to spend this money because you can make it back'' and plenty
more.
</P>
<P>
   Or, just as likely, not. Summers past were littered with the
bloated carcasses of such misjudged megaproductions as ``Wild Wild
West,'' ``Speed 2,'' ``Batman &AMP; Robin'' and ``Small Soldiers.'' And
this year will be no different.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this business, it's like the biggest gamble in the world
next to Las Vegas,'' said Fox's Sherak. ``You're putting all this
money up ... And you could be gone (from theaters) in the first
weekend. But to be successful, you have to get up to bat. You have
to be swinging.''
</P>
<P>
   DreamWorks' Press, for one, thinks that approach may not be the
best. That's because the focus on big numbers can obscure the most
important one, down on the bottom line. Sometimes a film that costs
very little can contribute far more to a studio's profits, she
said, pointing to the huge success of ``The Blair Witch Project,''
which cost a pittance to make, was bolstered by about $15 million
in marketing expenditures and raked in $140 million last summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think that they think (blockbusters are) what audiences
want, but last year, a movie about annoying people in the woods
with a black-and-white camera made a ton of money and had none of
this,'' Press said.
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
