<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LA-STREETS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CITY STREET REPAIRS WOEFULLY LAGGING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ALEXA HAUSSLER 
c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News 
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The streets of Los Angeles _ neglected for decades
_ are still crumbling faster than they are being repaired, despite
a massive increase in spending under Mayor Richard Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the mayor's proposal to launch the city's largest-ever
street repair program, Los Angeles still lags woefully behind in
patching thousands of miles of broken blacktop.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan proposed in his 2000-01 budget spending $17.5 million
more than last year to repair a record 245 miles of streets. But
that's still 15 miles fewer than the number of miles that are
deteriorating, leaving a backlog of 4,000 miles to be repaved.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have never been on track since the 1930s,'' said Greg
Scott, the city's Street Services director, who is credited with
expanding the street paving program and finding innovative ways to
get more road improvements per dollar.
</P>
<P>
   Under Riordan, the number of miles of broken roads repaired has
soared nearly 500 percent over five years, including the proposed
15 percent increase in the coming financial year.
</P>
<P>
   But in a city with the largest urban street system in the
nation, it would cost $1.5 billion over 10 years to rebuild or
repair the system of 6,500 miles of roads cracked and deteriorating
because of years of neglect.
</P>
<P>
   The potholed and rutted streets carry a heavy price for
motorists, who face heavy charges amounting to hundreds of dollars
a year per car because of road-caused damage.
</P>
<P>
   According to the city's latest estimates, there are 3,000 miles
of streets that need to be resurfaced, and 1,000 miles that need to
be completely rebuilt, an even more expensive and time-consuming
undertaking, Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Essentially, the city would have to resurface 350 miles of
streets each year for the next decade to catch up, and then
resurface 260 miles of streets each year after that to stay caught
up, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The backlog, street officials say, is the result of years of
fixing too few streets - the city repaved roughly 50 miles a year
between the 1950s and the mid-1990s.
</P>
<P>
   It costs an average of $130,000 to repave one mile of street,
Scott said, but depending on the width of the street, the cost can
reach $400,000 per mile.
</P>
<P>
   During the current budget year, which ends June 30, the city is
resurfacing a record 220 miles. In the spending plan Riordan
unveiled last week for the fiscal year beginning July 1, he
proposes to use surging revenues from a booming economy to help fix
more miles of city streets as well as sidewalks.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will make the city a better place,'' Riordan said. ``We
must ... improve the quality of life for all Angelenos, and that's
what this budget is all about.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's proposed budget would resurface 245 miles of Los
Angeles streets, including 100 miles of ``major'' streets - broad
Van Nuys Boulevard is one example of a major street - and 145 miles
of smaller ``local'' streets.
</P>
<P>
   His plan also calls for workers to perform preventive
maintenance, known as ``slurry sealing,'' on 100 miles more.
</P>
<P>
   Altogether, it would be the largest street resurfacing program
in the city's history, city officials say.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, officials and workers have found ways to shave
$4.4 million in costs in the Street Services Bureau, for example,
by recycling asphalt and using larger trucks that need to make
fewer trips with larger loads to haul asphalt.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan's proposal, city leaders said, is a step in the right
direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``This budget reflects that priority,'' said Councilman Michael
Feuer. ``We're almost double where we were just a couple of years
ago, but it's still not enough.''
</P>
<P>
   Feuer said fixing city streets is among residents' top
priorities, along with sidewalk repairs and tree trimming.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is a whole package of basic day-to-day quality-of-life
services people expect,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's budget plan also includes:
</P>
<P>
   -- Repairing 26 miles of city sidewalk, including sidewalks in
front of 2,800 homes citywide.
</P>
<P>
   -- Removing at least 5,100 tree stumps.
</P>
<P>
   -- Constructing 7,200 access ramps to bring high-priority areas
into compliance with the federal Americans with Disabilities Act.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to the boost in funds that the mayor is proposing,
city officials hope to lasso several million dollars from the
state's budget surplus to fix more streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are asking for the whole thing and will accept anything
because anything will help,'' Scott said.
</P>
<P>
   Neighborhood leaders applauded efforts to fix more city streets.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need it desperately,'' said Charney Herst, a resident of
Canoga Park. ``What we have is big ruts and cracks.''
</P>
<P>
   Herst said fixing streets won't just help her neighborhood's
drivers. It also will benefit walkers, bicyclists and pedestrians
pushing strollers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We often stand on the street corner and meet and we say, `Look
at this mess.'''
</P>
<P>
   Gerardo Guzman, president of the Pacoima Coordinating Council,
agreed, saying, ``Some of the streets in Pacoima are just
terrible.''
</P>
<P>
   Guzman pointed to specific intersections, including Louvre
Street and Bradley Avenue, that need to be rebuilt.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels like your car's falling apart while you are driving
down that street,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He also said he hopes the new budget will pour dollars into
neighborhood streets in the city's poorer areas.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's an issue of environmental justice,'' he said. ``This is
the best opportunity that we have, now that the economy is so good,
to put the money into areas like Louvre and Bradley.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X
</P>
</TEXT>
