<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 12:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0937 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT &LR;      04-29 1051
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NOTEBOOK-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NFL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE FREEMAN    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Carter Running an Option on When He Will Retire
</P>
<P>
   The National Football League career of the Minnesota Vikings
wide receiver Cris Carter will be remembered as one of the greatest
of all time for many reasons. His grace as a player is almost
unparalleled, as is his work ethic.
</P>
<P>
   He is a seven-time Pro Bowler who last year, at the age of 34,
had 90 catches for 1,241 yards and 13 touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   His personal story is of Hall of Fame caliber as well. A
one-time drug abuser, Carter is a brilliant example of how a person
can turn his life around. And Carter has not forgotten where he
came from, since he now dedicates many of his waking hours to
lecturing kids about the dangers of drugs.
</P>
<P>
   So it should be no surprise that Carter has recently hinted to
several teammates that he might retire after this season. It is
understandable; he has done just about everything a player can do
in football. So off he goes. Into the sunset. Into the Hall of
Fame. Catch you on the lecture-banquet circuit, right, Cris?
</P>
<P>
   Well, not so fast.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Carter's cryptic hints, it is still not definite, by any
stretch, that he will retire after this season. In fact, Vikings
Coach Dennis Green said the organization and Carter have an
understanding that Carter will retire after the 2002 season,
meaning he would play two more seasons instead of one.
</P>
<P>
   The reason Green insists Carter will remain in Minnesota for two
more years is because when the franchise recently renegotiated
Carter's contract to make it more salary cap friendly, both sides
decided Carter would retire in 2002. Green speaks to Carter almost
weekly, and in Green's mind, little has changed about Carter's
plans.
</P>
<P>
   ``There seem to be a lot of people who think this is Cris' last
year,'' Green said, ``but I don't think it is. He is going to play
two more years. He wants to play two more years. He restructured
his deal so he would retire then, not next year.''
</P>
<P>
   Carter causes much of the confusion about when he will retire.
He does not say he will retire after this season, but he does not
say he will not, either. ``I think in the back of my mind, I know
what I am going to do,'' Carter said. ``But all I'm concentrating
on is one season at a time. Is it going to be one more? Is it going
to be two more? Is it going to be three? I'm not going to say
publicly, but I do know.''
</P>
<P>
   So, is Carter headed to the rocking chair after this season, or
is he up for two years?
</P>
<P>
   Whatever Carter does, it will affect the Vikings in a number of
ways.
</P>
<P>
   The team is currently in a state of flux. It will have a new
quarterback in Daunte Culpepper, who is in only his second season.
Though Culpepper's physical skill and football smarts are solid, he
is bound to endure some rough spots. All young quarterbacks do.
That is where Carter will be so valuable _ he can help guide
Culpepper, and calm the team when the rough spots hit.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's guidance will also be needed two years from now. It is
expected that after this season, wide receiver Randy Moss, perhaps
the most spectacular offensive player in the game right now, will
most likely become the highest paid player in the game. So far Moss
has been a good citizen, but what will happen when Moss' wallet
becomes heavier than Fort Knox?
</P>
<P>
   Money affects some players in strange ways. Will the big cash
ruin Moss or not change him at all? With Carter at Moss' side, he
could be a strong moral compass to the young player.
</P>
<P>
   This coming season will be the key to Carter's future. If
Minnesota wins a Super Bowl this season, he would most likely leave
the game. Seven Pro Bowls and a Super Bowl ring would make nice
going away presents.
</P>
<P>
   If the Vikings do not win a championship, whether or not Carter
departs in one year or two will depend on how the season goes. He
most likely will not stick around if it looks like the team is
going to rebuild _ salary cap or no salary cap.
</P>
<P>
   Whenever Carter does leave, the NFL will lose a piece of its
soul. ``Cris is a first-ballot Hall of Famer,'' Green said, ``and
he is a first-class person.''
</P>
<P>
   Sanders Redskins-Bound
</P>
<P>
   Deion Sanders will most likely be joining the Washington
Redskins _ just not when you think.
</P>
<P>
   Sanders wants to play a complete season with the Cincinnati
Reds, then hop a jet to the East Coast and play with the Redskins.
Dallas will probably release Sanders after June 1, and the Redskins
plan to pursue him. The team is comfortable that Sanders would not
be able to join them until at least the end of September.
</P>
<P>
   Washington is already stacked with talent on both sides of the
ball, and Sanders will only make them better. Yet the Redskins
should be careful; many scouts think Sanders, because of a
constantly ailing toe, on which he has had surgery, is not the same
player he has been over the years.
</P>
<P>
   What made Sanders so special was that even when he was beat on a
pass play, he had great recovery speed. Scouts believe he no longer
has that speed.
</P>
<P>
   But despite what some personnel believe, next season Sanders
should still give some defensive coordinators nightmares if he
catches on with Washington.
</P>
<P>
   Off-the-Field Violence
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has continued to examine how to address the problem of
its players and off-field violence. One thing seems certain: There
are no changes planned in the league's violent-crime policy on the
immediate horizon, and there will be few new initiatives as well.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the NFL will tweak several of its existing programs.
Also, the league will try to work on the image of players by
stressing the good things players do in the community.
</P>
<P>
   Some of the more tangible changes the league plans include an
extension of the rookie seminar, emphasizing the importance of
staying out of trouble. The NFL might also have more seminars for
veteran players during the season.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL believes it already has more than enough programs to
deal with the complex issue of off-field violence. The league also
feels strongly that it has enough punishment protocols and does not
need more.
</P>
<P>
   There will most likely be some owners and others who feel the
league needs to take stronger measures. Nevertheless, that will
probably not happen.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1259EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
