<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0100 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 13:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0945 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS-A     04-29 0869
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PC USERS VOICE CONCERNS OVER MICROSOFT SPLIT 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Ill., Mass.)  (Eds.: Please note that the word AT within parentheses has been
used in the 2nd graf instead of the symbol, which is
non-transmittable to many newspaper systems.) 
(ART ADV: Photos NYT7 and NYT8 are being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By MATT RICHTEL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ While lawyers and regulators in Washington
ponder the fate of Microsoft Corp., Troy Anthony stands in a
computer store here, struggling with the conflict the case inspires
in ordinary consumers. He says he feels strongly that Microsoft
should not be divided in a way that destroys the Windows standard
he already knows how to use.
</P>
<P>
   But what brought him and his laptop to the PC(AT)more store on a
busy Thursday afternoon? ``I've got a bug in Windows 98,'' he said
sheepishly. Anthony added that he had developed a not-so-technical
remedy for the times his operating system crashes. ``I know how to
reboot the computer.''
</P>
<P>
   For many consumers, the Microsoft operating system, used on 85
percent of personal computers, is the devil they know. And many say
they are not sure what the devil will look like if federal
regulators succeed in splitting Microsoft in two, as they proposed
on Friday, with one half an operating-system company and the other
half holding everything else, including word processing and
spreadsheet programs, e-mail software and the other Microsoft
applications.
</P>
<P>
   When the legal theory, public-relations spin and courtroom drama
die out, what is supposed to be left is an environment that offers
the American consumer better, more innovative, less expensive
products, thanks to heightened competition. But many consumers are
skeptical. According to a Gallup survey released on April 12, some
69 percent of Americans said they thought Microsoft should be left
alone, while 21 percent favored a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   This is consistent with Gallup's finding that 80 percent of
those polled said Microsoft had a positive impact on the computer
industry, while 20 percent said it had a negative impact.
</P>
<P>
   As the government was preparing to announce its proposals for
Microsoft, Tom Gibney, finance director for Impiric Chicago, a
promotional advertising firm, said he thought the ruling against
the software giant was too harsh, even if some of Microsoft's
tactics have been ``unwholesome.''
</P>
<P>
   Microsoft's products work very well for him, he said, adding
that while he had heard vague comments about other operating
systems, he was not inclined to try them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't really have enough knowledge about the programs,'' he
said. ``I'm just a corporate wonk going around getting set up with
Microsoft, and it works great for me. I use a PC, and they all run
Microsoft. It's ingrained; that's just the way it is.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Steven McAfee, 38, a physician at Massachusetts General
Hospital, is also contented with Microsoft's current structure. His
concern is that a breakup of the company would fracture the Windows
standard, which could hurt his patients.
</P>
<P>
   ``I sense there will be a lot more glitches in the software,''
he said, if the company is broken up. That would be especially
troublesome because patient records may soon be on computers and
thus vulnerable to bugs. ``I would prefer not to go so backwards.
It's a hard thing to endure at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Others, even some who work with computers for a living, think
the outcome of the case will have little effect on them. Steve
Abbitt, 23, a computer system administrator at the Pacific Stock
Exchange in San Francisco, said he did not care about the trial and
was unconcerned about the possible breakup of Microsoft. He said
politics, not concern for the good of consumers, was driving the
legal wrangling. Abbitt worries that if there were more operating
systems available, companies might have to retrain workers, which
he said would be costly and time-consuming.
</P>
<P>
   Besides, ``I'm much more interested if a good rock concert comes
to town than in the Microsoft trial,'' said Abbitt, noting that he
was an avid Grateful Dead fan.
</P>
<P>
   If consumers are unsure what a divided Microsoft would mean,
they have plenty of company. Some of the best and the brightest in
the country, applying economic theory of the highest order, cannot
agree either.
</P>
<P>
   Advocates of the government's proposal say it may take time, but
that new competitors should emerge if Microsoft is broken up.
</P>
<P>
   The theory is that the new applications business will have an
incentive to create versions of programs for makers of other
operating systems like Linux. In turn, those new operating systems
will be able to offer better products with a broader range of
functions.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, other companies making applications would find it
easier to compete against a Microsoft that is half its current
size. And at least in theory, more operating systems and
applications makers would mean more innovation, more competition,
more competitive pricing and, eventually, more store shelves full
of software made by entrepreneurs.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   ``There will be more stable operating systems that boot up
immediately,'' said Steven C. Salop, professor of economics and law
at Georgetown University Law Center. ``Two or three years out,
consumers might be buying PCs with Linux and more choices of
network computers.''
</P>
<P>
   More competition would force Microsoft to lower its prices,
asserts Mark Cooper, research director for the Consumer Federation
of America. Citing well-known estimates, he said computer makers
pay Microsoft a fee of $45 to $60 for each PC they put the Windows
operating system on, but he figures that amount could easily fall
to $15 a machine if Microsoft faced more intense competition.
Cooper dismisses the dire prophecies that more operating systems
would mean chaos and confusion for consumers who are accustomed to
Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want you to believe that you touch one hair on the head
of this company, we'll go back to 1982, when you have to be a
computer programmer'' to use a computer, he said. ``No one is going
back to 1982.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe not 1982, but 1984, say economists on the other side of
the argument, alluding to what they see as inappropriate government
interference in the market. These economists argue that dividing
Microsoft would actually lead to higher prices and little new
innovation.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is anticonsumer,'' said Richard McKenzie, a management
professor at the University of California at Irvine and author of a
book about antitrust policy, ``Trust on Trial: How the Microsoft
Case is Reframing the Rules of Competition.'' ``The main reason is
that a breakup will lead to higher prices.''
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie argues that consumers benefit from having the
applications and operating system housed under one roof. The idea
is that engineers working on applications and operating systems
share ideas in hallways and cubicles, thus creating features they
might not think of if they worked in separate companies. This is
called the water-cooler theory.
</P>
<P>
   Then there is the slightly more complex ``double
marginalization'' theory. Jerry Hausman, the McDonald Professor of
Economics at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology and an
occasional consultant to Microsoft, said that according to this
theory, Microsoft can charge lower prices for both its applications
and its operating system when it operates both businesses, as it
does now. The ostensible reason is that if Microsoft lowers the
price of, say, word processing software, it stimulates demand both
for the software and for the operating systems that run it,
increasing revenue for both businesses.
</P>
<P>
   That will all change if Microsoft is broken up, Hausman said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Economic theory says this leads to higher prices,'' he said,
referring to a breakup.
</P>
<P>
   Such arguments fail to sway some Microsoft customers, though.
Akther Ahmed, 32, chief executive of an Internet startup called
Gomingle.com, said Microsoft had treated him arrogantly in business
dealings. He said that when he was negotiating to buy Web servers,
the powerful computers used to operate Web sites, Microsoft
representatives acted as if Ahmed had to take what they offered or
take his business elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Ahmed did decide to go to another company, a
decision that meant spending $500,000 more for the computers _
double the Microsoft price. But Ahmed said that Microsoft needs to
be taught a lesson.
</P>
<P>
   ``When a company gets too arrogant, its innovation goes down,''
he said. If Microsoft is broken up, he concluded, ``in the long
run, it'll be better for consumers.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
