<HEADLINE>
NBA NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MIKE WISE    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Honesty May Prove Not To Be Best Policy For Raptors Coach
</P>
<P>
   TORONTO _ He recently signed a $6 million contract extension and
has the best player on his team firmly in his corner. But have
Butch Carter's controversial remarks and deeds of the past week
done irreparable damage to his coaching future _ damage enough for
the Toronto Raptors to consider relieving him of his duties after
the season?
</P>
<P>
   According to a team official who spoke on condition of
anonymity, the franchise will not take any such action after its
first appearance in the National Basketball Association playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But as the chaos continues, you wonder whether the organization
is growing genuinely concerned about the relationship between the
ultra-provocative coach and some of his emotionally wounded
players.
</P>
<P>
   Carter's candor probably crossed the line last week. He bemoaned
the lack of a vocal leader in his locker room and cryptically
added, ``The most important advantage the Knicks have over us is
their top eight guys are all under contract and are focused on
winning.''
</P>
<P>
   But about those thin-skinned Raptor veterans: Doug Christie, who
has asked to be traded from Toronto on several occasions, ripped
into his coach and tried to persuade General Manager Glen Grunwald
to muffle Carter. Dee Brown called Carter's comments ``a copout.''
</P>
<P>
   Give Vince Carter this: At a time when his ultrasensitive,
allegedly more mature teammates were nursing their bruised
feelings, he understood his coach's motives _ however
unconventional they seemed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just understand,'' Vince Carter said. ``I don't let too many
things bother me. I try to see the big picture of where they try to
come from when they say things.''
</P>
<P>
   Of Butch Carter's mentoring, he added: ``I learned a lot. He's
taught me a lot. When he comes to me and yells at me, I laugh at
him sometimes. He doesn't like that. I know it.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach has had an extremely controversial week _ one that
began with Carter's dropping a defamation suit against Marcus Camby
and ended with his team publicly lambasting him. The thinking is
that Carter may have destroyed his chances for another high-profile
NBA job if he loses his current position.
</P>
<P>
   After Lenny Wilkens resigned last week, Isiah Thomas was said to
be seriously leaning toward pursuing the Atlanta Hawks' job,
provided he appeases league officials by selling his ownership
stake in the Continental Basketball Association.
</P>
<P>
   From the Nets to the Washington Wizards, Mike Jarvis, the St.
John's coach, keeps being mentioned as the next college coach to
catapult to the NBA
</P>
<P>
   They are rumors at worst, solid speculation at best. But no job
would be considered more plum than Toronto's, especially if the
Vince Carter-Tracy McGrady nucleus remains intact.
</P>
<P>
   After all the effort Butch Carter has put into grooming the two
wunderkinds, it would be a shame if the coach's curt honesty and
wild motivational ploys ended up costing him the chance to see
their development through.
</P>
<P>
   You wonder about double standards, too.
</P>
<P>
   People like Pat Riley and Phil Jackson are celebrated for the
creative manipulation they employ to coax spoiled millionaires into
believing in something greater than themselves. When a relative
newcomer to the profession attempts to inspire his beleaguered team
in provocative fashion, he is seen as plunging off a mental cliff
into the abyss.
</P>
<P>
   Butch Carter's style and tactics may be out there and
off-kilter. But he is not alone.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers Pulls Off an Upset
</P>
<P>
   Doc Rivers may be holed up in a TNT studio for the playoffs, but
he managed to pull off an upset last week by nudging out Phil
Jackson for the coach of the year award.
</P>
<P>
   A panel of predominantly national beat writers voted for Rivers
based on his ability to guide a group of decent role players _
unanimously picked in the preseason to finish in the Atlantic
Division basement _ within a missed 3-pointer of a playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson's maiden season with the Lakers produced 67 victories in
a rugged Western Conference, but somehow it was not enough. The
final tally: Rivers, 60 votes; Jackson, 53. Both coaches said they
voted for Jerry Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers is a former TNT analyst, whose affable, regular-guy
demeanor has endeared him to many factions of the news media, some
of whose members have grown jaded and cynical over aloof athletes
and coaches who treat them more like obstacles than people.
</P>
<P>
   Rivers was asked if he believed his relationships with the news
media helped him in the voting. ``No, I doubt it,'' he said. ``Phil
Jackson has probably better relationships and knows more people
than I do. I think the bottom line is a lot of people underrated
our talent.''
</P>
<P>
   Among others, Milwaukee Coach George Karl lobbed a verbal
grenade the Magic's way recently. Karl singled out Orlando General
Manager John Gabriel for preparing to rid the team of several
players in the off-season in order to make sure the Magic has
enough salary-cap room to lure a big-name free agent, at the
expense of the players who worked their tails off for Rivers and
the Magic this past season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess he calls that coaching,'' Rivers said. ``I basically
ignored it. I hope I never have to make comments about other
people's organizations to get what I want out of my team. Maybe
that's how George does things.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Rest for the Weary
</P>
<P>
   NBA Commissioner David Stern was recently forthright about the
reasoning behind the league's drawn-out, first-round playoff
series. Good spacing between telecasts not only means more
generated hype between games, but it also means more advertising
revenue for the respective network partners.
</P>
<P>
   But when the weekend began, five of eight teams were on the cusp
of sweeping their opponents in three straight games. Drama was
often at a premium, nowhere more than in Los Angeles, where a
competitive series has yet to emerge. In two victories, the Lakers
treated the Sacramento Kings like a younger, smaller sibling with
no chance of beating its older brother.
</P>
<P>
   Utah, Miami, Portland, the Knicks and the Lakers all have
something in common: Their rosters are significantly older than
their respective opponents'.
</P>
<P>
   In giving veterans like Patrick Ewing, Karl Malone, John
Stockton and Scottie Pippen ample time to rest their bodies, the
league essentially nullified the athleticism of its new, young
stars _ players such as Vince Carter, Minnesota's Kevin Garnett and
Seattle's Shammond Williams.
</P>
<P>
   Unable to bank on wearing the old guard down with three games in
five or six days _ a somewhat normal playoff format _ Carter and
Garnett may be on vacation by early next week, their next NBC
appearance coming in the Olympics in September.
</P>
<P>
   Slow Days in Washington
</P>
<P>
   Michael Jordan's job could have been made much easier if the
Washington Wizards had aggressively pursued moving some of their
higher-salaried players last season. Instead, Jordan, the Wizards'
head of basketball operations, will most likely have to live with
the $10-million-a-year players Rod Strickland and Mitch Richmond
for the next few years.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Western Conference team official who requested
anonymity, the Wizards were contemplating pursuing a trade for
Marcus Camby and another Knick for Strickland, a point guard the
Knicks coveted, last summer. Another part of their plan, the
official said, was then to draft Andre Miller, the stellar
Cleveland point guard who replaced Brevin Knight in the starting
lineup, and sign and trade Richmond to Miami for Jamal Mashburn.
</P>
<P>
   Washington's frontline would have included Juwan Howard, Camby
and Ben Wallace. The Wizards' backcourt would have been Mashburn
and Miller. A nice mix of veterans and youngsters, the building
blocks of a playoff team.
</P>
<P>
   Jordan could not be reached for comment last week. But a former
team official said the scenario was put forth at the time by a
prospective employee. He added, on condition of anonymity, ``It
sounds good, but none of it ever came close to happening.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1309EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0104 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 13:17 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0950 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     04-29 0954
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BASEBALL NOTES AND NEWS 
</HEADLINE>
   By MURRAY CHASS    
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Impostors? No, Just the White Sox
</P>
<P>
   He was a minor league outfielder getting older and going
nowhere. The Yankees, who had acquired him only a year earlier from
San Francisco, needed a spot on their 40-man roster, offered him to
any interested party, found none, then put him on waivers. This was
in December 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``We signed Bernie Williams back as a free agent and we were out
of roster spots,'' Brian Cashman, the Yankees' general manager,
said last Thursday. ``Chris was out of options so we designated him
for assignment. We had been shopping him all winter, but everybody
passed.''
</P>
<P>
   The Chicago White Sox told the Yankees they planned to claim
26-year-old Chris Singleton, so instead of giving him away for
$20,000, the Yankees traded him to the White Sox for Rich Pratt, a
minor league pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   Pratt, released by the Yankees at the end of spring training,
pitched for the Bridgeport (Conn.) Bluefish in the independent
Atlantic League last season. Singleton hit 17 home runs and batted
.300, highest batting average among major league rookies, for the
White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did not expect the player he is now,'' Cashman said. ``If
we did, we would not have designated him for assignment.''
</P>
<P>
   Singleton is one-third of an excellent young outfield that is an
integral segment of the team that had the best record in the
American League entering Saturday's games. The White Sox have
played so well that they have led the perennial AL Central champion
Cleveland Indians for nine consecutive days. The last time the
Indians were out of first place for that long was in April 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it should be that surprising to anyone who saw
the young players they had last year,'' Billy Beane, the Oakland
general manager, said of the White Sox's start, their best since
1973. ``They have a great talent base of young players.''
</P>
<P>
   Singleton is the center fielder, flanked by Magglio Ordonez in
right and Carlos Lee in left. Ordonez, 26, from Venezuela, and Lee,
23, from Panama, were signed as free agents and nurtured in the
White Sox's system. Singleton never played in that system, winning
a job with Chicago in spring training last year.
</P>
<P>
   That he was with the White Sox at all was a tribute to their
scouting staff. General Manager Ron Schueler said two scouts had
seen him in the minor leagues and thought he could be a reserve
outfielder for them. Moreover, he was a left-handed hitter, a
commodity the team needed.
</P>
<P>
   Singleton's status changed dramatically just before the end of
spring training. An injury to another outfielder, Brian Simmons,
opened a starting spot, and Singleton was ready to claim it, thanks
to intensive on-the-job training he received from Darrin Jackson, a
veteran outfielder with the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Darrin Jackson was like a father to him,'' Schueler said. ``He
talked to him about hitting, playing defense, the importance of
being a big leaguer. Chris grew up quick. D.J. did a good job with
him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez has also grown up, Schueler said. He is only thankful
that Ordonez has matured with the White Sox.
</P>
<P>
   ``We almost made a big mistake with him four years ago,'' the
general manager said. ``We left him off the roster because we had
some pitchers we wanted to protect. We heard three or four clubs
might be interested in him in the Rule 5 draft, but we were very
fortunate that no one took him.''
</P>
<P>
   Ordonez drove in 117 runs and hit 30 home runs while batting
.301 in his second season last year. Singleton batted .300 and hit
17 home runs. Lee, who was a rookie like Singleton, finished with a
.293 average and 16 home runs.
</P>
<P>
   Going into Saturday's game with the Detroit Tigers, with whom
the White Sox had a couple of costly brawls last weekend, Singleton
was hitting .310 with 20 runs batted in, Lee was .311 with 21 RBI
and Ordonez was .284 with 16 RBI.
</P>
<P>
   The outfield, however, is not the only reason the White Sox are
in first place. An assortment of other players has also helped make
them the best-hitting team in the league.
</P>
<P>
   Frank Thomas appears to have rediscovered his lusty stroke after
a couple of mediocre seasons. Paul Konerko, whom Schueler acquired
from Cincinnati about the same time he got Singleton from the
Yankees, is establishing himself as a solid, productive hitter.
Jose Valentin, obtained from Milwaukee in January, hit for the
cycle the other day.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think this is a carryover from the middle of spring
training,'' Schueler said. ``We struggled early and we worked on a
lot of things. All of a sudden we settled in. These guys started
swinging around the middle of March and they haven't stopped.''
</P>
<P>
   No one expects the White Sox to stay with the Indians, but they
may hit well enough to become a wild-card contender. Will they have
enough pitching to attain that status?
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard to say,'' Schueler said. ``Right now we're not
pitching up to our capabilities. Some of these kids are learning;
they're getting better.''
</P>
<P>
   White Sox fans remain skeptical. They remember how a few years
ago the team traded away veteran pitchers when the White Sox were
in the race. Even some executives of other teams wonder if Jerry
Reinsdorf, the managing owner, will spend money, if necessary, to
bolster the pitching staff later in the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``Depending on how we look and how we're progressing at the
All-Star break, I'd do it,'' Schueler said about a possible pursuit
of veteran pitching. ``Jerry's behind me 100 percent. The money
will be there. I see no problem going out and getting somebody.''
</P>
<P>
   The White Sox just have to give Schueler a reason to do it.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
nn
</P>
<P>
   Changing Their Colors
</P>
<P>
   With two games left in April, the St. Louis Cardinals had
already broken the major league home run record for the month by
swatting 52. That total not long ago would have come close to
representing a typical season for Cardinals' home runs.
</P>
<P>
   In an 11-season span from 1982 through 1992, the Cardinals did
not reach triple digits in home runs for any season. In 1986, they
hit only 58. Andy Van Slyke, with 13, was the only player in double
digits. That period for the Cardinals was the equivalent of the
dead-ball era before Babe Ruth. Now they are playing in the Mark
McGwire era.
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds on McGwire
</P>
<P>
   Having Mark McGwire as a teammate has been a revelation to Jim
Edmonds. ``Walking around a mall with him is like being with the
president,'' the Cardinals' center fielder said. ``He needs
security.''
</P>
<P>
   Edmonds and McGwire used to play against each other in the
American League, Edmonds with Anaheim, McGwire with Oakland.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's become a better hitter,'' Edmonds said. ``It's
unbelievable what he does, as big and as strong as he is. He stays
within himself and doesn't try to do too much. He was a free
swinger earlier in his career. He's more under control now, has
more concentration, more focus. It's fun to watch.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Cardinals acquired McGwire in July 1997, he had planned
to become a free agent after that season. But he became enamored of
the city and the team and signed a new contract. Edmonds, whom the
Cardinals obtained near the end of spring training this year, was
asked if he has had a similar experience that would keep him from
becoming a free agent after this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started to see that from Day 1 in spring training,'' said
Edmonds, who has become an instant hit because of his hitting. ``We
had more people and more noise at spring training than there was at
Anaheim Stadium. In the city, everywhere you go it's a sea of red.
It's been great. I'm going to take a wait-and-see attitude. It's
not up to me if I want to stay here. It's up to them. We'll see how
it works out.''
</P>
<P>
   Boomer the Sage
</P>
<P>
   When David Wells pitched for the Yankees, people might have
found it difficult to view him as a role model for younger
pitchers. But Dave Stewart, Toronto's assistant general manager,
said Wells has taken on that kind of role with the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   ``Boomer has been very big for our club,'' Stewart said. ``He's
been outstanding. He's assumed the role of helping these kids grow,
talking to them and giving them a better understanding of what they
need to be doing out there. He's also been a great example of what
they should be doing. He's thrown a couple games under 100 pitches.
He's been very supportive of the staff. He's being a leader and an
example to these kids.''
</P>
<P>
   Stewart, himself a former pitcher and pitching coach, credited
the 36-year-old Wells with a new maturity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the big difference,'' Stewart said, ``is he's been
given the responsibility. I don't think he's ever been given that
responsibility before. I don't think anybody has trusted him with
it, but he's been given the responsibility and he's done a good job
with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Vanishing Species
</P>
<P>
   In a season when balls fly out of and all around parks like sand
in a desert storm, the Los Angeles Dodgers played an astonishing
pair of games last week, losing 1-0 on consecutive days to the Mets
and the Atlanta Braves. Low-scoring games evidently are not
extinct. In fact, one general manager thinks they have a future in
the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the low-scoring games have brought more excitement
than I thought,'' Doug Melvin of Texas said. ``You think the next
run might be the winning run. Every hit, every play is critical. We
had a game in Cleveland where we were up, 1-0. Every time a guy got
on second base you started thinking about defensive strategy.
Everybody bears down more. You're on the edge of your seat. The
games with the Yankees, even though we lost them, they were
exciting games.''
</P>
<P>
   Melvin referred to a pair of 5-4 extra-inning losses the Rangers
had to the Yankees in Texas. ``They're better than those softball
scores,'' he said, alluding to the 18-11 type of games that have
been prevalent this season. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
