<HEADLINE>
IN NORTH CAROLINA, 2 TIGHT PRIMARY RACES FOR GOVERNOR 
</HEADLINE>
   By KEVIN SACK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ASHEBORO, N.C. _ It was only 7:30 a.m. when a group of
Republican loyalists began gathering Friday at Bailey's Coffee and
News, but it was not too early for state Rep. Leo Daughtry to start
calling his opponent for governor, Richard Vinroot, a liberal.
</P>
<P>
   Vinroot has been criticized by the National Rifle Association as
a gun-control advocate, Daughtry said. Vinroot is pro-choice,
Daughtry said. Vinroot proposed a tax increase while he was mayor
of Charlotte, Daughtry said. ``I think all those add up to being a
liberal,'' he concluded.
</P>
<P>
   Vinroot, of course, rejects Daughtry's characterization of his
record, and many observers of North Carolina politics consider it
laughable. He, in turn, has portrayed Daughtry as a big spender for
supporting appropriations bills that, as it happens, won nearly
universal bipartisan backing in the General Assembly. He has also
suggested that his opponent is soft on abortion because Daughtry
voted in 1997 for a bill to ban late-term abortions that allowed
exceptions when the mother's life was endangered or her health
``gravely imperiled.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He's trying to position himself as something he's not,'' said
Vinroot, who has called for an absolute ban on late-term abortions.
</P>
<P>
   As is so often the case in Republican politics these days, the
race for this state's Republican nomination for governor has become
a charge toward the right, with candidates showing little restraint
_ and often little concern for the facts _ in painting each other
as closet liberals.
</P>
<P>
   The final days of campaigning before Tuesday's primaries
resemble the bitter battle in the Republican presidential primary
in South Carolina in March, when Gov. George W. Bush of Texas
questioned the conservative credentials of his opponent, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona. Bush's symbolic move to the right helped him win
the primary and, apparently, the nomination. But he is now
struggling to position himself back toward the center in time for
the general election.
</P>
<P>
   Both parties will hold primaries in North Carolina on Tuesday.
The winners will battle in November to succeed Gov. James B. Hunt
Jr., a popular Democrat who has served four terms, first from 1977
to 1985 and then from 1993 to the present.
</P>
<P>
   Recent polls show Vinroot, who was Charlotte's mayor from 1991
to 1995, with a small lead over Daughtry, a lawyer and businessman
from Smithfield who was once majority leader of the State House. A
third candidate, Chuck Neely, a lawyer from Raleigh and a former
state representative, is trailing. The leading vote-getter must win
40 percent to avoid a runoff.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic race, where party loyalty has become a means
of separating two candidates with similar stands on major issues,
polls show Attorney General Mike Easley with a narrow lead over Lt.
Gov. Dennis Wicker. Wicker, the son of a prominent state
legislator, seems to have the support of the state's Democratic
establishment, which could be significant in a low-turnout
election. But Easley, a former prosecutor who pursued drug
traffickers and corrupt Democratic politicians with equal relish,
has capitalized on his image as a maverick.
</P>
<P>
   Wicker and Easley have vowed to maintain the state's emphasis on
improving schools, a hallmark of Hunt's four terms. In contrast to
their Republican opponents, they both favor bringing a lottery to
North Carolina to generate revenue for education programs.
</P>
<P>
   They differ, however, on how the proceeds should be spent.
Wicker, still boyish at 47, would dedicate the money to college
scholarships and universal prekindergarten programs, as is done in
neighboring Georgia. Easley, 50, who grew up on a tobacco farm
outside Rocky Mount, would use the money to reduce class size in
the lower grades.
</P>
<P>
   Wicker originally opposed the lottery but said he was persuaded
to change positions after watching North Carolinians cross into
neighboring states to buy lottery tickets. ``People all over this
state are playing the lottery right now,'' he said while
campaigning at a Charlotte day care center. ``There's $100 million
a year going to Virginia. They go to Georgia and play it. And they
play it on the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   The two leading Republican candidates oppose the lottery,
setting up a clear choice for voters in the fall. ``It's teaching
children that there's some solution to their problems in a
12-million-to-1 shot,'' Vinroot, 59, said in an interview in his
Charlotte campaign headquarters. ``The ends don't justify the
means.''
</P>
<P>
   Daughtry, who is also 59, agreed that the lottery ``sends a
wrong message to our young people that you can get something for
nothing.'' And, he added, ``it's a tax on poor people.''
</P>
<P>
   This is Vinroot's second race for governor, and it is by all
accounts more aggressive than his losing campaign against Robin
Hayes in the 1996 Republican primary. Vinroot, a former University
of North Carolina basketball bench-warmer, acknowledges that he let
Hayes define him that year, and he has spent much of this campaign
raising money for television attacks on his opponent. His chief
strategist this year is Carter Wrenn, who was the architect of
Republican Sen. Jesse Helms' toughest campaigns.
</P>
<P>
   But in the primary, at least, Vinroot remains vulnerable with
conservatives because of his past associations with Planned
Parenthood. He and his wife made small contributions to the group
for several years, and Vinroot cut the ribbon on a new Planned
Parenthood center as mayor of Charlotte. He said he only later
learned that Planned Parenthood performed abortions, and would not
have supported the group if he had known.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe everybody knew, but I didn't,'' he said. ``Wish I had.''
</P>
<P>
   Daughtry finds that explanation incredible. ``It was one of the
biggest abortion providers in North Carolina,'' he said.
``Everybody's convinced that he knew what it was.''
</P>
<P>
   This week, the Christian Coalition began distributing hundreds
of thousands of voter guides asserting that Vinroot supports
abortion on demand in the first three months of pregnancy. Vinroot
said the group had grossly distorted his position. He said that he
supported abortions in the first trimester only in cases of rape,
incest or danger to the life of the mother, and that he would ban
all abortions after the first trimester.
</P>
<P>
   In the Democratic race, Wicker is trying to catch Easley by
planting doubts with party loyalists about Easley's devotion to
their cause. In advertising, campaign statements and interviews
last week, Wicker has noted that Easley rejected calls to drop out
of the 1990 campaign for the U.S. Senate after forcing a runoff
with the front-runner, Harvey Gantt. Gantt won, but then lost the
general election to Helms.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's about loyalty, it's about steadfastness,'' Wicker said in
an interview. ``You have to know that the Democratic nominee is
going to stand tall in tough times, and I don't know that he's done
that.''
</P>
<P>
   Easley did not respond to a request for an interview.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
