<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0107 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 13:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0966 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-ADVISER-2TAKES(T     04-29 1135
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-ADVISER-2TAKES(TRIMS)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAN IN THE NEWS: BESIDE BUSH AT ALL TIMES 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Photo NYT4 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By FRANK BRUNI   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ He was there, in the cockpit, on the Sunday
afternoon in the mid-1970s when George W. Bush last took a plane
into the air, steered a wobbly and uncertain course over Midland,
Texas, nearly bungled the landing and seemed to realize that his
high-flying days were forever past.
</P>
<P>
   He was there, too, on the morning in the mid-1980s when Bush
woke up with a hangover and a pang of regret and decided never to
touch alcohol again.
</P>
<P>
   On the night before the Iowa caucuses in late January, he
distracted Bush with fine cigars and idle banter. And a week later,
as the first exit polls from New Hampshire were about to come in,
he and his wife were the only ones other than the Texas governor's
immediate family who sat with him in his hotel suite, helping him
relax.
</P>
<P>
   Donald L. Evans, it seems, has almost always been present at the
pivotal junctures in Bush's life, an important witness to the
evolution of both the man and the candidate and an integral part of
his political campaigns, especially the current one.
</P>
<P>
   But while Evans has attracted public notice over the last year
principally for his work as Bush's national finance chairman and
his hand in reaping a record-breaking sum of contributions, his
role is much broader, deeper and less tidily defined than that.
</P>
<P>
   And it will be equally important if Bush winds up in the White
House, a fact made even clearer late this week, when Evans was
appointed chairman of Bush's presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's obviously George's closest confidant other than
his wife,'' said Dr. Charles Younger, a physician in Midland,
Texas, who is a longtime friend of both men. ``He'll do whatever
George asks him to, whether it's go here or go there.''
</P>
<P>
   Before this week's appointment, there was speculation that Bush
would dispatch Evans to Washington, so he could represent and
safeguard the Bush campaign's interests at the Republican National
Committee.
</P>
<P>
   Aides said the governor's decision to send someone else only
validated the degree to which he depends on Evans, whom he wanted
to keep within quick and easy reach.
</P>
<P>
   The two men's friendship is significant not only for its length
and strength _ it began 25 years ago in Midland, where Bush had
once gone to elementary school with the girl who later became
Evans' wife _ but also for its crystalline window into salient
facets of Bush's personality and priorities, his likes and needs.
</P>
<P>
   Bush prizes the comfort of the familiar, and Evans is in some
ways a personification of that, a colleague with a background,
personal history and conversational dialect that resemble the
governor's own and helped them forge an almost instantaneous bond.
</P>
<P>
   They were both born in July 1946. They both have fathers who
fought in World War II. They both earned MBAs in the 1970s and
toted them to Midland to make a mark in the oil business. They are
both fiercely devout Methodists. They both favor the word ``buddy''
and lean on the phrase ``you're a good man'' to signal approval of
male acquaintances.
</P>
<P>
   There are limits to Bush's appetite for the stiff ceremonies and
weighty colloquies of political life, and Evans, like many of the
governor's best friends, is an essentially nonpolitical person who
connects him to a time before all the talk shows and television
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Bush can be a showboat, and Evans, like Bush's wife, Laura, is a
gentler, more subdued and more self-effacing companion who never
tugs too hard at the spotlight.
</P>
<P>
   Evans is a source of unstinting loyalty, which is a
nonnegotiable demand of anyone in Bush's inner circle and a vestige
of the Texas governor's belief that his father was occasionally ill
served by aides with excessive ambitions and egos.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of his advisers are his friends and are loyal to him, and
he trusts them,'' Evans said in an interview in his office in
Midland, where he is chairman and chief executive of Tom Brown
Inc., an oil and gas company.
</P>
<P>
   ``But it's a little different with us,'' Evans said. ``It's
different when you have a long-term friendship that's stood the
test of time.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know, there are people in politics for all different
reasons,'' Bush said. ``In his case, his question is, `What can I
do to help George W. Bush?' Some people first say, `What can I do
to help my career and, oh, can I help it maybe by helping
somebody?' That's not Don Evans at all.''
</P>
<P>
   His assessment was borne out by interviews with Evans, whose
ability to turn a question about the counsel he has given Bush into
a reverent testimonial about the governor's talents is a feat to
behold.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Asked about that afternoon in New Hampshire and what he did to
cushion the blow of Bush's defeat by Sen.r John McCain of Arizona,
Evans said, ``There was this question out there _ I had been asked
a number of times _ how does he handle adversity?
</P>
<P>
   ``He's one that can quickly let go of the loss,'' Evans added,
each word coming several seconds after the previous one and only
after pained consideration. ``He takes responsibility for it,
whatever the outcome is.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me back up. He'll take responsibility for the defeat. The
victory, he's quick to show his appreciation to others and all they
did.''
</P>
<P>
   If Evans is actually giving the candidate concrete advice, he is
not about to divulge what it is or take credit for it.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Several of Bush's other friends and advisers described Evans'
influence in terms not of how the candidate thinks or what he
advocates but of how he copes. Having Evans around clearly makes
Bush feel safe and calm.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bush once said, about his old man's advisers, that if a
grenade came along, it was their job to jump on it,'' said a senior
campaign aide. ``The governor wouldn't have to say that to Don. Don
would already be lying on it.''
</P>
<P>
   That helps explain why, during the most intense phase of the
primaries _ when there were not too many fund-raising events on the
schedule and Evans could technically have stayed home in Midland _
he was on the road with Bush perhaps more than any other senior
adviser except Karen P. Hughes, the campaign's communications
director.
</P>
<P>
   ``He knows that I don't particularly care for advice sometimes,
just conversation,'' Bush said. ``There's that mental down time
that candidates need _ not to be always on, always answering and
figuring out the next step. If he asks me a question, I can tell
him I don't want to answer it without hurting his feelings.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Evans' devotion is requited. Exemplifying how generous the Texas
governor has been to his friends with appointments to honorary
positions on state boards, Evans sits on the most coveted one of
all: the University of Texas Board of Regents. Bush put him there
in 1995; two years later, the other regents selected Evans to be
their chairman.
</P>
<P>
   Evans' roots in Texas are deep. The second of three children, he
was born and reared in and around Houston, where his father worked
as a manager with Shell Oil Co.
</P>
<P>
   His main sport in high school was golf. At the University of
Texas in Austin, he joined a fraternity, was elected to an elite
service organization named the Texas Cowboys, made good grades and
earned an undergraduate degree in engineering. He returned to the
university several years later for his MBA, which he received in
1973.
</P>
<P>
   By that point he had married Susie Marinis, a college classmate
and a native of Midland, where the couple headed in 1975 and he
took a job with Tom Brown.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Although he spent two months roughnecking on rigs to get a
glimpse of the business from the ground up, he was already on a
track to the upper rungs of the executive ladder. He said that he
had landed in the right place at the right time, joining a
fast-growing industry that was in desperate need of young talent
with the kind of financial savvy he had picked up in business
school.
</P>
<P>
   Evans' friends noted that his combination of a Texas drawl and
an innately suave, dignified demeanor made him a perfect bridge
between the oil fields of western Texas and the money wells of Wall
Street.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Bush also arrived in Midland in 1975, carrying a freshly minted
MBA from Harvard, and he immediately looked up Susie Evans, with
whom he had attended elementary school in Midland in the 1950s,
when his own father had looked to make his fortune in oil.
</P>
<P>
   Susie Evans welcomed Bush back with open arms and took pity on
his bachelor status. On his nightly visits to the Evanses, she got
his dirty clothes, while her husband got the company of a fellow
sports nut.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd watch TV and we'd eat and I'd do his laundry and he'd
be on his way,'' Evans said of Bush.
</P>
<P>
   Evans and Bush bonded over oil and weekend golf outings and
daily midafternoon runs. Bush relished being the faster of the two,
just as he reveled in being the ebullient and irreverent one.
</P>
<P>
   Evans was always a bit more ruminative and settled, a
temperament sealed by his earlier start on fatherhood _ he has
three children _ and the awesome responsibility he encountered.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, his second child, Jenny, was born with mental
retardation, the severity of which became clear only gradually.
Today, at 23, she is still unable to talk, although she can play
some sports and understand much of what is said to her.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Evans once remarked that she was the best thing that ever
happened to him. Asked recently to explain that, he bowed his head
for several seconds, and when he raised it, his eyes glistened with
tears.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's devastating for someone to tell you that your daughter is
retarded,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But once you get through that,'' he added, ``it causes you to
really get a deeper understanding of why you're here, what you're
doing here. It gave me a chance to get reminded, in a big way, that
I'm here to serve others.''
</P>
<P>
   Evans ended up on the boards of various organizations that help
people like Jenny.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   His charitable work reflected the prominence and affluence he
had achieved in becoming president of Tom Brown in 1979, when he
was just 33. His place in the Texas business world also helped him
raise money for Bush's political campaigns, beginning with his
failed bid for Congress in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Evans tilled the financial soil again in 1994, when Bush ran for
governor; in 1998, when he ran for re-election; and in 1999, when
he announced his presidential bid. By last month, the tally for the
latest effort was more than $80 million, a record in presidential
politics.
</P>
<P>
   That owed something to luck, something to Republicans' hunger
for the White House and something to the campaign's ability to tap
the network of Bush's father.
</P>
<P>
   But it also owed something to Evans' almost preternatural
graciousness, smoothness and air of quiet authority, a
confidence-winning persona that sometimes sets friends to wondering
how it is that Bush, and not Evans, wound up scaling the pinnacles
of politics.
</P>
<P>
   Evans has always been a steadying influence on Bush. He was
among the people who, in 1985, encouraged Bush to get into an adult
Bible study group, where according to a mutual friend Bush once
answered a question about the definition of a prophet by saying it
was the result of revenues exceeding expenditures.
</P>
<P>
   It was Evans who gave Bush a daily guide for reading the entire
Bible, in segments, over a year, something that the governor
subsequently did more than once.
</P>
<P>
   And it is Evans to whom Hughes and other senior advisers in the
Bush campaign frequently turn for the best, most accurate
prediction of how Bush will feel about events and issues in his
political life.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're almost like brothers,'' Hughes said.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Although Bush left Midland in 1988 to go to Washington _ and,
later Dallas and Austin _ there has never been any real distance
between him and Evans, whose sustained role in serving Bush's
aspirations has often required him to spend days on end away from
his family.
</P>
<P>
   He does not complain. He said he believed in Bush's goodness as
a person, fitness for leadership and worthiness as a friend. He
wants to do all he can to help his steadfast buddy achieve his most
ardent desires.
</P>
<P>
   And he wants to take care of him. Hughes recalled an early
encounter with Evans in 1994, when she signed on to Bush's campaign
for governor and was in the frequent business of haranguing him to
add yet another phone call or yet another interview to an already
crammed schedule.
</P>
<P>
   One day, she said, Evans simply took a look at his friend, read
the weariness in his features and told her: ``That's it. After
this, he's not going to do anymore. He's going to take a break.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Nobody questioned him,'' Hughes said, including Bush. ``That's
exactly what we did.''
</P>
</TEXT>
