u a BC-RACIAL &LR; - &UR; PROFILING-NY     04-29 0497
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RACIAL </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CALIFORNIA GOVERNOR TO SUPPORT BAN ON RACIAL PROFILING 

</HEADLINE>
 - PROFILING-NYT c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service  
  LOS ANGELES _ Gov. Gray Davis of California has agreed to support
legislation outlawing racial profiling by police officers, though
the bill no longer contains what critics say was a crucial
component for determining the extent of the problem.
<TEXT>
<P>
   The governor's decision follows a federal appeals court ruling
that ethnic appearance was not a relevant consideration in
assessing suspects.
</P>
<P>
   Davis vetoed legislation last year that would have required law
enforcement agencies to collect data to determine whether they
stopped minority drivers disproportionately, saying ``there is no
evidence that this practice is taking place statewide.''
</P>
<P>
   The legislation now supported by Davis was written by state Sen.
Kevin Murray, whose two previous versions of the bill were passed
by both houses of the Legislature only to be vetoed by Davis.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to declaring racial profiling illegal, the bill
would require all officers to undergo expanded diversity training
and to provide their business card and a complaint hot-line number
to people who are stopped but not cited.
</P>
<P>
   Previous versions were opposed by the law enforcement lobby and
big-city police chiefs.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Murray said that he did not believe data
collection ``is a significant part of the solution anymore'' and
that the new bill provided an important complaint mechanism for
people who feel they have been wrongly singled out.
</P>
<P>
   ``It took us some time to get here,'' he said, ``but I think it
will give us one of the most comprehensive racial profiling bills
in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   The American Civil Liberties Union criticized the latest
version, saying that raced-based stops are already illegal and that
the proposal lacks any component that would help determine whether
minority drivers were stopped disproportionately.
</P>
<P>
   The Los Angeles chapter of the ACLU is representing plaintiffs
in a suit against the Los Angeles Police Department over stops that
the group says were race-based.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's totally inadequate,'' said Ramona Ripston, the executive
director of the ACLU chapter in Los Angeles. ``This legislation
doesn't really change anything.''
</P>
<P>
   The governor's office declined to respond to the criticisms.
</P>
<P>
   The 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals in San Francisco ruled
this month that ethnicity was not a relevant criterion for police
stops.
</P>
<P>
   When Davis vetoed the data-collection bill last year, he ordered
the California Highway Patrol to collect the information and asked
local police departments to do so voluntarily.
</P>
<P>
   The San Jose Police Department, which had been collecting data
before the governor's request, has found that Hispanics and blacks
are pulled over in greater percentage than they are represented in
the population, though the department says the stops are in keeping
with racial breakdowns on a neighborhood-by-neighborhood basis.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1329EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
