<P>
   25-VIETNAM _ ``Ho Chi Minh Trail, napalm and body bags,
fragging, Khe Sanh, the Tet Offensive. ...'' Twenty-five years ago
today, Saigon fell to the Vietnamese Communists, the consequence of
a decision by President Nixon two years earlier to pull all U.S.
troops out of the country. Once the last helicopter had lifted off
Vietnamese rooftops, once the guns had fallen quiet there, all
those words that had seemed so fraught with meaning suddenly ceased
to matter, and ceased to be heard as well. (Bookman, Atlanta
Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   COMING-HOME _ WASHINGTON _ Vodka consumption is down. The
weather has improved. Life is more stable, though there is a
gnawing concern about the health of the economy. I'm not
summarizing the state of affairs in Russia. I'm talking about my
life in America since moving back to the States from Moscow five
months ago. My family and I have come home after seven years
abroad, and we're coping with culture shock in our own country.
(Holmes, Cox News Service) Also moving in (l) Lifestyle category.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ A study has found that at every step in the
juvenile justice system, minority kids are treated more harshly
than white kids. If you are wondering where that grotesque
disproportion of African-American men in state and federal prisons
comes from, here's the starting point. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Cox News Service columnist Howard Kleinberg
is on vacation. His column will resume May 22 for papers of May 24.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ Government prosecutors once foresaw U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson juggling his criminal docket for
years to come. Under such a formula, the judge would serve as a
sort of corporate truant officer, monitoring Microsoft's conduct to
bar any further illegal acts. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox
News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
