<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 13:56 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A0994 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-ART-NYT     04-29 0815
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KOSOVO-U.N.-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
U.N. DELEGATION WINDS UP VISIT TO KOSOVO 
</HEADLINE>
 (ART ADV: Photo NYT5 has been sent to NYT photo clients. A map is
being sent to NYT graphic clients. Nonsubscribers can make
individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
 By CARLOTTA GALL  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PRISTINA, Yugoslavia _ The eight-member delegation from the U.N.
Security Council, which came to Kosovo to give a stern message to
all sides to stop the violence and to urge on the U.N. mission,
wound up its visit on Saturday somewhat muted by the complexities
on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   Despite some clear differences within the delegation on the
performance of the peacekeeping mission and the U.N. civilian
administration in Kosovo, members said they were pleasantly
surprised by the progress made in bringing the ethnic communities
together after the war. The delegation included the U.N.
ambassadors from China and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   The unusual visit by the ambassadors came at the invitation of
the director of the U.N. mission in Kosovo, Dr. Bernard Kouchner,
who is seeking more support and personnel for his operations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I invited them so they could discover the reality,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   China and Russia in particular have criticized the operation for
its failure to protect Serbs and other minorities from revenge
attacks by returning Kosovo Albanian refugees, and for
peacekeepers' failure to carry out their full mandate.
</P>
<P>
   The peacekeepers came in last year after the 78-day NATO bombing
campaign forced President Slobodan Milosevic of Yugoslavia to
withdraw the troops sent into Kosovo, where a separatist movement
was seeking independence for the largely Albanian province of
Serbia.
</P>
<P>
   At the start of the Security Council visit, the ambassadors from
China and Russia sent a clear message of their countries'
opposition to the NATO bombing, when they traveled to Kosovo by way
of Belgrade, in a symbolic recognition of Yugoslavia's sovereignty
over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   The two ambassadors were guests of the Yugoslav government and
met with Milosevic and Deputy Prime Minister Nikola Sainovic, both
of whom have been indicted as war criminals by the war crimes
tribunal in The Hague.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was just traveling to Pristina through Belgrade in a
national capacity,'' the Russian ambassador, Sergei Lavrov, said
when he arrived in Kosovo. ``I did not go there as part of the
delegation.''
</P>
<P>
   The president of the Security Council, Robert Fowler of Canada,
nevertheless protested their action. Kouchner said it had sent the
wrong message to people in Kosovo, where memories of the war are
fresh.
</P>
<P>
   He also did not hide his disappointment that the ambassadors
from three of the five permanent members of the Security Council _
the United States, Britain and his own native France _ turned down
the invitation to Kosovo in favor of a trip to Congo. His request
that the Security Council also send someone to look specifically at
the issue of missing persons _ a source of continued tension and
weekly demonstrations in Kosovo _ also was ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Lavrov criticized what he said was a failure to meet the
requirements of U.N. Resolution 1244, which governs the mission's
operation in Kosovo. He called for stronger contacts with Belgrade
and greater recognition of Yugoslavia's sovereignty over Kosovo.
</P>
<P>
   But the chairman of the delegation, Anwarul Karim Chowdhury of
Bangladesh, said that the delegation had been favorably impressed
by the U.N. mission and would commend the work of Kouchner and his
team.
</P>
<P>
   ``Implementation of 1244 is seen by each of us from our own
point of view,'' Chowdhury said. He added that despite constraints
that hampered full implementation, the ``effort is being made in
full earnestness.''
</P>
<P>
   The delegation was given a tour of the province that took in the
law enforcement school that is training Serbs and Albanians to be
local police, and visited the divided city of Mitrovica and a
cemetery where the war crimes tribunal is exhuming 140 bodies
killed by Serbian forces last year. The delegates also met with
leaders of the various ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
   Kouchner seems to have won their support for a U.N. special
envoy to be appointed to take charge of missing persons and
detainees.
</P>
<P>
   An estimated 9,000 people died in two years of war in Kosovo,
but there are at least 3,000 people still missing. More than 1,000
Albanians remain in Serbian prisons, many of them civilians who
were arrested during the mass expulsions of Albanians from Kosovo
last year by Yugoslav forces. An estimated 500 Serbs and members of
other ethnic minority groups also are missing, most of them
abducted after NATO forces arrived in Kosovo last June.
</P>
<P>
   The U.N. resolution that ended the war did not include a clause
on missing or detainees, but Chowdhury said there was a need for a
high-level figure to be appointed to deal specifically with that
issue.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
