<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PRIVACY-LEGISLATION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLINTON TO CALL FOR TOUGHER PRIVACY RIGHTS
</HEADLINE>
 By STEPHEN LABATON  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Clinton administration is preparing legislation
to protect the financial privacy of consumers by limiting how
banks, insurers and other companies share sensitive consumer
information like personal spending habits, medical files and
insurance records.
</P>
<P>
   Administration officials said President Clinton would describe
the plan on Sunday at a commencement address at Eastern Michigan
University in Ypsilanti and that it was strongly endorsed by Vice
President Al Gore. But the package has already been denounced by
the financial services industry, which has chafed over less
restrictive privacy proposed regulations authorized by a banking
law passed last year, and by leading Republicans in Congress who
stripped some provisions similar to the new plan from last year's
legislation.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of the new privacy legislation say it will cost
companies too much and will discourage the consolidation of banks,
insurers and securities firms, which the law passed last year was
intended to promote through deregulation.
</P>
<P>
   The White House proposal would prohibit affiliates of large
financial conglomerates, say an insurance company and a bank, from
sharing information like medical records when a customer applies
for a loan without the consent of the customer. It would also
restrict the ability of banks from divulging the spending habits of
their customers that may be gleaned from checking accounts, or
credit or debit cards. It would give consumers a new right to
review their credit and financial information and correct errors.
And it would force companies to provide consumers with special new
privacy notices upon request to enable them to shop for the most
protective institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``To further the Clinton-Gore commitment to protecting consumer
privacy, the president is taking strong steps to enhance financial
privacy protections,'' a senior administration official said. ``The
president believes that firms should not be able to share
especially sensitive medical information, or information on
personal spending habits unless the consumer affirmatively
consents.''
</P>
<P>
   While the plan's prospects for passage by Congress this year are
dim, it appears certain to have deep resonance in the presidential
campaign, particularly as public opinion polls show the issue to be
of growing importance to voters and consumers who are increasingly
relying on both the Internet and on large financial conglomerates
to do banking, buy consumer goods and trade stocks.
</P>
<P>
   Gore and other leading Democrats have allied themselves with the
plan. Gov. George W. Bush's aides said he had not articulated a
position, although many senior Republicans in Congress and
supporters of Bush have been equally vociferous against taking any
further steps to increase the privacy protections of consumers
because they say they are too burdensome for the financial services
industry.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very clear that this a political act and the president is
playing to the traditional base of the party,'' said Kenneth
Guenther, a lobbyist for the Independent Community Bankers
Association, which represents many of the smaller banks and savings
associations and opposes the new measure. ``This is going to be a
humongous issue, particularly since there is nothing in the law
that right now prevents companies such as the Travelers, a unit of
Citigroup, from sharing medical records with Citibank. But the
issue is not going to be resolved now, not with with this Congress,
which at this late date is not going to touch this with a
10-foot-pole.''
</P>
<P>
   The financial privacy plan is the latest in a series of efforts
by the Clinton administration to strengthen the privacy rights of
consumers and medical patients. Last October, Clinton announced
proposed regulations to protect the privacy of billions of medical
records. And two months ago, Clinton issued an order prohibiting
federal agencies from using genetic information in any decision to
hire, promote or dismiss workers.
</P>
<P>
   In the next two weeks, federal officials are preparing to
complete new banking regulations that will require companies to
inform customers about how they handle records and whether they
disclose them to third parties. Those regulations, which were
required as part of the banking legislation signed last year, have
been heavily criticized by the banking industry for adding millions
of dollars in new paperwork and expenses.
</P>
<P>
   When Clinton signed the banking legislation last fall, he
praised the measure for containing some provisions that protect the
privacy interests of consumers but vowed to go significantly
further. He repeated the pledge during his State of the Union
Address earlier this year.
</P>
<P>
   Lobbyists and aides to Republican lawmakers gave the measure no
chance of passage this year.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will raise a lot of debating points, but as a political
matter, it's dead on arrival,'' said Edward Yingling, lobbyist for
the American Bankers Association. Yingling is part of a group of
lobbyists representing Wall Street, the insurance industry, bankers
and savings associations who are united against any significant
privacy initiative.
</P>
<P>
   Christi Harlan, a spokeswoman for Sen. Phil Gramm, the chairman
of the banking committee who co-sponsored the banking legislation
last year, said that the Texas Republican remained strongly
committed against any new and costly impositions on financial
services companies.
</P>
<P>
   ``His position is that the Gramm-Leach-Bliley legislation was
the most sweeping bill ever on the subject and we haven't even seen
the final regulations yet in this area,'' Harlan said. ``He's been
unbending in this.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
