<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 14:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1011 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-ROCK-STAR-BODYGUARD04     04-29 2239
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ROCK-STAR-BODYGUARD0430 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Former bodyguard banged heads for rock 'n' roll bad boys
 &HT;    By Lori Cumpston
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ Vic Robinson sat in the hotel room and
calmly waited as a deranged woman armed with a .38-caliber pistol
slipped past the doorman and made her way into the lobby of a
Seattle hotel to kill Mick Jagger. The woman claimed the Rolling
Stones lead singer was the father of her child. She wanted him
dead.
</P>
<P>
   ``The situation was quite tense,'' remembers Robinson, 46, a
Grand Junction music promoter who was Jagger's personal bodyguard
during the 1981 Tattoo You tour. ``The threat came through the
operator at the hotel. If she hadn't warned us, anything could have
happened.''
</P>
<P>
   The FBI set up a sting with plain-clothes detectives who were
briefed on the situation and given a description of the woman. She
was arrested in the hotel's lobby.
</P>
<P>
   It was later revealed that a hotel clerk, who was a friend of
the woman's, tipped her off as to what room Jagger was staying in.
</P>
<P>
   Beating people down, fistfights with frenzied fans, punching
paparazzi. Welcome to a day in the life of a bodyguard _ hired
muscle to protect the rich and famous.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, a 10-year veteran of the bodyguard wars, was hired to
protect Freddie Mercury of Queen and Dee Snider, lead singer for
Twisted Sister, in addition to Jagger. He's also toured with Iron
Maiden, Motley Crue and Billy Squire.
</P>
<P>
   He wears his battle scars proudly. Each representing a place in
time where he sacrificed his own skin to save a celebrity.
</P>
<P>
   ``People get so frenzied about these artists, and when they see
them, they come running with anything they've got in their hands,''
says Robinson. ``I got stabbed with a knife, I've been stabbed with
a fork, I got stabbed in the back with a pencil ... it can be
situations where people aren't doing it on purpose.''
</P>
<P>
   To hear Robinson recount how he got swept into a glamour-filled
world overflowing with sex, drugs, rock 'n roll and gargantuan
amounts of greenbacks, you would think he was lying. After all,
this kind of life doesn't just happen to anybody.
</P>
<P>
   It happened to Robinson, a street kid from Chicago, whose
working class father dabbled in retail while his mother worked for
an offshoot company of General Motors.
</P>
<P>
   Their life was far from glamorous.
</P>
<P>
   For a while he owned a fitness center in Michigan, but the
former competitive bodybuilder packed up and moved to Boulder at
the urging of a friend. He didn't have much to lose since he was
going through a divorce and would have moved just about anywhere to
start over.
</P>
<P>
   He was soon hired to work security by multi-millionaire
restaurateur Dick Horton.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was the kind of guy that used to have lunch with Anwar
Sadat,'' says Robinson, referring to the Egyptian president.
</P>
<P>
   He also moonlighted at the Dark Horse bar, a rough and tumble
biker bar notorious for ``fights that would last a half hour at a
time.''
</P>
<P>
   Then came word that the best rock 'n' roll band on the planet
was coming to Boulder.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's life would never be the same.
</P>
<P>
   The year was 1981. The Rolling Stones were on the U.S. leg of
their world tour to promote ``Tattoo You'' featuring the hit single
``Start Me Up.''
</P>
<P>
   The scene was surreal as 70,000 drunk, stoned and crazed fans
charged the turnstiles at Folsom Field on the University of
Colorado campus.
</P>
<P>
   The Stones, with band members Keith Richards, Ronnie Wood,
Charlie Watts, Bill Wyman and frontman Mick Jagger, were getting
ready to go on. At the last minute, Robinson was moved from his
outer perimeter security post and told to report to the barricade
at center stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought, `What the hell, man? They're trying to kill me,'''
recalls Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   Little did he know, his loyalty to a band he barely knew was
being tested.
</P>
<P>
   How far would he go to protect the Rolling Stones band members
and one man in particular, the English rocker known for his
trademark lips and midnight trysts, lead singer Mick Jagger?
</P>
<P>
   Jagger's former bodyguard was jailed two days prior to the
Boulder gig after stealing $10,000 from Jagger and jewelry from
Jagger's then-girlfriend, Jerry Hall, to support his alleged heroin
habit.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was blitzed with probing questions during the two-day
concert run. Then he got a 4 a.m. phone call summoning him to Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought it was a joke,'' says Robinson. ``I got the
impression that he wanted me to fill out an application for a job.
I figured there were going to be 300 guys who show up and I'm
out.''
</P>
<P>
   After arriving in Los Angeles, Robinson was met at the airport
by a man holding up a white card with his name on it. He was
whisked away in a stretch limo and driven to the swanky five-star
Westwood hotel with explicit instructions to talk to no one.
</P>
<P>
   The band was waiting for him in the 48-room penthouse suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``The door was opened by the man himself, Mick Jagger,'' recalls
Robinson. ``He puts the phone down and he's toking on this joint
and he says, `Want some?' I go, `No,''' says Robinson, imitating
the nervous high-pitched voice he used that day. ``Then he looks
right at me and says, `Have you ever been to jail?' There is nobody
but me and him in this room and he's looking me right in the face
... I'm thinking what should I say? I'm just going to tell him the
truth. I go, `Yeah.' He leans over and he says, `I'm glad you told
me the truth because I already knew the answer.' They did a
complete FBI check on me and that's why all those questions were
being asked.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson, who admits to being arrested for typical teen-age
stuff while growing up in Chicago's Westside, was led to another
suite.
</P>
<P>
   ``This guy is standing there and he's got a handcuff on one arm
and there are thousands and thousands of dollars on this table ...
stacks of money,'' says Robinson. ``He gives me this envelope and
there is $5,000 bucks in there in hundred dollar bills. He says,
`This is for Mick, if he needs anything, you'll have the money.' He
gives me another envelope with $1,000 in it and says, `This is for
you.' I don't know where this money came from and I don't know who
these people are.''
</P>
<P>
   The emotional strain of an adventure gone awry was starting to
take its toll.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson was beginning to wonder if he would ever see his
Boulder apartment again, let alone his girlfriend, whom he left in
tears as he boarded a plane in Denver.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a one-way ticket ... I didn't even check,'' says
Robinson. ``I was sure I had a round-trip ticket because I knew I
was coming home the next day. I take the key and open the door to
my suite and there were roses on the television and a big ol' box
of candy on the bed and I burst into tears like a 5-year-old kid. I
couldn't hold it in anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   The telephone in Robinson's suite rang and it was Mick. He told
him to be ready to go by 9:30.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no school or training,'' says Robinson, who worked in
intelligence and in the military police in the Marine Corps. ``It
happened,'' he says snapping his fingers, ``like that.''
</P>
<P>
   The first order of business was getting the limo driver
downstairs underneath the hotel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I go to Mick's room and he says, `Are you ready?' and I says,
`I'm ready' and he says, `We have money?'
</P>
<P>
   `I got money. I got more money than I ever had,''' Robinson
recalls, laughing.
</P>
<P>
   The limo driver pulls up in front of the famed Roxy nightclub in
Los Angeles, a favorite hangout of Jagger's when he was in town.
</P>
<P>
   On that night, Jagger partied with Jack Nicholson and John
Belushi.
</P>
<P>
   ``That was one of the hardest things to learn in the beginning
was how he wanted you to be,'' says Robinson. ``After the first
night, you knew exactly how you had to be and that was hard all the
time because it was a dangerous job.''
</P>
<P>
   ``People always ask me, `Oh, you mean you worked locally for
them when they came to town?' No. I slept in the same rooms with
them, I pulled his girlfriends off of chandeliers, pulled him out
of nightclubs and had to throw tablecloths around him. There is a
whole lot of stuff involved in the job and it's all yours.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson likens concert gigs to football games. He and Jagger
had a routine they faithfully followed each time the swivel-hipped
singer took the stage. First they would stretch. Then they would
meditate. Then each would retreat into his respective zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``My zone was getting myself prepared to protect him. You
couldn't do it drunk, you couldn't do it drugged out because if
something happened to him, what to you think is going to happen to
you?''
</P>
<P>
   The tour came on the fringes of an election year, which meant a
flurry of public appearances for Jagger and the band, including
dining with Sen. Ted Kennedy at the White House and appearing in a
commercial for then-San Francisco Mayor Dianne Feinstein, who was
drumming up support to restore the historic trolley cars.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson recalls a frightening experience following an
appearance at Candlestick Park. Jagger and Peter Wolf, lead singer
for the J. Geils Band, were eating dinner at Ernie's, an upscale
restaurant not far from the stadium district. Someone from the
restaurant called up a local disc jockey who announced on the radio
that Jagger was at the restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   What followed was a mob scene.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of them were drunk, they were wild ... beating on the
restaurant windows, people in the restaurant were starting to freak
out,'' says Robinson.
</P>
<P>
   ``My only options are, and I don't like doing this kind of
stuff, is start knocking people down.''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you got a hundred people between you and the car, all it
takes is one to get their hands on him or me and screw us up. We
had a system. Whenever I was going out the door first, he held on
to my belt. I had a special belt and I would always feel him, so if
you were in front of me when I was trying to get him out of a
place, you were history.''
</P>
<P>
   Jagger and Wolf were ushered out a side door in the kitchen to a
limo waiting in a narrow alley. The pair emerged shaken, but
unscathed. The limo wasn't so lucky.
</P>
<P>
   The most elaborate ruse Robinson ever used to disguise Jagger
was gluing a fake beard to his face and outfitting him in a fur
coat three times his size to get him into the Comedy Store to see
comedian Richard Pryor, who was making his first appearance
following a devastating accident that left him severely burned.
</P>
<P>
   What the fans didn't see behind closed doors was the ugly side
of show business. A side that was rife with drugs, free-flowing
booze, wild women and wham bam thank you ma'am sex.
</P>
<P>
   ``In that business, you're around lots of money, you're around
lots of drugs, you're around lots of everything,'' says Robinson.
``Lots of secrets ... wives secrets, girlfriends secrets, whatever
kind of secrets ... it's all there.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We were in Washington, D.C., staying at the Dolly Madison
Hotel and there was a guy who sent his wife to sleep with Bill
Wyman because that was her birthday present. It was freaky. I've
been around governors in a room smoking dope. They never had to
worry about it. It's like a code, there are certain things you
don't say or ever repeat.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there were the constant feuds between Richards and Jagger
over which direction the band should go.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson remembers one rehearsal at the Oakland Coliseum where
Richards kept nearly 100 crew people waiting for 12 hours while he
slept off a three-night party binge.
</P>
<P>
   The five-month tour, which took Robinson to Brazil, Australia,
England, Japan and Sweden, came to an end in February of 1982.
Robinson and Jagger parted ways. They haven't kept in touch.
</P>
<P>
   The Stones have moved on, still wildly successful, considering
prime seats to their latest No Security Tour cost upward of a down
payment on a new car.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota Gov. Jesse ``The Body'' Ventura, a former Stones
bodyguard in 1978 and 1981, even proclaimed Feb. 15, 1999, as
Rolling Stones Day. The proclamation cites the band's longevity,
including the fact that guitarist Richards is still alive at 55 and
that the band has always employed the best ``body'' guards.
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has moved on, too. His days on the road now consist of
meeting with potential sponsors as an event promoter for Just For
Fun Promotions, which he runs from a spare bedroom in his northeast
Grand Junction home.
</P>
<P>
   The walls of the makeshift office are filled with framed
memories.
</P>
<P>
   His personal favorite is one of himself sandwiched between an
army of Samoan security guards he hired to carry a coffin with
Twisted Sister lead singer Dee Snider inside to escape the throng
of fans who showed up for an appearance at an Australian nightclub.
</P>
<P>
   Absent are photos of Freddie Mercury who died on Nov. 24, 1991,
one day after he announced to the world that he had AIDS.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock,'' says Robinson. ``There aren't too many
people who could sing like Freddie Mercury.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson has no regrets when asked about why he left a life of
luxury. He just says it was time.
</P>
<P>
   ``You had to hate everybody,'' says Robinson. ``If you didn't,
you or somebody with you would get hurt. The person that I am right
now is different than that other person because it took me a couple
of years of therapy to be able to talk about things. It was harder
than hell to come off the road and back to a normal life.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
