<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-TRIBUNAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBODIA AGREES TO TRIBUNAL SETUP FOR KHMER ROUGE TRIALS 
</HEADLINE>
   By SETH MYDANS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HO CHI MINH CITY, Vietnam _ Sen. John Kerry, D-Mass., said
Saturday that Cambodia and the United Nations had reached a
compromise that would allow the creation of an international court
to try former leaders of the Khmer Rouge.
</P>
<P>
   Speaking to reporters in Phnom Penh, Cambodia, Kerry said that
Prime Minister Hun Sen had embraced a U.N. formula that would allow
foreign judges to make independent indictments.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen has resisted previous proposals that would reduce his
ability to keep personal control of the process. The United Nations
has insisted that Cambodia is not equipped politically or
technically to manage complex trials for crimes against humanity.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, who left Phnom Penh Saturday after meeting with Hun Sen
to mediate on the issue, said both sides had agreed to ``exert best
efforts to complete all the tasks necessary to be able to have a
formal agreement by June 15.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts reacted to his announcement with caution.
``Let's keep cool because there are still many things that can
happen between now and June 15,'' said a Western diplomat who has
watched Hun Sen seem to agree several times in recent months, then
back off citing new complications.
</P>
<P>
   Sixteen months have passed since the last surrender of a former
leader of the Khmer Rouge, whose brutal regime was responsible for
the deaths of more than a million people when they ruled Cambodia,
from 1975 to 1979. All but two prominent Khmer Rouge figures remain
free, some as the result of personal deals with the prime minister.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry said there were ``no obstacles'' left to the signing of an
agreement in June on a formula for a tribunal. He said the time
frame is a concession by the United Nationsthat will allow
Cambodia's National Assembly to meet first to approve a law on the
tribunal.
</P>
<P>
   In what he described as a new and untested model, Kerry said
that co-prosecutors _ one foreign, one Cambodian _ would issue
indictments, but that the foreign prosecutor would dominate the
process.
</P>
<P>
   The model involves a compromise proposed by the United States
that would allow a foreign prosecutor to issue an indictment
independent of his Cambodian colleague, subject to the veto of both
foreign and Cambodian judges.
</P>
<P>
   The United Nations had tentatively agreed to an American
proposal that would allow Cambodia to hold the majority on a panel
of judges. But there is concern that Cambodia could then block any
politically sensitive indictments.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
