<HEADER>
A1019 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-R-RUBIN-PROFILE-ART-N     04-29 0734
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-R-RUBIN-PROFILE-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ALBRIGHT'S SPOKESMAN ENDS SINGULAR TENURE 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (REPEATING to add photo note; no other changes.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
 By CHRISTOPHER MARQUIS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ James P. Rubin, the departing State Department
spokesman, will do anything for Madeleine Albright. Except carry
her lipstick.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's the only place he drew the line,'' said a Rubin friend.
``A lot of guys in the office had no problems carrying her purse.''
</P>
<P>
   During nearly eight years at the side of the first woman to
serve as secretary of state, Rubin fulfilled a number of roles:
friend, adviser, protege, gossip buddy, fashion consultant and
self-described ``intellectual mate.''
</P>
<P>
   Now, at 40, he is leaving Washington behind to move to London
with another high-powered woman, his wife, Christiane Amanpour, the
CNN foreign correspondent, who gave birth to their son a month ago.
</P>
<P>
   In a farewell ceremony last week, Albright said that Rubin had
evolved into one of the most influential and best-known spokesmen
for American diplomacy from his first press briefing, when he
resembled ``a deer on the first day of hunting season.''
</P>
<P>
   Hundreds of briefings and not a few arrows later, Rubin leaves
with a reputation for being accessible and well informed, if
sometimes self-promoting. Even his mentor could not resist a dig.
``What can we possibly say about Jamie Rubin that he hasn't already
said about himself?'' Albright asked.
</P>
<P>
   Journalists have relied on him for both the intricacies of
policy _ he is a former Senate foreign affairs aide and arms
control expert _ and as a witness who could recount how decisions
were made. Some of those decisions he even played a hand in
himself, expanding the spokesman's customary role, at Albright's
prompting.
</P>
<P>
   She gave Rubin an office next to her own, on the prestigious
seventh floor, a flight up from the quarters of previous spokesmen.
(Richard Boucher, a former ambassador, will succeed Rubin with a
sixth-floor office.)
</P>
<P>
   In particular, Rubin took on a senior envoy's role last summer,
when he traveled to Kosovo to try to persuade the Albanian rebel
leader, Hashim Thaci, to disarm with NATO guarantees. Rubin said
the ensuing accord and the gratitude of Kosovo Albanians was among
his most ``emotionally satisfying experiences,'' though some have
criticized the agreement as deferring too much to a ruthless,
irregular army and giving it too much of a role in settling the
conflict.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin has been a staunch defender of administration policy in
Kosovo and blamed the American news media for doubting that the
United States' bombing campaign last year would dislodge Serbian
control of Kosovo, which it did. ``It seemed like we were really
alone,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Playing the dual role of public voice and private counsel, Rubin
recast the spokesman's post in a relentless era of cable
television, 24-hour news cycles and, he says, an increasingly
impatient and adversarial American press.
</P>
<P>
   ``The compression of the news cycle has put a greater premium on
highly critical reporting,'' Rubin said in an interview last week.
</P>
<P>
   News organizations these days report and analyze information so
quickly, and with such skepticism, that the State Department hews
to a defensive crouch, he said. ``That harms our ability to get our
policy across to the public.''
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, Rubin plainly enjoyed the news media glare,
and with cameras rolling, rarely used four words when fourteen
would do.
</P>
<P>
   But Rubin's comfort in the public arena _ like Albright's own _
did not come easily. The pair grappled with searing scrutiny _ such
as when Albright learned of her Jewish heritage through press
accounts during her first week on the job.
</P>
<P>
   Rubin and the secretary's chief of staff, Elaine K. Shocas,
forged a tight circle, joining Albright at the movies on Sunday
afternoons. He dismissed as ``silly psychobabble'' the notion that
he filled the role of the son Albright never had. Albright's reply:
``Oy vey!''
</P>
<P>
   But, friends say, Rubin's proximity to powerful women has
groomed him well for marriage.
</P>
<P>
   ``We worked on him very hard to smooth out the rough edges,''
said Shocas, the chief of staff. ``Passing him off to Christiane
Amanpour is a great thing we've done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
