</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MOZAMBIQUE-REBUILD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MOZAMBIQUE CONFRONTS HUGE FLOOD LOSSES 
</HEADLINE>
   By RACHEL L. SWARNS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DURBAN, South Africa _ The angry waters have receded in
Mozambique but thousands of people remain homeless.
</P>
<P>
   The floods swept away schools and clinics, crops and cattle. And
nearly two months after the torrential rains ravaged the country,
the painful work of rebuilding is just beginning.
</P>
<P>
   In the first extensive assessments of the damage to roads,
schools, hospitals and lives, the United Nations, the World Bank
and government officials have determined that Mozambique must raise
about $427 million to pay for reconstruction.
</P>
<P>
   In February, heavy rains and floods battered Mozambique near the
foot of the continent. And for weeks, television viewers around the
world watched as soldiers in helicopters from South Africa and
other countries rescued thousands of people stranded in trees, on
rooftops, atop spits of land encircled by swirling water.
</P>
<P>
   But even though the reports included lengthy catalogs of
destruction and despair, there were startling glimmers of hope.
</P>
<P>
   The death toll, which was expected to be in the thousands, is
now believed to be around 700. And even though inflation is soaring
and economic growth has slowed, officials say that if the
government can raise the money for reconstruction, the economy may
still grow at a healthy rate of 6 percent to 8 percent this year.
</P>
<P>
   The task ahead is staggering. Despite the government's
impressive record of fiscal austerity, Mozambique remains one of
the poorest countries in the world.
</P>
<P>
   On Tuesday, President Joaquim Chissano will present his
reconstruction plan to international donors in Rome, where he hopes
to raise enough money to keep his country safely on track.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were all there when the floods were on, and then the
cameras left with the last helicopter,'' said Mark Malloch Brown,
the administrator of the U.N. Development Program, the co-host of
the donor conference with Chissano.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now, actually, is the tough moment for a country like
Mozambique,'' Brown said ``It is the ultimate poster child of good
economic management. And the test is whether or not we can stick
with it in the long nontelegenic time of reconstruction.''
</P>
<P>
   All told, about 4.5 million people _ or 27 percent of the
country's population _ were touched by the disaster, according to
Mozambique's disaster assessment. About 540,000 people were
displaced. And nearly 800,000 remain in need of assistance.
</P>
<P>
   Preliminary estimates indicated that about 10 percent of the
country's cultivated lands have been destroyed. More than 20,000
head of cattle have disappeared. The floods damaged roads and
highways, telephone lines and farms.
</P>
<P>
   More than 500 schools were damaged. The national highway, which
linked the capital, Maputo, to the rest of the country, is
impassable in certain sections. And the government now estimates
that more than a million people no longer have access to permanent
health clinics.
</P>
<P>
   The reconstruction will focus on rebuilding infrastructure,
housing and utilities, and building a flood preparedness system.
But it also seeks to restore the lost livelihoods of thousands of
farmers by distributing free seeds, hoes and medical kits for
livestock.
</P>
<P>
   ``The immediate effect on human life was less than people
feared,'' said Brown, referring to the initial death estimates.
``But without quick rehabilitation of the agricultural sector,
there's a real risk of dramatic increases in joblessness and
poverty.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1439EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
