<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 14:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1022 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-GORE-SURPLUS-ART     04-29 1281
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-GORE-SURPLUS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE AND BUSH DIFFER SHARPLY ON HOW TO USE SURPLUS 
</HEADLINE>
  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphics clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By ADAM CLYMER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ This is the first presidential election in memory
in which the candidates have a budget surplus to discuss, not a
deficit, and their sharply contradictory approaches on how to use
it are perhaps the biggest differences between Vice President Al
Gore and Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Bush has built his campaign around a five-year, $483 billion tax
cut that would send most of the surplus back directly to taxpayers.
Gore calls that risky, because the surplus so far exists largely in
the minds of economists, who once could foresee only deficits.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's risky is overtaxing people and leaving unspent money in
Washington,'' where politicians will waste it, Bush said last week
in Arkansas. If the government collects more money than it needs to
spend, he argues, then taxes are too high.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's proposals, derided by the Bush campaign as calling for
excessive spending, are harder to follow in detail, though plainly
they amount to a continuation of President Clinton's approach. Some
proposals for new programs that Gore favors, like a $115 billion
education trust fund, are part of Clinton's most recent budget
proposal but have not been approved by Congress. The Gore camp does
not count them as new spending.
</P>
<P>
   Gore would cut taxes only $250 billion over 10 years, and his
biggest spending proposal is for a $200 billion prescription drug
benefit for Medicare. He says the prudent thing to do is to devote
large sums to reducing the national debt, which should help keep
interest rates down, and to shoring up Social Security and
Medicare. An unspent surplus automatically reduces the debt.
</P>
<P>
   But, as Robert D. Reischauer, president of the Urban Institute
and former director of the Congressional Budget Office, observed,
``In historical perspective, you would have to conclude that both
candidates are fiscally prudent because both are attempting to
reserve the surpluses in the Social Security system for debt
reduction.''
</P>
<P>
   There is another index of shared prudence. Bush's tax cuts do
not approach the level urged by Ronald Reagan in 1980. Gore's
Medicare drug plan is nowhere near as costly as the national health
insurance plan Bill Clinton promised in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   Side-by-side comparisons are virtually meaningless. The
candidates assume surpluses of very different sizes, and Gore's
proposals cover the years 2001 to 2010 while Bush's cover 2002 to
2006.
</P>
<P>
   These are, moreover, campaign promises, not blood oaths.
Candidates change their minds after election, like Clinton on
middle-class tax cuts, or when circumstances change, as when a
freshly inaugurated Jimmy Carter had to confront rising inflation.
</P>
<P>
   But each approach can be judged for internal consistency _ and,
with less certainty, for the plausibility of the assumptions on
which it is based.
</P>
<P>
   On those scores, Reischauer says both candidates ``are skating
right along the edge of the ice,'' by proposing to ``absorb all of
the projected on-budget surplus'' in tax cuts and new spending.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's surplus is bigger, $586 billion in five years. Gore
relies on estimates by the White House Office of Management and
Budget, which expects the surplus to be $164 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The difference is not created by the old-fashioned ``rosy
scenario'' of the '70s and '80s, when government made wildly
optimistic guesses about growth rates. Lawrence B. Lindsey, Bush's
chief economic adviser, notes that among other forecasts, Wall
Street's Blue Chip forecast calls for 3.2 percent annual growth,
while the Bush campaign predicts 2.7 percent. ``We actually are
quite cautious on the growth side,'' he said. (The White House
budget office and Gore predict 2.6 percent.)
</P>
<P>
   Instead, the difference arises because Bush makes a much lower
estimate of what Congress will spend than do the Office of
Management and Budget and Gore. The agency estimate basically
assumes that spending will grow at about the rate of inflation, and
the Congressional Budget Office's latest study ducked the issue, by
offering three guesses. Lindsey said, ``Congress is capable of
spending that much money,'' but under pressure from a new President
Bush, he thinks it would not.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, but restraint from the Congress that thinks of the
constitutionally required decennial census as a spending emergency,
is pretty optimistic. Reischauer calls the Gore assumptions ``a
good deal more plausible,'' but even so, he says, Congress might
spend even more.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp says the Bush accounting overlooks that his tax
cuts and spending increases mean the national debt will not be cut
as much as the Congressional Budget Office had assumed, and that
interest payments on the national debt will cost another $56
billion. But $483 billion for tax cuts, plus promises of $46
billion for health care, $13 billion for education and $25 billion
for defense add up to $567 billion; so only $19 billion of surplus
would be left to pay $56 billion in added debt interest.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey replies that the issue is, ``Have we left ourselves
enough room? I think we have.'' He says Bush will soon speak on
``government reform'' and lay out enough spending cuts to make
things balance.
</P>
<P>
   The Gore camp also contends that Bush's tax cuts would balloon
in later years. Gore charged on Monday that even if the economy
grew fast enough to afford them through 2006, the last year the
Bush campaign's documents discuss, there is no hope that it could
pay for the $2.1 trillion they would cost through 2010.
</P>
<P>
   Lindsey says his estimate of the cost of the tax cut through
2010 is $1.3 trillion, and that it is affordable because
``surpluses grow quite quickly after 2006.''
</P>
<P>
   But out-year surpluses are the ``most speculative,'' said Robert
Bixby, executive director of the Concord Coalition, a nonpartisan
group of deficit hawks. That is a problem for the Gore campaign,
too. Three-fifths of the $746 billion, 10-year surplus it wants to
use would arrive in the last three years of its plan.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's $250 billion net tax cut is vague. Its details have not
been spelled out, but it will include some, if not all, of the cuts
proposed by Clinton in February. Some of the $146 billion Gore has
proposed for expanding health insurance for the poor comes in the
form of a tax credit, and so is also part of that $250 billion.
</P>
<P>
   The overlaps and vagueness of the Gore proposals invite
skepticism. For several weeks Gore's Web site produced nothing at
all when surfers clicked on ``Keeping the Budget Balanced.'' A
murky pie chart appeared on Tuesday, listing: $432 billion for
``Medicare Solvency and Prescription Drug Benefit,'' $380 billion
for ``Health care coverage and tax relief'' (with three asterisks
indicating ``includes other investments''), and $64 billion for
``debt service.''
</P>
<P>
   Ari Fleischer, a spokesman for the Bush campaign, said: ``It
appears that the vice president is doing his best to hide how much
money he wants to spend. Is it any wonder that sometimes people
question whether the vice president has a credibility problem?'' He
said he believed that if Gore is elected ``his first inclination
will be to spend more taxpayer money, particularly if that is what
organized labor wants.''
</P>
<P>
   But each side believes in the surplus. ``Nobody's lying. They
just have different assumptions,'' Bixby said. But those
assumptions ``of huge surpluses as far as the eye can see,'' should
be treated very skeptically.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1441EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
