<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0127 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 14:44 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1024 &Cx1f; taf-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-JAPAN-NYT &LR;      04-29 0704
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-JAPAN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ISLAND TALKS GET NEW PUSH FROM RUSSIA AND JAPAN 
</HEADLINE>
   By PATRICK E. TYLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ST. PETERSBURG, Russia _ In their first meeting as the new
leaders of Russia and Japan, President Vladimir Putin and Prime
Minister Yoshiro Mori pledged on Saturday to meet often, to call
each other by their nicknames and to try to conclude a long-sought
peace treaty by the end of the year.
</P>
<P>
   Such a treaty would formally end decades of antagonism between
the countries over a group of islands seized by Russia at the end
of World War II. In making this pledge, both leaders were
reaffirming the commitment of their predecessors to reach this
goal.
</P>
<P>
   Over the last two years, Russia and Japan have exchanged
proposals and counterproposals over one of the most nettlesome
territorial disputes left over from the war. Japan calls the
islands its Northern Territories, and Russia claims them as part of
the Kurile Islands chain.
</P>
<P>
   Russia forcefully reasserted its sovereignty over the islands on
April 21 by firing on, boarding and seizing a Japanese fishing boat
near there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We attach great significance to concluding a peace treaty by
the end of the year,'' Mori said at a joint news conference in the
Winter Palace of the Romanov czars, which now houses the Hermitage
Museum.
</P>
<P>
   For his part, Putin said he had accepted an invitation to go to
Tokyo this summer for a visit that both sides hope will yield a
compromise on the islands.
</P>
<P>
   For Russia, concluding the treaty would likely pave the way for
greater economic assistance from Japan, which has lent Russia $1
billion over the last three years. For Japan, ending the dispute
would remove a major domestic issue and a brake on overall
relations with Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   Putin and Mori spent a full day together, beginning with formal
exchanges in the Mikhailovsky Palace, which houses the Russian
Museum, then moving to the nearby Winter Palace. After lunch and a
performance of chamber music, Putin and Mori emerged to say that
they had already established such a close personal relationship
that they agreed to call each Yoshi and Volodya, the familiar forms
for their names.
</P>
<P>
   The two leaders also discussed preparations for the meeting in
Okinawa in July of the world's major industrial powers, and
Russia's view of nuclear disarmament issues.
</P>
<P>
   It was almost preordained that the Russian and Japanese leaders
would make no breakthrough on the sensitive issue of the islands
during their first meeting, especially with Mori's Liberal
Democratic Party facing parliamentary elections in June. Any
compromise on Japan's sovereignty over the islands could raise a
political storm for Mori, who made Moscow the first stop of his
inaugural tour of major Western capitals.
</P>
<P>
   Mori, who became prime minister this month after Prime Minister
Keizo Obuchi had a stroke and fell into a coma, also will visit
Italy, Germany, France, Great Britain, Canada and the United
States, where he will meet President Clinton on May 5.
</P>
<P>
   In the coming weeks, negotiations are expected on how to
structure a compromise on the Kurile Islands.
</P>
<P>
   After the collapse of the Soviet Union, President Boris Yeltsin
of Russia consistently balked in the face of Japanese demands to
return the islands as a precondition for any significant
development in economic and trade relations. But since 1997, Japan
has reversed policy, and under former Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto, it expanded trade and economic assistance to Russia.
</P>
<P>
   Yeltsin's most recent approach was to suggest a treaty of peace,
friendship and cooperation without resolving the islands issue.
Japan, however, had held to its demand to restore Japanese
sovereignty and delineate new borders.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Hashimoto-Yeltsin relationship became so effective
that the former Japanese leader turned up in Moscow last week to
see Yeltsin, now in retirement, and to determine how deeply
Yeltsin's successor was committed to resolving the territorial
issue this year.
</P>
<P>
   The Kremlin response was to state to a visiting Japan-Russia
friendship federation that Putin ``has inherited responsibility for
the conclusion of a Russo-Japanese peace treaty from Boris
Yeltsin.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
