<SLUG> BC-SOC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: FOR OLYMPIC SOCCER, LET THE MACHINATIONS BEGIN
</HEADLINE>
  By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   HERSHEY, Pa. _ For all the payoffs and ticket-hoarding scandals
involving the adults who run the Olympic movement, the Games still
retain some vestige of honor _ largely stemming from the enthusiasm
of the athletes.
</P>
<P>
   The aura of the Games was palpable as the Americans ran onto the
field wielding American flags after their 4-0 nearly textbook romp
over Guatemala on Friday night qualified them for September's
soccer tournament in Sydney, Australia.
</P>
<P>
   It is said that the Olympic Games are the most visible sports
event in which athletes actually make sacrifices, as opposed to
professional athletes who reap millions for their endeavors.
Sacrifice is surely the case for the kayakers and archers who
emerge from the ozone every four years, but there is also a risk
involved for these young soccer professionals.
</P>
<P>
   ``The World Cup is the greatest event in soccer, but I knew
about the Olympics before the World Cup,'' said John O'Brien, the
U.S. midfielder, now a serious pro in the Netherlands.
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien can remember the 1984 Summer Games, when he and his
sister Ann would watch television and then run outside to re-enact
the track-and-field events.
</P>
<P>
   ``She won because she's older,'' said O'Brien, now 22, noting
that she went on to play soccer at Yale, so his winning the family
silver medal was hardly a disgrace.
</P>
<P>
   This year, O'Brien and most of his teammates _ all infused with
the Olympic dream, even with its inherent conflicts with their
careers _ have qualified for the Games.
</P>
<P>
   All but one of the 18 Yanks are members of a pro club, either in
the United States or Europe. Going to the Games will involve taking
a sanctioned leave of absence, with no assurances that everything
will be the same.
</P>
<P>
   ``It has a negative side,'' O'Brien conceded. ``This is a
cutthroat business. You could come back and find somebody else
playing your role, but the Olympics are a childhood dream.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Brien has as much to lose as anybody, having forgone college
to join the soccer factory at Ajax Amsterdam, one of the great
teams of Europe. He is now a regular, but that is always a fluid
status in sports.
</P>
<P>
   By soccer law, the clubs are supposed to release their players
to the national teams for major international competition like the
World Cup, the Olympics and so on. But coaches, being coaches,
manage to lay not-so-subtle threats and guilt trips on their
players. Like: why would you want to play in the Olympics when you
could help us win the league championship?
</P>
<P>
   ``The country takes precedence over the club, and that's the way
it should be,'' said Chris Albright, the U.S. forward who plays for
DC United, which has quickly become the New York Yankees of Major
League Soccer. Albright played what might have been the most
creative game of his pro career Friday night, but he and his
teammate could be affected, one way or another, by the Olympic
wild-card intrigue.
</P>
<P>
   Because the world soccer body, known as FIFA, does not want the
Olympics to match the level of skill and excitement of the
quadrennial World Cup, the Olympic tournament is geared for players
under 23. There is a gimmick, however: each qualifying nation is
now allowed to pick three players of any age.
</P>
<P>
   The United States squad could add three MLS stalwarts and get
little grousing from U.S. coaches. Or, they could dip into the
growing list of Americans who have gone to Europe to gain money and
competition in equally high ratio.
</P>
<P>
   The gnashing of teeth would be heard across the Atlantic if
America tried to recruit Eddie Lewis, now playing for Fulham of
London, or one of their grizzled goalkeepers, Brad Friedel, now
with Liverpool, or Kasey Keller, now with Rayo Vallecano of Spain.
</P>
<P>
   ``They'd scream, but we'd get the players,'' said Robert
Contiguglia, the president of the U.S. Soccer Federation, who said
he does not believe the United States needs to bring in a
goalkeeper.
</P>
<P>
   Any way you look at it, three U.S. players who celebrated Friday
night may never get to Sydney. One U.S. player with a slight case
of paranoia is Landon Donovan, the absurdly mature 17-year-old who
scored two goals in his first start in three qualifying games here.
</P>
<P>
   Donovan, one of the youngest Americans ever recruited overseas,
is now learning his craft in the classic European guild-like system
of the reserve squad of Bayer Leverkusen in Germany. There is a
history of national coaches deciding that goal-scoring wunderkinds
are too young for the big event; Argentina cut the teen-aged Diego
Armando Maradona and won the 1978 World Cup without him.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's always pressure,'' Donovan said Friday. ``I'm happy to
be part of this, and I would hope to stay part of it, but you can
never tell.''
</P>
<P>
   It is a refreshing position for U.S. soccer, to have such talent
stored away in Europe. The United States reached a high level
Friday, scoring three times within 22 minutes to totally avoid the
specter of being humiliated by a smaller Latin-American country on
home soil.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks were able to show their stuff, including a set play
for the third goal, when Ben Olsen of DC United flicked a soft free
kick to Josh Wolff of the Chicago Fire, who nudged the ball toward
the goal mouth. Albright drew several defenders but let the ball go
through his legs (``dummied it,'' in soccer parlance) and Donovan,
all alone, tapped it into the goal.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't have missed if I tried,'' Donovan said.
</P>
<P>
   The Yanks play Honduras Sunday in the championship game between
two teams that have already qualified for Sydney. The jockeying to
upgrade the U.S. squad is just beginning.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1448EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
