<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0133 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 15:09 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1034 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-VIETNAM-REMEMBRANCE04     04-29 1093
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-REMEMBRANCE0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    For all who lived through war, Vietnam memories ring clear
 &HT;    By Bill Hendrick
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Luke Dollar hopes he won't see it, but he'll have to
leave his TV off and his newspaper in the driveway to miss it.
</P>
<P>
   The famous photograph, showing GIs frantically evacuating troops
and refugees from the top of a building as Saigon fell 25 years ago
today, still haunts the 52-year-old Vietnam veteran. It makes him
angry.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think there's a Vietnam vet alive that doesn't feel
terrible watching the way we left Saigon,'' says Dollar, an
insurance executive. ``It just makes me sick to my stomach, like
all my friends just died in vain.''
</P>
<P>
   For those younger than 35, the Vietnam War may seem as distant
in history as Lee's surrender at Appomattox. But for the generation
that fought in Vietnam _ or avoided fighting, or campaigned to stop
the war _ today's anniversary of the war's end is sure to evoke
emotions from pride to shame to sadness.
</P>
<P>
   Dollar never considered avoiding the draft. He spent his year in
Vietnam walking point as a scout dog handler.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw plenty of action, and it's a horrible experience,'' he
says. ``I try not to think about it much. But sometimes you do. You
see things, like that picture, and you just do.''
</P>
<P>
   Peter Nail, a 54-year-old executive-recruiter, was reared to be
patriotic, but he blanched when his draft notice arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was 1968, and I'd just graduated and I realized, `Idiot me
hadn't joined the reserves,''' Nail says.
</P>
<P>
   Nail still wonders what happened to some of the men he met in
Vietnam. Many knew each other only by nicknames, making it almost
impossible to find out who survived and who's listed among the
58,199 dead on the Vietnam Memorial Wall in Washington.
</P>
<P>
   When vets do get together, even those who've never met, there's
still a bond. ``Vietnam vets have an automatic reaction to each
other,'' Nail says. ``You can look at them and know. You can talk
and understand what others can't.''
</P>
<P>
   Don Pardue, 54, agrees. Most of his best friends are Vietnam
veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Pardue, who owns an Atlanta real-estate firm, got ``the note
from hell'' _ his draft notice _ when he took a quarter off from
college to earn tuition fees. He was accepted to officer's school
and arrived ``in country'' in July 1967 as a lieutenant.
</P>
<P>
   Two months later he was severely wounded, and within weeks was
shipped home ``with a bullet in my left lung for life.'' He earned
a college degree and is now active in the Atlanta Vietnam Veterans
Business Association, a group that, among other things, tries to
erase the image of Vietnam veterans as anti-social losers. In fact,
most vets came back and became successful, both in business and
life, Pardue says.
</P>
<P>
   ``This 25th anniversary is possibly a benchmark for healing,''
says Pardue, who still remembers when returning vets were scorned.
``It was very sad, depressing and disappointing for sure. But I
think that's changing. I think the sacrifices we made carries a
little more respect and admiration than it did 25 years ago.''
</P>
<P>
   Max Torrence, a 53-year-old mortgage firm executive was drafted
in 1966 and spent more than 20 years in the Army, retiring 12 years
ago as a lieutenant colonel. He says the broad public support for
the Persian Gulf War in 1991 caused many Americans to rethink old
views about Vietnam veterans.
</P>
<P>
   Torrence is a member of a military helicopter pilot's
association. One day, he was wearing an association T-shirt when a
boy walked up to him and said, ``Are you a Vietnam veteran?''
Torrence said yes. ``This kid said, 'Thank you for what you did.'
He was about 14, and it choked me up. It kind of renews your faith
in the youth of our country.
</P>
<P>
   For Cathy Campbell, the anniversary is a different kind of
benchmark. Her fighter-pilot father, William Campbell, was shot
down over Laos in 1969 and is still listed as missing in action.
</P>
<P>
   ``The war is getting some good publicity for a change, and it
feels good,'' Campbell says. ``It's almost a validation of what
happened. People are starting to think and talk about it more now,
and all these years the pain has been underground.''
</P>
<P>
   Most young men of the Vietnam era found a way not to go, either
by attending college for a deferment or by getting into state
militias or reserve outfits that almost guaranteed they'd stay home
_ or simply by being fortunate enough to get a high number in the
draft lottery.
</P>
<P>
   Avoiding service, though, is now haunting many of those men,
says Russ Christensen, 56, a humanities professor at Hamline
University in Minnesota who has studied the phenomenon _ and who
concedes he finagled his way out of combat himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a lack of community among men my age,'' Christensen
says. ``I have a hard time even talking to Vietnam veterans. And I
don't go to Vietnam movies.''
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence Baskir, co-author with William Straus of the book,
``Chance and Circumstance: The Draft, the War and the Vietnam
Generation,'' says ``every male who came of age during that time is
a veteran of Vietnam'' _ whether they served or not.
</P>
<P>
   Many who avoided service still feel ``very guilty about their
ability to avoid the worst consequences of the Vietnam War.''
</P>
<P>
   Conversely, many young men who were raised on John Wayne war
movies and reared by World War II vets chose to serve in Vietnam
because it's what they thought their fathers expected them to do,
Baskir says. Vietnam's shadow encompasses more than just the vets,
their loved ones and the avoiders. Even people who had no direct
connection still feel the war.
</P>
<P>
   For Peggy Barlett, an anthropology professor at Emory
University, the war still evokes bitter memories of a war fought
for suspect purposes. After she saw the movie ``Platoon'' more than
a decade ago, Barlett ``felt deep shame that I hadn't worked harder
to stop the war,'' she says.
</P>
<P>
   It there's a universal theme in the remembrances _ of vets,
their families, the men who didn't serve and people who wished
they'd been able to do more to stop the war _ it's one of horror.
</P>
<P>
   ``All the news about this anniversary is good,'' says Dollar,
one of the vets, ``because to me, it's like the Holocaust: I don't
think you should ever forget.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think all kids should have to serve their country for a
couple of years,'' Nail says, ``but I don't want my boys to ever go
into combat, or anyone else's kids. There's got to be a better
way.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
