<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0136 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 15:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1037 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-VIETNAM-PHOTOS0430-CO     04-29 1346
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-VIETNAM-PHOTOS0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Photos prompt stories of war
 &HT;    By Jim Auchmutey
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ If ever a picture told a story, it's the picture Larry
Burrows took of a muddy medevac zone during a 1966 firefight in
Vietnam. One of the best-known images of the war, the bleak tableau
is prominently displayed in the ``Requiem'' exhibit of Vietnam
photojournalism at the Atlanta History Center. It shows two wounded
Marines, one sprawled in the dirt, both legs bandaged, his blank
face splattered with red muck. The other soldier, his head swaddled
in a bloody cloth, appears to be stumbling toward his buddy with
arms outstretched. As it turns out, there's much more to the story.
</P>
<P>
   The man with the head wound is Jeremiah Purdie, a gunnery
sergeant now retired and living in Fayetteville, N.C. When Burrows
snapped the picture, an artillery round had just driven shrapnel
into Purdie's leg and into the flesh behind his left ear. He wasn't
reaching out for anyone; he was being led to a chopper, stunned at
what he had witnessed.
</P>
<P>
   ``The artillery explosion killed my commanding officer and tore
our radio man half in two,'' he remembers. ``I had just moved to
the right, or I would have been dead, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The fatal round came from U.S. guns; according to the Marine
Corps history of the battle, the Americans were killed by friendly
fire.
</P>
<P>
   It was early October, and the Marine 3rd Division was opposing a
major infiltration of North Vietnamese regulars near the
demilitarized zone that separated the Communist north from the
south. Burrows, a Life magazine photographer who had been covering
Vietnam for years, followed the Americans as they assaulted a
jungle stronghold designated Hill 484. He shot 36 rolls of film and
sent them to the States without the detailed information he usually
supplied for captions.
</P>
<P>
   ``The fighting was too intense,'' says his son, Russell Burrows,
a book publisher in New York. ``In his telex, he said it was
dangerous to be waving a white note pad.''
</P>
<P>
   Life dispatched a correspondent from Saigon to identify the
soldiers. He found Purdie, but he didn't get a name for the Marine
on the ground _ perhaps because the magazine didn't plan to run his
picture. The 10-page photo essay that Life published about the
fighting included only a vertical shot of Purdie.
</P>
<P>
   Burrows evidently preferred the frame with both Marines. In
1971, after the photographer died in a helicopter crash over Laos,
his editors found the image in a slide carousel he had used during
talks he gave on the war. Life ran it for the first time in a
tribute to Burrows; it has become the most published photograph of
his distinguished career.
</P>
<P>
   Purdie has gotten used to seeing his bleeding self.
</P>
<P>
   ``I flipped on the TV the other day, and there I was,'' he says.
The picture was on the screen because Time Warner had just
announced that the latest incarnation of Life would cease
publication.
</P>
<P>
   Now 69, Purdie has been out of the Corps for more than 30 years.
But he can still fit into his uniform to speak to schoolchildren.
The son of a poor family in Newport News, Va., he enlisted in 1948
because he thought the Marines had the sharpest-looking uniforms.
He saw combat in Korea and was nearing the end of a 20-year hitch
when the war in Vietnam started escalating.
</P>
<P>
   Purdie was wounded three times in six months. The photograph
captures his last moments in the country; moments later, he was
taken by helicopter to a hospital ship and never returned to
Southeast Asia. Doctors removed the shrapnel from his leg but left
the piece behind his ear, saying it would work its way out. It was
extracted in 1992.
</P>
<P>
   ``I carried that piece of metal around in my head for 26
years,'' Purdie says, with a laugh.
</P>
<P>
   Today he displays it over his fireplace, an evil, jagged
keepsake mounted to a framed print of the photo.
</P>
<P>
   Russell Burrows and his wife, Barbara Baker-Burrows, a former
photo editor at Life, located Purdie years ago and have stayed in
touch. They've always wondered who the other soldier was; Purdie
didn't know and neither have the veterans at the Marine reunions
they've attended. The couple would love to identify him for a book
of Burrows' Vietnam photos they plan to publish next year.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've heard from people over the years claiming to be him, but
nothing has ever come of it,'' Russell Burrows says.
</P>
<P>
   One of the more intriguing claims came from Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   For years, an Atlanta family has believed that the Marine in the
mud was their son, Gene Webb, a former high school football lineman
who was drafted and shipped out to Vietnam in September 1966.
</P>
<P>
   Webb's family saw the photo years after he came home and decided
it had to be him. They have the same eyes, the same profile, the
same chunky build. They even have leg wounds in the same places.
</P>
<P>
   The similarities are so striking that when Webb went to see the
current photo exhibit ``Requiem'' at the Atlanta History Center,
several museum-goers asked whether he wasn't the grunt on the wall.
One man, wearing a Virginia Military Institute sweatshirt, looked
back and forth between the blown-up, back-lit image of the young,
mud-caked soldier and the plump, gray-bearded veteran standing
before him with a walking cane. He finally asked, ``How many men
did you lose in that fight?''
</P>
<P>
   Webb couldn't answer him. Now 53 and working in a lithography
shop, he has never known whether he was the soldier in the photo.
He doesn't like to talk about Vietnam. He still takes prescription
medication to quell bad dreams and has managed to forget whole
stretches of his time in the combat zone.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't remember exactly how I got wounded,'' he says. ``I
just remember waking up in a hospital with a Purple Heart pinned to
my pillow.''
</P>
<P>
   Webb was curious about the photo _ if only for his family's sake
_ so he phoned Purdie and they compared notes. The two veterans
have much in common: Both suffered shrapnel wounds, both have
Purple Hearts, both have developed ailments they blame on Agent
Orange, the herbicide U.S. aircraft dumped on the jungles where
they were fighting.
</P>
<P>
   But Purdie quickly concluded that Webb couldn't have been the
man. The gunnery sergeant was in a position to know which units
were fighting on Hill 484, and he couldn't recall Webb's having
been there. In all likelihood, it wasn't. Marine Corps records
confirm that Pvt. Harold Eugene Webb was assigned to the 1st
division, 5th regiment, 1st battalion, which was deployed 100 miles
away near Danang. He saw his share of action in Vietnam, but there
wasn't a legendary photographer around to document it.
</P>
<P>
   Webb took the news philosophically. ``I figured it couldn't be
me,'' he says. ``My mother always told me to wear clean underwear
in case I got hurt. The man in that picture is definitely not
wearing clean underwear.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the first time families have mistakenly seen loved
ones in the fading images of Vietnam. Two years ago, The Washington
Post published a lengthy article about an Atlanta area man's
pilgrimage to Vietnam to visit the spot where his older brother was
killed in 1967. The story was based in large part on a picture that
the photographer and the younger brother erroneously identified as
his slain sibling. It turned out to be a Rhode Island man who was
surprised to see his picture in the newspaper so many years later.
</P>
<P>
   ``This sort of thing happens pretty often,'' says Bill James, a
Dallas veteran who is the unofficial historian of the First Marine
Division Association.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, it happened to James. During the Tet Offensive of 1968,
he took part in the bloody fighting for the city of Hue. A
much-published photo of that battle shows a wounded Marine getting
an IV line as he's evacuated on a tank. ``You can barely see his
face,'' James says, ``but my family thought it was me. It wasn't.
They just wanted to believe it was.''
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, in the cloudy window of war, people see what they
need to see.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
