<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 15:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1045 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-NY     04-29 1010
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-RAPTORS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAMBY EXPECTS AN EARFUL FROM THE FANS IN TORONTO
</HEADLINE>
  By SELENA ROBERTS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In a draft-day whirlwind, Marcus Camby was picked up and plopped
down in a strange land where a queen and a loon decorated the money
and goons were celebrated on ice.
</P>
<P>
   It was just across the border, but, at first, Canada was, for
Camby, well ... difficult. Nothing personal. The city of Toronto
seemed culturally hip, and the people were about as cool and
likable as ice cream. But no ESPN? The Toronto Raptors rookie would
flip to one channel, and he'd find a hockey game. He'd flip to
another, and he'd see hockey highlights.
</P>
<P>
   ``On TV, they'd even show minor league hockey and junior league
hockey,'' Camby said after the New York Knicks' practice on Friday.
``When I got up there, it was the NBA's second year of existence. A
game was almost like a tennis match. It was all quiet. And if
someone scored, then they'd cheer.''
</P>
<P>
   That was 1996. After four years of cramming on the difference
between a hand-check and a cross-check, the fans who pack the Air
Canada Center don't need cue cards anymore.
</P>
<P>
   They know when to cheer a great play. And, as Camby has learned,
they know when to heckle their enemies. In his first trip back to
Toronto just over a year ago _ months removed from the June 1998
trade that sent Charles Oakley from the Knicks to the basketball
outpost and allowed Camby, a Connecticut native, to click his heels
and go home _ he received a rude welcome from Raptors fans.
</P>
<P>
   As his name was announced, as the energetic Camby bounded onto
the floor as a Knick, the sound of a crying baby was played over
the arena's public address system. It was clear. The Toronto fans
had come to embrace the Tonka-tough Oakley and had turned on the
finesse game of Camby, their fragile former star.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Camby is braced for whatever happens Sunday. In the
aftermath of his critique of Toronto coach Butch Carter, and in the
swirl of excitement the Raptors fans are sure to feel Sunday for
Game 3 of this best-of-5 first-round series, a hostile reaction
toward Camby is bound to surface.
</P>
<P>
   ``It doesn't matter,'' Camby said. ``If we can pull this one out
on Sunday, I'll show you some reaction.''
</P>
<P>
   If the Knicks take Game 3, they will eliminate the Raptors and
move on to the next round against either the Miami Heat or the
Detroit Pistons. If Latrell Sprewell can hold his own against Vince
Carter once more in a Knicks victory, the moment will give Camby
the satisfaction of closing out his former team on its home court.
</P>
<P>
   He's ready. As tipoff closes in, Camby won't need the caffeine
hit he gets from his customary two cups of pre-game coffee. He
won't need rap music, pep talks or prodding. As it has been
throughout the series, Camby's body will probably give off a
100-watt glow from his own energy.
</P>
<P>
   This is where Camby has to be careful. This is how he has found
trouble in this series. In Game 1, Camby was so charged, his groove
blew a fuse. He was so convinced that Butch Carter had put special
emphasis on stopping him, he tried too hard, picked up three quick
fouls and finished with only five rebounds and four points.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 2, Camby was back to popping out of the paint for 13
rebounds, but opted for rushed tap-ins over emphatic dunks and
skittish layups instead of an aggressive putback. By the end of
Wednesday night, Camby was a forgettable 4 for 14 from the field,
scoring nine points.
</P>
<P>
   ``Brendan called me on the day off,'' Camby said, referring to
the Knicks assistant coach Brendan Malone. ``He was going over game
tape with me on the phone. He stays on me all the time. He just
told me to concentrate and slow down. I think I was so energetic in
Game 2, I rushed shots and didn't finish strong going to the
basket.''
</P>
<P>
   He was too up, too emotional. Was this a reaction to Butch
Carter? Was it the fever of the playoffs? ``Probably a combination
of both,'' Camby said. ``I have to stay in control.''
</P>
<P>
   He maintained that balance in the playoffs last year. Camby used
his adrenaline to elevate his game, particularly against Atlanta
and Indiana. He picked his spots, slithered through the cracks in
the defense like smoke and devastated the spirits of the Hawks and
the Pacers. Just when the defense forced a Knick to miss a shot,
just when the opposing fans started to rise in the stands, Camby
would snuff out their excitement by levitating over the paint for a
dunk.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's very emotional,'' Malone said. ``His game is speed and
quickness. And sometimes you have to harness that speed and
quickness. You don't want to rob him of his emotion. Last year, in
Indiana and Atlanta, that energy from the second unit helped us.
You don't put a stop on a mustang. You let those guys run. You let
him run, but he has to run with some intelligence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing about Marcus, he's very bright. I think he'll play
well.''
</P>
<P>
   Camby was smart enough to find his niche in New York. It wasn't
easy at first. Finding himself compared to a folk hero like Oakley
was just the start of his dysfunctional beginning as a Knick.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was definitely unfair,'' Camby said. ``Last year, I mean,
replacing Oak, he's irreplaceable. You can't replace a guy like
that because he brings so much to the table. People expected me to
be him. I can only be me, and that's all I can do.''
</P>
<P>
   The debate between pro-Camby and pro-Oakley factions raged until
the playoff last year. That's when coach Jeff Van Gundy was forced
to trust Camby because of injuries. That's when Camby developed his
identity as a Knick.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think the debate is there now,'' Camby said. ``Oak has
gone to Toronto and been the veteran they needed. And people have
gotten to know what I can bring to the team here.''
</P>
<P>
   In Toronto, they still remember him, too. In the franchise's
short history, there are few villains. Camby is among the first.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever they do, fine,'' Camby said. ``The satisfaction I'll
get out of it is when we close this thing out. Then I'll be
happy.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1533EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
