<HEADLINE>
KILLING GRABS AUTHOR'S ATTENTION 
</HEADLINE>
   By MARK ZALOUDEK   
 Herald-Tribune, Sarasota, Fla.  
 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SARASOTA, Fla. _ Best-selling author Ann Rule, who has built a
reputation writing about twisted, real-life murders, finds Sheila
Bellush's death too intriguing to pass up.
</P>
<P>
   The 1997 contract murder of the mother of quadruplets, who was
living in hiding in Sarasota in fear of her ex-husband in Texas,
will be the subject of Rule's 19th book.
</P>
<P>
   Simon &AMP; Schuster expects to publish the hardcover version of the
book, tentatively titled ``Every Breath You Take,'' next year. A
paperback edition will be out in 2002.
</P>
<P>
   Rule says there are several aspects of the murder, including
charges that Allen Blackthorne, Bellush's millionaire ex-husband,
planned it, that incline her to write about it.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you get a tremendously successful suspect who seems
like they would be the last person in the world to be charged with
murder, that really gets my attention,'' she said. ``People who
have everything, why would they risk throwing it all away, if
indeed he's guilty.''
</P>
<P>
   A growing number of letters and e-mails from Rule's fans
suggesting that she take a closer look into the troubling murder
also helped to sway her.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my readers have picked the topics of my past six
books,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   The popular Seattle author has written about other well-known
crimes and criminals, including serial killer Ted Bundy in ``The
Stranger Beside Me.'' Her current best seller is about prominent
Delaware lawyer Thomas Capano, who killed the governor's secretary
and dumped her body at sea after she tried to end their
relationship in 1996. Capano is on Delaware's death row. The book
is called ``... And Never Let Her Go: Thomas Capano, the Deadly
Seducer.''
</P>
<P>
   Rule plans to sit through the back-to-back trials this summer of
Blackthorne and Jose Luis Del Toro Jr., who is accused of being the
hit man.
</P>
<P>
   Blackthorne faces federal charges in Texas of committing
domestic violence across state lines and conspiring to commit
murder. His June trial will be in San Antonio. Del Toro's murder
trial is expected to be held in Sarasota in July.
</P>
<P>
   Daniel Alex Rocha and Samuel Gonzales, two other San Antonio men
with ties to Blackthorne, are serving time for their involvement in
the death of the 35-year-old mother of six. They may testify at
both trials.
</P>
<P>
   Bellush was found in her Gulf Gate home shot and stabbed on Nov.
7, 1997. Her 2-year-old quadruplets were nearby, toddling through
the blood unharmed and wearing life jackets.
</P>
<P>
   (The Herald-Tribune in Sarasota, Fla., is part of the New York
Times Regional Newspaper Group.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
