<HEADER>
A1056 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NUCLEAR-TRANSPORT-NYT     04-29 0835
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUCLEAR-TRANSPORT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
REPORT CITES FLAWS IN U.S. NUCLEAR COMPLEX 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1996, a truck carrying nuclear warheads skidded off an icy
road in Nebraska and crashed.
</P>
<P>
   For half a day, no one in government, including the president
and his cabinet, knew the degree of danger, or if any nuclear
material had escaped into the environment, because radiation
monitors on the government's fleet of weapon trucks had been
removed after complaints from drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers had said the monitors showed that they were facing
potential health risks from their cargoes.
</P>
<P>
   These accusations have been made by Robert Alvarez, who from
1993 to 1999 was a policy adviser in the Department of Energy,
which runs the nation's nuclear complex. Before that, as a Senate
aide, he specialized in helping oversee the department.
</P>
<P>
   In an article for a journal, Alvarez calls problems with the
atomic fleet ``emblematic of the department's inept and often
arrogant management culture.'' The mindset has become so backward,
he says, that the complex is now basically a ticking time bomb
waiting to go off in a serious accident or an inadvertent nuclear
blast.
</P>
<P>
   His 12-page analysis appears in the May/June issue of The
Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists, which was posted over the
weekend on the group's Web site, www.thebulletin.org.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Energy Department officials said that although
the department's handling of weapons had problems, Alvarez was
blowing them out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   In his article, Alvarez said the uncertainty in the Nebraska
incident cleared up after a federal crisis team arrived and found
no danger. But the underlying woes persisted.
</P>
<P>
   Energy officials and outside experts agree that the department
has serious problems, with roots in the vast responsibilities and
liabilities incurred during the Cold War in making 70,000 nuclear
arms. The challenges now lie in old age and downsizing. The
department owns more than 20,700 facilities and buildings,
including 89 nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major elements of Energy's complex are closing down,'' Alvarez
said in the article, ``leaving a huge unfunded and dangerous
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   The department's nuclear site at Oak Ridge, Tenn., he says,
stores 189 tons of highly enriched uranium _ enough for 9,450 bombs
the size of the one that destroyed Hiroshima. Yet some of the
atomic fuel sits in ``decades-old wooden buildings vulnerable to
fire,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   Oak Ridge and six other sites, Alvarez said, are at risk of
accidents the industry calls criticality, which occur when atomic
fuel undergoes a chain reaction and emits a bluish flash. In Japan
last year, such an accident exposed dozens of workers to radiation,
three of them to huge doses.
</P>
<P>
   ``Energy Department schedules to correct unsafe nuclear material
storage and processing at Oak Ridge and elsewhere continue to
slip,'' Alvarez wrote, in part because repair costs are higher than
expected.
</P>
<P>
   He said the department's Pantex Plant, in Amarillo, Texas, is a
time bomb. Mostly by hand, workers there are disassembling nuclear
weapons at a rate of hundreds a year.
</P>
<P>
   The Pantex workers have used the wrong tools and procedures,
Alvarez wrote, even as officials have bent rules and censored
safety reports. He quoted Frank Rowsome, a senior safety official
in the Energy Department, as saying in an internal department
report, ``There have been `a flock' of near misses.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez said Rowsome had called for Pantex to be shut down until
its safety problems had been fixed.
</P>
<P>
   Though a former government insider, Alvarez is seen by some
federal and industry experts as having an ax to grind. He was
considered something of an anti-nuclear crusader during his tenure
at the Energy Department, and was fired in December after his
daughter reported him and his wife to the police for growing
marijuana. His wife told the court that she used the marijuana to
treat a medical condition that produced migraines and muscle pain.
</P>
<P>
   Since the accident in Japan, Energy Department officials said,
special teams have been assessing criticality safety and found room
for improvement but no serious dangers. At Pantex, they said, the
teams have not found safety problems sufficient to warrant shutting
down the disassembly plant.
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to Alvarez's overall accusations, Ellen Livingston, the
department's senior adviser for environmental affairs, said,
``We've gone to great lengths to develop safety and training
programs to limit the hazards because we recognize the handling of
nuclear materials is a risky business.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, who is now a consultant to anti-nuclear groups, said
the department was wrong in playing down his charges but right in
calling him an antagonist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I was their golden boy and they booted me out
and now it's sour grapes,'' he said in an interview. ``They used me
as an internal critic. If I've got an ax, it's one I've been
grinding for 25 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
