<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 15:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1057 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-JEFFERSON-MONTICELLO0     04-29 1469
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JEFFERSON-MONTICELLO0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Sparks may fly at forum over recognizing president's possible
black kin
 &HT;    By Chris Burritt
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHARLOTTESVILLE, Va. _ What some believe Thomas Jefferson did
with slave Sally Hemings is threatening to turn from a historical
debate to a racially charged brawl between white defenders of
Jefferson and his disputed black kin.
</P>
<P>
   A gathering of both sides May 6 and 7 in Charlottesville, Va.,
might signal how the feud will shake out over the next year, as
pressure mounts on Jefferson's recognized ancestors to embrace
evidence that the nation's third president had children by Hemings.
In question is how Hemings' relatives, or anybody else, must prove
that they're descended from Jefferson. If they can, they're
entitled to membership in the Monticello Association, a private
group that owns and maintains the iron-fenced Monticello cemetery
where Jefferson and his white kin are buried.
</P>
<P>
   That burial privilege would be extended to Hemings' descendants
if they became members. Prospective members must prove ``some sort
of genealogical trail back to a known descendant,'' association
President James Truscott, 69, said.
</P>
<P>
   But in the 3 1/2 months since the Thomas Jefferson Memorial
Foundation weighed in on the side of the Hemings descendants,
outraged Jefferson defenders have swung into action. Planning their
public debut during next weekend's Jefferson family reunion, the
white defenders are intent on debunking what they consider a
historically suspect, politically correct rewriting of Jefferson's
relations with Hemings.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are putting together a group to articulate another possible
scenario: Maybe he did not do it,'' said John Works, 45, a
Jefferson descendant and former association president.
</P>
<P>
   From Bucharest, Romania, where he runs an oil company, Works has
spent long hours helping organize the Thomas Jefferson Truth
Foundation. One of his allies, amateur historian Herbert Barger of
Fort Washington, Md., is assembling a ``blue ribbon committee'' of
historians, scientists and ``just plain patriotic citizens'' to
compile historical evidence that rebuts the Thomas Jefferson
Memorial Foundation's conclusion in January.
</P>
<P>
   After months of examination by a research committee of
historians and Jefferson scholars, the memorial foundation said he
was ``most likely'' the father of Hemings' six children born at
Monticello.
</P>
<P>
   Hemings' offspring consider themselves defenders of Jefferson,
too. The ruling was a gratifying victory from the memorial
foundation, a private organization which has owned Monticello since
1923 and serves as caretaker of Jefferson's legacy.
</P>
<P>
   For the other side, the ruling was convincing evidence that the
memorial foundation is sacrificing its historical objectivity to
avoid offending African-Americans.
</P>
<P>
   ``You see a very big movement, in my sense, that the politically
correct group now controls Monticello,'' said retired
Charlottesville doctor Ken Wallenborn.
</P>
<P>
   An amateur Jefferson historian, Wallenborn, 70, resigned in
March from the memorial foundation's Jefferson-Hemings research
committee. Wallenborn said, the DNA test linking a living male
descendant of Eston Hemings to the Jefferson male line ``raises the
likelihood that it was Thomas'' who fathered Eston. ``But that is
not good enough,'' Works said. ``You have to prove that.''
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson's white defenders say Monticello's Getting Word oral
history project, consisting of interviews with more than 90
descendants of Monticello slaves, marked the memorial foundation's
departure from historical accuracy.
</P>
<P>
   A favorite target of the white defenders is Dianne Swann-Wright,
Monticello's director of special programs and historian for the
Getting Word project. She was hired in 1993, as the foundation's
first senior-level African-American staff member.
</P>
<P>
   Swann-Wright, 49, said some people will never be swayed,
regardless of evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``For them to understand that Thomas Jefferson had a
relationship with an enslaved African-American woman is beyond
their belief,'' she said. The foundation embraced 1998 DNA evidence
linking a living male descendant of Hemings' youngest son, Eston,
to the Jefferson male line. It also relied upon the Hemings' oral
history that linked Jefferson and Hemings. Then in 1998 pathologist
Eugene Foster published a scientific article based on DNA tests on
living male descendants of Eston Hemings. It found that one of the
descendants bore the same Y-chromosome as the male line in the
Jefferson family. The memorial foundation embraced that DNA test in
concluding that Jefferson probably fathered Eston, if not all of
Hemings' children. But Jefferson's white defenders say the memorial
foundation could have just as easily embraced another possibility
raised by the DNA test: that one of Jefferson's seven male
relatives fathered Eston. Some of Hemings' descendants are growing
impatient. ``The evidence that Thomas Jefferson did have offspring
with Sally Hemings is about as strong as it is going to get,'' said
Lance Balthazar, 64, a Marietta, Ga., businessman.
</P>
<P>
   One of Hemings' most outspoken descendants, Shay Banks-Young, of
Columbus, Ohio, suggests a DNA test on the remains of Jefferson.
Banks-Young, 55, said she is tired of Jefferson's ancestors
insisting that Hemings' kin be subjected to genetic testing. Most
recently, she and several other descendants of Hemings' son Madison
refused Herbert Barger's request to exhume the remains of William
Hemings, Madison's son.
</P>
<P>
   Barger said he believes a DNA test would bolster his belief that
Madison Hemings was not related to Thomas Jefferson. Barger added
he thinks Hemings' kin fear what a DNA test would find.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they want to dig up my family and do DNA,'' Banks-Young
said, ``then they should dig up Thomas Jefferson and do DNA on
him.'' From a genetic standpoint, pathologist Foster said, ``There
would be a logic to digging up both of them.''
</P>
<P>
   If their bones had not deteriorated and were reliable for DNA
testing, they could possibly provide evidence that Jefferson was
William Hemings' grandfather. Or, testing could prove otherwise.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be very, very reliable, so reliable that most people
would have to accept it,'' Foster said. ``But the chances of it
happening are slight.''
</P>
<P>
   What's also unlikely is an amicable outcome at the upcoming
Jefferson family reunion.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, for the first time, the Monticello Association
invited Hemings' relatives to attend the reunion. The association's
president, James Truscott, extended the same invitation last month,
and he expects about two dozen of Hemings' descendents to attend.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, about 80 of Jefferson's relatives are expected for
what typically has been a low-key private affair spread across the
lawn of Jefferson's Monticello plantation.
</P>
<P>
   But that changed last year, after some Jefferson ancestors tried
unsuccessfully to exclude the Hemings family from the association's
business meeting. The rancorous gathering spilled from the
Jefferson Ballroom in the downtown Charlottesville Omni into the
media-packed lobby. The bickering among would-be relatives reached
a national audience.
</P>
<P>
   Jefferson descendent John Works, the Romanian businessman, said
he'll try again Sunday to exclude the Hemings' family from the
business meeting.
</P>
<P>
   ''You can imagine what the TV cameras are going to see if they
throw a bunch of black people out of that meeting,'' said
Truscott's nephew, Lucian Truscott IV, a Los Angeles screen writer
and novelist. ''I think some of them are prepared to look like
redneck idiots.''
</P>
<P>
   A descendent of Jefferson, Truscott, 53, was the first to invite
Hemings' relatives to last year's reunion. Preferably in front of
the media, he's repeatedly accused his relatives of racism in
blocking the admission of the Hemings into the association.
</P>
<P>
   Not wanting to subject his family to a repeat of last year's
''unpleasant occurrences,'' Robert Golden, president of the Thomas
Woodson Family Association, decided last week he would not attend
the reunion.
</P>
<P>
   DNA tests of some of Woodson's living male ancestors failed to
link the Monticello slave to Jefferson. Golden, 70, of Pittsburgh,
said he believes his family's oral history is ample proof of
kinship to Jefferson. He added that some of Woodson's ancestors
would like to be buried in the Monticello cemetery.
</P>
<P>
   Banks-Young, the Hemings descendent, said she believes the
burial rights present the biggest obstacle to her family's
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   ''For them, to think that people related to the slaves on the
plantation would be buried with them, that would be devastating,''
she said. ''It would taint the reputation of the great man.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
