<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1059 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-SPORTSBIZ-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-29 0963
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SPORTSBIZ-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWEST GAME IS BUYING AND SELLING TEAMS 
</HEADLINE>
   By RICHARD SANDOMIR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Get out the tote board: another New York area team
has been sold.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1997, the New York Islanders have been bought three times
_ once, briefly, by a now-convicted felon _ the latest by Charles
Wang and Sanjay Kumar last Wednesday for $187.5 million. The New
Jersey Nets have been sold twice, the New Jersey Devils and the New
York Jets once.
</P>
<P>
   The New York Yankees, once chased by Cablevision, turned into
the hunter last year and merged with the Nets, then snapped up the
Devils last month.
</P>
<P>
   Cablevision may still be wooing the New York Mets, who may be
waiting for a dot.com gazillionaire to pay a half-billion to turn
them into software.
</P>
<P>
   With the New York Knicks and the New York Rangers secure under
the Cablevision umbrella, only the New York Giants have eluded the
local auction block.
</P>
<P>
   Since 1991, when Bob Tisch paid the Mara family $75 million for
50 percent of the Giants, nine NFL teams have been sold, including
the Jets last January. Four expansion teams were added in those
nine years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the Jets went for $635 million, the Giants would be worth
$750 million or $800 million,'' Tisch said. Despite the overheated
appetite for teams, he said he had not received offers for his half
of the franchise.
</P>
<P>
   ``Never,'' he said. ``They know I'm not selling. I don't know if
I should feel bad or not, but everybody knows we're in it for the
long haul.''
</P>
<P>
   Plenty of selling is going on nationally. Since 1998, 26 major
league teams have changed hands in whole or have sold large
minority stakes. Last week, Stan Kroenke, who owns 40 percent of
the St. Louis Rams, agreed to pay $450 million for the Denver
Nuggets, the Colorado Avalanche and the Pepsi Center in Denver,
beating out a group that included John McMullen, the departing
owner of the Devils, who was part of groups that tried to buy the
Jets and the Washington Redskins.
</P>
<P>
   Since the start of the year, the Vancouver Grizzlies have sold
for $165 million, the Dallas Mavericks for $280 million and the
Kansas City Royals for $96 million (less than one-third of the $322
million paid last year for the Cleveland Indians).
</P>
<P>
   The national trend has created a Wal-Mart sports bloc _ the blue
light special owners. Bill and Nancy Laurie, a daughter of Bud
Walton, who founded Wal-Mart with his brother, Sam, bought the St.
Louis Blues last year for $100 million ($10 million for the team
and $90 million for the debt on the Kiel Center). Kroenke's wife,
Ann, is Bud Walton's other daughter. And David Glass, a retired
chief executive officer of Wal-Mart, is the new Royals owner.
</P>
<P>
   ``The skyrocketing asset values of teams make them attractive to
sell, even with operating losses,'' said Marc Ganis, president of
Sportscorp Ltd., a Chicago consulting firm. ``Teams are also
selling when their owners die. But there is also a new breed of
owner, the technology entrepreneurs, willing to buy teams. So you
have a Mark Cuban spending a huge amount of money for the
Mavericks. It may be worth a lot in the future, but not now.''
</P>
<P>
   Cuban is a billionaire through his Broadcast.com Internet
company. Ted Leonsis used his AOL wealth to buy the Washington
Capitals and a minority interest in the Wizards, and Paul Allen
spent a bit of his Microsoft billions for the Seattle Seahawks and
the Portland Trail Blazers.
</P>
<P>
   Wang and Kumar built their technoriches through software at
Computer Associates International, and used it to keep the
Islanders on the sports world's most-sold list.
</P>
<P>
   From John Pickett, the team went to John Spano, who loved hockey
but loved a scam more and sits in prison for defrauding banks to
lend him the money to buy the team. Pickett took the team back, got
$25 million more from a group led by Howard Milstein, which said it
has lost $40 million over 28 months before Wang and Kumar developed
a sudden hunger for hockey.
</P>
<P>
   Wang really wanted the Nets, then tried to join Robert Wood
Johnson IV's bid to buy the Jets, but backed away last year when he
found that he would get no control for his investment.
</P>
<P>
   So Wang and Kumar overpaid to get the one New York team left _
and because Milstein wouldn't cut his price.
</P>
<P>
   The Pickett-to-Spano-to-Pickett-to-Milstein-to-Wang daisy chain
showed that a team could lose games and cash in mass quantities,
become a political hot potato but maintain its sale value. What a
country!
</P>
<P>
   Wang and Kumar deflected questions about a new lease, a new
arena or future cash losses by saying they weren't buying the team
as a financial investment or even because they love hockey, which
they don't. Their mentor was Alfonse D'Amato, New York's renowned
former ``Senator Pothole.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Once we stopped looking at it as a business, it was easy
then,'' said Wang, whose Computer Associates stock is worth $1.7
billion.
</P>
<P>
   Wang's view expands on the prevailing wisdom that a mogul can
earn better financial returns from Treasury bills or Beanie babies
than with a sports team.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you can't watch T-bills play,'' Alfred Lerner said when he
agreed to pay $530 million in 1998 for the renascent Cleveland
Browns.
</P>
<P>
   The Islanders' demise as a competitive team in the past decade
pegged them as an almost irretrievable charity case. Wang and Kumar
hope to deploy the team in the service of their charitable goals.
</P>
<P>
   That's admirable and works for the best community-minded teams,
like the Jacksonville Jaguars. But NFL economics are far healthier
than the NHL's. It will be instructive to see how long Wang and
Kumar view the Islanders as a noneconomic endeavor if their player
investments do not yield victories and a new arena remains an
unfulfilled dream.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
