<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0146 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1061 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-NY-SENATE0430-COX     04-29 1308
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-SENATE0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Outsiders vie for Giuliani-Clinton 'ringside' seat
 &HT;    By Jill Vejnoska
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Lawrence Garrett pulls no punches in discussing his
political donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our basic product is billboards,'' said Garrett, whose Duluth,
Ga. -based Formetco Inc. does business all over the country. ``So I
try to give to people who are good to us, who don't try to put us
out of business.''
</P>
<P>
   People like New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani?
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether Giuliani is friendly towards billboards
or not,'' Garrett admitted.
</P>
<P>
   What Garrett does know is that Giuliani is running against first
lady Hillary Rodham Clinton for the open U.S. Senate seat from New
York. That was pretty much enough to convince Garrett to donate
$500 to Giuliani's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not so sure that the wife of a current president running
for office is really appropriate,'' said Garrett, adding that he
thinks the Republican Giuliani has done ``great things'' in New
York. ``Also, she and I disagree in politics.''
</P>
<P>
   When Tip O'Neil declared ``all politics is local,'' he clearly
hadn't anticipated anything like the 2000 New York Senate race.
Giuliani's announcement Thursday that he has prostate cancer and
hopes to continue his campaign was just the latest bombshell in a
marquee matchup that has already shattered tradition (no other
sitting first lady has ever run for office), as well as records for
overheated media coverage. Now it's also attracting unprecedented
amounts of money, with huge chunks coming from out-of-state donors.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no question it will turn out to be the most expensive
Senate race in history,'' said Larry Makinson, executive director
of the non-partisan Center for Responsive Politics. ``People in
every corner of the country are paying attention and paying money
to get a ringside seat.''
</P>
<P>
   According to the most recent figures available, Giuliani has
raised $19.1 million _ nearly 44 percent of it from outside New
York. Of the $12 million Clinton's taken in, a whopping 56 percent
has come from outside New York.
</P>
<P>
   From Georgians, Giuliani received 74 donations totaling $42,350
(the Federal Election Commission requires candidates to report all
donations of $200 or more). Clinton's 37 donations totaled $23,440.
In both cases, Georgia ranks 19th among all states in
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   Among the local Giuliani donors are retired Coca-Cola president
Donald R. Keough and his wife, each of whom contributed $2,000, as
did Home Depot chairman and co-founder Bernard Marcus and his wife.
Clinton's Georgia donors include onetime Spelman College president
and current Emory professor Johnnetta Cole ($250), ex-CNN
Productions president Pat Mitchell, who recently became president
and CEO of PBS ($1,000), and former Atlanta Committee for the
Olympic Games chief operating officer A.D. Frazier Jr. ($1,000).
</P>
<P>
   Frazier now is president of the management firm Invesco Inc.
According to FEC records, 15 donors who listed Invesco under
``occupation'' contributed a total of $8,600 to Clinton on the same
day last November. Another Invesco employee, Luis Aguilar, said he
agreed to raise money in Georgia for Clinton when he accompanied
friends to a fund-raiser in New York and was ``impressed'' by a
speech the first lady gave.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's not an Invesco, corporate, reason for doing it,'' said
Aguilar, who gave $670 to Clinton last September. ``There are
people I went to, and where do I know them? Where I work.''
</P>
<P>
   Only one state seems to have resisted the temptation to grab
that ``ringside seat.'' Giuliani has received contributions from
every state except North Dakota. Among Clinton's donations from 45
states, a single $500 one came from North Dakota.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some state out there has to have some common sense, and as
usual, it's North Dakota,'' Drew Wrigley, executive director of the
North Dakota Republican Party, said only half-jokingly. ``People
here are just not swept off their feet by the passions of a far-off
Senate race, just because the national news tells us every night we
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Senate campaigns that attract massive amounts of ``outside''
dollars are not unheard of. Sometimes it's a lack of in-state
resources, and sometimes it's a matter of national reputation. For
instance, some 71 percent of contributions to Democrat Edward M.
Kennedy's 2000 re-election campaign have come from outside
Massachusetts. But this is something else again, if only because of
Southerners' usual penchant for pretending New York doesn't exist.
No one here can vote in next November's election up there. Nor
would Senator Clinton or Senator Giuliani be bringing home any pork
to the Peach State.
</P>
<P>
   So why are so many Georgians opening their wallets?
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes,'' said Michael Erlanger, 85, of Athens, ``you have
to put your money where your mouth is.''
</P>
<P>
   Erlanger's money _ $1000 of it _ went to Clinton because he
thinks she's ``an intelligent woman who believes in a great many
things I do,'' including helping the poor and children.
</P>
<P>
   But there's also this.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's both a positive and a negative to that,'' Erlanger
said of his contribution. ``I'm very pro-Hillary and very
anti-Giuliani.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many Georgians donating to the New York Senate race seem
to be at least as interested in slowing one candidate's career as
in advancing another's. Fred Alias, a hotel developer who lives on
Sea Island, gave $1,000 to Giuliani because he's done ``an
incredible job of cleaning up in New York'' and because he's
running against Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Clintons have done more to diminish the morality
of the United States than any one couple that I've known in my
lifetime,'' said Alias, who thinks President Clinton would have
some influence on the first lady as a senator. ``I would not be
making a donation to him if Hillary Clinton were not running
against him.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, Hillary Clinton _ and perhaps only Hillary
Clinton _ could have inspired Georgia resident Ellen Milholland to
contribute $250 to a Democratic Senate candidate running in New
York.
</P>
<P>
   ``If this were between Moynihan and Giuliani, no, we probably
would not give money to Moynihan,'' said Milholland, 45, referring
to Sen. Daniel Patrick Moynihan (D-N.Y.), whose decision to retire
led us to Giuliani vs. Clinton. ``It's Hillary Clinton we're giving
to. We've met Hillary Clinton, my son has met Hillary Clinton and
we think highly of her and her policies.''
</P>
<P>
   Milholland, a stay-at-home mother of two and former Democratic
state senate candidate, thinks Clinton would do better in the U.S.
Senate than Giuliani by virtue of her personality, intelligence and
understanding of Washington after nearly eight years in the White
House. And she disagrees with those who say the actions of a
senator from another state would have little impact on Georgia.
</P>
<P>
   So does Marla Chaliff. And that's a key reason why the
commercial real estate broker and mother of three contributed $950
to Giuliani's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``If she's elected, she will immediately be perceived as a
national leader, as opposed to any other freshman senator,'' said
Chaliff, 43. ``The thought of what she could do with that power is
what's so frightening to people like me who are opposed to her
policies and the thought of how that could possibly catapult her
into national office.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe so, but the Center for Responsive Politics' Makinson has a
slightly different perspective.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a great one,'' Makinson said of the Giuliani-Clinton
face-off. ``And everybody in the country has a little piece of it.
Except North Dakota.''
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
