<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0147 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1062 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-SOFIA-COPPOLA30-COX     04-29 0885
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SOFIA-COPPOLA30-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Another Coppola becomes filmmaker
 &HT;    By Bob Longino
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sofia Coppola knows about youthful obsessions.
</P>
<P>
   She was the ripe old age of 22 when a friend handed her a copy
of ``The Virgin Suicides,'' Jeffrey Eugenides' bold, mythic book
about five troubled teen daughters in Michigan and the suburban
neighborhood boys who, even after growing into adulthood, remain
obsessed with those beautiful girls and their brief, tragic lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took the book on a trip,'' Coppola says. ``It's funny
because I remember being so engrossed in it. I just loved it. I
thought the writer was just so funny and sensitive and achieved a
deft mixture of the tragedy and the humor in it all.''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola, 28, the daughter of Oscar-winning filmmaker Francis
Ford Coppola (``The Godfather'' films, ``Apocalypse Now'') and
recent wife to Oscar nominee Spike Jonze (``Being John
Malkovich''), simply could not get the book out of her head.
</P>
<P>
   So she did what many would consider a really dumb thing. Even
though the film option for ``Virgin Suicides'' was owned by the
independent company Muse Productions and a filmmaker had been hired
to direct his own adaptation, she started writing her own
screenplay.
</P>
<P>
   Persistence and, frankly, her pedigree paid off. Eventually,
Muse passed on its first filmmaker and asked Coppola to direct her
own script. ``The Virgin Suicides,'' starring Kirsten Dunst, James
Woods and Kathleen Turner, opens nationwide Friday. It's Coppola's
first feature-length film.
</P>
<P>
   ``Virgin Suicides'' is a dreamlike movie about the intense
passion of youth, fantasies, lust and obsession and
ice-cream-colored remembrances. And it's earning critical raves. In
his review, Matt Wolf of The Associated Press said, ``It's a movie
about loss in which a major film talent is found.'' The New York
Times has dubbed her ``an assured and imaginative filmmaker in her
own right.''
</P>
<P>
   They are words Coppola isn't used to in the press. A
photographer, clothes designer, model and one-time co-host of
Comedy Central's ``High Octane,'' she was savaged by critics when
she, at her father's request, tried acting and co-starred as Al
Pacino's daughter in ``The Godfather Part III.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The critics were harsh,'' Coppola says. ``But it's a business;
it just happens to be a big business. I don't have a resentment
about that.''
</P>
<P>
   She sometimes speaks in an innocent manner that belies her age.
She'll use a word _ like ``universality'' _ and then in the same
breath wonder aloud, ``that is a word, isn't it?''
</P>
<P>
   Coppola recently talked by phone from Los Angeles about ``Virgin
Suicides.''
</P>
<P>
   Q: Granted the story is fictional, but the film is a memory of
tragic events and five deaths _ as seen through one teen boy who's
grown up. For you, how much of what the film relates is real and
how much is perception?
</P>
<P>
   A: I definitely thought it was important that it was a memory so
that it's not realistic. It's about how you remember things. The
girls are more lovely. Even with the death of Cecilia (the first
teen to take her own life) it's described as sort of a circus act.
In life, you only remember parts of things. It's idealized and
surreal. But surreal doesn't mean it has to be weird.
</P>
<P>
   Q: When first reading the book, did you picture particular
actors, like Kathleen Turner as the overbearing mom?
</P>
<P>
   A: I didn't picture any actors when I was reading it. I guess I
wasn't thinking about it as a movie. Later, the casting people put
lists together. Her name came up, and I thought it was a great
idea. I think that character needed a great actress. She needed
depth, to have this power and be sympathetic.
</P>
<P>
   Q: Some people will likely have trouble with the film because
there are no definitive answers as to why things happen.
</P>
<P>
   A: When it was in script form there was concern about that. It's
not that common to have a mystery without an ending. But that's one
of the things I liked about the book. In life there aren't good
explanations for many things.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What was the toughest part of making the movie?
</P>
<P>
   A: You know, at the time it was really hard. But afterward you
sort of forget the hard parts. People say that about having kids.
It was hard working on such an intense schedule. We shot it in 29
days. I do remember shooting the scenes in the car as being
difficult. You see that in movies all the time. But that was one of
the hardest things for me.
</P>
<P>
   Q: What did your father say to you after he saw the film?
</P>
<P>
   A: What I remember the most is when he read my script and said
it was really good. I didn't think the subject matter was
interesting to him, but he thought the script was personal. He
thought it reinforced the universality ... of the themes in the
story. Even if you grew up somewhere completely different, the idea
of boys and girls and loss came through.
</P>
<P>
   Q: I've read where you used to make home videos as a kid. What
were those about?
</P>
<P>
   A: My friends and brothers and I made videos, usually horror
films. We'd just make up silly things. They weren't very
intellectual. I also got to where I'd do video reports for school
instead of written reports. I recall doing George Washington in
clay as Mr. Bill.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1625EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0148 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1063 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-MICROSOFT-ASSESS-1STL     04-29 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-ASSESS-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: BREAKUP CASE IS BUILT ON NOTION OF POTENTIAL RIVAL
FOR WINDOWS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif., Mass.)   (ADDS ``News Analysis'' to headline)  
 By STEVE LOHR   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   The overriding policy goal of a remedy in the Microsoft
antitrust case, the government has said repeatedly, is to make the
world safe for future innovation. The door to fair competition must
be left open, the government insisted, so that the Microsoft Corp.
cannot thwart its next head-on challenger with illegal tactics as
it did the Netscape Communications Corp., the pioneer in Internet
browsing software.
</P>
<P>
   In their papers supporting the government's proposal to split
Microsoft into two companies, three economists have identified the
