Technology. They are economists in their late 30s and 40s who focus
on the effects that innovation and new technology have on economic
growth, industrial organization and corporate behavior.
</P>
<P>
   The intellectual debate over the government's remedy will
revolve around the innovation arguments presented by the
government's economic advisers. The court's decision, Romer wrote,
``will profoundly affect the information industry, the most
technologically dynamic sector in our economy.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Microsoft would agree entirely with that statement,
but it argues that the government proposal is a dangerous gamble
with history, given the fast-changing conditions in high-technology
markets whose direction even entrepreneurs, let alone courts,
cannot predict.
</P>
<P>
   But Romer and his colleagues say the remedy is needed precisely
to protect and accelerate the innovation process. ``By encouraging
conditions that encourage increased competition in the operating
system market,'' Romer wrote, ``this remedy will increase the rate
of innovation in the software industry and thereby increase the
rate of growth for the economy as a whole.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``The lasting stream of benefits that can be expected
to follow from this remedy will substantially outweigh any
temporary costs that it may involve.''
</P>
<P>
   There are two ways, the economists say, that a stand-alone
Office business could bring new competition to the software
industry. The first is that Office, like Netscape's Navigator
browser, has the potential to become a software ``platform''
capable of competing with Windows. Netscape posed a frightening
challenge to Microsoft, trial evidence showed: As a layer of
software that sat on top of the Microsoft operating system, it
could replace Windows as the technology that controls the look and
feel of computing.
</P>
<P>
   And for software developers, the Netscape browser threatened to
replace Windows in providing the key software hooks _ known as
application programming interfaces, or APIs _ that programmers
write if their electronic commerce applications, e-mail and games
are to run smoothly on personal computers.
</P>
<P>
   In an internal memo in 1995, ``The Internet Tidal Wave,'' Bill
Gates, the chairman of Microsoft, warned that Netscape could
``commoditize'' the Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The breakup, Henderson wrote, will ``have the effect of putting
important middleware into the hands of a firm that has no incentive
to protect Windows.'' She added that both Office and the Internet
Explorer browser, which would be placed in the Office company under
the government proposal, are ``popular applications that expose
APIs and are widely distributed.''
</P>
<P>
   Henderson wrote, ``Office is, like Navigator, an application in
wide demand for its own sake that rivals Windows in its level of
penetration.'' Accordingly, she stated that an independent company
controlling Office ``might threaten Windows much as Netscape
threatened Windows in 1996.''
</P>
<P>
   The Office company, Romer wrote, could foster competition and
innovation in the operating system market in a number of ways. It
could, for example, develop its own operating system. Most likely,
this would be an operating system tailored to the Office
applications for computing in emerging markets, like on handheld
machines or so-called Web applications.
</P>
<P>
   For example, Word or Excel might reside on a central computer,
with customers tapping into it over high-speed networks using an
Internet appliance instead of a personal computer running the
Windows operating system.
</P>
<P>
   The other way for a stand-alone Office company to encourage
competition would e to support operating systems that compete with
Windows, like Linux, an increasingly popular version of the Unix
operating system. An independent Office business would have a
strong incentive to make sure Office programs run on Linux, the
economists say, because they would no longer be trying to help
Windows maintain its dominance.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
