<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1066 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      04-29 1098
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ON PRO BASKETBALL: RAPTORS SEEM TO BE CATCHING UP TO THE HYPE
</HEADLINE>
  By MIKE WISE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO  &UR; _  &LR; After a blowout loss at home earlier this season,
Charles Oakley delivered a blunt post-mortem: ``There's a lot of
hype around here, and you can't believe the hype.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Davis was not part of the hype. You have to have a
sports-drink commercial and throw down corkscrew dunks to be part
of the hype. Vince Carter and Tracy McGrady were part of the hype.
</P>
<P>
   Davis was more like Oakley, a big, strong rebounder with a
decent offensive game, traded to the Toronto Raptors for a younger
player with potentially more upside.
</P>
<P>
   Two hardened playoff warriors, essentially told by their former
teams, ``We're better off without you.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, who was a New York Knick for 10 years, was traded to
Toronto in the summer of 1998 partly because management felt he was
outplayed by Davis in a second-round loss to Indiana, where Davis
spent the first six years of his career.
</P>
<P>
   In turn, Davis was traded to Toronto last off-season after the
Pacers were stunned by a younger, athletic Knicks team in the
conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   There was almost symmetry to it, some sort of hoop karma. Davis
jumped over a worn-down Oakley one season. And Marcus Camby, the
player acquired for Oakley, swooped in for a rebound dunk over
Davis the next season _ hastening his departure.
</P>
<P>
   What came around in the NBA, indeed, went around.
</P>
<P>
   The younger, cheaper player acquired by the Pacers for Davis was
a corn-silk thin high school kid named Jonathan Bender, who may one
day be very good.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've never talked about that,'' Davis said Friday afternoon
after a Toronto practice. ``We just never have. New York may still
use that as an excuse. But if that's the reason they traded
Charles, then that was a big mistake.''
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``I've just been happy that I've had a chance to play
with Charles. I've learned a lot from him. And I understand why
he's been the player and the leader he's been.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley on Davis: ``A.D. knows how to play, simple as that.''
</P>
<P>
   This is the story of two veterans exiled to the Canadian border
to play out their careers on a lottery team. Somehow, the plot
changed. The kids they were supposed to slowly nurture turned out
to be better and more mature than advertised. The veterans had more
than a little game left. And together, in a woeful marketplace none
of their peers wanted to play in less than two years ago, they
enraptured a hockey province. They constructed a nice model for the
new millennium:
</P>
<P>
   Oak and A.D., T-Mac and V.C., working it out with their
supporting cast over time.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe you see what is in front of the Raptors: an 0-2 deficit
against the Knicks in a best-of-5 first-round series, an exit from
the playoffs as early as Sunday afternoon in front of the
franchise's first postseason crowd. Maybe their coach, Butch
Carter, is Canada's answer to Kathie Lee Gifford _ they cannot keep
quiet for their own good.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe the brush fires and the difficult losses are merely
growing pains, stones in an unfinished wall. Maybe being
transferred from an established company to a start-up shop _ rife
with mad geniuses _ is not the worst thing to happen to an NBA
veteran anymore.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Davis, Oakley had a choice to leave Toronto last summer.
Rather than teach and baby-sit Carter and McGrady, he could have
been Shaquille O'Neal's bodyguard. The Lakers offered him their $2
million a year veteran exception, a three-year deal worth about $6
million.
</P>
<P>
   When Oakley and Jerry West, the Lakers' president, were filmed
walking through the not-yet-completed Staples Center in hardhats
last summer, Oak's legions had to nod and smile.
</P>
<P>
   Here was the gritty former Knick who came to embody the team's
scrapping '90s style, the player so broken up weeks after the trade
for Camby that he spent most of one afternoon at a summer golf
outing barking to former teammates, ``Watch out, I'm comin' back
with Shaq.'' Patrick Ewing left the links early that day.
</P>
<P>
   A year later, Oak had a real shot to win a title. Fitting, no?
</P>
<P>
   But he went for the money. No one could blame him. Toronto was
able to offer $18 million over three seasons. Oakley's last NBA
contract was worth three times more than the Lakers could pay. He
took the Canadian exchange rate over the untold value of a possible
championship ring. With Davis, he continued to help run a day care
center, watching the kids grow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't even thought about that,'' said Vince Carter when
asked if he ever envisioned playing without Oakley. ``I just got so
used to him being here, you don't even think about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Oakley and Davis have clashed with the team's young stars over
offensive roles (Translation: the old guys wanted more shots). But
grudges die quickly here. ``Their experience means a lot,'' Carter
said. ``What it comes down to is, they've been in the playoffs. We
haven't.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis grabbed nearly 3,000 rebounds and became a better
offensive player each season in Indiana. He wanted to start instead
of coming off the bench. The Pacers decided to pledge their loyalty
to Dale Davis.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sometimes you look back,'' he said. ``I still love that team.
I wish them all the best in the world. I didn't want to leave. It
was just a situation where I wanted more responsibility. They
trained me to be that way. They trained me to be this type of
competitor. I want to win. I want to contribute. And then once I
get to the point, you're not going to give me the opportunity?''
</P>
<P>
   As Davis spoke, reporters and camera crews scurried wildly about
the team's practice facility, trying to find another player to
denounce Butch Carter's latest controversial remarks.
</P>
<P>
   This has been some week in Toronto. Players benched. Court
papers served. Roiling cauldrons of dissension, about to spill
over. Reminds you of Knicks practice, circa 1999.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's tough to deal with sometimes, especially in Indiana when
things were so cut and dry,'' Davis said. ``There was a history of
the team since the ABA days. That's just how it's been. You don't
have all these growing pains that this team has.
</P>
<P>
   ``But,'' he added, ``you have to go through them in order to
understand them.''
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Davis managed a rueful smile. His coach was popping off
in the gymnasium. Oakley meandered by, his head bobbing, mumbling
something that made Davis laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The Raptors are not imploding. Held up by a couple of adults,
they are taking their first, courageous steps. In time, you can
believe the hype.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
