<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:35 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1068 &Cx1f; tad-z
u p BC-microsoft-breakup-cox     04-29 0990
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-microsoft-breakup-cox </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    CAUTION URGED ON MICROSOFT BREAKUP
 &HT;    By ANDREW J. GLASS
 &HT;    c.2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON Both Microsoft's critics and defenders want the judge
to take his time before agreeing to the government's plan to cleave
the software giant in two.
</P>
<P>
   But they differ sharply how the breakup proposal made on Friday
by the Justice Department and 17 states would impact one of the
most dynamic sectors of the nation's economy. Nor do they agree on
the potential impact on investors, who have seen Microsoft's stock
lose one-third of its value in recent weeks.
</P>
<P>
   And some antitrust figures who approve of U.S. District Thomas
Penfield Jackson's verdict on April 3 that Microsoft is a predatory
monopolist also feel the remedies the government wants, which
include slapping on regulatory handcuffs until the breakup takes
hold, go too far while others feel they don't go far enough.
</P>
<P>
   The far-reaching proposal, which has infuriated top Microsoft
executives, calls for one company to own only the Windows operating
system. The other would market such Microsoft applications as Word
and Excel while also laying claim to the Internet Explorer browser,
the chief issue that caused the landmark suit to be filed two years
ago.
</P>
<P>
   The two companies -- only one would be permitted to retain the
Microsoft named -- would be barred from merging for another 10
years. The actual terms of the corporate divorce would written by
Microsoft itself, subject to review by the government and the
courts.
</P>
<P>
   Bill Neukom, Microsoft's chief counsel, who sat at the defense
table throughout the 77-day trial, contends that the current
timetable set by Jackson to move the case forward needs to be
revised.
</P>
<P>
   Says Neukom: ``The government's unprecedented and extreme remedy
proposals will require a significant expansion of the remedy
process currently contemplated by Judge Jackson's order. Even the
government will have to agree that an American company deserves
more than 12 days to respond to a government proposal to tear apart
a $400 billion company.
</P>
<P>
   Neukom argues that ``the government's excessive demands will
require months of discovery and evidentiary hearings and added that
government's proposals ``simply delay the ultimate resolution of
this case because Jackson ``all parties recognize this case
(ultimately) will be decided by the appellate courts.''
</P>
<P>
   Two figures in the case whom Neukom eagerly wants to depose are
Robert Greenhill and Jeffrey Williams, the chief executive and the
managing director of Greenhill &AMP; co., an investment advisory firm
that served as a consultant to the justice department in devising
the breakup formula.
</P>
<P>
   In a supporting brief filed with the court, the Wall Street
analysts wrote that the breakup ``will not result in a material
decrease in (Microsoft's) market value over the intermediate to
longer-term.'' Under the right conditions, they said, it could even
be ``positive.''
</P>
<P>
   That view upsets Microsoft chairman Bill Gates, who told Wall
Street analysts in a conference call Friday night: ``Microsoft will
be greatly damaged by this kind of split. No one should think that
shareholder value would be preserved with this kind of activity.''
</P>
<P>
   Gates also told the analysts that ``Microsoft could never have
developed Windows under these rules ... because without the great
work of the Office team and the Windows team it never would have
come together.''
</P>
<P>
   It is an admission that may come to haunt Microsoft's co-founder
since, in the past, the company has always strenuously maintained
that there exists ``a Chinese Wall'' between the two sets of
programmers that has never been breached.
</P>
<P>
   Software competitors have often complained that Office
developers held an inside track to vital parts of the Windows code,
a charge that the Microsoft brass in the past have vigorously
denied. The Justice Department chose not to make the applications
suite part of the case, although the original complaint filed by
the state attorneys general did so.
</P>
<P>
   Even as an embattled Microsoft seeks to extend the remedy phase
of the trial, a go-slow signal to Jackson was also flashed by
Robert Litan, a former Justice official involved in an earlier
phase of Microsoft's duel with the government who directs economic
studies at the Brookings Institution, a Washington think tank.
</P>
<P>
   Litan favors ``breaking up the Windows monopoly itself, perhaps
in three equal-sized pieces, each with the same intellectual
property to the Windows source code.''
</P>
<P>
   ``With the monopoly gone,'' he says, ``there would be no need
for continued judicial supervision, either of the new Windows
competitors or the rest of the company.''
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, he adds, ``the claim that Microsoft's monopoly is so
important to the U.S. economy is a little hard to square with the
company's claims that technology is moving so fast as to render any
severe sanction overkill.''
</P>
<P>
   Along with three other well-known economists, Litan has
submitted a brief to Jackson that reads in part: ``We believe that,
because the underlying remedy issues are so complex, the key
concern is the quality of the assessment rather than the speed of
the resolution. Hence, a careful study and assessment of
alternatives should not be sacrificed in the rush to resolve
uncertainties surrounding the outcome of this case.''
</P>
<P>
   Ohio and Illinois, two of the 19 states that are parties to the
case, declined to go along with the government's formula. Ohio
Attorney General Betty Montgomery: ``A reorganization could be
difficult to undo, and its effects would be difficult to predict.''
</P>
<P>
   ON THE WEB:
http://fullcoverage.yahoo.com/fc/Tech/icrosoftAntitrustTrial/
</P>
<P>
   Andrew J. Glass's e-mail address is andyg(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
