<SLUG> BC-POLITICAL-BRIEFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR ILLINOIS GOVERNOR, AN EXPLANATORY TOUR 
DUST SWIRLS IN BATTLE FOR A KEY HOUSE SEAT 
OREGON INITIATIVES TORMENT GOVERNOR 
ADDING UP THE SCORE: BUSH 308, GORE 160
</HEADLINE>
 
 (ATTN: Ill., Utah, Ore.) By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Almost since the day he took office in early 1999, Gov. George
Ryan of Illinois has been under heavy political fire.
</P>
<P>
   First, he had to deal with the fallout of a federal corruption
investigation into the way the state handed out leases and drivers'
licenses. Next, he found himself struggling to explain to angry
taxpayers why vehicle fees had been increased. Then came taxpayer
outrage about increases in liquor levies, followed by criticism of
the governor's support for riverboat gambling.
</P>
<P>
   By early March, Ryan, a Republican, was in such bad standing
with voters that polls found only one in four had a favorable
opinion of him and only one in three approved of the way he was
running the state.
</P>
<P>
   Last Wednesday, things got even worse.
</P>
<P>
   Jack Roeser, the president of the Family Taxpayers Network, a
group of Illinois conservatives who favor tax reform, demanded that
Ryan step down as chairman of Gov. George W. Bush's presidential
campaign effort in Illinois, a crucial state in Election 2000.
Ryan's troubles, Roeser warned, would drag Bush down in the state
this fall and, equally bad, would doom Republican efforts to seize
full control of the Illinois Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   Roeser said he was forming a new conservative group, Republicans
United, that would press Ryan to give up the Bush campaign post and
that would seek to overturn bills Ryan had pushed through the
Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   The governor countered that he had the full support of Bush and
accused Roeser of being on ``the right fringe.''
</P>
<P>
   On Thursday, Ryan said he would embark this week on a
border-to-border tour of Illinois to meet constituents in a series
of town hall gatherings. ``This is an important opportunity to
explain to people the work we've been doing and hear what's on
their minds,'' said the governor's spokesman, Dennis Culloton.
</P>
<P>
   DUST SWIRLS IN BATTLE FOR A KEY HOUSE SEAT
</P>
<P>
   With only a six-vote majority in the House, Republican
congressional leaders are taking no seat the party holds for
granted _ especially the one held by Rep. Merrill Cook of Utah.
</P>
<P>
   Cook, a two-term conservative who represents the state's 2nd
Congressional District, which includes most of Salt Lake City, is
about as vulnerable as any House Republican running this year, not
so much because of his politics as his contentious,
shoot-from-the-lip behavior. Over the last 18 months he has gotten
himself banished from the Utah Republican Party's headquarters
because of an angry, profane outburst; he has feuded with, and
fired, his chief of staff, who accused him of delusional behavior;
and he has been found guilty by a jury of reneging on a $175,000
payment he owed his 1996 campaign manager.
</P>
<P>
   State Republican leaders became so concerned about Cook's
behavior last year that some quietly began casting about for
someone to challenge his renomination, and two candidates
eventually signed up: Derek Smith, a computer company founder, and
Jeff Wright, a venture capitalist. Some national party leaders
toyed with the idea of joining the state leaders in their search,
but they eventually decided to follow the usual policy and stick
with the incumbent, however troubled.
</P>
<P>
   No matter.
</P>
<P>
   Cook is still in political trouble. And so, too, are Smith and
Wright.
</P>
<P>
   On May 6, at a convention of district Republicans, a vote will
be taken to choose the nominee. But the winner must get 60 percent
of the vote. Otherwise, there will be a primary runoff on June 27
between the convention's two top vote-getters.
</P>
<P>
   All of the major House leaders have rallied to Cook's side in
the struggle for convention votes. But Smith and Wright are
campaigning hard.
</P>
<P>
   The best bet is that there will be a June runoff, but who will
be in it is only a guess. And it may not matter.
</P>
<P>
   The latest 2nd District preference poll, conducted 10 days ago
by The Deseret News of Salt Lake City, had the Democratic nominee,
Jim Matheson, son of former Gov. Scott M. Matheson, beating all the
Republican hopefuls by two to one or better.
</P>
<P>
   OREGON INITIATIVES TORMENT GOVERNOR
</P>
<P>
   When it comes to ballot initiatives, the growing bane of
governors and state legislatures, no one does it better than Bill
Sizemore.
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore is the director of Oregon Taxpayers United, a
conservative group that sees government as a meddlesome, wasteful
squanderer. For the better part of a decade, he and his
organization have been end-running and bedeviling Oregon governors
and the Oregon Legislature with anti-tax and anti-spending
initiatives.
</P>
<P>
   Two years ago, it appeared that Sizemore had finally overreached
and met his match in Gov. John Kitzhaber, a popular Democrat. He
challenged the governor's re-election effort and was thrashed by a
ratio of better than 2 to 1.
</P>
<P>
   But no. Sizemore is back. Big time.
</P>
<P>
   By Election Day, he will have no fewer than five Taxpayer United
initiatives on the ballot, one of which would allow Oregonians to
deduct their entire federal tax bill from their state tax return.
Should the referendum pass, finance experts say, it would cost the
Oregon treasury about $1 billion a year, requiring huge cuts in
state programs. By one calculation, the cuts in the education
budget might force schools to close a month early.
</P>
<P>
   Kitzhaber is working so hard to defeat the Sizemore initiatives,
especially the tax deduction measure, that he has less and less
time to devote to other state business and has abandoned his own
tax reform and education proposals.
</P>
<P>
   Asked the other day whether he felt that Sizemore was dictating
how the state was run, Kitzhaber replied, ``Sometimes I think that
my destiny in my eight years as governor is to keep my finger in
the dike.''
</P>
<P>
   Sizemore's reading on that: ``The governor is kind of a sideline
player in this game.''
</P>
<P>
   ADDING UP THE SCORE: BUSH 308, GORE 160
</P>
<P>
   The Hotline, the popular Internet political tip sheet, keeps a
running tab of presidential preference polls in various states as
they become available. Here is how they added up as of the end of
last week:
</P>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush led in 27 states, together worth 308
electoral votes. Vice President Al Gore led in 12 states, together
worth 160 electoral votes.
</P>
<P>
   Needed to capture the White House: 270 electoral votes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
