<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1070 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-RAPTORS-DISSENSIO     04-29 0621
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RAPTORS-DISSENSION-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A PLAYOFF TEAM IN TURMOIL, EXCEPT IT'S NOT THE KNICKS
</HEADLINE>
  By STEVE POPPER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PURCHASE, N.Y. _ It was a familiar situation for the New York
Knicks, waking up in recent days to headlines of dissension and
controversy. But as they rubbed the sleep from their eyes, they saw
that the stories were about their opponents, the Toronto Raptors,
and not them.
</P>
<P>
   While the Raptors seem on the verge of disintegrating as they
approach what could be their last game of the season, the Knicks
found themselves in a position that they were unaccustomed to,
being the poised and focused team. But after enduring a tumultuous
season in 1999 that still finished with them earning a spot in the
NBA finals, the Knicks were one team that did not believe that the
Raptors' bickering rendered them any less dangerous.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know whether it's nice to see it or not,'' Houston
said of the Raptors' problems. ``But we've learned from that. You
really can't let those kind of things distract you. What it does is
put more negative things in your mind that directs your attention
from what you're supposed to be doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Especially in the playoffs, this is not a time to get into
quarrels. When things go wrong within a game or within a series,
you have to stick together even more, especially here in New York.
We've learned that.''
</P>
<P>
   For the Raptors, the off-the-court intrigue has been more
interesting than their performance on the court. Before the series
began, coach Butch Carter was prompting laughter in both locker
rooms by filing a defamation lawsuit against Knicks forward Marcus
Camby. While he dropped that suit, he stopped the laughter in his
own locker room by yanking the co-captain Doug Christie from the
starting lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Then, after the Knicks took a 2-0 lead in the best-of-5-game
series, Carter criticized his team, without naming names, saying
that players who were potential free agents were focused as much on
their individual situations than the team's. He then said that the
team lacked an on-floor leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were able to put it aside last year,'' Latrell Sprewell
said. ``So that shows it can be done.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks' problems last season make the sniping in Toronto
seem tame, with General Manager Ernie Grunfeld being fired late in
the regular season, and the status of coach Jeff Van Gundy dangling
while the Madison Square Garden president, Dave Checketts, courted
Phil Jackson. Sprewell was still coming off of the bench until the
Eastern Conference finals, and his lawyer was openly threatening to
move his client out of New York if he was not going to be in the
starting five.
</P>
<P>
   Still, the Knicks somehow overcame all of that, as well as a
season-ending injury to Patrick Ewing, to advance to the NBA
finals.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be productive as a team you have to stick together,''
Houston said. ``You can't start pointing fingers. That's one thing
we've always been able to do, is make sure everybody is on the same
page. You look at yourself in the mirror and see if you're doing
your job correctly and then you go about your business.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's one of the reasons we haven't gotten down on each
other, haven't gotten down on Jeff, because we realize that we have
to just go out and do our jobs. We can't blame each other.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I know is when we're here together as a team, we're
together. We're all focused on one goal and that's winning. Guys
may go home and tell their wives something different. I don't know
and I really don't care. The difference is, when we're here
together or when we're on a plane, when we're together we're
family. We're brothers. That's what it has to be in order for you
to win the game.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
