<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 16:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1072 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-YALE-DOCTORS-LAWSUIT-     04-29 1172
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-YALE-DOCTORS-LAWSUIT-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCTORS SUE YALE, SAYING COST CUTS HURT PATIENTS
</HEADLINE>
 By PAUL ZIELBAUER  
c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW HAVEN, Conn. _ Three longtime physicians have accused Yale
University's School of Medicine of implementing policies that
endangered the lives of patients, and then punishing the doctors
when they complained.
</P>
<P>
   The university denies the claims, which are contained in a
lawsuit the doctors filed against Yale in January. The claim
focuses on how doctors in the school's diagnostic radiology
department have been treating patients at Yale-New Haven Medical
Center, the teaching hospital for the medical school. It takes
specific aim at the department's chairman, who the suit says
implemented measures, as early as 1995, that saved the school money
but carried ``unacceptable patient-care and safety consequences.''
</P>
<P>
   When the doctors complained to the radiology department, they
said in the suit, the chairman retaliated by cutting their
salaries, disrupting their sabbaticals and disparaging them to
executives at other medical schools.
</P>
<P>
   ``Patients have suffered,'' said one of the plaintiffs, Dr.
Morton Burrell, a professor of radiology who has been on the
school's faculty for 27 years. ``We chose to speak out about wrongs
that are going on all around us,'' he said, calling the suit a
defense of academic freedom. ``They put their foot on our
throats.''
</P>
<P>
   A spokesman for the university, Lawrence J. Haas, said the
suit's claims were baseless and that the medical school's policies,
which he refused to discuss, put no patients in danger.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've looked into all of these allegations, we took them quite
seriously, and we devoted extensive resources to investigating
them,'' including hiring outside medical experts, Haas said. ``We
found no irregularities. We have been quite mystified that this
lawsuit was even filed. The facts don't support what they said.''
</P>
<P>
   A judge is expected to soon start hearing the case, which is
steeped in leaden medical language and the intricacies of the
federal Medicare system.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways this is a very simple story; in other ways, it is
extremely complicated,'' said Dr. Robert Smith, 39, one of the
plaintiffs, who has left Yale for Cornell University.
</P>
<P>
   The third plaintiff is Dr. Arthur Rosenfield, an author of two
books on radiology, who has taught at Yale since 1975.
</P>
<P>
   Yale has not filed an answer to the suit, and Haas declined to
discuss the doctors or their claims before the university
responded. But in a five-page memorandum to the doctors dated Feb.
1, the university's vice president and general counsel, Dorothy K.
Robinson, dismissed many of the suit's charges and warned the
doctors that if they repeated them out of court, the university
might take legal action against them.
</P>
<P>
   In January 1998, the suit charges, the chairman of Yale's
radiology department, Dr. Bruce L. McClennan, directed doctors to
sign a backlog of radiology studies, some as old as two years, on
Yale-New Haven patients whom the doctors had never treated. Shortly
after that, the suit says, McClennan began ordering residents _
doctors with less than four years of experience _ to examine X-rays
of emergency room patients, which the suit contends is unethical
and a violation of Medicare laws.
</P>
<P>
   ``As part of these cost-cutting measures, a lot of people on
staff, including myself, felt they went way too far,'' Smith said
in an interview. ``This is Yale University, this isn't some little,
tiny practice place. We felt there were many other ways to go about
saving money than severely compromising patient care.''
</P>
<P>
   McClennan did not respond to several telephone calls and e-mail
messages seeking comment. But in her memorandum, sent nearly a
month after the three doctors filed their lawsuit, Robinson said
there had been no orders to sign unseen radiology reports.
</P>
<P>
   Attending physicians did, in fact, maintain control of patient
diagnoses made by less-experienced doctors, said Robinson's
memorandum, which was provided to The New York Times by Burrell,
who is 58. ``Consequently, we believe that patient care was not
compromised.''
</P>
<P>
   Robinson's memorandum speculated that unusually ``heated''
e-mail exchanges between Burrell and a supervisor may have led to a
misunderstanding of some of the department's new rules.
</P>
<P>
   The lawsuit's most serious points, however, center on charges
that the policies caused ``untrained people'' in the department to
misread CT scans of patients. In September 1998, for example, the
doctors charge, one unqualified doctor mistakenly identified a
brain hemorrhage in a patient who did not have one, and failed to
diagnose such a hemorrhage in another patient.
</P>
<P>
   After Smith's and Burrell's continual complaints about these and
other policies, the suit charges, Yale responded by cutting their
salaries, ``saying some extremely bad things about'' Smith, issuing
threats to Burrell and delaying Rosenfield's yearlong sabbatical by
five months.
</P>
<P>
   In a July 1998 memorandum announcing a 5 percent pay cut for
Smith, to $158,550 a year, McClennan criticized his ``consistently
adversarial positions and attitudes'' and ``reluctance to cooperate
in the evolutionary process of change.'' The memorandum, provided
to The Times by Smith, urged him to consider the ``abruptly altered
pressures on the hospital, the university and, in fact, the
community of medicine,'' and to ``refrain from your critical public
and private activism.''
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Smith's salary was cut to $135,646, the suit said,
and Burrell was demoted and told that his friends would suffer if
he did not amend his ways.
</P>
<P>
   After meetings with the Yale University president, Richard C.
Levin, the university began an investigation, according to the
lawsuit, that found nothing wrong. Haas said the university also
brought in outside doctors to review the charges and found no basis
for the complaints.
</P>
<P>
   The university believes the suit is primarily ``an employment
complaint,'' rather than a patient care or freedom of speech issue,
Haas said. ``This lawsuit drags in a lot of unsupported and
unfounded allegations about patient care.''
</P>
<P>
   Dr. Jeffrey Neitlich, who spent eight years in the radiology
department before leaving in January 1998, said he understood why
his former colleagues were upset. ``They feel with a large staff at
an academic hospital, you shouldn't be running it as a community
hospital,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He said the three doctors, who have sent dozens of e-mail
messages and letters to Yale executives, were known to be extremely
persistent in their criticisms. ``I think Bruce found that very
difficult to deal with,'' Neitlich said, referring to McClennan.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this month, Yale lawyers, who tried unsuccessfully on
Feb. 9 to block public access to the complaint the doctors filed,
submitted a request to Judge Michael Sheldon of Superior Court to
order the doctors to pare down their suit to make resolving it
easier.
</P>
<P>
   Sheldon has not yet set a hearing date on that request.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1653EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
