<HEADER>
A1073 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-TEN-ATP-MASTERS-NYT &LR;      04-29 0876
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TEN-ATP-MASTERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATP WEIGHS THE EFFECTS OF ITS NEW MARITAL VOWS
</HEADLINE>
  By CHRISTOPHER CLAREY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``It's not easy for three to get married,'' said Patrice
Dominguez, the co-director of last week's men's tennis tournament
in Monte Carlo, Monaco.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly not, but that is precisely what has happened in
Dominguez's sport. There is the ATP Tour, which represents the male
players. There are the tour's nine most prestigious non-Grand Slam
tournaments, including Monte Carlo, which used to be called the
Super 9 and are now known as the Tennis Masters Series. There is
also ISL Worldwide, the company that paid $1.2 billion for the
exclusive rights to market and profit from the Masters Series for
the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   It is the sort of alphabet soup that is becoming a common dish
in contemporary sport, and though it is unfair to judge the quality
of a bouillabaisse until the ingredients have had the proper time
to stew, there is already some cause for hovering nervously over
the pot.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the repackaged men's tour is supposed to guarantee
that all of the world's top players compete in each of the main
events, many of the game's big attractions were missing in Monte
Carlo because of aching bodies or other priorities, including Pete
Sampras, Andre Agassi, Patrick Rafter, Lleyton Hewitt and Nicolas
Kiefer. Despite bold predictions, there is also the lack, for the
moment, of a singular look for the nine series events: a uniform
identity that tells the spectator that the tournaments are linked
and special, if not nearly as special as the four Grand Slam
events.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the television companies to whom ISL has sold the
rights to the Masters Series in the bulk of western Europe and
Japan are satellite and cable broadcasters with small subscriber
bases. OnDigital, which holds the rights in Britain, has
approximately 650,000 subscribers. Pathe Sport in France does not
reach a great many more.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Renner, the director of ISL's tennis division, concurs
that this is not ideal. ``You look at the scope of the events we
work with, like the Olympics and the World Cup, and the reason they
are as big as they are is their reach, which is mostly on
terrestrial television,'' Renner said. ``Certainly if we want to
make tennis one of the top two or three sports in the world, we
have to do that. With most of the world, we've done a good job, but
in Europe, we've had some problems.''
</P>
<P>
   The fact that Germany's traditional ratings busters, Boris
Becker and Steffi Graf, have retired is certainly a factor. ``It's
like coming to a big house the day after a big party,'' Renner
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would we like broader coverage to start with? Yes,'' he added.
``But if you look at the Premier League six years ago when it
signed its deal with BSkyB instead of the BBC, everyone said it was
the death of soccer in England. It turned out to be very good. Why?
I think it's because government stations like the BBC don't have
the financial motivation to make the most out of a sport and to lay
down the money to get more spectators. OnDigital and Pathe, for
example, do have quality, and they are enthusiastic about it.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the two-year agreements the tournaments
signed do not give them much time to grow. Meanwhile, tennis runs
the risk of losing more market share and momentum in its
traditional stronghold and of confusing and frustrating an audience
that now has much greater access to lower-case events like this
week's stop in Barcelona through the pan-European channel Eurosport
than to the more important Masters Series. Eurosport, which now has
the rights to the top-tier women's events, could have had the whole
men's package but negotiations with ISL broke down.
</P>
<P>
   There were 14 cameras tracking Sunday's soggy final in Monte
Carlo in which Cedric Pioline beat Dominik Hrbaty. Moreover, the
television deals ISL signed with ESPN and Fox in the United States,
with one of the principal terrestrial networks in Gustavo Kuerten's
Brazil and, intriguingly, with a group of channels in China
guarantee more universal coverage in those countries.
</P>
<P>
   It is possible that China could even have a Masters Series event
by 2001. The Stuttgart indoor tournament is for sale, and Hong Kong
is the most promising prospective buyer.
</P>
<P>
   For now, the Masters Series is only in Europe and North America.
Taking it to Asia and South America would edge tennis closer to the
global Formula One model in auto racing that tennis administrators
openly envy. The downside is that cars don't get jet-lagged and
world weary, but tennis players do, and an obligatory trip to Asia
in November would only exacerbate the problem.
</P>
<P>
   Less is truly more in sports. And though the ATP Tour has
simplified its ranking system and made every Grand Slam and Masters
Series event count on the computer, players can still count their
five next best results. And some of the ATP's scheduling is
dubious, for instance, cramming the three Masters Series clay-court
events (Monte Carlo, Rome and Hamburg) into five weeks before the
French Open.
</P>
<P>
   ``At least give a chance to rest a bit, otherwise you just burn
out,'' said Alex Corretja of Spain, who is back in form after
burning out last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
