<HEADER>
A1078 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MICROSOFT-VOICES-NYT &LR;      04-29 1210
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MICROSOFT-VOICES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE MICROSOFT CASE: 4 EXPERTS GIVE THEIR VIEWS 
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: This text consists of the responses of four antitrust experts
to the government's request that Microsoft Corp. be broken into two
parts.)  
(With MICROSOFT-ASSESS, MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   STEVEN C. SALOP, GEORGETOWN UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   Salop, a professor of law and economics at the Georgetown
University Law Center, said the proposed remedies were, if
anything, too modest. ``I understand why the government chose this
as the best compromise,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Salop said the government had taken into account concern about
severely disrupting the lives of Microsoft employees. It had also
accommodated widely expressed fears that one remedy he and many
other experts favored _ splitting the Windows operating business
into three competing enterprises _ would lead to incompatible forms
of Windows, which could disrupt a world where 90 percent of all
personal computers are sold with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   But Salop said the fears of fragmentation were exaggerated.
Windows companies would have a strong incentive to keep the core
programs identical to run existing software. Marginal differences
would develop with new versions, but they would not affect most
users, he said, and computer users could be counted on to push hard
for programs to preserve compatibility.
</P>
<P>
   The problem with simply splitting Microsoft into two companies
is that there is a strong chance they would operate with a ``tacit
nonaggression pact,'' Salop said. At the very least, the Internet
and browser operations should also be split off, he said. The
Internet-centered Microsoft offspring would have a much different
business orientation, he said, and tacit collusion would be much
less likely with Microsoft in three pieces.
</P>
<P>
   Salop served as a Federal Trade Commission consultant when that
agency investigated Microsoft, and helped the Justice Department
fashion a consent decree in its first action against Microsoft. He
said he was convinced that any plan to leave Microsoft intact and
rely only on restrictions on behavior would fail.
</P>
<P>
   ``Conduct remedies are particularly difficult to enforce against
a company bent on exploiting any loopholes,'' he said, adding that
Microsoft's continued insistence that it had done nothing wrong
made it clear the government could expect little cooperation.
</P>
<P>
   Salop said that while he understood the government's goals in
proposing three years of behavioral restraints if Microsoft is
split up and 10 years of such restrictions if it is not, it made
more sense to have them open-ended ``until a competitive
environment is achieved.''
</P>
<P>
   ROBERT E. LITAN, BROOKINGS INSTITUTION
</P>
<P>
   Litan, vice president and director of the Economic Studies
Program at the Brookings Institution, supervised the government's
first antitrust investigation of Microsoft as deputy assistant
attorney general in the Justice Department's antitrust division
from September 1993 until March 1995.
</P>
<P>
   ``This moves the ball across the 50-yard line toward the goal,
but it doesn't get there,'' Litan said. The proposal to split the
company is far better than relying only on conduct restrictions,
Litan said. But the government has no guarantee that after a split
the applications half of Microsoft would take crucial steps that
today's Microsoft has avoided, like developing business software
for the Linux operating system that competes with Windows.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a riverboat gamble,'' Litan said.
</P>
<P>
   Moreover, the operating systems side would maintain its monopoly
over Windows and the company's current goal of extending the
operating system from the desktop environment it dominates into the
world of servers and Internet devices _ ``Window for the world,''
as Bill Gates, Microsoft's chairman, calls the strategy.
</P>
<P>
   ``If they pull it off,'' Litan said, ``you would end up with an
even stronger, more durable monopoly.''
</P>
<P>
   RICHARD B. MCKENZIE, UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA AT IRVINE
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie, a professor at Irvine's graduate school of management,
sees the request that Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson break Microsoft
into two parts as a policy blunder.
</P>
<P>
   ``This remedy will likely do what antitrust is not supposed to
do: help competitors and not consumers,'' the 58-year-old economist
said. The best indication that the breakup would not benefit
consumers, McKenzie said, is that it is the remedy favored by
Microsoft's rivals.
</P>
<P>
   ``They want Microsoft to be hobbled so it will not compete as
aggressively against them,'' McKenzie said. ``The effect will
likely be to keep prices higher than they would be otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   In his new book, ``Trust on Trial: How the Microsoft Case is
Reframing the Rules of Competition'' (Perseus Books), McKenzie, who
said he had no financial stake in Microsoft, argues that the
antitrust case stems from Microsoft's introduction of its Windows
NT operating system in the early 1990s. The more powerful operating
system meant Microsoft was moving beyond desktop personal computer
operating systems and into the lucrative market for software that
runs on bigger computers on which corporate networks are built.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prior to mid-1993, the rivals were perfectly happy to let
Microsoft dominate the desktop,'' McKenzie said. ``But these other
companies got very concerned that Microsoft was invading their
remaining domain.''
</P>
<P>
   While McKenzie opposes breaking Microsoft up, he described some
of the restrictions on conduct that have been proposed as
``doable.'' His favored minimal remedy would be to require
Microsoft to offer two versions of Windows, one with Internet
browsing software and one without at a discounted price.
</P>
<P>
   GEORGE L. PRIEST, YALE UNIVERSITY
</P>
<P>
   Priest, a professor at Yale Law School, said the proposal to
split Microsoft's operating system business from all of its
applications software, Internet and other enterprises went ``far
beyond'' the issues actually litigated, which focused on
Microsoft's behavior in the market for Internet browsers.
</P>
<P>
   Some narrow remedies limiting how Microsoft marketed or licensed
some products might be sustainable on appeal, he said, but there is
far too little evidence to support breaking up the company.
</P>
<P>
   Unless Jackson orders extensive hearings that produce evidence
that splitting the company would increase competition, the
government's plan is no more than a ``wild guess,'' Priest said.
</P>
<P>
   Priest said his guess is that such hearings might not produce
support for the government's proposal. ``It's not obvious that a
duopoly would be any better for competition than a monopoly in this
case,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Priest said he had accepted an invitation from Microsoft to
critique Jackson's opinions but had yet to produce or be paid for
such work. While criticizing the proposed remedies, he expressed
sympathy for the government's predicament.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's important symbolically to go after monopolists,'' Priest
said, noting that society benefits from believing that no company
can be so big it is beyond the law. But fashioning justifiable and
effective remedies has never been easy. ``There has always been
greater faith than merited in the ability of antitrust laws to
affect monopolization,'' he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1702EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
