<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 17:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1107 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-GORE-SPEECH-NYT &LR;      04-29 1102
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE GIVES HARSH APPRAISAL OF BUSH IN SCHEDULED SPEECH 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: This story is an added starter on the front page.) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In a foreign policy speech to be delivered on
Sunday, Vice President Al Gore gives one of his harshest
assessments to date of Gov. George W. Bush, saying his Republican
rival is stuck in a Cold War time warp, has serious gaps in his
experience and knowledge and would rely on right-wing advisers for
guidance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore faults Bush for proposing to ``skip'' a generation of
military weapons while emphasizing research into more advanced
ones, leaving the United States unprepared for battlefields of the
next two or three decades, and for wanting to deploy an implausible
``Star Wars'' system.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president casts the Texas governor as unrealistic and
irresponsible for regarding Russia and China as enemies of the
United States.
</P>
<P>
   ``Governor Bush dangerously fixates on the Cold War past when
speaking of the use of force,'' Gore says in prepared remarks that
were provided by his staff the day before they were to be delivered
in Boston. ``Stuck in a Cold War mindset, Governor Bush continues
to view Russia and China primarily as present or future enemies.''
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore presents himself as more forward thinking _
constructing a kind of Gore doctrine that he calls ``forward
engagement,'' which essentially is to nip problems in the bud
rather than let them swell into crises. He says he views Russia and
China not as enemies but as ``vital partners.'' And he goes on to
give his most staunch support to date for moving China into the
World Trade Organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``One has to assume that these gaps in Governor Bush's foreign
policy views and experience will be filled by the ideologies and
inveterate antipathies of his party _ the right-wing, partisan
isolationism of the Republican congressional leadership,'' Gore
said.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president links Bush with Sen. Jesse Helms, the
conservative Republican from North Carolina who heads the Senate
Foreign Relations Committee. Helms has said he will block any new
arms control agreements until a new president is inaugurated,
scuttling any hope President Clinton might have of reaching an arms
control pact with Russia, which he is to visit in June.
</P>
<P>
   Regarding China, Gore says, ``It is wrong to isolate and
demonize China, to build a wall when we need to build a bridge,''
speaking here less to Bush, who also supports open trade with
China, than to his own backers in organized labor, who vehemently
oppose such an agreement.
</P>
<P>
   Gore does not articulate any departures from his well-known
world view that he supports a strong military and would act
aggressively toward rogue nations. And he does not separate himself
from any Clinton administration foreign policy.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president does carry forward the administration's
approach of elevating new issues _ the economy, health and the
environment _ to the top of the international agenda.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need a new security agenda for the global age based on
forward engagement,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Bush campaign has increasingly criticized the Clinton
administration's foreign policy as being devoid of strategic vision
and characterized by case-by-case responses to crises. For that
reason, perhaps, Gore does not mention Clinton's name once in his
speech.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore does not seize the opportunity, in what his staff says
is a major foreign policy address, to lay out a foreign policy
agenda that diverges from the main outlines of the Clinton
administration's policies. The speech contains no specific new
foreign policy proposals.
</P>
<P>
   To bolster his standing as a Democrat with strong defense views,
Gore notes that he pushed for a new generation of missiles during
his years in the Senate and was one of the few Democrats to break
with the party and vote in favor of going to war against Saddam
Hussein in 1991 after Saddam's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's political intentions are clear. The speech is one more
block that Gore is using to build his case that Bush is too
unprepared, naive and reckless to be president, and that these
failures appear perilous when they are placed against a backdrop of
an increasingly complex world.
</P>
<P>
   By contrast, Gore portrays himself as far more worldly wise than
the governor, noting that he served in Vietnam, albeit as a
journalist, a conflict that ``I witnessed with my own eyes.'' Bush
served in the Texas Air National Guard at the time. The vice
president also reminds his audience, the International Press
Institute, that he has always been more hawkish than his fellow
Democrats on foreign policy matters, notably by supporting the use
of force against Saddam and in pressing for a strong national
defense and a new generation of missiles.
</P>
<P>
   Gore accuses the Republican leaders of Congress of a blend of
isolationism and obstructionism.
</P>
<P>
   ``They have refused to adequately fund our diplomatic and
international development efforts, from promoting peace in the
Middle East to fighting drugs in South America,'' he says. ``They
have held our contributions to the United Nations hostage to their
own political agenda for years. They have repeatedly tried to
sabotage this administration's programs even in places like Bosnia
and Kosovo where what is needed is steadiness and continuity of
purpose. They have made themselves the sworn enemies of a worldwide
effort to deal with the global environment.''
</P>
<P>
   And he lambasts Bush for having ``joined with the isolationist,
partisan Republican majority in Congress in opposing the
Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore essentially calls for an Americanization of the world
economy, saying America has a vital interest in promoting its own
economic prosperity throughout the world, an idea that could prompt
resentment in regions that have no desire to adapt to the free
market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We need to promote the stable flow of investment around the
world,'' he says, although he does not describe a mechanism for
doing that within a free market system, where investors have as
much right to pull their money out as they have to put it in.
</P>
<P>
   His critique of Bush is that he is so focused on Cold War
thinking that he ignores the economic opportunities to be had.
</P>
<P>
   Bush appears to be relying on the same foreign policy advisers
used by his father, former President Bush. Without naming her, Gore
criticizes ideas put forward by Condoleezza Rice, a senior national
security adviser to President Bush and the foreign policy
coordinator for Gov. Bush.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
