<SLUG> BC-NY-INDEPENDENCE-PARTY-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIULIANI WOOS INDEPENDENCE PARTY, SEEKING HELP IN REACHING OUT TO
BLACKS
</HEADLINE>
  (Eds: Will be updated with Clinton's comments.) 
 By ELISABETH BUMILLER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHEEKTOWAGA, N.Y. _ Mayor Rudolph Giuliani eagerly asked the
fractious Independence Party to endorse him for U.S. Senate here
Saturday, and added that the group might help him reach out to
black voters.
</P>
<P>
   When Lenora Fulani, a leader of the left-wing New Alliance Party
who controls a faction of the party, asked the mayor if the
Independence Party could help him with black voters who have been
furious over his response to a series of police shootings, Giuliani
replied, ``I hadn't thought of it that way. The answer is yes.''
</P>
<P>
   He added that his problems with black New Yorkers were perhaps
because of his own ``inadequacies as a public communicator.''
</P>
<P>
   The mayor's opponent, Hillary Rodham Clinton, also was to speak
to the Independence Party on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   It was the mayor's second day of campaigning since announcing he
has prostate cancer. For now, the diagnosis seems to have given
Giuliani a new focus and an enthusiasm for a race that he had been
treating sometimes half-heartedly.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm even thinking maybe I can campaign from a hospital,''
Giuliani told an enthusiastic group of Erie County Republicans at a
breakfast meeting at Chef's restaurant in Buffalo.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani recounted how a reporter had asked him the night before
in Saratoga Springs about the support he had been receiving.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some people say I'm doing this for sympathy,'' Giuliani said,
laughing. ``I said, `OK, right. Well then I really am ready for the
loony bin.'''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani did not say Saturday that he would definitely stay in
the race for Senate, but his advisers described him as a ``changed
man'' after he received the news on Friday that the cancer was
contained to his prostate and had not spread. Giuliani did not know
that on Thursday when he held a news conference to disclose the
cancer diagnosis. Advisers also described him as unusually buoyant,
and said that on the plane to Buffalo, the mayor talked about
theology, and inquired about their own well-being.
</P>
<P>
   The Independence Party, the New York affiliate of the national
Reform Party started by Ross Perot, is potentially important on the
ballot and could choose its candidate for Senate by early June. In
1998, Charles Schumer received more than 100,000 votes on the line
in his winning Senate race.
</P>
<P>
   The party is in a state of confusion, however, since a judge
this month removed its chairman, Frank McKay, and reinstalled Jack
R. Essenberg. The third-largest party in the state, the party is
leaning toward endorsing Pat Buchanan for president, whom Giuliani
once called anti-Semitic and anti-immigrant.
</P>
<P>
   This week, Giuliani said he had ``problems'' with Buchanan on
the Reform Party ticket. Saturday, the mayor would only say that he
``disagreed'' with Buchanan and that he supported his right to be
on the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Third-party endorsements are particularly critical in this
year's Senate race in New York, because the race is expected to be
extremely close and the number of undecided voters is small.
Republicans typically also seek the state's Conservative Party
endorsement, but Giuliani and that party's chairman, Michael Long,
have been at odds for months. Giuliani said he spoke to Long two
days ago, but added that the conversation was personal, and he
would not say whether he had asked Long for his support.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1734EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
