A1111 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-RANGERS0430-COX     04-29 0610
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RANGERS0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Where the elite compete
 &HT;    By Tinah Saunders
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   COLUMBUS, Ga. _ Two camouflage-clad Army Rangers crouched low in
the leafy undergrowth, trying to spot the sniper firing on them.
Suddenly, one stood and hurled a smoke bomb into the trees. Amid
the acrid green smoke, both raced forward, shooting as they ran.
</P>
<P>
   And reached the finish line.
</P>
<P>
   They had survived the fire of Cpl. Jorge Nunez, sniper
extraordinaire and one of the many challenges facing them in the
18th annual David E. Grange Jr. Best Ranger Competition, being held
this weekend at Fort Benning.
</P>
<P>
   Here, for 60 consecutive hours, the best of the Army's elite
commandos compete for little more than bragging rights.
</P>
<P>
   Second Lt. Marcus Messerschmitt was competing for the third
time. He and buddy Second Lt. Fred Ahern were in third place
Saturday, hard on the heels of their competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first time, I did it to see if I could, the second time,
because I thought I could have won, and this time, I'm here to
win,'' Messerschmitt said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I won't do it again,'' added Messerschmitt, 29. ``I'm
getting too old.''
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday morning, only 27 two-man teams out of the original
45 that started Friday remained to continue the event. A grueling
19-mile foot march with full equipment and 60-pound rucksacks had
taken its toll. And one team had voluntarily dropped out so one of
its members could be at his wife's side for the birth of their
10-pound baby boy.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have our priorities straight,'' said Col. Sam Rollinson.
</P>
<P>
   The other teams, however, had moved on with little more than a
catnap between competitions. There was the prusik climb, a
hand-over-hand rope ascent to the top of a 60-foot tower, followed
by a rappelling descent down the other side. The time to beat was
33 seconds. No one was close.
</P>
<P>
   At the edge of the field, under the trees, camouflage netting
sheltered exhausted teams awaiting the next competition.
Red-shirted medics tended the few injured. The most prevalent
complaint was blistered feet.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday night, after finishing the grenade toss, tying
intricate knots, assembling a myriad of weapons and completing the
bayonet assault course, the teams were scheduled to make their way
across 18 to 27 miles of wooded terrain, guided only by a map and
compass.
</P>
<P>
   At least one team was confident that it could not only complete
the night land navigation course, but make up the points it needed
to come from behind and win the Best Ranger title.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been eating Motrin like candy. I'm hoping that will help
the pain in my shoulders and neck,'' said the confident
Messerschmitt.
</P>
<P>
   Strategy is at least 45 percent of what it takes to win, said
Capt. Michael Trembley, a Ranger instructor. The other 50 percent
is physical and mental skills and experience.
</P>
<P>
   ``They pick up the little things, like which events score
highest and where to put their focus and how to pace themselves,''
said Trembley.
</P>
<P>
   The officials who devise the competition are constantly throwing
surprises into the mix. ``Last night they had to put on their gas
masks during the march. That was a first. It makes it harder to
breathe and it's hot, and if you've packed it at the bottom of your
rucksack, you lose time digging it out,'' said Monica Manganaro, a
Fort Benning spokeswoman.
</P>
<P>
   For those teams that lasted through Saturday night, there's more
to come today, including an obstacle course, a swim that begins
with competitors dropped with full pack from a helicopter and a
2.3-mile buddy run.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
