<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 17:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1112 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-MRS-CLINTON-NYT &LR;      04-29 1155
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MRS-CLINTON-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUDDENLY, MRS. CLINTON IS EVERYWHERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (With NY-INDEPENDENCE-PARTY) 
 By JONATHAN P. HICKS   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ There can be little doubt about it. Hillary Rodham
Clinton is getting around the state.
</P>
<P>
   In just the last week, Clinton visited a dairy farm in Wyoming
County, N.Y., talking about agriculture policy to the strains of
mooing cows in the background. She spoke to a group of Democrats at
a luncheon in Penn Yan, a town of about 3,000 in the Finger Lakes
region, telling them about her vision of the upstate economy and
confessing her first experience hunting ducks. And she stood on the
stage at Alfred University, in Allegany County, to be inducted into
Omicron Delta Kappa, a national leadership honor society.
</P>
<P>
   For those who might have questioned how fully or comfortably the
first lady of the United States would immerse herself in the
minutiae of a statewide Senate campaign, the answer can be found in
the schedule Clinton has been keeping over the last few weeks.
Indeed, she seems to be in every corner of New York, from hamlets
to large cities.
</P>
<P>
   By the time she left an appearance at a high school in Watkins
Glen, in Schuyler County, on Thursday, Clinton had visited 58 of
the state's 62 counties. And, in a point she underscored several
times last week, she has every intention of visiting the remaining
four counties in the next few weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The first lady's campaign schedule signals a significant shift
from her earlier forays into New York State politics, when her
events were carefully choreographed with little spontaneous
interchange between Clinton and voters.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Clinton is spending significantly more time
interacting with voters, taking time to shake hands, pose for
pictures, sign autographs and talk with people. For example, after
an hourlong, nationally televised town hall meeting in Buffalo last
week, Clinton spent nearly another hour taking more questions from
the audience and shaking hands.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton insists that her campaign style is unchanged from the
early days of her ``listening tour,'' when she spoke to relatively
small groups and rarely plunged into crowds. ``I don't feel like
I'm doing anything differently,'' she said in an interview last
week. ``I thought I spent a lot of time back in the listening tour.
But I was trying to cover a lot of ground, so I didn't have,
perhaps, as much time in my schedule.''
</P>
<P>
   Discussing her campaign schedule, she said: ``I'm doing what I
said I would do when I started: I'm meeting as many New Yorkers as
I possibly can meet and going to every county. I'm going into a lot
of different settings to see where people live and work, and I'm
having an absolutely wonderful time.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Clinton seems less inclined to engage in regular
question-and-answer periods with the news media, unlike her
Republican rival, Rudolph Giuliani, who, as mayor of New York City,
typically conducts a news conference every day.
</P>
<P>
   Her schedule and campaign style seem intent on making voters
comfortable with the notion that a woman who has never held public
office and who, until recent months, had never even lived in the
state is nonetheless a fitting choice to be U.S. Senator. Moreover,
her frequent trips _ many from dawn to late into the night _ are
also intended to provide a sharp contrast to Giuliani, who has
largely remained in New York City during the last few months.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani, who revealed on Thursday that he has prostate cancer,
traveled this weekend to Buffalo, for a meeting of the Independence
Party, and to Saratoga Springs, for a Republican dinner. His
campaign aides suggest that Clinton is able to travel the state
freely since she is unencumbered by the responsibilities of running
a city _ or anything else for that matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``A year ago, Clinton was at 57 percent in the polls,'' said
Juleanna Glover Weiss, a spokeswoman for Giuliani's campaign. ``She
is now approaching going to every county in the state. It seems
that the more people see her, the less they like her, given her
rapid decline in poll numbers in the last year.''
</P>
<P>
   But a recent New York Times/CBS News poll showed Clinton was 8
points ahead of Giuliani overall and was even with him upstate.
</P>
<P>
   The extent to which her numerous trips produce dividends at the
polls in November remains to be seen, of course. Many in the crowds
she attracts are undoubtedly motivated by the novelty of seeing the
wife of the president.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's pretty exciting,'' said Debra Almeter, who operates a
large dairy farm in Strykersville with her husband and went to see
Clinton at a campaign stop last week in Wyoming County. ``I'm not a
very political person. But how often does a first lady come out
here?''
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   That seems to be a common reaction to Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   ``No candidate ever, ever comes here. Ever. Ever,'' Barbara
Steinwachs said after Clinton's speech in Penn Yan. Steinwachs, an
independent training consultant and the Democratic Party chairwoman
in Yates County said: ``People are thrilled. And to have it to be
the first lady makes it even more thrilling. I think people are
impressed just that she came.''
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Many of the people who come to see Clinton _ particularly in
small communities in western New York _ are registered Republicans
who say they have no intention of voting for a Democratic
candidate. Yates County, for example, is considered territory where
Giuliani is likely to do well, with Republicans making up 56
percent of the registered voters and Democrats accounting for 24
percent.
</P>
<P>
   But it is Clinton's strategy, her aides say, that by going to as
many cities as her schedule allows, as frequently as possible, she
will become a political figure that voters are increasingly
comfortable with. Visiting upstate communities and discussing the
details of, say, milk prices or high air fares, her aides suggest,
Clinton is likely to pick up slivers of support and chip away at
what is perceived to be Giuliani's political strength.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   And it is clear that Clinton continues to elicit strong passions
from New Yorkers. On the road to Alfred University, last week, for
example, several huge banners were placed along the highway, saying
``Go Home Hillary'' and ``Stand By Your Man _ In Arkansas.''
</P>
<P>
   On the other hand, her very appearance on the stage in the
college auditorium produced wild cheers from the crowd.
</P>
<P>
   At one point last week, Clinton spent time in the early morning
hours looking at the Middle Falls, a picturesque waterfall in
Letchworth State Park in Wyoming County.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's beautiful,'' she said to an entourage of reporters
traveling with her. ``Have you ever seen this sight before?'' Most
of the reporters responded that they had not. ``Well, you travel
with me,'' she said, ``and you see New York.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1741EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0165 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 18:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1113 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DOOM2000-COX     04-29 2350
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOOM2000-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Friday is doomsday? Cosmic lineup
 &HT;    may trigger disaster, author says
 &HT;    By Jeffry Scott
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ELLIJAY, Ga. _ Richard Noone is a man ahead of his time, and his
time is coming, May 5, the day Noone has predicted the planets will
line up, Earth's poles will shift, continents will crack, buckle
and collide, and we will all have a very bad day.
</P>
<P>
   So why is Richard Noone mowing his lawn? Why is his house for
sale? Why is he fretting about the extra pounds he put on this
winter?
</P>
<P>
   It is a beautiful, cool, sunny Saturday afternoon at Noone's
4,000-square-foot brick and cedar hillside home in Ellijay. Sitting
on the back deck, Noone realizes he's gotten perhaps more than he
wished for.
</P>
<P>
   The stocky 56-year-old writer with a mane of gray-blond wavy
hair, a trimmed mustache, wire-rim glasses and a baritone voice
that cracks from so many interviews, is a captive of his own
prophetic title.
</P>
<P>
   His book, ``5/5/2000: Ice: The Ultimate Disaster'' (Crown, $16
paperback), which has sold more than 400,000 copies since its
publication in 1982, is a thoroughly researched, 390-page, roughly
1-pound monument to deduction, intuition, cosmic leaps and theories
that _ if deemed loopy by much of the world _ don't entirely
collapse under scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   But, there's the matter of that title.
</P>
<P>
   Is he nuts?
</P>
<P>
   A reporter keeps asking him about it. Is he sure that on Friday
a continental shift will move him and his Georgia home to somewhere
like Costa Rica?
</P>
<P>
   Noone pauses, and smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what the first title was?'' he says. ```The Great
Pyramid: A Structural Analysis.' Boy, with a title like that, I
would have sold four books.''
</P>
<P>
   Instead, Noone became a prophet of doom. And, with doom looming,
lately a lot of people are asking Noone a lot of questions.
</P>
<P>
   The main one: Where did you get that cockamamie theory?
</P>
<P>
   THE GENESIS OF A THEORY
</P>
<P>
   It's a long story, and it doesn't get any shorter in Noone's
retelling.
</P>
<P>
   A high school graduate, Noone is smart, forthcoming, devoid of
pretense. But he's also bereft of degrees in any of the subjects _
astronomy, physics, geology, architecture, engineering _ his book
bestrides like Colossus.
</P>
<P>
   He attributes everything. Getting him to condense his story into
the kind of snappy paragraph Hollywood screenwriters use to sell
$100 million action flicks is a monument of research itself.
</P>
<P>
   Ask a simple question _ ``When was the first Ice Age?'' _ and,
15 minutes later, Noone somehow is talking about Giorgio de
Santillana and Hertha von Dechend and their obscure but insightful
book, ``Hamlet's Mill: An Essay on Myth and the Frame of Time.''
</P>
<P>
   At this point, the impatient interviewer, looking for a quick
sound bite, wishes Friday would hurry up.
</P>
<P>
   The story is not simple. But, in Hollywood _ which, by the way,
has not bought rights to the book _ they'd sum it up like this:
</P>
<P>
   An Atlanta importer of wigs and jewelry, who years earlier had
developed a vague interest in ruins during a post-high school trip
to Mexico, reads a book on the Great Pyramid of Giza and, through
seven years of research, concludes the pyramid was the power plant
for an ancient technologically advanced Egyptian civilization that
was wiped out by a polar shift and whose astronomers predicted
another devastating polar shift on May 5, 2000, that will be set in
motion by the gravitational pull of a rare alignment of the sun,
moon and six planets.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you told me in high school that I'd be a writer,'' Noone
says, ``I would have told you you were crazy.''
</P>
<P>
   Noone wrote the book in longhand on legal pads _ 750 pages _ and
shortly thereafter, not a few people in the publishing business
figured he was crazy, too. After he sent manuscripts to about 50
publishers, a big New York house wrote back. Publishable, yes, the
editor wrote, but here's the catch:
</P>
<P>
   Could Noone at least imply that the Great Pyramid was built by
aliens from outer space?
</P>
<P>
   ``I advised them,'' says Noone, ``to visit the place of eternal
damnation.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1982, he sold the manuscript to Astraea Publishers Inc. in
Atlanta, which printed 15,000 hard-bound copies, and then went
bankrupt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went down there with my accountant to collect my $15,000 in
royalties,'' says Noone, ``and the building was empty. Nobody was
there. Just a couple of chairs and desks. I never got a cent.''
</P>
<P>
   Determined not to let the book go out of print, Noone found
another Atlanta publisher. In 1986 Random House picked it up, and
Noone finally got the exposure he had sought. Coast to coast he
became a cult figure.
</P>
<P>
   BACKING UP THE CLAIMS
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago he moved from Florida to Georgia because he
figured when the cataclysm hit, the Sunshine State would be ``under
40 feet of water.'' As it was, he was already swimming in
publicity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I must have been interviewed 10,000 times,'' he says of the
last few years.
</P>
<P>
   He appeared on the usual suspects, and a few odd ones:
``Oprah,'' ``Donahue,'' CNN, ``CBS This Morning,'' NBC's ``Ancient
Prophesies,'' A&AMP;E's ``The Unexplained,'' ``X-Files'' creator Chris
Carter's TV show ``Millennium,'' and in The New York Times
Magazine, which last year included Noone as a member of ``America's
millennial Chicken Littles.''
</P>
<P>
   The fame is fine, Noone says: ``Otherwise people won't be aware
of my work.'' But getting lumped in with the loonies? No thanks.
</P>
<P>
   He formatted the book so all his distilled theories, contentions
and connections are backed by either an expert or another published
work.
</P>
<P>
   ``That way,'' he says, ``if the reader finds what I've written
unbelievable, he can argue with the expert. I'm just a reporter, a
researcher, a writer, like Carl Sagan.''
</P>
<P>
   And a tireless researcher at that. He constantly combs the news
for indications of the coming Ice Age. He waves a handful of recent
news stories at you:
</P>
<P>
   Two huge icebergs have broken off Antarctica _ one the size of
Delaware, one the size of Jamaica _ in the past two months.
</P>
<P>
   Also _ more clips _ a growing number of scientists believe the
world is inching toward what could be another severe and relatively
sudden change in climate.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fifteen years ago, nobody would have believed that,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Noone's book contends that the existence of frozen woolly
mammoths with full meals in their stomachs indicates there was such
a sudden change in climate on the planet probably 10,000 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were flash-frozen,'' he says. ``They may have lived in
the area that is now France, and suddenly, maybe even the same day,
the poles shifted, the continents moved, and they were in what is
now Siberia.''
</P>
<P>
   `JUPITER ALIGNS WITH MARS ...'
</P>
<P>
   Noone hasn't rewritten the main text of his book since its first
publication in 1982. Instead, he keeps redrafting its lengthy
epilogue. In 1996, he added what he believes is his greatest _ and
most contrarian _ contribution to the body of knowledge about
Egypt's Great Pyramid of Giza.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't built, as Egyptologists claim, as a tomb, and it
wasn't built by slaves pushing huge blocks up ramps under the lash
of the whip,'' he says. ``It's a huge water pump, and it was built
by a technologically advanced civilization using machinery that was
powered either by water, or maybe electricity. The pyramid was a
source of power for an entire civilization.''
</P>
<P>
   Noone's assertion that the Great Pyramid is something other than
Egyptologists claim has been the Holy Grail of fringe theorists for
more than a century.
</P>
<P>
   In his 1998 book, ``The Giza Power Plant,'' writer Christopher
Dunn argues the pyramid was powered by ``harmonic resonance.''
</P>
<P>
   Noone lifted his theory from obscure tinkerer/inventor Edward J.
Kunkel, who published ``Pharaoh's Pump'' in 1962 and was, until his
death, a long-distance friend of Noone's.
</P>
<P>
   ``His book is impossible to read,'' says Noone. ``It's terribly
written. When I would get to a part I didn't understand, I'd call
him and we'd talk for hours until I understood what he was trying
to say.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, Kunkel or no Kunkel, Egyptologists still believe
Noone's _ and others' _ wild revisions of ancient Egyptian history
are fragrant flapdoodle.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those kinds of theories have been around since the 1880s,''
says Peter Lacovara, an Egyptologist at Emory University's Michael
C. Carlos Museum who has visited the Great Pyramid 15 times.
</P>
<P>
   ``People say that the dimensions of the pyramid are some sort of
predictor for the past and future human history, that it's
everything except a tomb. It's just ridiculous.''
</P>
<P>
   Astronomer Chris Impey at the University of Arizona is just as
incredulous about Noone's theory that Friday the gravitational pull
from a rare alignment of the moon, sun, Earth, Mercury, Venus,
Mars, Jupiter and Saturn will set off a polar shift.
</P>
<P>
   Noone says May 5, 2000, is predicted by the Great Pyramid
because it's the last date on the pyramid's time line.
</P>
<P>
   ``The most graphic way to explain it,'' says Impey, ``is that
the newspaper your readers are holding when they read this story
has more gravitational effect than any of the outer planets, no
matter how they're lined up.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are hunting around for something to get excited about
since the turn of the century didn't bring the apocalypse many
expected.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd say this is a pretty poor excuse.''
</P>
<P>
   Y2K REDUX?
</P>
<P>
   While Noone's fame as a prophet of doom is wide in weird
circles, he's a mystery to many, even in Ellijay, population 1,180.
</P>
<P>
   It's an anonymity he works hard to maintain, doubly easy because
he works from home, running a business by telephone, selling orange
peel oil as fertilizer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd rather people don't know I live here,'' he says. ``I'm a
very private person. I don't know many people up here.''
</P>
<P>
   The Gilmer County Public Library added ``5/5/2000'' to its
collection a year ago after a librarian read a story about Noone in
the newspaper and realized he's a local. In a year, the volume has
been checked out 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   Ellijay Mayor Al Hoyle, who mixes around town pretty well and
runs a pizza parlor, apologizes: ``I'm sorry. I never heard of
Richard Noone, or his book.''
</P>
<P>
   Noone says he has a network of experts around the world he stays
in touch with through his Web site (www.rnoone.com) and on the
telephone. And, lately, there have been many press inquiries.
</P>
<P>
   A film crew from ``Extra'' was out filming a segment slated to
air this week.
</P>
<P>
   And a reporter from the Canadian magazine ``Saturday Night''
wants to come down, interview Noone, stick around for Friday, and
then ask people in town what it feels like to still be alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't see any point in that,'' says Noone. ``Now, if he
wants to talk to me on May 18, because that's the window, May 5
through May 18, then maybe that would make sense.''
</P>
<P>
   Even the contrarian experts whom Noone counts as colleagues _
many of whom back some of his theories and have appeared on talk
shows with him _ squirm when asked about that Friday prediction.
</P>
<P>
   Mac B. Strain, a career geologist with the U.S. Geological
Survey and author of ``The Earth's Shifting Axis,'' pauses when
asked what his plans are that day.
</P>
<P>
   ``My calendar is open,'' he says by telephone from his home in
Colorado. ``I don't have anything planned.''
</P>
<P>
   Well, aren't you worried?
</P>
<P>
   ``Uh, oh,'' says Strain. ``No. There are too many unknowns. I
absolutely will not lose sleep over it.''
</P>
<P>
   One of Noone's most devoted believers is 44-year-old Steve Myers
of Coquille, Ore.
</P>
<P>
   Myers picked up Noone's book seven years ago and became so
transfixed by his revelation about Kunkel's pump that, two years
ago, he formed the Pharaoh's Pump Foundation, which counts 40
members, is starting a newsletter and has a Web site
(www.thepump.org).
</P>
<P>
   Myers and his followers have half-built a 20-foot-tall version
of the pump Kunkel described _ and patented it _ based on the
configurations of the internal passageways of the Great Pyramid.
</P>
<P>
   In two months, says Myers, it will be complete and they'll test
it. He says the pump, which is fueled by fire, could change the way
the world obtains drinking water and irrigates crops.
</P>
<P>
   If the pump works, ``it will be confirmation that the Great
Pyramid was not built by God as a confirmation of Bible prophecy,
or a ruthless Pharaoh using the backs of slaves,'' Myers says.
</P>
<P>
   ``It will say that it was built by a civilization of advanced
technology that was erased by something, maybe a polar shift.''
</P>
<P>
   THE END MAY NOT BE NEAR
</P>
<P>
   Noone would rather not die to prove his point.
</P>
<P>
   All the same, his plans for staying alive _ which include
finishing a mountain house in Blue Ridge with walls that can
withstand 450 mph winds _ are behind schedule.
</P>
<P>
   ``The house isn't finished,'' he says, ``and won't be by May
5.''
</P>
<P>
   The one he lives in is pretty stout, and is stockpiled with
enough food _ gallon tins of freeze-dried spaghetti and meatballs,
and tossed salad, for starters _ that he and his wife and three
children should survive for a year if his prophecy comes true.
</P>
<P>
   His main worry, this Saturday afternoon on his deck overlooking
a small valley and three pecan trees he just planted, is another
matter: Is he being sandbagged by the reporter? Will this be
another one of those tongue-in-cheek stories like that writer at a
St. Louis newspaper did a few weeks ago?
</P>
<P>
   He is assured that the reporter did think he must be crazy,
which is why he came up to do the story.
</P>
<P>
   The truth is, Noone probably fricasseed his credibility himself
with that doomsday title.
</P>
<P>
   What do his wife and children think while they watch him
puttering around the yard thinking he can win May Garden of the
Month? Isn't the end in two weeks?
</P>
<P>
   He exhales, smiles.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm undecided about what will happen May 5,'' he says. ``I've
done everything I can to protect my family, and what I've predicted
may not happen for another 10,000 years. That's what I tell them.
</P>
<P>
   ``For all I know, that day I might have a Cinco de Mayo party.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
