<P>
   INTERNATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-UKRAINE-$ADV30 _ The Ukraine _ What does this former
Soviet republic think about new Russian President Vladimir Putin?
His first trip ``abroad'' is supposed to be either to Belarus or to
Ukraine, two countries that have extremely different views toward
their old Soviet masters. The Ukraine in the last nine years has
tried to break free from dependence on Moscow _ and not very well,
however, because of its basketcase economy _ while Belarus has
towed the Soviet line. But one of the ways Ukraine has given Moscow
the finger is flirting with NATO, which Moscow didn't take very
kindly too. A bit too close to the Russian border for its comfort.
Developing. (Coker, Cox News Service) WITH PHOTOS
</P>
<P>
   MEXICO-ELECTION-$ADV30 _ MEXICO CITY _ Mexico heads into
uncharted territory with the most competitive presidential election
ever held in this country. Challenger Vicente Fox is closer than
any opposition politician has ever been to defeating the candidate
of the PRI, which has controlled the presidency for 71 years. By
most accounts, Fox won a debate this week, catapulting him even
further toward a possible victory on July 2. But analysts say don't
underestimate the PRI, which has a formidable political machine and
is often accused of benefitting from every tool at its disposal _
including sympathetic media and the government itself _ to win
elections. On Friday Mexico's independent Federal Elections
Institute, an agency charged with trying to ensure clean elections,
releases a report showing, among other things, that television news
coverage this month has tilted dramatically toward favoring the
ruling party's candidate, Francisco Labastida Ochoa. (Ferriss).
EDs: MOVED Fri., April 28.
</P>
<P>
   WASHINGTON
</P>
<P>
   EDUCATION-CONGRESS _ WASHINGTON _ Disagreements divide the
Senate on the eve of its its biggest education policy debate of the
year, which will concern whether to change the Elementary and
Secondary Education Act and renew it for another five years. The
divisions are so deep and sincere that Congress may founder,
letting the next president break the logjam. (Mollison, Cox News
Service). MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   MICROSOFT _ WASHINGTON _ The government wants to ``fix''
Microsoft so consumers and competitors won't be harmed by its
monopoly, but is its proposed remedy the right tool for the job?
There's a large body of expert of opinion that regards the new
breakup proposal as either too drastic or ineffective. (Glass, Cox
News Service).
</P>
<P>
   Moving Saturday in (w) Washington and (f) financial categories.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARCH _ WASHINGTON _ Organizers of the Millennium March for
Equality in Washington are hoping that the April 30 rally will be
the largest-ever gathering of lesbian, gay, bisexual and
transgender activists and their families. The
</P>
<P>
   event aims to ``energize and galvanize'' the gay and lesbian
community into an effective voting bloc for the November elections.
(Dart, Cox News Service). MOVED Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   GAY-MARCH-MONTOYA _ WASHINGTON _ Daniel Montoya, director of the
White House Council on HIV and AIDS policy, will address the gay
rally Sunday on his challenges as a Hispanic gay man. A look at
Montoya and his message. (Dart, Cox News Service). WITH PHOTO.
</P>
<P>
   HOLOCAUST-RESCUE _ WASHINGTON _ When World War II broke out,
about 3.1 million Jews were living in Poland. Only a small sliver,
some 100,000 in all, would escape the Holocaust. Among the
survivors were 2,200 Polish Jews who survived through the
intervention of a Japanese diplomat in Lithuania, Chiune Sugihara,
who personally issued them travel visas despite Japan's alliance
with Nazi Germany. The story of that flight and rescue is now to be
told in a special exhibit that opens at the U.S. Holocaust Museum
May 4. It covers the experiences of those very few who received
life-saving travel papers, including this writer (then 6) and his
parents. (Glass, Cox News Service)
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   JEFFERSON-MONTICELLO _ What Thomas Jefferson did with Sally
Hemings is fast turning from a historical debate to a racially
charged brawl. Ken Wallenborn resigned last month as a guide at
Monticello, Jefferson's plantation, because he refused to tell
visitors that the third president probably fathered some of
Hemings' children. Despite that recent conclusion by Monticello's
caretaker, the Thomas Jefferson Memorial Foundation, Wallenborn
represents an increasingly vocal backlash to DNA evidence and
Hemings' ancestors' oral history that the widower Jefferson and
Hemings were lovers. A curtain riser pegged to the Jefferson
family's reunion in Charlottesville May 6-7, during which
Wallenborn's group plan to unveil a foundation aiming to debunk
what they consider ``politically correct'' revisionist history.
Says African-American historian Dianne Swann-Wright of the
Jefferson Memorial Foundation, ``I think they have a difficult time
imaging that he could find beauty in the beast.'' (Burritt, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   DOOM2000 _The world survived Y2K. So count your blessings now.
Because they're about to run out on May 5, 2000. That's the date
Elijay doommonger, and author, Richard W. Noone, predicts the world
will suffer a cataclysmic shift of the poles and Florida will be
under 40 feet of water. Noone, 56, who earns his living as an
importer, articulates his prediction in the book ``5.5.2000,''
published by Random House. In 18 years, through several publishers,
the book has sold about 400,000 copies and developed a cult
following. He's been on Oprah, and CNN, and CBS ``This Morning.''
(Scott, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED. EDS: This is the
CoxNet Focus page for the week.
</P>
<P>
   RANGERS _ Army Rangers are the ones you send in for the
impossible missions. Every year at Fort Benning, the training HQ
for the Rangers, a competition is held to see which two-man Ranger
team is capable of the most incredible feats of survival and
ingenuity. The competition takes 2 1/2 days., beginning Friday, and
contestants don't know in advance what mission they will be given.
(Saunder, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POLITICS
</P>
<P>
   NY-SENATE _ When Tip O'Neil declared ``all politics is local,''
he clearly hadn't anticipated anything like the 2000 New York
senate race. The matchup between Hillary Clinton and Rudy Giuliani
has already shattered tradition as well as records for most
overheated media coverage. (Vejnoska, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   POL-TICKER _ A brief roundup of the day's campaign events,
pulled from Cox staff and wire reports. (Cox News Service) ETA: 9
p.m.
</P>
<P>
   OPED/EDITORIAL
</P>
<P>
   25-VIETNAM _ ``Ho Chi Minh Trail, napalm and body bags,
fragging, Khe Sanh, the Tet Offensive. ...'' Twenty-five years ago
today, Saigon fell to the Vietnamese Communists, the consequence of
a decision by President Nixon two years earlier to pull all U.S.
troops out of the country. Once the last helicopter had lifted off
Vietnamese rooftops, once the guns had fallen quiet there, all
those words that had seemed so fraught with meaning suddenly ceased
to matter, and ceased to be heard as well. (Bookman, Atlanta
Constitution) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   COMING-HOME _ WASHINGTON _ Vodka consumption is down. The
weather has improved. Life is more stable, though there is a
gnawing concern about the health of the economy. I'm not
summarizing the state of affairs in Russia. I'm talking about my
life in America since moving back to the States from Moscow five
months ago. My family and I have come home after seven years
abroad, and we're coping with culture shock in our own country.
(Holmes, Cox News Service) Also moving in (l) Lifestyle category.
</P>
<P>
   TEEPEN-COLUMN _ A study has found that at every step in the
juvenile justice system, minority kids are treated more harshly
than white kids. If you are wondering where that grotesque
disproportion of African-American men in state and federal prisons
comes from, here's the starting point. (Tom Teepen is national
correspondent for Cox Newspapers.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   KLEINBERG-COLUMN _ Cox News Service columnist Howard Kleinberg
is on vacation. His column will resume May 22 for papers of May 24.
(Kleinberg, Cox News Service.)
</P>
<P>
   GLASS-COLUMN _ Government prosecutors once foresaw U.S. District
Judge Thomas Penfield Jackson juggling his criminal docket for
years to come. Under such a formula, the judge would serve as a
sort of corporate truant officer, monitoring Microsoft's conduct to
bar any further illegal acts. (Andy Glass is a columnist for Cox
News Service in the Washington bureau.) MOVED THURSDAY.
</P>
<P>
   LIFESTYLE
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND-MOVIES _ BALTIMORE _ Some movie trivia: What's the
common thread connecting ``The Blair Witch Project'' and ``Runaway
Bride'' and ``Patriot Games'' and ``Hairspray'' and ``Tin Men'' and
Alfred Hitchcock's 1964 thriller ``Marnie''? Two thumbs up for
those who knew that all were filmed in Maryland. Better known for
its Chesapeake Bay oysters and crabs and for its baseball Orioles,
this scenically diverse state has been a favorite locale for
filmmakers for nearly a century. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With MARYLAND-LIST.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and a CoxNet illustration.
</P>
<P>
   Moved Monday in (e) entertainment and (t) travel categories.
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-REMEMBRANCE _ ATLANTA _ Luke Dollar hopes he won't see
it, but he'll have to leave his TV off and his newspaper in the
driveway to miss it. The famous photograph, showing GIs frantically
evacuating troops and refugees from the top of a building as Saigon
fell 25 years ago today, still haunts the 52-year-old Vietnam
veteran. It makes him angry. ``I don't think there's a Vietnam vet
alive that doesn't feel terrible watching the way we left Saigon,''
says Dollar, an insurance executive. ``It just makes me sick to my
stomach, like all my friends just died in vain.'' (Hendrick,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution). Also moving in (l) Commentary
category. MOVED
</P>
<P>
   VIETNAM-PHOTOS _ If ever a picture told a story, it's the
picture Larry Burrows took of a muddy medevac zone during a 1966
firefight in Vietnam. One of the best-known images of the war, the
bleak tableau is prominently displayed in the ``Requiem'' exhibit
of Vietnam photojournalism at the Atlanta History Center. It shows
two wounded Marines, one sprawled in the dirt, both legs bandaged,
his blank face splattered with red muck. The other soldier, his
head swaddled in a bloody cloth, appears to be stumbling toward his
buddy with arms outstretched. As it turns out, there's much more to
the story. (Hendrick, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) WITH PHOTOS.
Also MOVED (l) Commentary category.
</P>
<P>
   COMING-HOME _WASHINGTON _ Vodka consumption is down. The weather
has improved. Life is more stable, though there is a gnawing
concern about the health of the economy. I'm not summarizing the
state of affairs in Russia. I'm talking about my life in America
since moving back to the States from Moscow five months ago. My
family and I have come home after seven years abroad, and we're
coping with culture shock in our own country. (Holmes, Cox News
Service). MOVED Wednesday in (k) commentary and (l) lifestyle
categories.
</P>
<P>
   ENTERTAINMENT/ARTS
</P>
<P>
   ROCK-STAR-BODYGUARD _ Vic Robinson sat in the hotel room and
calmly waited as a deranged woman armed with a .38-caliber pistol
slipped past the doorman and made her way into the lobby of a
Seattle hotel to kill Mick Jagger. The woman claimed the Rolling
Stones lead singer was the father of her child. She wanted him
dead. ``The situation was quite tense,'' remembers Robinson, 46, a
Grand Junction music promoter who was Jagger's personal bodyguard
during the 1981 Tattoo You tour. ``The threat came through the
operator at the hotel. If she hadn't warned us, anything could have
happened.'' (Cumpston, Grand Junction Daily Sentinel) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   SOFIA-COPPOLA _Movie interview: Q &AMP; A with Sofia Coppola,
daughter of ``The Godfather's'' Francis Ford Coppola. She wrote and
directed ``The Virgin Suicides,'' the expertly made movie about
teen passions and obsessions opening Friday in metro Atlanta.
(Longino, Atlanta Journal-Constitution). MOVED
</P>
<P>
   FREAK-PLAYERS _ Baltimore Ravens star Ray Lewis and Joseph
Sweeting, both charged with two counts of murder in the Buckhead
slayings, appeared in rap impresario Luther Campbell's triple-X
video entitled ``Luke's Freak Show: Cancun 1999.'' The video offers
proof of close ties between the defendant as well as raising
questions about Lewis' character and associates that could be an
issue in his trial, scheduled to start May 15. (Chapman, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). Also moving in sports (s) category.
</P>
<P>
   MARYLAND-MOVIES _ BALTIMORE _ Some movie trivia: What's the
common thread connecting ``The Blair Witch Project'' and ``Runaway
Bride'' and ``Patriot Games'' and ``Hairspray'' and ``Tin Men'' and
Alfred Hitchcock's 1964 thriller ``Marnie''? Two thumbs up for
those who knew that all were filmed in Maryland. Better known for
its Chesapeake Bay oysters and crabs and for its baseball Orioles,
this scenically diverse state has been a favorite locale for
filmmakers for nearly a century. (Dart, Cox News Service).
</P>
<P>
   With MARYLAND-LIST.
</P>
<P>
   With photos and a CoxNet illustration.
