<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 18:27 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1115 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-NY     04-29 0814
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-YANKS-BLUEJAYS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WELLS GAINS THE VICTORY FOR BLUE JAYS IN THE BRONX
</HEADLINE>
  By BUSTER OLNEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Since the New York Yankees traded David Wells to the
Toronto Blue Jays last year, Yankee Stadium might have been the one
place in the city where Wells was not made to feel welcome. He
could go to Dorian's and raise a glass, stop by Howard Stern's
studio and trade bawdy stories, but twice last year Wells was
beaten by his former teammates in The House That Ruth Built.
</P>
<P>
   Wells did not last long in Saturday's game, either, but long
enough to finally get a victory in Yankee Stadium, as Toronto
dumped the Yankees, 6-2, before 38,783. Wells (4-1) pitched five
innings before leaving with stiffness in his lower back.
</P>
<P>
   Orlando Hernandez, who had won his first four decisions, was
charged with the loss, having allowed nine hits, a walk and five
runs (four earned) over 6 1/3 innings.
</P>
<P>
   Before Toronto catcher Alberto Castillo batted in the top of the
third inning, he stood at the edge of the batter's box and chatted
with his positional counterpart, the Yankees' Jorge Posada, and it
appeared that Castillo was telling Posada something about Wells.
Castillo tugged at his shirt as he spoke to Posada, in the same
manner Wells had done the previous inning, when Wells and Castillo
had to discuss their signs repeatedly.
</P>
<P>
   Posada and Castillo would have many stories to tell about their
respective pitchers, both as talented and athletic as they are
unusual in manner and style. Wells' huge body is hidden underneath
the folds of his baggy uniform, but teammates say he is so flexible
that he can do leg splits like a 96-pound gymnast. He makes no
secret of the fact that he loves to go out and have a good time,
and he loves to be in the middle of a crowd, the center of
attention; as Bernie Williams watched him go through rehearsals for
an appearance on David Letterman's television show on Thursday, the
thought occurred to Williams that Wells is, without a doubt, a New
Yorker.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez is perched on his toes in his delivery, with the
balance of a ballerina. He has mixed more easily with teammates
this season, his third with the Yankees. Last Sunday, he and Cone
carried on a conversation about their respective pitching
mechanics, Cone speaking enough Spanish and Hernandez using enough
English to communicate.
</P>
<P>
   Wells was the ace of the Yankees in one of their greatest
seasons, in 1998, and Hernandez is the ace now, and Saturday they
seemed perfectly matched, each navigating through offensive squalls
into the middle innings, fighting off rallies when neither really
had the best of stuff.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees jabbed at Wells in the first two innings. Paul
O'Neill singled with two out, stole second and scored when Williams
singled. Posada ripped a double leading off the second, and with
one out, Felix Jose lined a single to left, his first hit in the
major leagues since May 5, 1995; Posada stopped at third. Wells
looked uncomfortable at times, squatting once, which is what
pitchers do when they have back trouble, and Wells has been beset
all spring by a bad back.
</P>
<P>
   But the Yankees' threat was thwarted when Jose took a minimal
lead off first and got a poor jump against Wells, and was thrown
out trying to steal second, the second out of the inning. Scott
Brosius grounded out.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto tied the score in the fourth, after Posada lost his grip
on the ball while trying to throw to second base, setting up the
run. The Blue Jays had runners at first and second and one out in
the fifth, but Hernandez struck out Jose Cruz Jr. and retired Homer
Bush on a popout. To that point, opponents were 3 for 31 (.097)
with runners in scoring position against Hernandez this season.
</P>
<P>
   Wells was still straining and stretching, repeatedly asking for
a new baseball from the umpire. As always, Hernandez looked to be
in complete command, despite the fact that his slider was somewhat
benign, lacking the sharp bite. He retired Raul Mondesi and Carlos
Delgado to start the sixth inning.
</P>
<P>
   Brad Fullmer singled, and there were a succession of three
right-handed batters due to hit. Hernandez usually dominates
right-handers because of his slider.
</P>
<P>
   Hernandez reached a two-strike count against Tony Batista, and
Batista slammed a double to left-center, Fullmer rounding the bases
and scoring the go-ahead run. Hernandez jumped ahead in the count
to Marty Cordova, one ball and two strikes, and he could not finish
off the left fielder, who drew a walk.
</P>
<P>
   Alex Gonzalez fell behind in the count no balls and two strikes;
Hernandez could not close out the at-bat quickly, the count reached
3-2 and Gonzalez blistered a double over the head of Williams in
center field, and two runs scored.
</P>
<P>
   Wells was relieved for the bottom of the sixth inning, having
allowed one run on five hits, without a strikeout.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
