<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 18:30 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1116 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-GALLAGHER-NYT &LR;      04-29 0433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-GALLAGHER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILLIAM F. GALLAGHER, 77, LEADER OF FOUNDATION FOR THE BLIND
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Mass.)  By WOLFGANG SAXON   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ William Francis Gallagher, a retired president of the
American Foundation for the Blind, died on April 19 at his home in
Webster, Mass., south of Worcester. He was 77 and had long been
ill, said the foundation, based in Manhattan, where Gallagher
formerly lived on the Upper East Side.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher, who lost his own sight in boyhood, joined the staff
of the foundation in 1972 as director of program planning. In that
role, he oversaw policies carried out by regional branches
stretching from New York to San Francisco, and advised on matters
like fund raising, public relations and research objectives.
</P>
<P>
   He was named associate director for advocacy in 1978, managing
field services, government relations, publications, conferences,
workshops and training sessions. He advanced to executive director
in 1980, added the title of president in 1989 and retired the next
year.
</P>
<P>
   The foundation, which in addition to serving the blind preserves
the archives of Helen Keller, the organization's principal
fund-raiser and adviser into the 1950s, credits Gallagher with
having kept staff and trustees abreast of the needs of the blind by
establishing national advisory boards of leaders in education,
rehabilitation and aging.
</P>
<P>
   It says he also helped improve standards for the accreditation
of specialized schools and agencies that offer services to the 10
million Americans who are blind or have limited sight.
</P>
<P>
   William Gallagher was born in Maynard, Mass., near Boston, and
graduated from the Perkins School for the Blind in Watertown,
Mass., where he was president of the student council, president of
the athletic association, captain of the wrestling team and a
member of the debating society. He graduated from Holy Cross
College with a degree in sociology in 1948 and received a master's
in social work at Boston College in 1950.
</P>
<P>
   He started 40 years of service to the blind that year as a
children's social worker for the city of Boston and for the
Catholic Guild for All the Blind in Newton, Mass. He then worked at
rehabilitation centers in Newton and in Bridgeville, Pa., and in
1965 was named director of rehabilitation services for the New York
Association for the Blind.
</P>
<P>
   He remained in that position until recruited by the American
Foundation for the Blind in 1972.
</P>
<P>
   Gallagher is survived by a sister, Mary Langan, of Clifton Park,
N.Y. His wife, Catherine O'Brien Gallagher, died in 1990.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1830EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0169 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 18:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1117 &Cx1f; tad-z
u e BC-FREAK-PLAYERS0430-COX     04-29 2399
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FREAK-PLAYERS0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Haunted by his homies
 &HT;    By Mike Fish and Dan Chapman
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ The party is kicking this night as Luther Campbell of
2 Live Crew fame tries to create the ``ultimate freak party,'' a
XXX-rated, booze-fueled sin fest inside the Coco Bongo nightclub in
Cancun, Mexico.
</P>
<P>
   He has the money: $2,000 in cash that guys eagerly hand over to
entice the ladies to get wild.
</P>
<P>
   He has the talent: a handful of buxom, skimpily clad young women
willing to perform sexual acts for the prize money.
</P>
<P>
   He has the celebrities: ``Ladies and gentlemen _ Ray Lewis,''
Campbell announces on the 1999 video.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis, the Baltimore Ravens star linebacker, enters Coco Bongo
with Joseph Sweeting. Rap music blares. Lights strobe. A shirtless
Lewis dances between two women, all grinding hips in time with the
music.
</P>
<P>
   One of the women is soon seen engaging in sexual acts _ first
with a woman, then with a man. The crowd of hundreds goes wild.
Lewis and Sweeting don't participate in any sex acts. But they've
got front row seats.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a year later, Lewis and Sweeting find themselves charged
with two counts of murder in the Jan. 31 stabbing deaths of two men
in Buckhead shortly after this year's Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   It's unclear whether prosecutors or defense attorneys are even
aware of the mail order video. As of Friday, it had not been
mentioned in either defense or prosecution documents filed with the
court. It's even less clear whether jurors will be shown the tape
during the trial.
</P>
<P>
   Legal experts question the video's relevance _ except to
establish a relationship between Lewis and Sweeting.
</P>
<P>
   ``The prejudice of that sort of tape greatly outweighs its
probative value,'' says Alan Baverman, an Atlanta criminal defense
lawyer.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the tape, ``Luke's Freak Show: Cancun 1999,'' could still
play a peripheral role in the case. For prosecutors, it supports
their contention Lewis was friends with co-defendants Sweeting and
Reginald Oakley, the third man charged with murder. In his initial
statement to police, Lewis denied knowing much of anything about
the people he partied with after the Super Bowl. His lawyers filed
a motion to have Lewis tried separately and have attempted to
distance Lewis from his co-defendants.
</P>
<P>
   The tape could also serve to refute defense lawyers' efforts to
portray Lewis as a solid family man _ a recurring theme in the NFL
linebacker's February bond hearing.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever role it plays, the video illustrates part of what has
made the case so intriguing to the public: the close relationship
between up-from-the-streets pro-athletes and the friends they don't
leave behind.
</P>
<P>
   FRIENDS FROM THE PAST
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting is a fledgling music producer in Miami who also
promotes shows at strip clubs along Miami Beach. Oakley is a small
time songwriter, producer and wannabe actor in Baltimore who, until
last year, ran a hair salon.
</P>
<P>
   While Lewis and other big-time athletes with eight-figure
contracts may have left their poorer, rougher upbringings behind,
they don't turn their backs on friends and family. To do so would
invite ridicule and opprobrium, say those familiar with the
intersecting worlds of sports and entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   So the newly wealthy and celebrated sometimes continue to
surround themselves with some of the unsavory trappings _ the thug
life, the misogyny, the hard-core partying _ of their previous
lives, at times with disastrous results. It's an environment
sometimes peopled by hookers and drug dealers, con men and killers.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting has been arrested for cocaine possession, car theft and
possession of a firearm by a felon, for which he was twice sent to
federal prison. Oakley has been arrested a handful of times on
charges of car theft, assaulting an officer, firing a gun into a
man's house and more. Lewis has been accused three times _ but
never convicted _ of assaulting women.
</P>
<P>
   All three grew up relatively poor, in neighborhoods where
athletes, musicians and their moneyed lifestyles were idolized.
</P>
<P>
   ''The rapper and ball players,'' says Campbell, who successfully
straddles the worlds of sport and entertainment, ``all come from
the same area, came up the same way. The combination has always
been there. The music, hip-hop culture, is really the hip-hop
nation, know what I'm saying? So everybody has a degree of respect
for each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell, former leader of 2 Live Crew, gained infamy the last
dozen years for his raunchy rap music denigrating women. Campbell
and two band mates were arrested on obscenity charges in 1990 after
their appearance at a Hollywood, Fla., nightclub. A judge had
previously ruled obscene the band's 1989 album, ``As Nasty as They
Wanna Be.''
</P>
<P>
   An appellate court judge, though, later overturned that ruling.
The album sold more than 2 million copies.
</P>
<P>
   For Lewis, the music and film worlds can provide glitz and
gorgeous women and the high-octane rush typically found on the
football field. For Oakley and Sweeting, hanging with big-time
athletes adds panache to their lives, boosting their prestige and
marketability.
</P>
<P>
   ''We're talking about people from a particular community who
happen to have money, fame and visibility,'' says Todd Boyd, an
assistant professor at the University of Southern California who
wrote ''The Day the Niggaz Took Over: Basketball, Commodity
Culture, and Black Masculinity.''
</P>
<P>
   ''Those things are not necessarily abundant when it comes to the
African-American community as a whole,'' Boyd adds. ``Athletes and
entertainers make a lot of money. So when you start to think about
who travels with whom, who hangs with whom _ at some point water
seeks its own level.''
</P>
<P>
   `NICE, EASYGOING CAT'
</P>
<P>
   A former high school wrestling star, Joseph ``Oomph'' Sweeting
broke into the entertainment business staging promotions at South
Florida strip clubs like Club Baby Doll and Black Gold. That's
where Sweeting crossed paths with Lewis and Campbell, a friend and
counselor to a long line of players in the University of Miami's
high-profile football program.
</P>
<P>
   ''Everybody knows him,'' former Miami player Tolbert Bain says
of Sweeting. ''You see him out. He promotes things in nightclubs
and most players go to nightclubs.''
</P>
<P>
   Adds Campbell, ''He's a nice, easygoing cat. I know he was a
good friend of Ray's. I know they're all right.''
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting and Campbell are close. The soundtrack for ``Freak Fest
2000,'' Campbell's latest XXX video, debuted last month and
Sweeting produced the single ''Lay Your A_ Down.'' He also plays a
pimp in the video.
</P>
<P>
   At 18, Sweeting was sentenced to a year in jail for grand theft
in North Florida's Duval County. A year later, he was charged with
stealing a car in the Fort Lauderdale area. Sweeting was also
arrested for cocaine possession, but charges were never filed
because the search was deemed illegal.
</P>
<P>
   Sweeting was later reportedly linked to the Untouchables, which
authorities described as a violent street gang responsible for
drive-by shootings and drug trafficking.
</P>
<P>
   In 1988, when Sweeting was 22, he was sentenced to federal
prison for possession of a firearm by a convicted felon. Within
months of his release, he was again charged with possession of a
firearm and returned to prison.
</P>
<P>
   ''He was one of the first people prosecuted by the feds for a
felon in possession of a firearm,'' said Metro-Dade County homicide
Detective Jerry Starkey. ``He was singled out because of his record
and the fact he was so bad.''
</P>
<P>
   But Sweeting changed, family members say.
</P>
<P>
   ''Joe had some problems, but that's all long ago,'' says his
mother, Daisy, outside their cinder block home in Goulds, a rough
section southwest of Miami.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Sweeting says his older brother is now legit and argues
the rap sheet is old news.
</P>
<P>
   ``Some of that is 15 years ago, half his life,'' Anthony said.
''You got so many people in the black community that go into
institutions and change their life. All you hear about are the
have-nots.''
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Sweeting said he discussed going with his brother to the
Super Bowl, but decided he couldn't break away from his beauty and
hair care supply business. His brother, he said, went to Atlanta
searching for contacts to enhance his entertainment career.
</P>
<P>
   ''He's writing music, working with a lot of up-and-coming people
here in Miami,'' Anthony said, adding that his brother would also
occasionally visit Lewis and other friends in Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING FOR EXCITEMENT
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, in Baltimore, was also trying to expand his professional
horizons.
</P>
<P>
   While growing up in small town North Carolina, Oakley wrote
poetry and songs and loved music, says mother Novella. Bored with
life in sleepy Oxford, N.C., Oakley moved to Charlotte, 150 miles
westward, for his last two years of high school. He'd bop back and
forth between the two towns, getting into trouble in each. From
1985 to 1992, Oakley was charged with roughly 25 criminal counts,
including assault, possession of a stolen vehicle, embezzlement,
assault on a law enforcement officer and firing into an occupied
dwelling.
</P>
<P>
   In June 1989, Oakley stole a Nissan Maxima, ran two police
roadblocks and jumped from the car while it was traveling at 35
mph, according to a police officer in Granville County. He escaped.
</P>
<P>
   The next year, Oakley was convicted of assaulting an officer and
other charges and sentenced to two years in prison. While being
transferred between jails, Oakley escaped. He was recaptured four
years later and finished serving his sentence in February 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He went to Baltimore to pursue a career producing and managing
musical acts. Oakley also ran Garfield's Phase II Beauty Salon in
the rundown Pimlico neighborhood of northwest Baltimore.
</P>
<P>
   Garfield Yuille, the featured national model for clothing line
FUBU, invited Oakley to live with him. He also introduced Oakley to
Lewis, according to Jesse Ingram, a Maryland entertainment lawyer.
The limousine driver who put Lewis at the scene of the Atlanta
murders told police he'd routinely chauffeur Oakley, Yuille and
Sweeting from Lewis' suburban mansion to Baltimore Ravens home
games.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors want Yuille to testify about the friendship between
Oakley and Lewis. Yuille wasn't in Atlanta during the Super Bowl,
says Ingram, who has represented him.
</P>
<P>
   Garfield's salon closed in 1999. Yet employees and customers
recall Oakley bragging about knowing Lewis, Denzel Washington and
members of the R&AMP;B group Dru Hill. Oakley also insisted he'd become
a big-time record and movie producer someday.
</P>
<P>
   Oakley has a business card that reads ``Azjha Songwriter and
Producer.'' His mother says Oakley managed a band that played
``love stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It sounded good to me,'' she says. ``I always felt like he
could make it.''
</P>
<P>
   THE BIG PARTY
</P>
<P>
   Oakley, Sweeting, Lewis, Campbell and others made it to Atlanta
for a Super Bowl week of partying. Lewis and Campbell took rooms at
the Georgian Terrace hotel and hung out with the legions of NFL
players and former Miami Hurricanes in town for the big game.
</P>
<P>
   Campbell says he called Lewis to discuss his troubles between
the time he was first questioned by police the morning of the
murders and his arrest about 10 hours later. He says Lewis remains
his favorite player. On Campbell's Web site, the rapper wears
Lewis' No. 52 Ravens jersey while promoting videos and CDs.
</P>
<P>
   ''There's a respect there, man,'' says Campbell. ''Of all the
guys I know at (Miami) _ and I know them all, from Jerome Brown to
Warren Sapp _ this man is the only one that ever said, 'Hey, man, I
appreciate all the conversations you ever had with me. I want to
bring you to Baltimore, put you up in a box and watch me play. I
want to do something for you.' This is what kind of cat this is.
That ain't no murderer.''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell recounts an incident the night before the Super Bowl
outside Club 112, an Atlanta nightspot.
</P>
<P>
   ''We were walking up to the club _ me, him, (NFL offensive
rookie of the year) Edgerrin James _ and people were running from
the club,'' Campbell recalls. ``The first thing Ray said was, 'Hey,
man, if they're fighting at the front door we don't need to go up
in there.' He said, 'I get paid to hit people on the field, I don't
get paid to hit (people) off the field, so we need to keep
going.'''
</P>
<P>
   Campbell headed back to Miami soon after the Super Bowl, missing
the partying that ended tragically outside the Cobalt lounge.
</P>
<P>
   The VIP room at Cobalt was full that night, with celebrities
like Lewis and former Atlanta Brave David Justice sipping champagne
while surrounded by beautiful women.
</P>
<P>
   Jacinth Baker and Richard Lollar were nearby. So, too, were
friends Jeff Gwen and Marlin Burros. The four pals from Akron,
Ohio, were also involved in the entertainment business, just like
Oakley and Sweeting. And Baker, Lollar and Gwen had criminal
records.
</P>
<P>
   Gwen is a fledgling rapper who goes by the name Chino Nino. His
recently released CD includes songs titled ``Crawl Till We Ball,''
``Club Hoppin,'' and ``Playas-N-Hustlers.'' He was on probation for
a drug conviction when he came to Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   Lollar, a cousin of Gwen's, was a barber who had been arrested
three times in Ohio for drug offenses. Baker, an aspiring artist,
was wanted by police for a probation violation involving drugs and
a gun. Burros, a music producer who also partly owned a hair salon
where Lollar worked, admitted firing the shots at Lewis' limousine
as it sped from the murder scene.
</P>
<P>
   Lollar and Baker were stabbed to death outside the Cobalt after
the two groups of men confronted each other early that Monday
morning. Lewis, free on bond, awaits trial in his Baltimore home,
leaving only to check in with house-arrest officials, consult with
attorneys, or work out at the nearby Ravens complex. It's a life
far removed from Cancun and Coco Bongo.
</P>
<P>
   There, Lewis wandered the streets and clubs with Styrofoam cup
in hand, ``Luke's Girls'' nearby.
</P>
<P>
   In one scene from the video, Luther Campbell waves Lewis and
Sweeting into the club for a night of ``Freak Show'' debauchery.
Campbell seems concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope you can play some football this year,'' he tells a
glazed-looking Lewis.
</P>
<P>
   Why do you worry? Lewis asks.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because you're partying too hard, baby.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
