</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 29, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS-2
-- Akther Ahmed, 32, chief executive of an Internet startup called
Gomingle.com, says Microsoft had treated him arrogantly in business
dealings. In the end, Ahmed did decide to go to another company, a
decision that meant spending $500,000 more for the computers,
double the Microsoft price. But Ahmed says that Microsoft needs to
be taught a lesson. ``When a company gets too arrogant, its
innovation goes down,'' he says. ``If Microsoft is broken up,'' he
concludes, ``in the long run, it'll be better for consumers.'' (Dan
Krauss/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 29, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS-1
-- With the government's proposal to split Microsoft into two
companies, many consumers are concerned about the impact on the
Windows operating system. Troy Anthony, at a computer store in
downtown San Francisco, uses the Windows system, and despite a
recent bug in his computer's Windows software, says he opposes
dividing Microsoft if it means destroying the Windows system. (Dan
Krauss/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) EDS: THE FOLLOWING PHOTO WAS SUBBED TO CORRECT THE
IDENTIFICATION IN PHOTO OF GEORGE SOROS -- NEW YORK -- April 30,
2000 -- MUST-SUB-SOROS-FUND --With bets that went sour on
technology stocks and on Europe's new currency, Soros' investment
group has suffered a 20 percent decline this year and, at $14.4
billion, is down roughly a third from a peak of $22 billion in
August 1998. In a letter sent Friday to shareholders and at a news
conference, George Soros, right, said that two of his two top money
managers including Stanley Druckenmiller, left, would leave their
posts shortly. (Frances Roberts/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) MITROVICA, Yugoslavia -- April 29, 2000 -- KOSOVO-U.N. --
Sergey Lavrov, center, the Russian ambassador to the United
Nations, talks with Oliver Ivanovich, a Serbian leader in
Mitrovica, on a tour of the divided city, Saturday, as
international peacekeepers stand by. The unusual visit by the
ambassadors came at the invitation of the director of the U.N.
mission in Kosovo, Dr. Bernard Kouchner, who is seeking more
support and personnel for his operations. (Andrew Testa/The New
York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) HILTON HEAD, S.C. -- April 29, 2000 -- BUSH-ADVISER --
Donald L. Evans, center, 53, a Texas businessman who was appointed
chairman of Texas Gov. George W. Bush's presidential campaign last
week, with Bush and Karen P. Hughes, Bush's communications
director, after a campaign stop in Hilton Head, S.C., on Feb. 16,
2000. Evans, it seems, has almost always been present at the
pivotal junctures in Bush's life, an important witness to the
evolution of both the man and the candidate and an integral part of
his political campaigns, especially the current one. (Andrea
Mohin/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) MIDDLETON, Mass. -- April 29, 2000 --
HIGHSCHOOL-GAY-ATHLETE -- For school systems around the country
struggling with such complex issues as diversity, tolerance and
jock culture, Corey Johnson's story is a hopeful model. Johnson,
18, co-captain of the Masconomet High School Football Team in
Middleton, Mass., is gay. For gay activists trying to shatter
stereotypes, Johnson is a rare find, a bright, warm quick study who
also wrestled and played lacrosse and baseball as he earned three
varsity letters on a winning football team. Johnson after a 1999
game. (New York Times Photo)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) WASHINGTON -- April 29, 2000 -- GAY-MARCH-2 -- Caroline
and Anne Cook-Rose of Richmond, Va., left, and Carla Carlson and
Jackee Phillips of Wisconsin, couple at right, were among the
hundreds of gay couples participating in a mass commitment ceremony
at the Lincoln Memorial in Washington, Saturday. The ceremony was
part of the ``The ``Millennium March'' taking place in the U.S.
capital, in which throngs of gays and lesbians and their supporters
will march on Sunday to demand public legitimacy and to mobilize as
a voting bloc this November. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) WASHINGTON -- April 29, 2000 -- GAY-MARCH-1 -- Judy
Shepard, with her husband, Dennis, directly behind, greeting a
guest at a party at the Ronald Reagan Building and Internatonal
Trade Center, Friday. The couple, parents of Matthew Shepard, a gay
youth who was beaten to death in 1998 in Laramie, Wyo., were
honored for their work on behalf of gays. The Shepards are planning
to be a part of The ``Millennium March'' taking place in the U.S.
capital, in which throngs of gays and lesbians and their supporters
will march on Sunday to demand public legitimacy and to mobilize as
a voting bloc this November. (Stephen Crowley/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
