<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 04/29/00. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT14) NEW YORK -- April 29, 2000 -- NY-SPRING-EXERCISE-FLOAT
-- Ng Wong, Jenny Lum and Sam Luk practice Tai Chi in Seward Park
on the Lower East side of Manhattan, Saturday. As Spring like
temperatures finally surfaced many New Yorkers took to the outdoors
for a breath of fresh air. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT13) NEW YORK -- April 29, 2000 -- NY-CHERRY-BLOSSOMS-FLOAT
-- Randy McKean and his daughter Sophia, 4, check out the blossoms
and enjoy the scents of Spring during the 19th annual Cherry
Blossom Festival at the Brooklyn Botanical Gardens, Saturday. Arts,
crafts, dance, Japanese taiko drumming and other activities were
featured as part of the event. (Vincent Laforet/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT12) ATLANTA -- April 29, 2000 -- VIETNAM-PHOTOS-COX --
Harold E. Webb poses near a famous photograph taken by Larry
Burrows during the Vietnam War in October 1966. The photo is a part
of the Requiem exhibit at the Atlanta History Center. The exhibit
features photos taken during the wars in Vietnam, Indochina,
Cambodia and Laos by photographers who died covering the war. The
man sitting in the foreground of the battle picture is believed by
many to be Harold Webb. Webb says he can't be sure because he
doesn't remember much from that day. He was wounded in both legs,
as was the man in the photo. If the soldier in the photo is Webb,
the picture would have been about a week before his twentieth
birthday. (Jean Shifrin/The Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT11) NEW YORK -- April 29, 2000 -- NY-BUSH-TALKRADIO-FLOAT --
Texas governor and Republican presidential candidate George W. Bush
answers a question for the WOR New York radio station after
addressing the National Association of Radio Talk Show Hosts at the
Empire Hotel in Manhattan, Saturday. Richard Neer from WFAN sports
talk, at left. (Ruth Fremson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT10) NEW YORK -- April 29, 2000 -- JESUS-ARTISTS -- In a
two-month exhibit billed as ``35 of the top images of Jesus Christ
for the new millennium,'' featured artists and winners of a contest
sponsored by The National Catholic Reporter, a weekly newspaper,
based in Kansas City, Mo., prepared to display their art at the
gallery of the Schimmel Center for the Arts, at Pace University.
The contest was intended to elicit the many faces of Jesus as seen
by an increasingly diverse human family in this day and age. Sister
Joanna Chan, left, a Maryknoll nun, with her image of Jesus. The
contest's winner, Janet McKenzie, right, of Island Pond, Vt., used
a black woman as her model for Jesus. (Dith Pran/The New York
Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) WASHINGTON -- April 29, 2000 -- RUBIN-PROFILE -- James P.
Rubin, 40, the State Department spokesman, is leaving Washington
behind to move to London with his wife, Christiane Amanpour, the
CNN foreign correspondent. During nearly eight years at the side of
Madeleine Albright, the first woman to serve as secretary of state,
Rubin fulfilled a number of roles: friend, adviser, protege, gossip
buddy, fashion consultant and self-described ``intellectual mate.''
Playing the dual role of public voice and private counsel, Rubin
recast the spokesman's post in a relentless era of 24-hour news
cycles. (Susana Raab/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 29, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS-2
-- Akther Ahmed, 32, chief executive of an Internet startup called
Gomingle.com, says Microsoft had treated him arrogantly in business
dealings. In the end, Ahmed did decide to go to another company, a
decision that meant spending $500,000 more for the computers,
double the Microsoft price. But Ahmed says that Microsoft needs to
be taught a lesson. ``When a company gets too arrogant, its
innovation goes down,'' he says. ``If Microsoft is broken up,'' he
concludes, ``in the long run, it'll be better for consumers.'' (Dan
Krauss/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) SAN FRANCISCO -- April 29, 2000 -- MICROSOFT-CONSUMERS-1
-- With the government's proposal to split Microsoft into two
companies, many consumers are concerned about the impact on the
Windows operating system. Troy Anthony, at a computer store in
downtown San Francisco, uses the Windows system, and despite a
recent bug in his computer's Windows software, says he opposes
dividing Microsoft if it means destroying the Windows system. (Dan
Krauss/The New York Times)
</P>
