<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 18:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1124 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT     04-29 0275
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CORRECTIONS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK TIMES CORRECTIONS FOR SATURDAY, APRIL 29
</HEADLINE>
 Eds.: These corrections will appear in The New York Times on
Saturday. Days and dates refer to the original article's
transmission by the New York Times News Service, and may need to be
adjusted by NYT clients.)  
(ss) 
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   BC-CANADA-POLITICS-NYT(moved Tuesday, April 25)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Tuesday, April 25
about Stockwell Day, a conservative politician from Western Canada
who hopes to become prime minister next year, misstated the
precedent for Western Canadians. If elected, Day would be the
fourth in nearly four decades, not the second. The article also
referred incorrectly to Joe Clark, a former prime minister who
would be left out of a proposed merger of conservative parties. He
was not the last prime minister from Western Canada; Kim Campbell
of British Columbia was, in 1993.
</P>
<P>
   BC-CT-MLK-DAY-NYT(moved Wednesday, April 26)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service article sent on Wednesday, April
26 about the Rev. Jesse Jackson's visit to Wallingford, Conn., to
urge town officials to observe Martin Luther King's Birthday,
referred incorrectly to a white supremacist's use of a bullhorn. He
used it to shout, ``You people are inferior!,'' not to give his
name to a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   BC-SCI-SPIN-ART-NYT(moved Monday, April 24)
</P>
<P>
   A New York Times News Service Science article sent on Monday,
April 24 about the mathematics of spinning coins, misstated the
location of a company whose toy inspired the research. The company,
Tangent Toy, is based in Sausalito, Calif., not San Diego.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
