<P>
   GUSEWELLE-COLUMN (Undated) _ column by C.W. GUSEWELLE. Story
will move in the ``k'' category.
</P>
<P>
   WAR-VIETNAM: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For many whose lives collided
with the Vietnam War, the cost has been exorbitant: More than
58,000 Americans dead. Three million Vietnamese. Hundreds of
thousands more wounded or missing. Billions in dollars lost. A
country torn to pieces. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Those intimately involved with the war _ combat veterans,
refugees, families of the American and Vietnamese dead _ still pay
a price.
</P>
<P>
   For veterans it can be flashbacks, alienation, bitterness. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   For refugees, it's the loss of home and family.
</P>
<P>
   And for families of the dead it's the steepest price of all: the
relentless imagining of what might have been. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   On the 25th anniversary of the end of the war, what follow are
glimpses into lives touched by Vietnam, short stories about a few
of the many who remember, a few of the many who still hurt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   FISHER-VIETNAM: WAMEGO, Kan. _ On a windy March day in 1967, the
first of Wamego's Vietnam War funerals took place _ that of Sgt.
Steven Szijjarto, 26. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Although Wamego saw three more of its sons killed in the war,
which ended 25 years ago today, Szijjarto's burial is the one that
most remember here. For Vietnam wasn't Szijjarto's first fight
against Communism. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Szijjarto was a refugee from the 1956 Hungarian revolt, a
``freedom fighter.'' He survived that fighting, only to be killed
10 years later. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Shot in the head after jumping from a helicopter in a ``hot''
landing zone, he was one of 626 Kansans and 1,411 Missourians who
died in the war, who came home in aluminum caskets to towns big and
small. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By JIM FISHER. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
<P>
   WAKE-VIETNAM: KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The job sounded perfect for a
meteorologist: be a weatherman on a sleepy tropical island in the
South Pacific. Palm trees. Ocean breezes. Great pay. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Lowden applied. And in 1973 he flew to a place few people
ever visit: Wake Island. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   What he didn't think about was how isolating it would be. The
population was 150 _ all men.
</P>
<P>
   But when Saigon fell to the North Vietnamese, overnight, the
sleepy island awoke. It became one of the few places where Vietnam
refugees could stay until transferred to the United States. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In less than two weeks, the island's population grew from 150 to
8,000 _ men, women, children and babies. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Lowden captured it all with his camera. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH. Story will move in the ``a'' category.
</P>
