<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 19:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1132 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-ZIMBABWE-MUGABE-BOS &LR;      04-29 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ZIMBABWE-MUGABE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MUGABE VOWS TO INVOKE SPECIAL POWERS TO SEIZE LAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KURT SHILLINGER  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   HARARE, Zimbabwe _ Rebuffing concerted regional and
international initiatives, President Robert Mugabe planned to
invoke special powers to confiscate and resettle white-owned farms,
his justice minister announced Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   ``Within 10 days, the legal framework to take land and
redistribute land to the people will be in place,'' Minister
Emmerson Mnangagwa said.
</P>
<P>
   The statement exacerbated tensions inside Zimbabwe, where
violence has claimed at least 15 lives in the runup to Mugabe's
most serious electoral challenge in two decades.
</P>
<P>
   The British government and Commercial Farmers Union said the
call violated the spirit of progress toward ending the violence in
Zimbabwe, which is suffering its worst crisis since independence.
</P>
<P>
   But it was not entirely clear what powers Mugabe would invoke,
or why. Before disbanding this month, Parliament passed a
constitutional amendment allowing the government to take land
without compensating the owner. ``It's quite clearly an election
gimmick,'' said David Coltart, a senior lawyer and member of the
opposition Movement for Democratic Change.
</P>
<P>
   Violence has escalated across Zimbabwe since opposition and
civic leaders rallied voters in February to reject a new
constitution proposed by the government, dealing Mugabe and his
ruling party their first ballot defeat in 20 years.
</P>
<P>
   Encouraged by the president, veterans of the 1970s war for
independence and other government supporters marched onto
white-owned commercial farms, beating farm workers, destroying
property, and claiming the land as their own. Vast stretches of
prime agricultural land lies in the hands of roughly 4,500 whites,
while the majority of rural blacks live as peasants on marginal
plots.
</P>
<P>
   Roughly 1,000 farms have been invaded, but the opposition
continues to hold widespread support ahead of the parliamentary
elections _ due by August _ and violence is shifting to new arenas.
Opposition leaders have been killed in roadside ambushes and their
homes have been fire-bombed. Local and foreign journalists face
growing harassment.
</P>
<P>
   A bomb exploded last Saturday night in the Harare office
building of the Daily News, Zimbabwe's only independent daily
paper. Four days later, police arrested South African Obed Zilwa, a
photographer for the Associated Press, at the airport. They
detained him for three days, releasing him on bail only Saturday
after confiscating his passport.
</P>
<P>
   The state blames Zilwa, who was one of the first journalists on
the scene after the explosion, for planting the bomb. The newspaper
disagrees, and had traced a threatening call placed before the
blast to the ruling party's headquarters.
</P>
<P>
   Emerging dirty and haggard from detention, Zilwa said Saturday
that ``the whole thing was politically related. There were police
officers who called me the `journalist bomber.' '' The state is due
to decide whether to prosecute Zilwa on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   The heightened rhetoric and intimidation follow a flurry of
international efforts to defuse Zimbabwe's crisis. A week ago, in a
meeting between Mugabe and regional leaders at Victoria Falls,
South African President Thabo Mbeki offered the Zimbabwean leader a
private deal: If Mugabe ended the farm invasions and organized free
and fair elections, Western donors would finance land reform and
shore up the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Britain reinforced that plan on Thursday, offering to add $57
million to previous _ now frozen _ aid in exchange for land reform
if Mugabe ended the violence.
</P>
<P>
   Zimbabwe refused to ensure that the invasions would end. One day
after assuring farmers that the attacks would end, war veteran
leader Chenjerai Hunzvi Saturday marched through the streets of
Harare with 2,000 supporters, vowing to deal ruthlessly with
opposition members, farm workers, and the whites who back them.
</P>
<P>
   The march, combined with Mnangagwa's announced intention to
seize more land, threatened to scuttle whatever diplomatic progress
had been made. ``There can be no justification for this,'' said
British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook, responding to the justice
minister's statement. ``If it takes this step, the government of
Zimbabwe will make it impossible for those who want help with land
reform in Zimbabwe to do so.''
</P>
<P>
   Mnangagwa shrugged off Cook's comment. ``Britain's stance is not
our problem,'' he said. ``It does not matter what they think or
say.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
