<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMBODIA-TRIBUNAL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UN, CAMBODIA NEAR DEAL ON KHMER ROUGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN DONNELLY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ In an apparent breakthrough toward justice for the
wrongdoing at Pol Pot's killing fields in Cambodia, the United
Nations and the Cambodian government have reached a tentative
agreement to try Khmer Rouge leaders on genocide charges, Senator
John Kerry said Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   The Massachusetts Democrat, who has worked on Cambodian issues
for more than a decade, acted in Phnom Penh as mediator between the
UN and the Cambodian government on Friday and Saturday. He said he
has helped bridge their differences.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pol Pot has died. There has been 20 years now without any
trials,'' Kerry said in an interview from Bangkok, where he stopped
for a layover on his way to Boston. ``This is the final hurdle
toward starting the trials.''
</P>
<P>
   From 1975 to 1979, the Khmer Rouge oversaw a reign of terror,
killing an astounding 1.7 million people. Three years ago, Cambodia
requested assistance from the United Nations to convene a genocide
tribunal, but the negotiations have run into numerous difficulties,
including whether foreign or Cambodian judges and prosecutors would
participate.
</P>
<P>
   The tentative deal, which has to be completed by June 15, calls
for an arrangement that includes a Cambodian and foreign prosecutor
deciding what cases to bring from the 1975-1979 period. If they
disagree, an arbitration panel then must rule within 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   The tribunal would consist of three Cambodian judges and two
international judges. Indictments would stand unless struck down by
judges from both sides, a point the UN had insisted upon.
</P>
<P>
   Cambodian officials had long stressed that a tribunal couldn't
override their sovereignty, but UN negotiators refused to
relinquish power because of Cambodia's politicized judiciary and
because of the precedent it would set in the emerging field of
international justice.
</P>
<P>
   Now, UN negotiator Hans Corell is expected to travel to Phnom
Penh soon to negotiate remaining details, and the Cambodian
Parliament must ratify the arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   A top Cambodian negotiator confirmed the handshake deal in Phnom
Penh.
</P>
<P>
   ``As far as Cambodia is concerned, the government has given its
agreement,'' said Om Yentieng, an aide to Prime Minister Hun Sen.
</P>
<P>
   Sara Colm, a researcher at Human Rights Watch who has followed
Cambodian issues since 1985, said that it was hard to judge the
deal without seeing more specifics. She expressed concern, however,
about the arbitration panel, saying that it might politicize the
process by voting on contested indictments as outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   She also said it would take some time before anyone could say
the deal was certain.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's fairly easy to announce victory in Cambodia, and then
find it reversed, given the political winds,'' Colm said. ``The
best strategy is to support the UN in its original approach to the
Cambodian problem with its fairly high standards.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry, the ranking member of the Senate Foreign Relations
Committee's subcommittee on Asia and a Vietnam War veteran, agreed
that more steps need to be taken to finish the deal.
</P>
<P>
   He added, ``All of us, myself included, have our eyes open for
mischief here and there. But you must remember that there will be
international scrutiny in this process. If anyone tries any monkey
business in the course of this, it will be quite evident.''
</P>
<P>
   Kerry met with Hun Sen for more than three hours Friday night.
He then held meetings with a series of top officials who opposed
earlier deals, including Deputy Prime Minister Sar Kheng and Prince
Norodom Ranariddh, and with four local human rights groups. Kerry
said all supported this arrangement.
</P>
<P>
   Hun Sen and several other top officials in his ruling Cambodian
People's Party are former Khmer Rouge. Many in the party wanted to
limit the tribunal's jurisdiction to minimize chances of
prosecution. Hun Sen, 48, has never been linked to any atrocities.
</P>
<P>
   Only two major Khmer Rouge leaders are in custody. Pol Pot, its
main leader, died of an apparent heart attack in 1998. Many of his
former aides live freely in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Kerry's mediation, along with efforts by other US officials,
including David Scheffer, the State Department's war crimes
specialist, has followed a parallel path to the UN-Cambodia
negotiations. Kerry said the UN supported his recent efforts.
</P>
<P>
   Part of his motivation, he said, was personal.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a Vietnam vet, I feel a personal linkage and responsibility
for helping to see if we can build a system of justice, and of
accountability for the terrible things that happened,'' he said.
``We played a significant role in Cambodia during the war, with the
bombings and the overthrow of the government. That is an
inheritance of that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
