</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BEST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
JACK BEST, 87; HELPED HATCH A DARING ESCAPE FROM NAZIS
</HEADLINE>
  By WILLIAM H. HONAN   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Jack Best, one of the last survivors of the audacious group of
British prisoners in World War II who constructed a glider under
the noses of their Nazi captors in order to fly from the roof of
their prison to freedom, died April 22 in a hospital in
Herefordshire, England. He was 87.
</P>
<P>
   Before the glider could be put to the test, the notorious
Colditz prison, a huge Saxon castle near Leipzig in eastern Germany
where Best and many other British airmen were imprisoned, was
liberated by U.S. forces in 1945. But because the plan was so
daring and its secrecy so effective, it has become one of the
legends of World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Last winter, Best was a consultant for Channel Four, a British
commercial television channel, when it constructed a full-scale
replica of the glider with its 32-foot wingspan and flew it for a
documentary called ``Escape From Colditz.'' The original glider had
been broken up and used for firewood at the war's end.
</P>
<P>
   Later this year, the glider replica, together with some of the
actual tools Best made to help construct it, and other memorabilia,
will go on display at the Imperial War Museum in London.
</P>
<P>
   The plan to build the glider was hatched by Best and two of his
fellow British prisoners at Colditz Castle. Their plan was to
construct a two-man glider in a secret workshop in one of the
castle's attics. When completed, the glider was to be taken to the
roof and launched by a catapult, which consisted of a series of
cables and pulleys.
</P>
<P>
   The planners reckoned that their captors would be looking for
tunnels and underground escape routes, nothing as audacious as a
leap to freedom. The catapult was to be given its impetus by a
massive counterweight _ a bathtub filled with concrete that was to
be dropped to the ground, flinging the glider into the air.
</P>
<P>
   If all went well, said Kenneth Lockwood, the secretary of the
Colditz Association, a survivors' group, the glider would
noiselessly soar for about a mile from a height of about 100 feet
down over the town of Colditz, over farmland and finally over the
River Mulde, landing on the far side of the river.
</P>
<P>
   ``The key thing was to cross the river,'' Lockwood said in a
telephone interview on Friday. ``If they could clear that they
could reach a nearby railroad station, board a train and make it to
Switzerland, which was neutral.''
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood also said that Best, having failed at an earlier chance
to escape, agreed to give his seat on the glider to someone else.
``Even though he was a pilot who could have flown the glider,''
Lockwood said, ``he said he would stand down for someone else. His
specialty became making the tools to construct the glider _ like a
saw, a plane and a chisel.''
</P>
<P>
   The glider was basically made from wood taken from bed slats and
floorboards. Its skin was fashioned from cotton sleeping bags. It
took nine months to construct.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood, who had been captured in Belgium, said he was part of
the ``stooging system'' in which he would serve as a lookout to
warn those constructing the glider to cease their work if a guard
approached.
</P>
<P>
   It was only after liberation that the Germans learned that the
glider had been constructed. The survivors of Colditz were
especially pleased by the success of the replica glider almost half
a century later because it proved to them that their plan was a
smart one and that they could have soared away from the supposedly
escape-proof Colditz Castle.
</P>
<P>
   John William Best was born in Vivod near Llangollen in North
Wales. As a young man, he moved to Kenya to learn farming. It was
from Kenya that he enlisted in the Royal Air Force in 1939.
</P>
<P>
   Best was captured in 1941 after he was forced to ditch his plane
off the coast of Greece. He was held at the Stalag Luft III prison
_ known from the film ``The Great Escape'' _ but tunneled his way
out with a fellow prisoner. They made it 125 miles to Szczecin,
Poland, before being recaptured. They were then sent to Colditz.
</P>
<P>
   After the war, Best returned to farming in Kenya, but in the
1960s he returned to England, where again he went into farming.
</P>
<P>
   Best's marriage to Constance Otter ended in divorce. He is
survived by his second wife, Elisabeth Bunting of Leominster,
Herefordshire; a son, Bob, and a daughter, Tanda Wilson-Clarke,
both of North Wales; and five grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   ``Jack Best had a most wonderful sense of humor,'' Lockwood
said. ``If we hadn't had a sense of humor about all this we would
have gone around the bend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1920EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
