<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1139 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-POLITICIANS-HEALTH-2T     04-29 1107
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POLITICIANS-HEALTH-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEWS ANALYSIS: LIKE IT OR NOT, PUBLIC IS NOW PRIVY TO POLITICIANS'
HEALTH
</HEADLINE>
  By JOYCE PURNICK   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Americans once knew little about Franklin D.
Roosevelt's paralysis from polio or John F. Kennedy's struggle with
Addison's disease. Woodrow Wilson's failing health was kept dark
and mysterious, and Sen. Jacob Javits told voters less than they
needed to know about his terminal fight with Lou Gehrig's disease.
</P>
<P>
   But when a biopsy of his prostate gland came back positive last
Wednesday, New York City Mayor Rudolph Giuliani held a news
conference on Thursday. When a predecessor, Edward Koch, collapsed
at his gym a few years back, he told reporters from his gurney that
he was fine. We know that Janet Reno's shaking hands betray not
nervousness but the impact of Parkinson's disease, that Bill
Bradley has an irregular heartbeat and that President Clinton's
hearing is not what it used to be.
</P>
<P>
   We know a great deal today about the health problems of
prominent people _ more than some of us want to know. But we know
it anyway, because they tell us. Because what used to be private
has become public, in every arena of life. Savvy public figures _
especially political candidates _ reveal all before the rumor mill,
fed by an aggressive, competitive press, does it for them.
</P>
<P>
   What happened between then and now? Nearly a half century.
``Things have changed and changed radically, and I think for the
better,'' said Richard Reeves, a biographer of President Kennedy.
``We've moved along with the curve of openness that is the 20th
century.'' An openness sometimes bordering on performance art.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oprah did it,'' Reeves said, only half kidding.
</P>
<P>
   Since the Kennedy years, there have been Watergate and its
aftertaste of cynicism. The de-demonization of cancer, a word that
once was only whispered. Treatments for cancer, AIDS and other
diseases that control or cure them. The confessional nature of a
society filled with people who want their 15 minutes. The ``rapidly
diminishing, if not disappearing zone of privacy for public
officials,'' in the words of Alan Brinkley, a historian at Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   There is also a sense of obligation these days, a feeling that
talking publicly about illness informs people, emboldens them to
have mammograms and colonoscopies and blood tests for prostate
cancer _ the tests that alerted Giuliani to his problem.
</P>
<P>
   For many of the prominent, shame has been replaced by a candor
that can veer from the refreshing to the relentless. Illness gives
the celebrity patient an opportunity to become a representative for
his or her condition, to inform and educate, sometimes with
remunerative rewards.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dole _ the failed presidential candidate who became a
national spokesman for erectile dysfunction and Viagra after his
surgery for prostate cancer _ praised Giuliani last week for
speaking publicly about his cancer, saying his openness ``will
benefit potentially hundreds of thousands of people.''
</P>
<P>
   The city comptroller, Alan Hevesi, who had prostate cancer four
years ago, talked about it at the time and says he is sure his
openness saved the lives of other men. Telephone calls and letters
convinced him that the impact ``was extensive,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Joe Torre, the Yankees manager, who was treated for prostate
cancer last year, said the same. ``I thought it was best to be as
honest as I could be, and then after getting all the letters and
cards from all the people who have had this, I realized this was
the best thing.''
</P>
<P>
   For politicians, there is also ample proof that any attempt to
color the truth can hurt much more than telling the public about a
disease, unless it is debilitating or life-threatening. ``It's not
a crime to be unhealthy, but exactly the same as with a crime, it's
not the crime, it's the cover-up.'' Reeves said.
</P>
<P>
   Even absent a cover-up, a candidate can hurt himself if he is
not candid enough. Many contend that happened with Bill Bradley
during his unsuccessful campaign for president last fall. He has
paroxysmal atrial fibrillation, which produces brief bursts of
irregular heart rhythm. It is a common condition _ a nuisance,
Bradley called it. But he did not mention the condition, first
diagnosed in 1996, until he had to be hospitalized after suffering
a bout of irregular heartbeats.
</P>
<P>
   ``He should have disclosed it before the campaign,'' said Howard
Rubenstein, the New York public relations consultant. ``Here he
goes portrayed as a jock, athlete, intelligent strongman. Suddenly
he's seen as vulnerable.'' There were many reasons the Bradley
campaign faltered, but that was clearly one of them.
</P>
<P>
   Long after full disclosure of health matters had become common
in politics, Sen. Paul Tsongas of Massachusetts, a presidential
candidate in 1992, had to acknowledge that he had mishandled the
matter of his cancer. At first, he told voters he had been
successfully treated for lymphoma, but later, after dropping out of
the race, he acknowledged under pressure that he and his doctors
had concealed a recurrence. He died of cancer in January 1997, just
as his first term would have ended.
</P>
<P>
   Even what was known about his lymphoma probably hurt his
candidacy, political analysts say today. Many also believe that had
the public understood the serious nature of Addison's disease,
Kennedy would have lost to Richard Nixon in 1960. And mental
illness is still generally considered damaging to a candidate, as
it was in 1972 when George McGovern was forced to replace his
running mate, Sen. Thomas Eagleton of Missouri, after it was
disclosed that he had been hospitalized for depression.
</P>
<P>
   But generally voters do not recoil at knowledge of a treatable
condition, say advisers to candidates and the politicians
themselves. Plus, what, they ask, is the choice?
</P>
<P>
   ``There is always the downside in that people can start a
whisper campaign and question whether someone is up to the job,''
said Peter Powers, Giuliani's friend and adviser. ``But if you are
up front and honest about it and confront it, especially today with
the media so large and the Internet out there, people would know
everything anyway. So you just deal with it.''
</P>
<P>
   Koch, who advised his doctors to tell the public everything
there was to know about the stroke he had while in office (and then
he told people everything he knew about it, too), agreed. ``In
today's world, it's going to get out, so it's far better to get it
out in a responsible way.''
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani's story, for instance, was already leaking by the time
he held his news conference.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Americans knew only sketchy outlines of Dwight D. Eisenhower's
heart problems, compared with what they would know today. Some
candidates kept the truth from the public. In 1972, Bella Abzug
made many an enemy by challenging Rep. William Ryan of New York,
who was suffering from throat cancer but denied he was ill. He won
the primary, then died three months later.
</P>
<P>
   But President Lyndon B. Johnson was showing the world his
gallbladder surgery scar in 1965; nine years later, Betty Ford was
forthcoming about her breast cancer and drinking problem, getting
plaudits for raising awareness.
</P>
<P>
   Ronald Reagan did try to maintain his privacy when he had
surgery for colon cancer in 1985, but then wrote an open letter to
the American public when he was found to have Alzheimer's disease
in 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Now the expectation of openness is a given. ``It's just
unacceptable in our culture for someone running for office to say
my health is my own business,'' Brinkley said. ``Because to some
degree, for people running for office, their health isn't their
business.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0192 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 19:22 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1141 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-JESUS-ARTISTS-ART-NYT     04-29 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-JESUS-ARTISTS-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ARTISTS FASHION IMAGES OF JESUS THAT GO BEYOND THE CRUCIFIX 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Vt., Germany, Ill.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT10 is being sent to NYT photo clients.
Nonsubscribers can purchase one-time rights by calling 888-603-1036
or 888-346-9867.) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ On the walls of the gallery at Pace University hang
pictures of Jesus as a poor black death row inmate. The Messiah as
a panhandler. Christ as TV anchor. The savior as a woman.
</P>
<P>
   In a two-month exhibit billed ``35 of the top images of Jesus
Christ for the new millennium,'' the featured artists are winners
of a contest sponsored by The National Catholic Reporter, the
weekly newspaper. The contest was intended to elicit the many faces
of Jesus as seen by an increasingly diverse human family.
</P>
<P>
   More than 1,000 people from 19 countries submitted entries. The
judge for the 10 finalists, Sister Wendy Beckett, the BBC's art
critic, wrote of the winners, ``Every viewer will understand our
Lord more deeply as he or she thinks of what this image could be
and responds to what the artists have made visible.''
</P>
<P>
   The winner, Janet McKenzie of Island Pond, Vt., used a black
woman for the model of her ``Jesus of the People.'' When it ran on
the cover of The Reporter, feathers flew, with one parish
threatening to protest her painting.
</P>
<P>
   The newspaper's editor, Michael J. Farrell, wrote in the
exhibition's program that Jesus remained still controversial, 2000
years after his birth.
</P>
<P>
   ``Were it otherwise, he would scarcely be kin to the original,
the charismatic Messiah who stirred up and, for better or worse,
left no one unaffected,'' he wrote.
</P>
<P>
   McKenzie's picture includes a yin-yang symbol and an eagle
feather, evoking Asian and American Indian cultures.
</P>
<P>
   ``There hasn't been an aspect of the painting that hasn't been
ripped apart and celebrated,'' she said. ``The essence of Jesus is
just love. I don't think it matters what image he's celebrated in,
as long as you get the essence, the point of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Another artist, Michael F. Di Nunzio of Bad Wiessee, Germany,
depicted Jesus as a news broadcaster next to a phone on a
television screen.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guiding thought beyond all my pictures of Jesus is what
would Jesus do if he were to live today,'' said Di Nunzio, who was
visiting New York for the opening. ``Of course he would make use of
the medium of television, not only to communicate his message but
to communicate himself, because he is the message.''
</P>
<P>
   Sister Joanna Chan, a Maryknoll nun and host of the exhibit,
also submitted an entry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a young, exuberant, risen lord, dancing in the streets of
Jerusalem, dancing with an Arab,'' she said. ``It's my dream of
world peace.''
</P>
<P>
   Other artists featured were a 1983 Nobel Peace Prize nominee, S.
Graham Sargent, who depicted Jesus as a jug spilling water into the
sea, and Father John B. Giuliani, an internationally known icon
painter.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit opens Monday and runs through June 30 in the gallery
of the Schimmel Center for the Arts, at Pace University, on Spruce
Street in lower Manhattan. It is free and is open Monday through
Friday from 1-5 p.m.
</P>
<P>
   The exhibit will travel to Chicago's Catholic Theological Union
in July.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1922EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
