r s BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COWBOYS-     04-29 0827
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-GALLOWAY-COWBOYS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOR COWBOYS, ALL THAT IS OLD AND BORING IS NEW AND EXCITING AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ A little more than two years ago, Ernie Zampese
packed up himself and his boring, predictable offense, then headed
on down the NFL road. The Cowboys needed massive change.
</P>
<P>
   Out with the old. In with the new.
</P>
<P>
   A few months ago, Chan Gailey packed up himself and his boring,
predictable offense and headed on down the NFL road. The Cowboys
needed massive change.
</P>
<P>
   Out with the old. In with the old.
</P>
<P>
   Say there, Mr. Jones. Are we confused, or is it just you?
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, I was a little surprised,'' the 64-year-old Zampese said
Friday at Valley Ranch, where he's unpacked himself and his offense
for another stay. ``Jerry and I were talking at the Senior Bowl
\Rin February\S, and he mentioned he'd like to bring back the old
offense. Then he said he wanted me to come with it. As a
consultant. I never knew exactly what a consultant did. But I'm
willing to find out.''
</P>
<P>
   All of this makes perfect sense, if, that is, you're willing to
believe the system makes players instead of the players making a
system. As long as there has been football, that's been an ongoing
debate.
</P>
<P>
   But the offensive philosophy of Zampese was in place when three
Super Bowls were won at Valley Ranch. The offensive philosophy of
Gailey had no such local roots, nor any prayer of establishing
same. Two years and gone. Things moved fast, particularly once
Jerry Jones started doubting his original decision to throw out the
Zampese system and have Gailey take the offense in another
direction.
</P>
<P>
   Did, however, the system really matter in the first place? Both
ended up failing. Or was it players within both systems who failed?
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe the system matters,'' said new head coach Dave
Campo, who as the Cowboys' defensive coordinator worked daily in
practice against what Zampese and Gailey wanted to do. But at the
first minicamp of his regime, Campo watched Friday as a Zampese
protege, Jack Reilly, began to re-install the offense of choice for
Campo.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is obvious to everyone we've got a strong-armed quarterback
who can get rid of the ball in a hurry,'' Campo said of Troy
Aikman. ``What I want is an offense that is based on the
quarterback getting rid of the ball in a hurry, and getting it into
the hands of playmakers. The old offense \Rnow the new offense\S
does just that.''
</P>
<P>
   But, of course, that didn't happen in that woeful 6-10 season of
'97, making it, temporarily anyway, Ernie's last stand at Valley
Ranch, as well as the last stand of imitation head coach Gunsmoke.
</P>
<P>
   What happened? Could it have been receivers Anthony Miller and
Stepfret Williams disappearing as alternatives to Michael Irvin? Or
tight ends Eric Bjornson and David LaFleur being a bit overmatched
in trying to replace Jay Novacek? Or Emmitt Smith having the worst
season of his career, leading to speculation he was finished? Or
maybe it was that awful offensive line of George Hegamin and Erik
Williams at tackles, Larry Allen and Nate Newton at guards, and
Clay Shiver at center? Three of them were gone within a year.
</P>
<P>
   Is it the system, or the players within the system?
</P>
<P>
   Campo, of course, won't exactly spend sleepless nights debating
the subject. He doesn't care which one or why. It's now his head
coaching butt on the line, and he wants offensive results. Pronto.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason I think it will be different is we've got talented,
game-breaking kind of people at wide receiver \RJoey Galloway and
Rocket Ismail\S, and in Jackie Harris \Ra tight end, H-back type\S;
I feel we've made one of the most important free agent signs of the
off-season,'' Campo said. ``Harris gives us that inside threat in
the passing game.''
</P>
<P>
   Then Campo invoked the name of Emmitt without a direct
reference.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we do offensively will involve contributions from Jack,
Ernie and myself,'' he said. ``I will be involved in the philosophy
of the offense but not in calling the plays. I want a power attack,
I know that. One thing I understand is attacking a defense. I was
on the other side for too long.''
</P>
<P>
   The Zampese critics long have said he commits to the pass first,
the run second. Zampese long has said he strives for balance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just a personal opinion, but I've felt we got a little
predictable with what we tried to do in the running game,'' Campo
said. ``I want a running game that is more diversified. And the
very last thing I want anyone to say is we're boring on offense.
With our playmakers at receiver, and with Emmitt and with Troy, we
absolutely can't be boring.''
</P>
<P>
   At Valley Ranch, it's the kind of thing that can get you fired.
Then get you rehired. This, of course, leads to confusion, unless
it's Dave Campo, who is perfectly clear about what he expects. As
of this first minicamp weekend, so is everyone else.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
