<HEADER>
A1144 &Cx1f; ttx-z
r s BC-HKN-STARS-SHARKS-TEX     04-29 0658
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-SHARKS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS STILL HAVE FEAR OF SHARKS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   IRVING, Texas _ If you thought the San Jose Sharks looked bad in
Game 1, you should have seen them lose Game 6 to St. Louis in the
first round.
</P>
<P>
   They were worse. They weren't only beaten. They were
embarrassed.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, the Blues are no longer in the playoffs, bounced by
those same Sharks a game later.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what we should be afraid of right now,'' Stars winger
Brenden Morrow said. ``You don't want to count the Sharks out too
soon because I think a lot of people had them counted out after
Game 6, and they came back and dominated Game 7.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks are neither the prettiest nor the most talented team
in the NHL. But when it comes to going quietly, they simply don't
know how to do it. So the Sharks' sorry performance in Game 1
against Dallas is a pretty good indicator that they are going to
come out with raised sticks, harder hits and adrenaline pumping for
Game 2 of their best-of-seven series at 6:30 tonight at Reunion
Arena.
</P>
<P>
   ``They are not ones to go away with adversity,'' Stars coach Ken
Hitchcock said. ``It's not so much Game 1 vs. Game 2 or Game 2 vs.
Game 7. It's every time they seem to have adversity, they respond
in a very strong manner and a very determined manner.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars must at least match and preferably better that emotion
and determination if they are going to hold on to home-ice
advantage. The players know this and have discussed it.
</P>
<P>
   But saying and doing are totally different.
</P>
<P>
   ``Edmonton did the same thing to us,'' Stars center Guy
Carbonneau said. ``We know they were going to come back hard in the
third game, and we didn't react the right way.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars figure the Sharks' plan for Game 2 will be much like
Edmonton's in Game 3 of the first round.
</P>
<P>
   ``Be physical, be more desperate,'' Stars winger Blake Sloan
said. ``All those Hitchisms.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, the Sharks want to be more physical. They have to be better
defensively.
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks allowed 16 goals in their three losses to St. Louis
and only six in their four victories, including one in Game 7. The
Stars won, 4-0, in Game 1 on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Coincidence? Not likely.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to focus on realizing how we beat St. Louis and the
games we lost against St. Louis. Game 1 against Dallas was similar
to Game 1 against St. Louis,'' Sharks winger Jeff Friesen said.
``It shows you if you give up four goals to Dallas with \REd\S
Belfour in net, you are not going to win many games. ... If we play
like we did \RFriday\S night, it will be a short series.''
</P>
<P>
   Both teams expect the series to go six or seven games. So what's
the big deal? This is, after all, only Game 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you lose it, the momentum of the series swings the other
way,'' Hitchcock said. ``I always felt Game 2 determines the flow
of the entire series for the team that has home-ice advantage as
Game 3 determines it for the other team.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars last lost a Game 2 on May 9, 1998, against Edmonton,
going 6-0 in Game 2s since.
</P>
<P>
   The players realize the importance of Game 2. It doesn't allow
them to retain home ice, but it puts the pressure on the Sharks to
win at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't want to go home down 2-0,'' Stars winger Mike Keane
said. ``It's something where we have to win our games and put
pressure back on them. Your building can work for you and against
you. ... I think we're happy with the first game, but still, big
deal, it's one game.''
</P>
<P>
   That is another lesson the Stars learned from the Blues. If you
have the Sharks on the mat, don't let them up.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues did, and they're no longer in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``You bet we learned from that,'' Stars winger Jamie
Langenbrunner said. ``If we let up, we'll get in trouble. We don't
want that to happen to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Morrow: ``We can't get caught in the same trap St. Louis
did.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 1943EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
