<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 19:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1147 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-LPGA0430-COX     04-29 0617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LPGA0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Gustafson keeps lead, but Webb lurks
 &HT;    By Glenn Sheeley
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sweden's Sophie Gustafson is hanging in there at the
Chick-fil-A Charity Championship, leading by two strokes, but
there's a shootout brewing for today's final round at Eagle's
Landing Country Club.
</P>
<P>
   Fortunately for those hopeful of overtaking Gustafson, who shot
a 3-under-par 69 Saturday to move to 10-under 134, the par-5 18th
only allowed her a par. The way red numbers were flying at the
finish Saturday, that almost felt like a bogey.
</P>
<P>
   In a late scoring flurry, eagles at the 18th by Karrie Webb, Amy
Fruhwirth and Michelle McGann helped tighten the leaderboard and
add some tension to the conclusion of the $900,000 tournament
hosted by Nancy Lopez.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think Sophie did us a favor there by not making a birdie or
an eagle there,'' said Webb, who climbed to 7-under after another
so-so day. ``She could have had a three or four-shot lead.''
</P>
<P>
   Looking for her first LPGA win after six international
victories, Gustafson, 26, is being chased at 8-under by 1995
champion Laura Davies, who stormed into contention with a 66 that
included 18 greens hit in regulation; and McGann, who fired a
second consecutive 68. Fruhwirth (70) is three shots back at
7-under along with Webb.
</P>
<P>
   While an unknown player to American audiences, Gustafson is no
stranger to her LPGA colleagues. A long hitter who can reach most
of the par-5's, she has an aggressive swing that can produce a wide
expanse of numbers. This week she's in a scoring groove. Saturday's
round included her third eagle in two days, at the 13th after a
3-wood to 15 feet, two birdies and two bogeys.
</P>
<P>
   Gustafson struggles with a severe speech problem, but has spent
two days of smooth shotmaking. Of the big names below her on the
leaderboard, Webb included, she said, ``I've played with them
before and I've beaten them before.''
</P>
<P>
   Gustafson goes into the final round with nothing to lose and
nearly certain to better her highest finish on the LPGA Tour this
year, a ninth in Hawaii Feb. 19.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's going to be fun,'' said the Swede, who played on
the 1998 Solheim Cup team. ``This is good for me and it's a great
field. If I can play (this well) after two rounds, I know I can
handle it.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Webb of Gustafson, ``She has a tremendous amount of talent.
When she's on, she hits it long and extremely straight. I've seen
her hit it off the planet as well. Being as aggressive as she is,
she's bound to make a few mistakes, but also a good amount of
birdies.''
</P>
<P>
   ``Chances are,'' said Davies, her Solheim Cup teammate, ``she'll
be tough to beat tomorrow. I've never seen her lay up in my life.
She reminds me of me about 12 years ago, when I didn't care less
where I hit it, as long as it was far.''
</P>
<P>
   The cut came at 4-over 148.
</P>
<P>
   Defending champion Rachel Hetherington solidified making the cut
by eagling the 18th for a 72 and 146. Just making it was tournament
host Nancy Lopez, who shot a 75 for a 148. Mary Beth Zimmerman made
the cut at 148.
</P>
<P>
   Rosie Jones shot a 72 for 146. Krissie Register missed the cut
at 153 on a second-round 80.
</P>
<P>
   Davies is making a serious run after two consecutive missed cuts
in the Chick-fil-A. With so much length _ even with her driver
holstered _ and so many short irons in her hand, Davies knocked
approach shots close all day. Which for a chance to beat Webb, not
to mention Gustafson, is mandatory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Karrie's probably more dominant in her world than Tiger
(Woods) is in his,'' Davies said. ``I'm even actually practicing a
little more.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
