u p BC-COX-GAY-MARCH-0430     04-29 0937
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-COX-GAY-MARCH-0430 </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    GAYS HOLD MASS ``WEDDING''
 &HT;    By BOB DART
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Lynn Gallagher and Liz Stanley came from
Alpharetta, Ga., to stand before the Lincoln Memorial on this sunny
Saturday and exchange vows of love and commitment.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been together for a year,'' said Gallagher. ``And I
wanted to make a public statement that we're going to be together
for the rest of our lives.''
</P>
<P>
   ``And I wanted to let those people across the street know that
we don't need their permission to love who we love,'' said Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   Those dozen or so people across the street were anti-gay
protesters who carried a wooden cross and placards warning ``Repent
or Perish.'' But they failed to deflate the buoyance and defiance
of the more than 1,000 couples who were joined in same-sex union.
</P>
<P>
   The mass ``wedding'' was not legally recognized, of course,
since only Vermont has granted marriage-like rights to homosexual
couples. But the Rev. Troy Perry, the Universal Federation of
Metropolitan Community Churches minister who performed the
ceremony, told the couples to take heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``We stand here knowing that love makes a family -- nothing
more, nothing less,'' said Perry.
</P>
<P>
   The staged wedding was among scores of activities arranged
around Sunday's Millennium March on Washington for Equality.
Although some gay rights groups are boycotting the event, the
streets of nation's capital were crowded on Saturday with activists
and supporters who did respond to the call for a national
mobilization.
</P>
<P>
   Organizers said the march is needed to galvanize a massive gay
and lesbian turn-out in the November elections and to energize a
new generation of their movement. About 300,000 participants are
expected for the Sunday parade and rally.
</P>
<P>
   This is the fourth national gathering of homosexual rights
groups in the past two decades and comes at a time of both triumphs
and setbacks. Last week, Vermont enacted its law giving legal
rights to homosexual couples and President Clinton urged Congress
to pass a Hate Crimes Prevention Act protecting gays and lesbians.
</P>
<P>
   However, California voters recently approved a referendum
denying marital rights to homosexual couples. The Supreme Court
will decide by July whether the Boy Scouts can bar a gay man from
serving as a troop leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have attained a certain level of visibility. But visibility
isn't civil rights,'' said Dianne Hardy-Garcia, the Texas lobbyist
for lesbian and gay rights who is serving as executive director of
the march.
</P>
<P>
   Especially outside of cities, activists said, homophobia has not
been cured.
</P>
<P>
   ``Atlanta is okay if you stay within the Perimeter,'' said
Nicole Wilson, who came to the march from Georgia. The Perimeter is
a road that rings Atlanta.
</P>
<P>
   ``But you don't feel that it's as accepted outside the
Perimeter,'' said Ginny Perrine, another Georgian.
</P>
<P>
   At the mock wedding, the mood was festive as couples crowded the
steps between the Lincoln Memorial and reflecting pool. Attire was
eclectic. Outfits included wedding gowns and bouquets and tuxedoes
and T-shirts and black leather and plaid Bermuda shorts. One
lesbian couple wore identical baseball caps labeled ``Bride.'' A
preppy gay couple wore khakis, white shirts with button-downed
collars and pastel ties.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Street and Rob Lett, from Richmond, Va., wore matching
tuxedoes with turquoise vests and invited a dozen friends to share
the event.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been together almost 11 years but we had never done
anything like this before,'' said Street. ``We thought it would be
a fun thing to do and exciting.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a good opportunity to share our relationship with folks
we love,'' said Lett.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Jett and Rich Greene had exchanged rings over a decade ago on
their fifth anniversary together. But they came from the Atlanta
suburbs to join this ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a house, a dog, wonderful neighbors. For 16 years,
we've been a family,'' said Jett. ``We wanted to declare that
commitment. Rich is the miracle in my life.''
</P>
<P>
   While refusing to legally marry them, they noted, DeKalb County
willingly accepts their property tax payments.
</P>
<P>
   Jennifer Mullins and Terri Funderburk said they came from
Rossville, Ga., to show their commitment to each other and the
cause of gay and lesbian rights.
</P>
<P>
   If Georgia ever recognizes same-sex marriages, said Mullins,
``we'll be the first in line.''
</P>
<P>
   David Newton and Eduardo Andrade of Decatur, Ga., exchanged
rings at the ceremony.
</P>
<P>
   ``We wanted to show the world that we're a couple and that we
plan to stay together,'' said Andrade.
</P>
<P>
   Other events on Saturday included a concert starring Garth
Brooks, Melissa Ethridge, k.d. lang and the Pet Shop Boys and the
unveiling of new panels to the AIDS memorial quilt on the Mall.
</P>
<P>
   However, the march has been criticized by some groups within the
gay rights movement who charge that there was not enough grassroots
involvement or outreach to people of color.
</P>
<P>
   The organizers ``alienated many constituencies, ... replacing
democracy and accountability with Hollywood celebrities and
back-room dealing,'' said William Dobbs, a spokesman for a
coalition of activists opposed to the march.
</P>
<P>
   ``The march's purpose, insensitive elitism, is not our purpose.
Our purpose will not be advanced by the Millennium March on
Washington,'' Ed Brown, co-chairman of the National Association of
Black and White Men Together, told the Associated Press.
</P>
<P>
   Bob Dart's e-mail address is bobdart(at)coxnews.com
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
