<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 20:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1151 &Cx1f; tad-z
u s BC-KLESKO0430-COX     04-29 0451
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KLESKO0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Klesko finds comfort zone in San Diego
 &HT;    By Carroll Rogers
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN DIEGO _ For all the trade talks concerning Ryan Klesko in
his 10 years with the Braves organization, when it finally happened
last December it came as a relief of sorts.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko, who was traded to the Padres with Bret Boone and minor
leaguer Jason Schiell for Reggie Sanders, Quilvio Veras and Wally
Joyner, is comfortable here in his native Southern California.
</P>
<P>
   He's renting a house on the beach. His mother, Lorene Klesko, is
only an hour's drive away. And he's sporting some blond streaks in
his hair and mutton-chop sideburns.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it worked out for both teams _ Andres (Galarraga) is
coming back and they've got a good outfield,'' Klesko said of his
former team. ``I was coming from one good organization to another
good one over here. The whole change was a positive. They wanted my
leadership and experience over here to help them win. I know most
of the guys from playing against them in high school and growing
up. Nine or 10 guys are from California.''
</P>
<P>
   Klesko is the Padres' everyday first baseman. He still struggles
against left-handers, a deficiency that made him a platoon player
with the Braves. He was hitting .182 (2-for-11) entering Saturday,
and Padres manager Bruce Bochy sometimes goes to veteran Ed Sprague
off the bench. But Friday night, Klesko doubled off Braves
left-hander Mike Remlinger
</P>
<P>
   The Padres are calling him their best power hitter since Fred
McGriff, another former Brave. In his last few years as a Brave,
Klesko was criticized for overswinging and not living up to his
34-homer, 93-RBI season in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He's responded to his new environment by hitting .289 through
Friday night with six homers. He's driven in 20 runs, which would
put him on a pace to drive in 100 runs for the first time in his
career. Entering Saturday's game against the Braves, Klesko had hit
in seven consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   He's mainly hitting fifth, though he's occasionally appeared in
the third slot when Tony Gwynn has been out of the lineup.
</P>
<P>
   Klesko said he hasn't had much time since the start of the
season to keep up with his friends on the Braves, though he does
talk to John Rocker on a regular basis. The two went hunting
together in the offseason. Klesko still has his 250-acre farm in
Covington, Ga. and doesn't plan to give it up anytime soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Playing for the Braves) was part of my past; I enjoyed it,''
Klesko said. ``It's something I'll always remember. Atlanta is
basically my home, and it probably still will be for a while.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
