</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POL-TICKER0430-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    POLITICAL TICKER: Gore fields marathon questions
 &HT;    (EDs: A brief roundup of the day's campaign events, pulled from
Cox staff and wire reports.)
 &HT;    c. 2000 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Four hours of voter questions wasn't too much for Vice President
Al Gore, who took on immigration, education, abortion and dozens of
other topics at a record-long town hall meeting Friday night in
Albuquerque, N.M. Gore kept his promise to stay until every person
with a question was served. He set a new personal record, talking
to the audience for more than two and a half hours and then took
questions one on one for another 90 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   Tough questioner Jessica McKenzie, 17, asked: ``Why is it
illegal to kill a baby five seconds after it's born and not illegal
five seconds before it's born?'' Gore responded with: ``Didn't she
do a good job of presenting her point of view?'' then went on to
say women should be allowed to choose abortion. ``I think he
avoided the question,'' Jessica said later.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, Gore helped assemble a playground in a low-income
neighborhood in Kansas City, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH WINS TEEN MOCK-ELECTION
</P>
<P>
   Texas Gov. George W. Bush accepted the Republican presidential
nomination Friday _ from a mock-convention put on by teen-agers in
Portland, Ore. Bush was nominated Thursday by a 3-1 margin over his
former rival Sen. John McCain. In accepting the nomination by
telephone from Austin, Bush told the 2,000 students that he will
``run a campaign that will lift our spirits.'' The students play
the parts of delegates, committee chairs and caucus chairs in the
event that dates to 1964.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AND MCCAIN MAKE UP DIFFERENCES
</P>
<P>
   A May 9 meeting between Bush and McCain will go ahead as
scheduled after aides to both Republicans met Friday and patched up
their differences. McCain threatened Thursday to pull out of the
meeting because of publicity surrounding the event and reports that
Bush wanted to discuss the vice presidency, a prospect the U.S.
senator from Arizona said he has ruled out. But on Friday, McCain
adviser John Weaver and Bush campaign manager Joe Allbaugh agreed
on an agenda for the meeting.
</P>
<P>
   BUSH AHEAD IN OHIO, POLL SHOWS
</P>
<P>
   A new presidential poll of Ohio voters by the University of
Cincinnati has Bush leading Gore by eight points. The poll,
conducted April 5 through 22 of 531 likely voters, found Bush ahead
of Gore 47 percent to 39 percent in a state that political analysts
say could go to either Bush or Gore. Ralph Nader of the Green Party
got 4 percent, Pat Buchanan of the Reform Party, 3 percent, with 7
percent undecided.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington state, a newly released preference poll has Bush
ahead 39 percent to 38 percent, with 18 percent of the respondents
undecided. The poll, by Elway Research, surveyed 400 registered
voters April 11 and 12 and has a margin error of plus or minus 5
percentage points.
</P>
<P>
   DEMONSTRATIONS TO BE PART OF SHOW
</P>
<P>
   Protesters have agreed to drop their free-speech lawsuit against
the city of Philadelphia, and the stage has been set for a week of
noisy demonstrations at this summer's Republican National
Convention. The Pennsylvania Consumer Action Network is leading the
creation of an anti-Republican coalition named ``R2K'' that hopes
to coordinate a mass rally and parade. ``This city, thankfully,
recognizes that dissent is an integral part of our democracy,''
said ACLU legal director Stephan Presser. But the settlement is
contingent on the approval of Philadelphia 2000, host committee for
the July 31-Aug. 3 convention.
</P>
<P>
   For in-depth reporting, opinion and cartoonists, visit the Cox
News Campaign 2000 Web site: http://www.coxnews.com/2000.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
