<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WILL MAGIC BE WORKED ON CLIPPERS?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Magic Johnson looks around the NBA and sees his contemporaries
everywhere. Michael Jordan is a part-owner/general manager in
Washington. Larry Bird is coaching in Indiana. Isiah Thomas is
being courted by Atlanta. Byron Scott seems certain to land a
head-coaching job this summer.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson might own a small percentage of the Lakers, but he knows
his name, personality, knowledge and skills could probably be best
used to turn around a franchise. And there's a perfect opportunity
for him to perform some Magic on a certain troubled team in Los
Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's the Clippers. Perhaps it seems strange to Laker fans,
but Johnson would be willing to offer himself to the woebegone
organization, if given a percentage of the team and complete
control over personnel decisions.
</P>
<P>
   But someone with the Clippers has to call him.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone knows where I live,'' Johnson said. ``I won't toot my
horn.''
</P>
<P>
   Translation: He's available if the Clippers make the right
offer.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson certainly has a good handle on the current mess that
management has made of things.
</P>
<P>
   ``Until they have people who want to win and put people in the
right positions, they won't,'' Johnson said. ``You can't do it with
a low payroll and what they've been doing for 20-some years. I
don't know what's the problem, but they have one.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson knows he would immediately add credibility to the
Clippers' sorry reputation, probably even more than Jordan did in
Washington.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's going on right now (in the NBA), you have to give fans
a sign (for hope),'' Johnson said. ``You have to bring in free
agents.''
</P>
<P>
   And he knows he could convince a free agent to come to L.A. and
play for the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, no free agents even want to look at them. Look
who's out there: Tim Duncan, Eddie Jones, Grant Hill, Tracy
McGrady. If they were serious about winning, they could get one of
those guys.
</P>
<P>
   ``But none of those players will even look at them. Orlando,
Miami ... those are the teams they are talking about now.''
</P>
<P>
   It's a tantalizing scenario, watching Johnson run a franchise
that could be $11 million under the salary cap. He might even be
willing to coach the team.
</P>
<P>
   But it will never happen. Clippers owner Donald Sterling would
sooner re-sign Maurice Taylor to a $71 million contract than
relinquish a piece of his franchise, even if it is rotten.
</P>
<P>
   It's still something Johnson thinks about, but he knows bold
moves that make sense and excite fans have never been a trademark
of the Clippers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've been down this road too many times,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   SINKING IN SEATTLE: The Sonics are not going down quietly, but
unfortunately for them, it's mostly been off the court.
</P>
<P>
   There's rampant speculation that coach Paul Westphal will be
fired after the season. Guard Gary Payton was fined $10,000 for
refusing to speak to reporters, and owner Barry Ackerley underwent
surgery Friday for an unspecified cardiac procedure.
</P>
<P>
   But the real fireworks began with a published report that
forward Chuck Person had checked himself into Game 2 when Westphal
wasn't looking. Westphal and Person both denied the story.
</P>
<P>
   But when Person was questioned about the story, he exploded.
</P>
<P>
   ``You want to know why we are losing?'' he shouted. ``It's all
of your fault. This team is working its (rear ends) off, and you
guys are making it lose.''
</P>
<P>
   The whole incident left Westphal exasperated.
</P>
<P>
   ``I agree with his sentiment, but it's not the media's fault we
are losing,'' Westphal said.
</P>
<P>
   Poor Westphal. He thought the Sonics' usual hijinks would be
eliminated by keeping Vernon ``Mad Max'' Maxwell off the playoff
roster.
</P>
<P>
   REUNITED: There's one player who wouldn't mind playing for the
Clippers. Former point guard Darrick Martin, currently with the
Kings, has an opt-out clause in his contract after the season and
would like to return to Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Nuggets are ready to approach the Clippers
regarding free-agent guard Derek Anderson. Denver would like to
offer guard Tariq Abdul-Wahad in a sign-and-trade deal.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're willing to work with the Clippers to help them get back
something in return,'' Nuggets coach Dan Issel said.
</P>
<P>
   SWIFT TURNAROUND: LSU forward Stromile Swift is apparently
getting ready to turn pro, despite previously saying he intended to
stay in college. Swift is hearing the legitimate talk that he could
be a top-five pick in the draft.
</P>
<P>
   If the draft were held today, the top five picks probably would
be Cincinnati forward Kenyon Martin, Iowa State forward Marcus
Fizer, Swift, Minnesota center Joel Pryzbilla and Cincinnati
forward DerMarr Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   RETREAD DEPT.: Lenny Wilkens barely left Atlanta before the
Hawks were going to fire him, and his name already appeared on the
short lists of New Jersey, Washington and Seattle. He will get a
formal interview with the Wizards next week. Isn't Bill Fitch
available?
</P>
<P>
   At least Detroit is expected to do the right thing this week by
signing George Irvine to a long-term deal. Irvine's presence is
expected to be the only chance the Pistons will have retaining
Grant Hill.
</P>
<P>
   ROGERS REWARDED: Phoenix forward Rodney Rogers will officially
be named the NBA's Sixth Man of the Year on Monday. &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
The NBA column appears Sundays in the Daily News. Staff Writer
Scott Wolf can be reached via e-mail at Hooptalkaol.com. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2038EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
