<HEADER>
A1158 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HN     04-29 0800
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-ASTROS-BREWERS-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Astros walk away with win over Brewers
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By CARLTON THOMPSON &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 2000, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL; 
MILWAUKEE _ Considering how eager baseball teams are to sell
sponsorships and naming rights, it's a wonder no one managed to get
the March of Dimes lined up for this one.
</P>
<P>
   After all, they are synonymous with walkathons.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros drew 14 walks, a club record for nine innings, en
route to a 10-3 victory over the Milwaukee Brewers on Saturday
afternoon. After drawing 11 walks in the first game of the series,
the Astros tied a 56-year-old record National League record for
walks in consecutive games.
</P>
<P>
   The teams combined for 25 walks Saturday and just 12 hits,
including five by the Astros.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was an ugly game all around,'' Astros first baseman Jeff
Bagwell said. ``That wasn't much fun for either club. This game was
such a debacle that it's hard to get a feel for how the game went.
The only good thing that came out of it was that we got a win.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros won consecutive games for only the third time this
season, the first since beating St. Louis on April 12 and San Diego
on April 14. The only other back-to-back victories for the Astros
came in the first two games of the season.
</P>
<P>
   With a victory in one of the next two games, the Astros could
win a series for the first time since taking two of three in the
season-opening set at Pittsburgh.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're capable of throwing up six or seven wins in a row, and
now would be a good time to do that,'' Astros shortstop Tim Bogar
said.
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers are running a promotion this weekend called ``Spring
Madness,'' and most of the seats in County Stadium could be had for
less than $4. Nevertheless, the paying public still had every right
to cry rip-off.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a very entertaining game,'' Astros manager Larry
Dierker said. ``But at least we came out on the good side of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither Astros starter Scott Elarton nor his Brewers
counterpart, Everett Stull, managed to throw more strikes than
balls in their abbreviated outings. Stull was yanked after 3
innings, and Elarton's poor control cost him a victory despite
being supported by 10 runs. Elarton, who walked eight batters, was
done after throwing 103 pitches in just 4 innings.
</P>
<P>
   ``I usually don't struggle to throw strikes,'' said Elarton, who
walked only one batter in his previous start, a six-inning outing
against the Padres. ``But I just couldn't figure it out. That was
pretty obvious all day long. I couldn't make an adjustment. I
tried, but I just never could do it. I'm not happy with the way I
pitched, but we won the game, and that's the main thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Mike Maddux pitched 2 scoreless innings to get the win, and Jay
Powell and Jose Cabrera worked a scoreless inning apiece to close
out the victory. It was a solid effort by the Astros' bullpen,
which got a much-needed rest thanks to Chris Holt's one-hit shutout
in the first game of the series.
</P>
<P>
   Stull, who allowed seven runs but only one hit, set the tone for
the day by walking Craig Biggio and Roger Cedeno on his first eight
pitches. Two batters later, Stull walked Ken Caminiti with the
bases loaded to force home the first run of the game. Richard
Hidalgo also drew a bases-loaded walk, and Mitch Meluskey had a
sacrifice fly as the Astros took a 3-0 lead in the top of the first
inning, which lasted 25 minutes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been in a game where you didn't even think about
swinging the bat,'' Bogar said. ``I heard a comment on the bench
that (Stull) will throw four balls before he throws a strike, so
just stand there.''
</P>
<P>
   The Astros sent nine batters to the plate in the first, fourth
and fifth innings, scoring four runs in the fourth and three more
in the fifth. Caminiti drew his second bases-loaded walk in the
fourth, and Daryle Ward had a two-run double.
</P>
<P>
   Caminiti drove in two runs in a more conventional manner with a
fifth-inning single, while Bagwell kept the theme of the day alive
in that inning with the fourth bases-loaded walk of the game.
</P>
<P>
   ``You just have to be patient in situations like this,'' Bagwell
said. ``It's hard enough to hit in the big leagues, but it's even
harder when you're trying to hit (pitches out of the strike
zone).''
</P>
<P>
   The Brewers left the bases loaded against Elarton in the second,
third and fourth innings before his good fortune finally ran its
course. Lyle Mouton's three-run homer in the fifth put the Brewers
on the scoreboard, and Elarton lasted only two more batters. The
24-year-old righthander fell two outs shy of qualifying for his
first win of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``By the end I was just trying to throw the ball down the middle
of the plate and make them hit it,'' Elarton said. ``Mouton made me
pay.''
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
