<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 21:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1163 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u a BC-KELLY-INTERNET-HNS &LR;      04-29 1332
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-KELLY-INTERNET-HNS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORS: KELLEY MC IS CQ &HT;    
 &HT;    SUSPECT IN SLAYING OF A&AMP;M STUDENT LURKED IN SHADOWS OF INTERNET
 &HT;   
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)   &HT;    By POLLY ROSS HUGHES 
and JOHN W. GONZALEZ 
c.2000 Houston Chronicle &HT;    
<TEXT>
<P>
   AUSTIN, Texas _ Kelly had her charms, for sure. She was 21,
strikingly pretty and didn't go in for wild body-piercing or
tattoos. Even better, she attended Texas A&AMP;M University. Proximity
was the biggest plus.
</P>
<P>
   Or so Scott Schneider, a psychology major and creator of the
``Aggie channel'' Internet chat room, first thought. It was Sept. 3
when he met ``Kelley mc'' online. He knew little about this ``nice
girl'' other than that she seemed to care about his life. Yet, for
a girl so close, she sure was hard to meet in person.
</P>
<P>
   That's because Kelly wasn't a person at all. She was instead,
according to an arrest warrant, a 31-year-old San Antonio man named
Kenny Wayne Lockwood.
</P>
<P>
   Lockwood, police believe, used the anonymity of the Internet to
pose as a young woman and converse with men at Texas A&AMP;M. When one
student, Kerry J. Kujawa, got too close, police believe Lockwood
shot him in the back of the head and dumped his body in a Hays
County field.
</P>
<P>
   Early Thursday, police arrested Lockwood at a hospital in San
Antonio. He confessed to the killing, they said.
</P>
<P>
   Dorm roommate Charlie Branham last saw Kujawa April 7, leaving
College Station, hoisting a blue duffel bag and saying he was en
route to San Antonio to meet his Internet interest, Kelly. She was
having problems with some other guy and needed help, Kujawa said.
</P>
<P>
   Instead of a face-to-face meeting with his elusive
correspondent, the 20-year-old mechanical engineering major with a
prestigious scholarship met his death. His body was found April 19,
about 500 feet from a cattle guard on a Hill Country ranch near
Dripping Springs. The medical examiner who performed the autopsy
could not say for certain what day he died.
</P>
<P>
   During the week and a half that he was missing, posts from
Kujawa continued to appear in an Internet chat room. Kelly also
chatted, sharing happy news that the two were engaged. She was
going to meet Kujawa's parents.
</P>
<P>
   Before Kelly ever met Kujawa, she had a bumpy relationship with
Schneider. Some of the tumults played out in the chat room in front
of other anonymous participants. Regulars took sides, some with
Schneider, others with Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't take long for Schneider to doubt Kelly's very
existence, at the very least, her gender. He had his reasons.
</P>
<P>
   The relationship started promisingly. Schneider and Kelly
chatted several times a day, every day, for about two months.
Almost from the beginning, Schneider wanted to meet Kelly, but she
kept putting him off with one excuse or another.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a dating relationship,'' Schneider said Friday. ``It
was more of like a friendship thing because I made it clear that it
wasn't going to be a personal, intimate relationship until I met a
girl. I just made that clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Schneider tried to arrange a date to attend an A&AMP;M football
game. Kelly couldn't make it but her little brother ``Isaac'' would
love to go, she said. Schneider agreed. Maybe, Isaac could share
details about his interesting sister, Schneider thought.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider found Isaac to be something of an oddball. For one
thing, Isaac's teeth were very yellow, almost green, Schneider
said. Also, Isaac seemed very cautious in what he said,
circumspect, as if trying to say something Schneider might want to
hear. And although he claimed to be 19, he looked more like he was
30, Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider's suspicions would not be confirmed until months later
when police showed him a photograph of ``Isaac,'' who in reality
was Lockwood.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider's relationship with Kelly deteriorated after the
meeting with her ``little brother.'' Kelly, it seemed, always had
an excuse for not seeing him or even talking to him on the
telephone.
</P>
<P>
   To placate his concerns, Kelly sent pictures. The photographs
were of a slender, attractive brunette with hazel eyes. In the chat
room, she shared stories about a large ranch where she had ridden
horses and gone deer hunting. She said she shot a deer, but then
wept when she saw it was dead. That comment _ an unusual reaction
if this were a man, Schneider thought _ somewhat assuaged him.
Still, he could not shake his skepticism.
</P>
<P>
   ``As soon as I started having doubts that this person was real
because they wouldn't call or weren't what they said they were,
then I tried to cut off a lot of communication,'' Schneider said.
</P>
<P>
   He went so far as to block Kelly from entering the chat room.
</P>
<P>
   ``I did a lot of things to prevent future contact,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider lifted the ban in January after an outcry from Kelly's
chat room friends.
</P>
<P>
   Karey Lynn Lee, a moderator at the chat room, knew the frequent
visitor named Kelly as a female pre-law student at A&AMP;M. Lee, of
Etoile, and other chat room regulars _ some from as far away as
Australia _ congratulated Kelly on her engagement announcement.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the virtual world, I knew her very well,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee and others got to know Kelly last fall in the chat room
where Aggies and others play trivia games about A&AMP;M traditions, as
well as general topics such as science, history, geography and
music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Kelly was always talking about her new boyfriend,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   Lee doesn't recall being online at the same time as Kujawa and
Kelly. But he said Lockwood had more personas than just Kelly.
Lockwood also logged on to chat rooms as Kelly's little sister
``Kate.'' Kate was Internet savvy, Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   On Good Friday, Lee received his final message from Kelly.
</P>
<P>
   ``She and Kerry were on their way to Houston to spend Easter
with his parents. The ruse was still going on,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   It seemed normal that she would go with Kujawa for Easter, so
Lee and others thought nothing of it. However, on Sunday, the
friend in Australia told Lee she'd heard a rumor that Kelly's
boyfriend had been found dead and that Kelly was missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I figured out what had happened,'' Lee said.
</P>
<P>
   On Monday, Lee went to the Texas Rangers with his information
and identified others in the chat room who had talked with Kelley.
On Tuesday, the investigators located Schneider, who had Isaac's
phone number on his caller ID. He gave it to police, and it turned
out to be Lockwood's number.
</P>
<P>
   One reason other chat room visitors weren't suspicious was that
Kujawa continued to log in and chat online, even after he was
missing.
</P>
<P>
   Branham said he received a message from his roommate on April 9.
The message was sent from Kelly's screen name. The sender
identified himself as Kujawa and said he would be staying with
Kelly through April 10. The sender also wrote that Kelly's little
brother would be coming to College Station. Don't be surprised, the
sender told Burnham, if the little brother should turn up in the
dormitory room.
</P>
<P>
   The little brother did, at least that's who Branham assumed he
was. He found the man sitting at Kujawa's computer. Kujawa's blue
duffel bag was on the bed.
</P>
<P>
   Schneider believes it was Lockwood posing again as little
brother Isaac. He assumes Lockwood was trying to destroy evidence
at the computer, perhaps a sign that the slaying was not
well-planned.
</P>
<P>
   The A&AMP;M police force, the Hays County Sheriff's Department and
the Texas Rangers tracked Lockwood down by piecing together the
complex computer relationship. After identifying Kujawa's body,
they began piecing together the computer puzzle.
</P>
<P>
   A&AMP;M University Police Director Bob Wiatt still uses a pen and
paper or a telephone to communicate. He said Kujawa's mother begs
everyone to be careful while on the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mrs. Kujawa is telling everybody, `My God, be wary of the
Internet and who you're speaking with,''' Wiatt said. ``Her son was
killed because he believed that this girl, Kelly, was really
Kelly.''
</P>
<P>
   XXXXXXXXX END OF STORY
</P>
<P>
   $$$
</P>
