<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-ORIOLES-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ORIOLES, MUSSINA ADD TO RANGERS' WOES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Rangers manager Johnny Oates freely predicted before
the season his team might get off to a slow start and get better as
the year went along.
</P>
<P>
   But this was not quite what he expected. A slow start is one
thing, but burying yourself early is another. The Rangers are in
danger of doing just that after a 3-1 loss to the Baltimore Orioles
yesterday afternoon at Camden Yards.
</P>
<P>
   Mike Mussina's complete-game performance for the Orioles handed
the Rangers their 10th loss in 12 games and left them 8-15 on the
season. It's the most losses in April in club history.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not going in the direction we want to go,'' Oates said
``We preach patience. We want to be patient but ... we're missing
something. I thought we would be more consistent. To think we'd
start \R8-15\S ... I honestly thought our offense would be more
consistent top to bottom, I thought our bullpen would be a whole
lot better and I thought our defense had a shot at being better
than it's shown.''
</P>
<P>
   Hitting proved to be the Rangers' downfall yesterday against
Mussina. They managed only one infield hit through four innings,
then, after a few balls got through or fell in, they were 1-for-8
with runners in scoring position over the last five innings.
</P>
<P>
   It didn't help that the Rangers had to go against one of the
best right-handers in the American League without three of their
best left-handed hitters. The Rangers have Rusty Greer and Frank
Catalanotto on the disabled list, and Rafael Palmeiro couldn't
start yesterday because of a strained left hamstring.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would be a little different; it would make it a little
tougher for him if you could throw more left-handers out there,''
shortstop Royce Clayton said. ``But that's `what if.' ... You can't
look at it that way. You have to give him credit. He pitched a
great game. Sure, we're missing a couple of bats in the lineup ,but
we should have better efforts than what we've shown the past couple
of days.''
</P>
<P>
   Mussina said it's a much different lineup, both without the
left-handers and the players the Rangers lost in the off-season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a much different team,'' Mussina said. ``Even their
colors are different. It's almost like they're not the Texas
Rangers anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Oates knew there would be a change, but he didn't expect the
Rangers to slip this much so soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get better, yeah. But when you've been in this
game 34 years, your gut tells you something. That edge is not
there,'' Oates said. ``We don't have it right now, and it's up to
me to find it. My job is to find a way with this personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers used to be able to count on their offense to bash
the opposing team into submission. But with some big bats missing
from last year, that's no longer the case.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's no margin for error when you're scoring two or three
runs a game, whether it's pitching, base running, defense,'' Oates
said. ``This team is eventually going to score runs, but it's going
to take time to get the offense going. Those other things can be
made better now.''
</P>
<P>
   Palmeiro didn't start, but he did pinch hit in the tense ninth
inning, when the Rangers broke up Mussina's shutout bid with a
leadoff double from Chad Curtis and David Segui's one-out
run-scoring single.
</P>
<P>
   After Ruben Mateo singled and Gabe Kapler popped out, Palmeiro
came to the plate to pinch hit for catcher Bill Haselman. But
Mussina walked him to load the bases, then got Mike Lamb to fly out
to right to end the game.
</P>
<P>
   Darren Oliver took the loss, but Oates said, ``Three runs beat
us today. In today's game, you'll lead the league if you can give
up three runs. You'll run away with it. But I wouldn't want us to
have one on the other side.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
