<SLUG> BC-BBA-RANGERS-THOMPSON-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RANGERS PITCHER THOMPSON HAS NEXT REHAB START POSTPONED
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By T.R. SULLIVAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   BALTIMORE _ Rangers pitcher Justin Thompson was forced to shut
down his bullpen throwing session yesterday after feeling pain in
his left shoulder and has been scratched from Tuesday's start for
the Tulsa Drillers.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson underwent shoulder surgery Aug. 27 to repair a torn
labrum, and the Rangers had been hoping he was close to joining
their rotation. He has made three starts on a medical
rehabilitation assignment in the minors, but the Rangers don't know
when he'll throw again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm frustrated, yeah, but I'm not going to get discouraged,''
Thompson said. ``I talked to Dr. \RJohn\S Conway, and he said if
I'm feeling any discomfort, not to try throwing through it at this
stage.'' Conway is the Rangers' orthopedic consultant.
</P>
<P>
   Thompson threw 25 pitches in the bullpen yesterday and said
``three or four pinched me pretty good.''
</P>
<P>
   That was enough to leave manager Johnny Oates concerned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, anytime somebody says they have a sharp pain at the
point of surgery,'' Oates said. ``I don't know a whole lot right
now, but I have no idea when his next rehab assignment will be. ...
That's a pretty big change.''
</P>
<P>
   However, trainer Danny Wheat said, ``It's just a little bump in
the road. He's very fortunate it hasn't happened before. It's
unrealistic to think he could have gone through this thing without
a setback.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rangers are calling it inflammation in the shoulder, and
Wheat said the Rangers aren't planning for Thompson to undergo
X-rays or an MRI.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really can't put a timetable on it,'' Thompson said. ``I'm
going to let it calm down, and when I can throw a little bit in the
bullpen without discomfort, then we'll go again.''
</P>
<P>
   Thompson, who was acquired from the Detroit Tigers in the Juan
Gonzalez trade, was scheduled to pitch Tuesday for the Tulsa
Drillers. If all had gone well in that game, the Rangers were
planning on his pitching for them against the Oakland Athletics
five days later.
</P>
<P>
   His last outing was Tuesday for the Triple-A Oklahoma RedHawks.
He pitched 5 2/3 innings and threw 102 pitches, allowing eight runs
on 10 hits. His 30-day medical rehabilitation assignment ends May
15. At that point he must be activated or put back on the disabled
list.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
