r a BC-FISHER-VIETNAM-KAN &LR;      04-29 0918
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FISHER-VIETNAM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVEN BEFORE FIGHTING _ AND DYING _ IN VIETNAM, STEVEN SZIJJARTO WAS
NO STRANGER TO BATTLING COMMUNISM 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM FISHER  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAMEGO, Kan. _ On a windy March day in 1967, the first of
Wamego's Vietnam War funerals took place _ that of Sgt. Steven
Szijjarto, 26.
</P>
<P>
   Although Wamego saw three more of its sons killed in the war,
which ended 25 years ago today, Szijjarto's burial is the one that
most remember here. For Vietnam wasn't Szijjarto's first fight
against communism.
</P>
<P>
   Szijjarto was a refugee from the 1956 Hungarian revolt, a
``freedom fighter.'' He survived that fighting, but was killed 10
years later.
</P>
<P>
   Shot in the head after jumping from a helicopter in a ``hot''
landing zone, he was one of 626 Kansans and 1,411 Missourians who
died in the war, who came home in aluminum caskets to towns big and
small.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, yes, I remember,'' said Katie Glynn, who was at St.
Bernard's Catholic Church the other day. She remembers the
incredible dignity of Szijjarto's foster parents, Fred and Helen
Kilian.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Army had come early in the morning to notify them that
he'd been killed, and they came directly to the church. Right
away.''
</P>
<P>
   Szijjarto's burial in St. Bernard's cemetery, north on Kansas
99, didn't occur, however, until March 30, 1967.
</P>
<P>
   The delay was caused by what then was an everyday reality _ the
Cold War.
</P>
<P>
   Szijjarto was born in Hungary in 1940. In 1956, the Hungarian
revolution erupted. Szijjarto, 16, picked up a gun and fought
against the security police and the invading Soviet army.
</P>
<P>
   Joseph Deak, Szijjarto's buddy from those days, remembered that
he had a Tommy gun and Szijjarto an old rifle. Deak said ``it was
very bad.''
</P>
<P>
   Szijjarto, Deak, and a young kid named Nick Edvy fled to
Austria. Those three, like thousands of others, ended up in
America.
</P>
<P>
   Deak went to Michigan; Szijjarto and Edvy were placed with the
Kilians. Neither boy spoke English. They would point at something
and the Kilians would say the English word.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I remember is how big the sky was,'' said Edvy, now 56, a
retired captain in the Riley County police force who lives in
nearby Manhattan. ``And bananas. I'd never eaten a banana before I
came to America.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were free. We'd get in the Kilians' Oldsmobile and maybe go
up to Concordia. Just do it. That would be a trip that would take
days and all kinds of planning in Hungary if you could make it at
all. Things like that absolutely blew me away.''
</P>
<P>
   Right out of high school and well before Vietnam, Szijjarto
joined the U.S. Army. By 1965, Edvy had been drafted and was in
Vietnam running truck convoys to and from fire bases. It was
dangerous duty. Edvy wrote Szijjarto, his ``brother.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him, `You don't want to come here,''' said Edvy. ``I
told him that we were pulling our punches. We weren't fighting to
win. He wrote back that he had to come. Steven knew the communists.
</P>
<P>
   ``Steven had never finished that war in Hungary.''
</P>
<P>
   Szijjarto was killed in December, within 30 days of arriving in
Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
   The Army, because Szijjarto had a mother and sisters still in
Hungary, shipped the body to Europe.
</P>
<P>
   The Hungarians wouldn't accept it. The casket was stored in a
warehouse in Germany. There were negotiations. After almost three
months the Hungarians refused to change their minds. Edvy
remembered their stated reason was that Szijjarto was a traitor
because he'd fought against the communist state in the revolution.
</P>
<P>
   The body was shipped back to America. Finally there was the
funeral, with hundreds packing the cemetery here. Among them was
Alf Landon, the former Republican candidate for president of the
United States. Landon didn't know Szijjarto. He was there, he said,
as a matter of simple respect.
</P>
<P>
   After the service the crowd ebbed. And the war went on.
Eventually, Wamego would see three more burials.
</P>
<P>
   Two were brought back in 1968 _ John G. Southall, 22, a Marine
corporal who'd been wounded once and then died of injuries in a
jeep accident, and Spec. 4 Michael C. Zeller, 20, a medic killed in
a firefight.
</P>
<P>
   In spring 1969, David Lee Kitchen, 19, a Marine lance corporal,
came home. He died of ``hostile fire.''
</P>
<P>
   Southall, who is buried in the Wamego City cemetery, was also an
immigrant. He was born in London. His father, Fred Southall, who
died in 1991, had been a British soldier in World War II.
</P>
<P>
   Zeller is buried in the Catholic cemetery in St. Marys, just
east of here. His mother Bertha, 73, still lives on the south side
of Wamego.
</P>
<P>
   There have been other misfortunes for the Zellers over the
years. Bertha's husband and the father of Michael is in a home in
Manhattan with Alzheimer's disease. Their youngest son, Pat, 50,
lives at home, paralyzed from the waist down and in a wheelchair
since 1959 when he was struck by a car.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Michael got killed it just tore this family up,'' said
Pat Zeller. ``Never been the same since. But, you know how it is,
life goes on.''
</P>
<P>
   Kitchen was the last young man to come home. He was buried in a
small cemetery in Michigan Valley. Lyle Honig, who's worked at the
Wamego Times since the 1950s, said the Kitchens have been gone from
town for years.
</P>
<P>
   Time does heal some wounds.
</P>
<P>
   Edvy has been back to Hungary several times. He has seen
Szijjarto's family. They want the body to remain here.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what Steven is in Hungary now?'' asked Edvy. ``He's a
hero.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2127EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
