<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAKE-VIETNAM-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRILLIANT MEMORIES FROM A DESOLATE ASSIGNMENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The job sounded perfect for a meteorologist:
be a weatherman on a tropical island in the South Pacific. Palm
trees. Ocean breezes. Great pay.
</P>
<P>
   Dennis Lowden applied. And in 1973 he flew to a place few people
ever visit: Wake Island.
</P>
<P>
   What he hadn't thought about was the isolation. The population
was 150 _ all men. No television. Infrequent mail. No phone. And
the only news came from a scratchy shortwave radio _ between
high-pitched squeals. ``The lack of news didn't seem to bother
anyone else,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I cheered when I heard that Nixon resigned,'' said Lowden, one
of the few civilians on the island back then. ``And the commanding
officer reprimanded me. I learned to keep my political views to
myself.''
</P>
<P>
   But when Saigon fell to the North Vietnamese, the sleepy island
immediately awoke. It became one of the few places where Vietnam
refugees could stay until they were transferred to the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   In less than two weeks the island's population grew from 150 to
8,000 _ men, women, children and babies.
</P>
<P>
   ``Suddenly we were madly building tents and cleaning up old
buildings,'' he said. ``The air base brought in doctors, nurses,
dentists, teachers and even set up a chow hall to serve Vietnamese
food. We had two weeks' notice. Then the refugees arrived.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowden captured it all with his camera.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was kind of shy, but the camera was a great way to meet
them,'' said the Kansas Citian, now 59. ``I just wanted to
experience people again. I missed beautiful women and kids. To have
squealing, giggling kids around me _ that was wonderful. I tried to
give them a sense that America would be OK, that they could put
roots down.''
</P>
<P>
   Lowden befriended many refugees. Once, a Vietnamese mother asked
him with tears in her eyes whether he would adopt some of her
children _ she had heard rumors that large families were going to
be split up.
</P>
<P>
   ``That really touched me,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   A few years later he helped some refugees find sponsors on the
East Coast and in the Midwest. Lowden moved to Kansas City in 1978
and now teaches philosophy at Maple Woods and Longview community
colleges.
</P>
<P>
   In 1979 a flood in his basement destroyed all letters, addresses
and anything else he had connected to the refugees at Wake. Luckily
the hundreds of photos he had snapped during those four months in
1975 were upstairs. He had been looking at them.
</P>
<P>
   ``I have tried and tried on the Internet to find some of the
families that I met there,'' Lowden said. ``But I've had no luck.
It would thrill me to meet anyone who went through Wake back then.
I might even have pictures of them or their family.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that made Wake Island a bright spot for me were
those people. Otherwise it would have been the most desolate memory
of my life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
