<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 21:33 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1175 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-WAR-VIETNAM-2TAKES-KA     04-29 1313
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WAR-VIETNAM-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
25 YEARS AFTER THE FALL OF SAIGON: A JUNGLE OF MEMORIES 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By LEE HILL KAVANAUGH  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ For a nation, the cost of fighting a war is
measurable: in bodies crushed and lost, in commitments made and
broken, in prestige gained and squandered.
</P>
<P>
   For those whose lives were touched by the Vietnam War _ combat
veterans, refugees, families and friends of the American and
Vietnamese dead _ the price cannot be gauged.
</P>
<P>
   Veterans cope with flashbacks, alienation, bitterness.
</P>
<P>
   Refugees mourn the loss of home and family.
</P>
<P>
   Families and friends of the dead pay the steepest price of all:
the relentless imagining of what might have been.
</P>
<P>
   Twenty-five years ago the Vietnam War ended, after taking more
than 58,000 American and 3 million Vietnamese lives. Hundreds of
thousands more had been wounded or were missing. Billions of
dollars had been spent. And a country had been torn to pieces.
</P>
<P>
   On the anniversary of Saigon's fall, The Kansas City Star offers
a few glimpses into lives touched by Vietnam _ short stories about
a few of the many who remember, a few of the many who still hurt.
</P>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ At 62, Ca Ho still has the seamless face of
the young. But when asked about Vietnam, his eyes turn old as time.
</P>
<P>
   Ho left Vietnam in a desperate search for freedom after Saigon
fell, a refugee from the war that has haunted America for a
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Freedom, he discovered, had a price.
</P>
<P>
   ``The boat carried 170 people,'' he says in Vietnamese through
an interpreter. ``One hundred fifty-two died that day.''
</P>
<P>
   Among them, his wife and son.
</P>
<P>
   The horror behind his words hangs in the stillness of the Kansas
City night.
</P>
<P>
   Ho stops and then smiles at his visitors. Silence fills the room
as he pours water into tiny flowered cups. Tea leaves swirl into
figure eights of brown. He folds his hands small in his lap, and
waits.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, Ho's story is very sad,'' says his interpreter, Doan
Nguyen, also a Vietnam refugee who fled Saigon. ``But his story is
like so many others. We Vietnamese in Kansas City are very sad for
the 58,000 Americans and those who died in our country. They leave
family and friends. Why were they sacrificed for nothing?
</P>
<P>
   ``This anniversary is sour and bitter,'' she says, referring to
the 25th year since the fall of Saigon and the end of the war. ``In
Vietnam on Sunday, they will be celebrating and having parades.
</P>
<P>
   ``But we over here remember. We will not forget....Some people,
like Ca, remember every day.''
</P>
<P>
   Killed in action
</P>
<P>
   The man in the photograph looks familiar to Jamie Derleth _ he
has her eyes, her mouth.
</P>
<P>
   She was 1 year old when he died. Too young to remember her
24-year-old father, James ``Mack'' McClafferty, killed in action in
1968.
</P>
<P>
   ``All I remember is that I grew up hating slanty-eyed people,''
says Derleth, now 32. ``All I knew from a very young age was that
people with slanted eyes killed my dad, so I hated them all.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't hate Asians today. But as a little girl, that was the
only way I could put a face on his death.''
</P>
<P>
   On July 14, 1968, two soldiers from the 101st Airborne Division
arrived at the Lee's Summit door of Diane McClafferty. The soldiers
didn't have to tell her why they were there. When she saw them _ in
their white gloves and dress uniforms _ she knew.
</P>
<P>
   The McClaffertys had two children: Jamie and 2-year-old Mike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm still really angry about the Vietnam War,'' says Diane
Flores, 54, now remarried to a husband she calls a wonderful man.
She became a psychiatric nurse at the Veterans Hospital. ``I felt
like, in a way, by helping the veterans I was helping my husband.''
</P>
<P>
   Her children never knew their biological father. But the war
touched them in different ways.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up wanting to learn all I could about the Vietnam
War,'' says Mike McClafferty, 33, who at one time signed up to be a
Marine but withdrew his application. ``But what I've learned about
the war is mostly from the Vietnam vets I meet. They didn't offer
any courses on it when I was in college.''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's a Vietnamese?'' Miranda Derleth, 13, asks, after
listening to her uncle talk.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's someone from Vietnam,'' he says. ``It's like an Italian
is someone from Italy; an American is from America. Do you know
what the Vietnam War was?''
</P>
<P>
   She bites her lip for a second. ``Was that when Japan bombed
America?''
Forever changed
</P>
<P>
   ``I'll be there in a minute,'' says Chris Woelk, yelling over
the chugging of his riding mower. Slowly he becomes a tiny speck in
the verdant fields as he shears one last row of grass next to
stubbly blackberry stalks.
</P>
<P>
   Here, 50 miles from the hubbub of Kansas City and working
beneath blue skies, Woelk, a veteran of the Vietnam War, finds
peace.
</P>
<P>
   In the open air the only sounds he hears are the occasional
cattle lowing. Or the rustle of leaves by summer breezes. The
buzzing rhapsody of insects.
</P>
<P>
   ``So, how many vets does it take to change a light bulb?'' he
asks, once he returns to his barn. He squints, takes a toke on an
imaginary reefer and answers: ``You'll never know ma-a-a-a-an,
'cause you weren't there!
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what most people expect to hear from a Vietnam vet,''
he says with a laugh. ``I don't see myself as the typical vet. I
feel like that time in history is so political, so historical that
I share it with people if they're interested. I don't want people
to forget the lessons we learned over there.''
</P>
<P>
   Woelk, 54, farms 116 acres in Wellington, Mo. But the Vietnam
War is planted deep in his Midwestern soul. And on each anniversary
the memories come tumbling back, usually in his dreams.
</P>
<P>
   Images of deep greenery, smells of rotting earth, the stench of
human waste. The dream always begins with him crossing out each
date on his homemade calendar with a large ``X,'' watching his time
in country grow ``short.'' In 1968 this was part of Woelk's daily
ritual.
</P>
<P>
   But his dreams always morph into nightmares, reruns of the same
theme: His hitch in Vietnam is up, he returns home to Kansas, and
then the government makes a mistake and sends him back for another
tour of duty.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't sleep last night knowing we'd be talking today,''
he says. ``Yeah, I dreamed about Nam last night. Not much can keep
it from seeping into my world. It was too intense an experience. It
took me 32 years before I'd talk about it. Now I can't shut up.''
</P>
<P>
   And now Woelk can see one benefit from the war.
</P>
<P>
   It was Aug. 15, 1968, and he been in Vietnam just a few hours.
His convoy stopped. He and another soldier slid into a ravine for
cover as others worked on the engine of the lead truck. He shared a
drink of liquor with the older soldier. Then it was time to move
out.
</P>
<P>
   Just as he turned to look at his new friend, a land mine went
off. The soldier's legs seemed to hover in the air, and then
liquified. It was over in less than a second.
</P>
<P>
   And for the next 32 years, Woelk could not lose the image.
</P>
<P>
   That night back in camp, he sat away from the others, crying.
That's when the man came over. A man that was well over 6 feet
tall, very brawny, and very black.
</P>
<P>
   For Woelk, who is white and at the time clung to racial
stereotypes, what happened next changed his world. Again.
</P>
<P>
   ``He told me it was OK to cry,'' Woelk says. ``He told me that
everybody does with their first. I couldn't believe that this man
who so intimidated me at first was so kind to me. Me a perfect
stranger.''
</P>
<P>
   Even today Woelk cannot tell the story without tears rolling
down his cheeks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I vowed at that moment to never judge another person except
for his personality,'' Woelk says. ``If there's anything good the
war did for me, it was to open my eyes to my own prejudice....I'd
really like to go back to Vietnam for that reason.''
-- more --
</P>
<P>
   for that reason.''
The war on campus
</P>
<P>
   David Awbrey tries to show his media ethics students at the
University of Kansas what it was like on the KU campus in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   He has the photos of the protests about a war that few people
understood.
</P>
<P>
   He shows his students the snapshots capturing the anger, the
intensity. He tells them about Kansas' history of activism, about
John Brown a century earlier.
</P>
<P>
   But like the smoke that billowed out of the Kansas Union in
1970, his words float away. He fails to ignite his students'
curiosity about the Vietnam War, except for one question.
</P>
<P>
   ``They always want to know how long my hair was back then,'' he
says. ``My students just aren't interested in the Vietnam War. It's
out of their realm of experience. They are interested in their own
corner of the world, however. Habitat for Humanity is really big in
their lives.
</P>
<P>
   ``But their version of that time in history is based on Austin
Powers and the other media stereotypes of drugs, sex and rock 'n'
roll. They don't get it that flunking out of a course back then
meant Saigon would be graduate school.
</P>
<P>
   ``That Austin Powers stereotype reduces a whole era to the point
that it obscures important issues like civil rights and America's
foreign policy.''
</P>
<P>
   Awbrey, 51, was once a student protester. In 1969-70 he was the
student body president of KU. He was also in Army ROTC _ Reserve
Officers' Training Corps. For him Vietnam was close.
</P>
<P>
   ``The student union burned down, the city of Lawrence imposed a
curfew dusk to dawn. Forty-five students were arrested, and I was
one of them. Every day there was something happening, either there
was a bombing or a protest or a curfew. It was turmoil, turmoil,
turmoil.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kent State happened, May 4th, the university closed down
the school for the rest of the semester.
</P>
<P>
   ``It saved me from flunking out....But the powers that be wanted
blood in the street. I tried to keep that from happening, along
with some other people, including the chancellor. I was in a unique
position to be a go-between.''
</P>
<P>
   The story of Vietnam has yet to be played out, he says. Vietnam
was really a war of the classes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's profoundly disturbing that the men who did go over got
screwed by the government,'' he says. ``The top priority for the
United States today should be the Vietnam veterans. They deserve
much better treatment. What's lasting from this war is the trauma
on this group of men....It's profoundly sad what happened to
them.''
Present at the fall
</P>
<P>
   He retired from the military in 1980. But Vasco Martin is still
a soldier.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once a Marine, always a Marine,'' he says, with a little
chuckle.
</P>
<P>
   He's 62 and has cancer. If he lives five more years, he says, it
will be a miracle. He blames the war and Agent Orange, the
herbicide used to defoliate Vietnam's jungles.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I at least came home and had 25 more years to live,'' he
says.
</P>
<P>
   He's a native of Carrollton, Mo., and was one of the last
soldiers to leave Saigon before it fell April 30, 1975. He was head
of the security guard detail for the Defense Attache Office at Tan
Son Nhut Air Base.
</P>
<P>
   It was cloudy that day. Stores, banks, airline offices and even
the open-air markets were closed. Terror wrapped the faces of South
Vietnamese families trying to flee.
</P>
<P>
   The communists were coming. Shelling and rocket fire was heard
within miles of the city.
</P>
<P>
   Martin was in charge of 16 other Marines. Their job was to
evacuate military personnel at the Defense Attache Office. More
than 5,000 people would be airlifted to safety from that site. An
additional 2,000 would be rescued from the U.S. Embassy, six miles
away.
</P>
<P>
   The United States was leaving South Vietnam for good. Odd, then,
that the Marines had assigned to his detail a new soldier, a
teenager, just arrived in the country days before.
</P>
<P>
   He remembers thinking: Gee, they're still sending people here
now?
</P>
<P>
   Early the next morning, he checked the area and gave two of his
sentries a ``thumbs up,'' and then moved on. Minutes later, at 3:45
a.m., a rocket fell at the entrance, killing both men: Darwin
Judge, 19, of Marshalltown, Mo., and Charles McMahon Jr., 21, of
Woburn, Mass.
</P>
<P>
   The last Americans killed by hostile fire in the Vietnam War.
</P>
<P>
   Yesterday, Martin traveled to Iowa for a ceremony remembering
Judge and McMahon, whose families were presented with the Purple
Heart.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had a lot of close calls in Vietnam: was shot at, ran over a
land mine in a jeep and even the last day as we were flying out of
Saigon, rockets were exploding all around us,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   He smiles. Then the smile fades.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've worked hard all my life. I just retired, and I have a
perfect wife. Been married three years.'' He sighs. ``Yes, I'm
bitter.
</P>
<P>
   ``How could I not be? The war is still going to get me. It's
cutting my life short. But at least I wasn't left over there. A lot
of other guys were.''
Freedom's price
</P>
<P>
   For the Vietnamese community in Kansas City, Vietnam is not the
name of a war, but of their former home. A home now turned into
ugly memories of re-education camps, poverty, discrimination and
loss of freedom.
</P>
<P>
   Ca Ho was a South Vietnamese policeman in Saigon. When the North
Vietnamese took over, they sent him, like thousands of others, to
the camps.
</P>
<P>
   But Ho was released after 10 days because he had no skills the
communists wanted. He and his family were condemned to the jungle.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we were pushed to the forest, we had no nails. No tools.
No electricity. No water,'' he says. ``We dig holes in ground with
rocks and branches. It was very hard.''
</P>
<P>
   For a few years the Ho family tried to survive this way. But it
was unbearable. The family planned its exodus. Destitute, they
split up: Ho and his eldest son, Dzung Viet Ho, would board a boat
first. Later they would send for Ho's wife and youngest son, and
life would smile once more.
</P>
<P>
   In 1980 with the help of Catholic Charities, Ho and his son
arrived in Kansas City, two months after their passage to Thailand.
Every day they burned incense and prayed for the safety of their
family.
</P>
<P>
   The news came a year later. His wife and son's boat had sunk,
killing most everyone aboard. The date was May 7, 1981. Today it is
one of the only sentences Ho can say in perfect English.
</P>
<P>
   But moving into freedom cost him even more a few years later.
</P>
<P>
   Ho and his son tried to adjust to their new land. His son
enrolled in Northeast High School. Ho studied English at Donnelly
College. One day in 1986, Dzung went to school and never came back.
</P>
<P>
   The Vietnamese community rallied around Ho. Missing-person
reports were filed with the police. Ho and his friends called other
Vietnamese communities across the country asking if anyone had seen
his son. But he heard no news. Learned no answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Each other was all we had after the other deaths,'' he says.
``It doesn't make sense. We love each other very much. I hope he is
still alive.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life is very hard for me.''
</P>
<P>
   Ho spreads identification cards across the living room table.
Among them, a photo of Dzung smiling.
</P>
<P>
   It's late. A soft drumming of rain on the front porch cloaks the
stillness of the night.
</P>
<P>
   ``Freedom is expensive,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   Would he do it again, knowing what would happen?
</P>
<P>
   Ho slides the photos back into an envelope. He waits, then
answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``He says he would do it all again,'' the translator says. ``He
says, freedom is worth everything.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even life.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
