<SLUG> BC-GUSEWELLE-COLUMN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FOREIGN AID TOO OFTEN GIVES LEADERS A LICENSE TO STEAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By C.W. GUSEWELLE  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sometimes, like planets aligning, items in the news fall into a
logical and illuminating conjunction. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case on that recent day when it was reported in a
dispatch out of Geneva that Swiss authorities have begun filing
charges in the alleged looting of Nigeria's treasury by one of that
country's former dictators. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The $650 million found in Swiss bank accounts of Sani Abacha,
his family members and cronies surpasses by a full $100 million the
amount stashed there by Ferdinand Marcos during his long misrule in
the Philippines. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Meantime, a story out of New York on that same day told of a new
United Nations report whose conclusion was that bad government is
one of the chief reasons why many nations remain desperately poor. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It's astonishing that something so obvious and so widely known
by so many for so long should now be regarded as news at all. The
real news is that the unsayable has finally been said aloud _ and
by the agency that is the largest single aid-distributor on the
planet. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The report by the U.N. Development Program calls into question
some of the long-held assumptions about the development process. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The worst fallacy is belief that top-down foreign aid _
assistance provided to central governments _ will be used to
improve the lives of the worst-off, when the truth is that
frequently it never reaches the intended beneficiaries. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Instead, much of it is simply stolen by those in power at the
top, or diverted to pet projects that serve their personal or
political interests. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the 1960s and early 1970s, there was a genuine hope that
assistance from the wealthy countries could, over a reasonable span
of years, raise the most impoverished peoples out of absolute
misery and put them on the way, if not to prosperity, at least to
bearable lives. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   As time passed, however, conditions in many parts of the Third
World were seen actually to worsen by every objective measure:
widening illiteracy, poor nutrition, increased infant mortality,
shortened life expectancy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Predictably, enthusiasm for development aid began to flag. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Examples of rotten rulers have been legion, but Joseph Mobutu
was the poster boy. He was our client, and one of the larger
recipients of U.S. support. The Congo _ Zaire under his rule _ was
strategically placed and immensely rich in natural resources, yet
its people continued to suffer terribly. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   An estimate toward the end of his reign put the one-time
colonial soldier's personal worth at nearly $13 billion. In plain
words, Mobutu built his fortune by stealing us and his own country
blind. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In such intractable places, the report declares, the old
strategies simply don't work. When the regime at the top is inept
or corrupt, help can't reach the targeted needs. Therefore, if
development is to occur, aid's top priority must be to foster
honest and capable governments. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Such talk evokes wounded squeals from Third World tyrants, who
complain that donor countries are attempting to meddle in their
internal affairs. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The powerful, it is argued, have /{always/} enriched themselves.
And they have /{always/} showered the blessings of rule on their
kinfolk, their clans, their villages and tribes. It's the tradition
in such places. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Well, the aid-givers have a tradition, too. When they invest in
something, they expect a result. Recipient nations will do well to
understand that. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   There was a time when they could play West and East against each
other, but that time is past. The Cold War has ended. The world _
and the rules _ have changed. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
