<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBO-HAAKENSON-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HOME RUNS GETTING OUT OF CONTROL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JOE HAAKENSON  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM, Calif. _ Former Dodgers shortstop and manager Bill
Russell stood on the fake grass at Tropicana Field in Florida last
weekend, holding a baseball in his hand.
</P>
<P>
   Russell, now a bench coach for the Tampa Bay Devil Rays, flipped
the ball around like he was a child with a new toy. The seams on
the baseball are so flat, he noted. The ball is so hard, more like
a golf ball.
</P>
<P>
   Russell didn't say it, but you had to believe he was thinking,
``If they used this ball when I played, I could've hit home runs
like Kevin Elster.''
</P>
<P>
   Baseball commissioner Bud Selig claims the ball is the same.
Sure it is. And Enron Field in a pitcher's park.
</P>
<P>
   The home run has always been a fan favorite. Even the term
``home run'' has meaning beyond the baseball park. But now, it is
also baseball's cash cow. It is baseball's Golden Goose.
</P>
<P>
   Mark McGwire and Sammy Sosa showed exactly how important the
home run was to fans, and consequently, the owners' pocketbooks. So
baseball, it seems, made a business decision. Make the ball harder.
Make the parks smaller. Expansion means more teams, which means
diluted pitching. Umps, don't be afraid to squeeze the strikezone.
Players, go ahead and use Andro, Creatine, etc. Bulk up.
</P>
<P>
   Selig won't admit to any conspiracy theory, but the evidence is
in.
</P>
<P>
   The Cardinals have hit 52 homers in April, more than any team in
April in baseball history (and for those who bash the American
League for its lack of pitching, the Cardinals play in the National
League).
</P>
<P>
   At Houston's Enron Park, there have been 46 homers in 12 games.
Last season in the Astrodome, there were 118 homers in 81 games.
Suffice it to say, that number will be surpassed sometime in June.
</P>
<P>
   But the best evidence is all around us. Home runs are being hit
everywhere, by everybody. Through Friday, there were 20 players on
a pace to hit 50-plus homers this season. There were seven players
on a pace to hit 60-plus.
</P>
<P>
   Sure, it's early. But to put it in perspective, one only needs
to look at the 1980s. Nobody during the decade hit 50 homers in a
season. Between Cincinnati's George Foster in 1977 and Detroit's
Cecil Fielder in 1990, not a single player hit 50. Fielder was the
first American League hitter to get 50 since Roger Maris and Mickey
Mantle in 1961.
</P>
<P>
   Now, Jermaine Dye is on a pace for 77.
</P>
<P>
   Even before McGwire and Sosa hit it big, baseball was moving
toward the home run ball. Before Fielder in 1990, the 50-homer mark
had been reached only 17 times by 10 players in major-league
history. Since Fielder, six players have done it 10 times.
</P>
<P>
   That's just the way it is now. Baseball determined what the
owners needed to make money. But is it what baseball needed?
</P>
<P>
   ``No,'' said Angels manager Mike Scioscia, who played the entire
decade of the '80s, when hitting 30 homers in a season was a big
deal. ``Power is part of the game and it gets a lot of notoriety.
But for every Tony Gwynn, there are three Mark McGwires as far as
guys coming up.
</P>
<P>
   ``As the run total gets higher and higher, a lot of strategy is
washed under the bridge. We stole four bases in a game against
Toronto and it didn't mean a thing as far as the outcome. Playing
for one run early these days plays into the other manager's hands,
because he can sit back and wait for his guys to pound the ball. A
lot of strategy used for a long, long time might be phased out.''
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia was quick to note that players today are bigger and
stronger, and consequently there will be more power in the game.
What he said doesn't make sense is juicing the baseball.
</P>
<P>
   Scioscia remembered when the Angels played an exhibition game
against Cal State Fullerton just before the start of the season.
The Titans used their own college baseballs when they pitched, and
the ball had considerably less jump off the bat than when his
pitchers threw the major-league baseballs to the Titans hitters.
(Please, no jokes about the Angels pitching).
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope nobody is playing with the specifics of the ball,'' he
said. ``The game did pretty well for the first 120 years.'' &QL; 
 &QL; 
 &QL; 
Joe Haakenson is a staff writer who covers the Angels. His column
appears every other week. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2138EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
