<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 21:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1180 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBA-FICK-LOCAL-LADN     04-29 0692
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-FICK-LOCAL-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FICK TRYING TO FIND HIS PLACE IN DETROIT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HEATHER GRIPP  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Robert Fick hears the cliche all the time, but he refuses to
utter the popular phrase of professional athletes without adding to
it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm happy to be here,'' he said, rolling his eyes and not
sounding excited as he sat in the dugout before a recent game.
``But not that happy.''
</P>
<P>
   Fick was forced to be a spectator last season. He doesn't want
to do it again.
</P>
<P>
   Almost a month into what he hopes will be his first full season
in the major leagues, Fick has spent far more time on the Detroit
Tigers' bench than playing. Not playing last season because he was
rehabilitating from shoulder surgery was difficult enough, but not
playing when he is healthy is more discouraging.
</P>
<P>
   Being asked to play positions other than catcher and being on a
team with the worst record in the major leagues doesn't make coping
easier.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard,'' Fick said. ``I'm sure you know the line
</P>
<P>
   you hear a lot of people say they'd do anything just to be in
the big leagues and it's great just to be here.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well ... it's just like playing Little League. You want to
play every day, no matter where you're at.''
</P>
<P>
   Fick's first taste of not playing came in 1999 when he injured
his left shoulder taking a swing during spring training. He needed
surgery that left him on the disabled list until September.
</P>
<P>
   ``Looking back on it, it's probably one of the better things
that ever happened to me,'' said Fick, who was dealing with
off-field problems such as the death of his father.
</P>
<P>
   ``I looked forward to getting on the field and trying to forget
about everything, and I ended up being hurt,'' he said. ``I spent
the whole summer in Florida rehabbing by myself. It was kind of a
reality check. Baseball wasn't there for me. It was the first time
I had to struggle without my dad there. I'm a stronger person
because of it. I learned that baseball's not always gonna be there.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a kid. I had a hard time growing up, but that kind of
helped.''
</P>
<P>
   The 26-year-old can't remember a time when he wasn't involved in
baseball. His five older brothers _ including his oldest brother,
Chuck, a professional scout _ taught him the sport he played at
Newbury Park (Calif.) High School and Cal State Northridge before
signing with the Tigers as a fifth-round draft pick in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   He was the 1997 Midwest League MVP and batting champion when he
batted .341 and had a 32-game hitting streak at the Single-A level.
He was one of the Southern League's top offensive players in 1998
and made the jump from Double-A to the majors at the end of the
season.
</P>
<P>
   Fick made his mark last season by hitting a grand slam that
nearly cleared the right-field roof for the final home run hit at
Tiger Stadium.
</P>
<P>
   The left-handed hitter's ability to hit to the opposite field,
handle breaking pitches and not strike out often encouraged the
Tigers, but his room for growth as a catcher prompted Detroit's
offseason trade for Brad Ausmus.
</P>
<P>
   Since Ausmus is signed through 2001, Fick is not expected to see
much time at at catcher and vows he will play regularly for some
team, if not the Tigers.
</P>
<P>
   Fick's easiest way into the starting lineup is as a designated
hitter, but three of his nine starts this season have been at first
base. He also works out at third base. He has three errors and is
batting .243.
</P>
<P>
   Even if Fick's stats were better, Tigers first-year manager Phil
Garner insists he is not ready to alter the starting lineup of his
struggling team because, ``It's been going on for a while since
before I got here and you're not gonna change the stripes on a
zebra in a few weeks.''
</P>
<P>
   A five-game suspension, scheduled to begin May 6, for his
participation in a recent brawl, ensures Fick more time off the
field.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's hard on me,'' Fick said. ``I'm used to playing every day.
I'm used to being counted on.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm the 10th guy around here. There's only nine positions, so
you know. ... Right now, I know my role is just to be ready when
called upon.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2140EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
