<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 21:41 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1181 &Cx1f; kan-z
r w BC-GORE-VISIT-KAN &LR;      04-29 1039
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GORE-VISIT-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE'S VISIT DRAWS ATTENTION TO KC NEIGHBORHOOD'S REVITALIZATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By SCOTT CANON and DIANE CARROLL  
 c. 1999 The Kansas City Star  
<TEXT>
<P>
   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Having stood in the midday sun Saturday,
overseeing the transformation of a central-city park from
drug-trafficking trash pit to safe haven, Kevin Evans perspired a
bit.
</P>
<P>
   Even in the heat, the Kansas City Parks and Recreation worker
was happy to heft another tool _ and hand it to Vice President Al
Gore.
</P>
<P>
   Shiny, new purple and pink playground equipment had been bolted
snugly together _ all except for a final curving slide saved for
the vice president to wrench together in front of the assembled
cameras.
</P>
<P>
   Soon Gore _ dressed candidate casual in khaki pants, polo shirt,
cowboy boots and a Palm Pilot hanging on his left hip _ put his
elbow grease into a socket wrench under Evans' direction.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm trying to figure out why Kevin here is sweating while I'm
doing all the work,'' Gore quipped. His joke, of course, was
stating the obvious, that this campaign stop piggybacked on the
efforts of Kansas Citians who had refurbished Montgall Park, near
22nd Street and Benton Boulevard.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's done their part,'' Gore told a crowd of about 100
people at the park in a short speech a few minutes later. ``This is
like celebrating a birth, because a neighborhood is being reborn.
It's a born-again neighborhood.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is exactly why Evans was glad to have Gore, or anyone who
comes with a media entourage, in the neighborhood.
</P>
<P>
   ``Any time you can bring attention to revitalization like this,
it can only help,'' Evans said. ``And where (Gore) goes you have
all the TV and the radio and the rest.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore, the presumptive Democratic presidential nominee, used the
park and a backdrop of children perched on the new playground
equipment to call for a variety of things he believes government
can do to help troubled neighborhoods restore themselves: ``more
after-school programs ... universal preschool ... a commitment to
connect all the classrooms to the Internet ... to treat teachers
like the professionals that they are ... more community police
officers who are working with the community.''
</P>
<P>
   Later his campaign issued a release touting Gore's plan that he
says would put an added 50,000 police officers on the street. The
campaign also said Texas Gov. George W. Bush, the near-certain
Republican presidential nominee, has a tax-cut plan that would make
paying for such crime-fighting programs impossible. The campaigns,
naturally, differ on whether Gore's approach would reduce crime or
whether Bush's plans would hurt efforts to pay for police officers.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Gore's visit to Montgall Park unveiled no new administration
or campaign initiatives. Rather, his staff passed out releases
recapping a grab bag of positions he'd talked about through the
campaign. One said: ``Gore would fight to provide a prescription
drug benefit under Medicare, a strong, enforceable patients' bill
of rights and universal health care access for children.''
</P>
<P>
   At the park, he called on people to make old neighborhoods shine
in a way that suggests a healthy community. And key to that health,
Gore said, were efforts like the one that teamed Children's Mercy
Hospital, police officers, parks workers and volunteers to start
converting the neighborhood from one in decline to one on the mend.
</P>
<P>
   And to make that happen, Gore said, the community must carve out
a territory that allowed children a safe place to play. ``When
children feel safe, and families feel their children are going to
be safe, then the neighborhood comes back to life,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Later at a town hall-style meeting, Gore would emphasize the
message again that Kansas City was taking positive steps.
</P>
<P>
   Arriving at Downtown Airport on Air Force Two about 1:30 p.m.,
Gore was greeted by Democratic U.S. Rep. Karen McCarthy of Kansas
City and Missouri Auditor Claire McCaskill.
</P>
<P>
   He made no public remarks at the airport but spent 30 minutes
inside the terminal meeting supporters and local political
officials, such as Jackson County Legislature Chairman Victor
Callahan, Kansas City Councilman Troy Nash and Woody Overton,
General Services Administration regional administrator.
</P>
<P>
   Gore's police-escorted motorcade included two limousines, seven
control and staff vehicles, a press bus and a Johnson County
ambulance.
</P>
<P>
   It took him to the corner of Agnes Avenue and 22nd Street, where
he strolled one block west and one block south.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the 100 or so people at the park _ nearly equaled by
police officers, Secret Service agents, city workers and
journalists _ stuck to tossing flying discs or playing basketball
when he first arrived. But a few lined up along an orange temporary
fence for a better look.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, Al!'' shouted 12-year-old Christine Vedros of Leawood,
Kan. ``Say hello to Tipper (his wife) for me!''
</P>
<P>
   ``I will,'' he yelled back with a smile.
</P>
<P>
   He greeted a few families on their porches, talked to a young
woman on the corner and then _ by her cell phone _ to one of her
friends.
</P>
<P>
   As he walked, the vice president chatted casually for less than
five minutes with a handful of police officers who were familiar
with the neighborhood. Before the speech he spent about 20 minutes
helping Evans assemble the slide.
</P>
<P>
   Next he headed for Attucks Elementary School _ and a catered
dinner of smoked ribs _ before holding court before a meeting of
ostensibly undecided voters who had been selected by civic
organizations contacted by the Gore campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that many of you are undecided about this election,''
Gore was quoted as saying in a press release handed out before the
event. ``That's why I've invited you here tonight. I want to give
you a chance to hear directly from me, and I want the chance to
listen and to learn from you.''
</P>
<P>
   More than 100 people were gathered in the school's small
gymnasium, a relatively intimate setting where the vice president's
staff said he planned to stay until he had fielded everyone's
questions.
</P>
<P>
   At a similar meeting Friday night in Albuquerque, he spoke for a
Gore campaign record: four hours and five minutes.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2141EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
