<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 21:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1182 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BBN-NL-NOTEBOOK-LADN     04-29 0606
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-NL-NOTEBOOK-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG BALL MIGHT CHANGE WAY ASTROS PLAY GAME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Houston Astros went from the hardest place in baseball to
hit a home run to a place that resembles a field in Williamsport,
Pa., and it's forced manager Larry Dierker to change his style of
managing.
</P>
<P>
   Speed, defense, manufacturing runs, strong pitching _ you know,
the fundamentals that make up a good ballclub _ are on their way
out in Houston because no longer are 2-1 and 3-2 games part of the
equation.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've always been a team that won by emphasizing pitching,
speed and defense, but we might not be able to rely as much on that
part of our game (at Enron Field) as we did at the Astrodome,''
Dierker said. ``We might have to rely less on manufacturing runs
and more on trying for the big inning.''
</P>
<P>
   Dierker said he'll wait a little longer before making that his
final judgment since the Astros have had only two homestands, but
so far, it's certainly heading that way.
</P>
<P>
   Houston's new bandbox has averaged 12.6 runs through 12 games,
nearly 4 more than at the Astrodome last season. And there's an
average of 3.67 homers hit per game at Enron Field, compared to 1.3
per game at the Astrodome last season.
</P>
<P>
   And the Astros aren't adjusting well. Houston is 3-9 at home,
the pitchers are going nuts, and the Astros entered Saturday six
games out of first place. The last time Houston was that far away
from the top of the division was 1996.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think two homestands is enough of a sample to say for
sure, but based on what I've seen so far, we might need to change
our philosophy a little,'' Dierker said. ``We may be sacrificing
less or maybe not using the hit and run as much early in the game,
or certainly not as much as we used them in the Astrodome.''
</P>
<P>
   REGARDING HENRY: Florida Marlins owner John Henry is racking his
brain to figure out how to make the residents of South Florida buy
him a new ballpark. Even Gov. Jeb Bush shot down a cruise tax, so
now Henry has brainstormed another idea to make people pay for
something they apparently don't want.
</P>
<P>
   Henry came up with the idea of building a 25,000-seat ballpark
that left room for expansion. That would spread the cost over time
and allow him not to have another fire sale on players who are
eligible for salary arbitration.
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, that's got to be just grand for baseball. No longer are
teams dumping soon-to-be free agents; the Marlins are getting ready
to dump players three years from free agency.
</P>
<P>
   CY JOHNSON: Arizona lefty Randy Johnson is 5-0, has a 1.06 ERA,
and leads the National League in strikeouts (53), innings (42),
shutouts (two) and opponents' batting average (.148). He's pitched
in all but 2 innings of games he's started.
</P>
<P>
   ``If we win, I've done my job,'' said Johnson, the reigning Cy
Young Award winner. ``I try not to get caught up in numbers. I'm
surprised more pitchers haven't done that.''
</P>
<P>
   ODDS AND ENDS: Cincinnati general manager Jim Bowden wasn't
pleased about watching his club get walloped by the Dodgers last
weekend. The Dodgers won the three games by a combined 36-7 score,
and the Reds led for half an inning in one game.
</P>
<P>
   ``For whatever reason right now, we're atrocious,'' Bowden said.
``We're just playing bad baseball. You can't put too much
camouflage on it. Right now, the general manager stinks, the
starting pitchers stink, the relief pitchers stink, the hitters and
fielders stink. We need to buy some deodorant and cologne.''
</P>
<P>
   The Reds responded by winning two of three from the Mets. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2142EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0219 </DOCNO>
