<HEADER>
A1185 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-BUSH-BUDDHISTS-NYT &LR;      04-29 0570
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-BUDDHISTS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH TAKES NOTE OF THE FOURTH ANNIVERSARY OF A FUND-RAISING
FIASCO 
</HEADLINE>
   By ALISON MITCHELL   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gov. George W. Bush homed in on one of Vice President
Al Gore's potential vulnerabilities Saturday, gleefully telling a
convention of radio talk show hosts in New York City that they were
meeting on the anniversary of Gore's fund-raising appearance at a
Buddhist temple in California.
</P>
<P>
   Bush, the presumptive Republican presidential nominee, quickly
got into the irreverent spirit of talk radio, mocking his
Democratic opponent in his brief appearance in the city. ``This is
the fourth anniversary, to this very day, of his historic visit to
the Buddhist temple,'' he told the National Association of Radio
Talk Show Hosts.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor, who earlier in the week headlined a $21.3
million Republican fund-raiser, said Gore had performed an
``amazing fund-raising act where you can convert poverty into
wealth.'' Bush added, ``I'm sure he's celebrating this occasion in
private.''
</P>
<P>
   As the crowd applauded, Bush said: ``Too bad he's not here. He's
a man who knows a lot of things about a lot of subjects, including
radio technology.'' Bush added, in a reminder of how Gore once took
credit for the Internet, ``I'm sure he invented it.''
</P>
<P>
   For four years, Republicans have been using Gore's appearance at
Hsi Lai Temple in Hacienda Heights, Calif., to tie him to the
Democrats' campaign finance excesses in the last presidential race
and to raise questions about Gore's integrity.
</P>
<P>
   The vice president gave several different accounts of his
appearance at the temple, saying he did not know the lunch had been
a fund-raiser, and eventually drawing a distinction between a
fund-raiser and a ``finance-related event.''
</P>
<P>
   Maria Hsia, a longtime Gore fund-raiser, was recently convicted
on five felony counts for her role in arranging illegal donations
to the Democratic National Committee, including some from the event
at the Buddhist temple. The Justice Department charged that she had
arranged for monks and nuns to write checks to make it appear that
they were the donors to the Democrats. In fact, they were
reimbursed by the temple, which is barred from making political
contributions because it is a tax-exempt religious institution.
</P>
<P>
   After his short speech, Bush hopped from stand to stand in the
Empire Hotel, near Lincoln Center, where radio hosts were on the
air. He was interviewed by four hosts in rapid succession, and was
heard on a computer-oriented show and WFAN, a sports station.
</P>
<P>
   Responding to Gore's plan to hold local schools accountable for
student performance, Bush derided the plan as ``pretty shallow
accountability.'' And of his scheduled meeting in May with his
former rival, Sen. John McCain of Arizona, Bush said: ``I know what
I want to achieve. I want to have a good visit with a man I knew
before the primaries. He was a friend of mine and I'm confident
he'll be a friend of mine after the primaries.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush said he understood that the changing political times meant
that the talk show hosts needed some consolation. ``The Clinton
era's ending,'' he said. ``This is a guy who provided you with a
lot of interesting material.''
</P>
<P>
   The visit to the broadcasters was Bush's only campaign stop
Saturday in New York. He spent more time flying from Austin, Texas,
and back, than he did in the city.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
