<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-BLUES-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WHAT IS CURE FOR SPRINGTIME BLUES? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Blues folded up faster than anyone expected, and that no
doubt will trigger changes in St. Louis next season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't want to overreact, but we didn't play very well,''
said general manager Larry Pleau, reached at his office just before
the weekend. ``And we've got to remember to give some credit there
to the Sharks. At the same time, though, we have to put blame on
our own shoulders. There are no excuses for what happened. We
played our game in spurts, but we didn't do it consistently.''
</P>
<P>
   No league has as many early-round upsets as the NHL. It's the
nature of the sport. Pucks end up in the net for no reason.
Witness: Jaromir Jagr's shot in Game 1 vs. Philadelphia Thursday
night that banged off John LeClair, ricocheted off a defenseman's
skate, and beat an unsuspecting Brian Boucher. The shot appeared to
be about 10 feet off net. But the end result was a 1-0 Penguins
lead, and from there the Flyers never mounted much of an attack on
netminder Ron Tugnutt.
</P>
<P>
   The Blues didn't exit the postseason as a result of such, shall
we say, shooting serendipity. But the sight of St. Louis defenseman
Marc Bergevin cuffing a puck and literally throwing it in his own
net (what was he thinking?) for a San Jose goal early in the series
was a showcase piece from the Museum of Stanley Cup Horrors. Wow.
Back in the days when Gerry Cheevers was coaching the Bruins, I saw
Wayne Cashman make a similar move (hard to believe, referee Wally
Harris had put the whistle away), but he tossed it by the Winnipeg
goalie. The Bruins hustled onto the bus and got out of town with
the tie.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it's no surprise that Pleau will shop for a defenseman
this summer.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're like all 30 teams,'' Pleau said. ``Everyone wants to get
defensemen.''
</P>
<P>
   The picture might have looked different in St. Louis had the
Blues won the Ray Bourque swap-a-thon back in March. Pleau made a
serious pitch (believed to include Marty Reasoner) for Bourque.
Word around FleetStreet is the Blues came in second. The magic
Bourque is working behind the Colorado blue line very well might
have worked for the Blues. Faced with a backline of Bourque, Chris
Pronger, and Al MacInnis, the Sharks likely wouldn't be tangled up
with the Stars in Round 2.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not a believer in what a lot of people say, that the
regular season means nothing,'' said Pleau, whose club finished
with the league's best record (51-20-11, 114 points). ``That's a
lot of hogwash. The players and coaches here did a great job. Did
we play well in the playoffs? No. Is that because (of the toll) of
the regular season? No. That would be the easy way out. We just
didn't play well enough in that series _ period.''
</P>
<P>
   Pleau knows he faces abundant second-guessing and media
scrutiny, especially because his team went from regular-season
domination to first-round elimination.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone _ management, coaches, and players _ we're all more
responsible to the media today than we were 20 years ago,'' said
Pleau. ``I like that. I think it's great. It makes us all more
accountable in this business.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sure, the second-guessing is incredible. But to me, that's
great. The fans love it. If you listen to the talk shows here, it's
full of, `Should Larry Pleau be fired? Should (head coach) Joel
Quenneville be fired?' Hey, people care, and they want answers _
that's why they're paying $85 a ticket to go to the game, right?''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A future in the NHL
</P>
<P>
   Avalanche general manager Pierre Lacroix is convinced that
Swedish forward Sami Pahlsson, whom he swapped to the Bruins in the
Bourque deal, will play in the NHL. ``To think of him as a top-line
player, that would be a little too much,'' said Lacroix. ``But
he'll definitely be a solid player. If he was (with Colorado), I'd
think of him more as a third- or fourth-line player, especially
with the people we have here.'' Pahlsson, by the way, is working on
a Team Sweden line with fellow Bruin P.J. Axelsson at the World
Championships, which began Saturday in St. Petersburg, Russia . . .
Lacroix on tough guy Martin Grenier, another component of the
Bourque deal: ``I think he's too young to tell how he'll project.''
. . . Boucher, of Woonsocket, R.I., entered Round 2 with the
second-lowest goals-against average (1.58), all time, for rookie
netminders in the playoffs. No. 1 is Bill Durnan, 1.53 for Montreal
in 1944; No. 3 is Terry Sawchuk, 1.68 for Detroit in 1951 . . . At
last count, there were no fewer than 280 NHLers, enough to fill 14
teams, who were making $1 million or more per year. A penny's worth
of perspective: In 1991-92, there were only eight skating
millionaires _ Wayne Gretzky, Mario Lemieux, Brett Hull, Steve
Yzerman, Scott Stevens, Paul Coffey, Chris Chelios, and Bourque . .
. Reports circulating late last week had the Flames, if they go up
for sale at the end of June, possibly landing in Oklahoma City.
Please, stop the insanity. There are still bona fide big league
towns out there, including Houston, Portland, and San Diego. The
last thing the NHL needs is another small US town trying to play
big boy hockey . . . Great sight in the Denver Pepsi Center
Thursday night: a pair of true-blue Bourque fans wearing game
sweaters that were one-half Bruin and one-half Avalanche. Think Jay
and Michael Feenan, from Boston, order the surf 'n turf special (8
oz. sirloin, 8 oz. lobster tail) when they go out to eat, too?
Relax. No one is selling the sweaters. They were home-tailored.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   No hits on lottery
</P>
<P>
   The NHL hasn't fixed a date for the lottery that will determine
the order for the June 24-25 entry draft in Calgary. At the moment,
the Bruins hold the No. 7 pick, their second-highest pick since
1987, when Glen Wesley was chosen third. Other than Joe Thornton,
No. 1 overall in '97, their highest picks have been a pair of No.
8s (Sergei Samsonov, '97; Johnathan Aitken, '96) and one No. 9
(Kyle McLaren in '95). Based on the outcome of the lottery, the
Bruins could pick as high as fourth and as low as eighth . . . Jeff
Gorton, the Bruins' assistant VP of hockey operations, just
returned from a scouting tour through Russia and Switzerland.
``It's no secret that it will be a European draft,'' he said.
``That's where the skill is, and out of 30 first-round picks, I'd
say a minimum of 20 will be from Europe.'' . . . OK, Kevin Stevens
got himself into a stupid jam when he was arrested in January, and
his brief time here in the Hub didn't earn him Hall of Fame status,
but both of his former Ranger bosses, ex-GM Neil Smith and ex-coach
John Muckler, believe he can still be an effective player in a
limited role. He is a free agent July 1, and he says he'll work for
bottom dollar, accepting even a training camp invite. History
aside, he would be worth a look here. His upside might not be more
than 18-20 goals and, say, 45 points, but he could be worth it at
the right price. Nothing wrong with having guys in the lineup who
feel they have something to prove . . . Junior hockey standout
Jonathan Roy, a high-scoring center for Moncton in the Quebec
League, recently was a patient at the Lahey Clinic in Burlington,
where he was treated for a rare form of cancer (rhabdomyosarcoma)
that attacks the muscle tissue. The club owner is Robert Irving,
billionaire owner of Irving Oil in Canada and longtime friend of
the Lahey. Roy, who had 123 points this season, is back in Moncton,
awaiting word on tests to determine his treatment . . . Look for
the Oilers to entertain offers this summer for ex-BC Eagle Bill
Guerin and slick defenseman Roman Hamrlik. Both would be fine
additions for the Blues, but they'd have to part with some young,
cheap talent _ the likes of Jochen Hecht and Michal Handzus . . .
Oilers boss Glen Sather emphatically denies any interest in moving
to Manhattan to be part of the Rangers' new management structure.
One source believes the Rangers will hire three front office types
to direct the club.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Coyote may roam
</P>
<P>
   What's next for Coyote power forward Keith Tkachuk? Surgery,
possibly. According to his Boston-based agent, Bob Murray, Tkachuk
may have ligament damage inside an ankle, which required
pain-killing shots just to suit up for the playoffs. ``He shouldn't
have been playing,'' said Murray. ``But that's Keith. He's a
warrior, and he wants to be in there even when he knows,
healthwise, he shouldn't be.'' Meanwhile, Murray isn't sure what
sweater Tkachuk will wear in 2000-01. ``Much of that will be
determined by the ownership situation out there,'' said Murray.
``For Keith's part, he loves it out there, he loves his teammates,
and he wants to play for Phoenix. But based on the track record _
you're talking about a team that essentially traded him twice last
year, once to Carolina and once to the Rangers _ I'd have to think
they'd probably trade him over the summer. I'd like to be
optimistic and say he'd be back, but I can only go on their
history.'' On May 17, the Coyotes' new ownership, Ellman Co., is
expected to hand over $10 million toward the purchase of the club.
If Ellman takes control, it remains to be seen whether drastic
changes, including the replacement of GM Bobby Smith, will take
place . . . BU freshman goalie Rick DiPietro has until Monday to
declare for the draft. If he does, he will surrender the remaining
three years of his college eligibility, and he'll likely be
destined for a one- or two-year tuneup in the minors (IHL or AHL).
Word along Comm. Ave. is that it's highly likely DiPietro will
enter the draft. One teammate put the odds at 70-30 of DiPietro
going pro. ``He's a terrific prospect, and fun to watch,'' said
Gorton. ``He brings that element to the ice that not too many do,
the way he's able to handle the puck like a third defenseman.'' In
all likelihood, said Gorton, DiPietro will be selected in the first
round whenever he enters the draft . . . It's a reach, and maybe a
long one right now, but the dollars NHL clubs might generate from
the Internet could be the money stream, if pooled and divvied up
equally, that could keep the struggling Canadian clubs afloat. Come
to think of it, baseball's small-market woes might be similarly
remedied . . . Bruins trainer Don Del Negro accompanied Hal Gill
and Steve Heinze on the Team USA squad bound for the World
Championships. Onetime Boston draft pick Ben Clymer, who signed as
a free agent and played 60 games with Tampa Bay this season, also
is with the Yanks . . . If the Avalanche do win the Cup, do you
suppose the parade route will start in Denver and end in Danvers?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
