<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 22:07 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1266 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKC-PROVIDENCE-FRIARS     04-29 2228
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-PROVIDENCE-FRIARS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HARD TIMES, HARD FEELINGS AT PC 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MARK BLAUDSCHUN  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PROVIDENCE _ It was the first week of April, and Tim Welsh was
feeling good, better than he had during the longest season of his
coaching career: a 1999-2000 campaign in which the Providence
basketball team had finished a dismal 11-18.
</P>
<P>
   The record was bad enough. Welsh had never had a losing season
in three years at Iona. And in his first season at Providence,
Welsh's team had gone 16-14 and received an NIT bid.
</P>
<P>
   But there was more to it. Welsh had been forced to scramble from
the get-go when his planned starting backcourt disappeared. One
guard, Sean Connolly, a 6-foot-4-inch sophomore from Peabody,
Mass., transferred to Ohio State. The other, John Linehan, a 5-9
junior, missed almost all of the season with a groin injury.
</P>
<P>
   But now the winter was over, and Welsh felt upbeat. Golf season
was ahead of him, and he could start thinking about better things
for next year.
</P>
<P>
   At 39, Welsh was not so far removed from his playing days at
Potsdam State that he didn't know what his players were feeling at
the end of a long season. He called a team meeting. No assistant
coaches. No one but Welsh and his players.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know what it's like at this time of year,'' Welsh said.
``It's spring. Basketball season is over, and you want to have some
fun. That's fine. I did that when I was a player myself. But be
careful out there. Don't do anything foolish.''
</P>
<P>
   After two seasons, Welsh thought he knew the character of his
team, as well as the characters. He knew kids such as Linehan,
Erron Maxey, and Abdul Mills had potential to be much better. He
knew Donta Wade, Llewellyn Cole, and Jamaal Camah had had ups and
downs during their careers and needed some structure in their
lives.
</P>
<P>
   When the meeting broke up, Welsh sat in his office and thought
he had done what he needed to do. Said the things he needed to say.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, things changed.
</P>
<P>
   The first call came late on a Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was already asleep,'' said Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   That call was followed by another _ and another.
</P>
<P>
   Four of his players had been arrested in an off-campus fight,
four others were implicated, and a program that had seemed to be
heading north was now heading south. Again.
</P>
<P>
   The dispute had begun over the weekend when Thomas Cook, a
Providence senior who worked as a bouncer at an off-campus
gathering spot called the Prime Time Cafe, refused to admit one of
the players into the bar.
</P>
<P>
   Words were exchanged. The basketball players, regarded by many
in the student body as mercenaries with very little link to campus
life, moved on. But after a weekend in which tempers slowly began
to flare, the players apparently sought to reopen the issue. At
about 10:30 p.m. on Monday, April 10, eight of them showed up at an
off-campus house shared by Cook and two other seniors, Mark Hogan,
and Ryan Kerwin.
</P>
<P>
   Reports vary on what occurred next. But the bottom line is that
four of the players _ Wade, Camah, Cole, and forward David Murray _
were deemed the point men in a confrontation that turned very
physical, with Cook and Hogan receiving severe facial injuries.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Players' futures uncertain
</P>
<P>
   Wade, Murray, and Cole are facing felony assault and
conspiracy-to-assault charges. Camah is facing a misdemeanor
assault charge.
</P>
<P>
   As the legal proceedings unfolded last week, a six-member
committee appointed by PC officials also conducted hearings on
campus, charging the eight players with violations of the school's
code of conduct.
</P>
<P>
   The college's penalties ranged from expulsion to suspension and
probation. Expulsion is the most severe, with no chance of
returning. Suspension means a one-year absence, while probation
allows a return to school but not to the team.
</P>
<P>
   The players have another week to appeal, but most observers feel
that given the public nature of the incident and the prevailing
mood on campus, a reversal is unlikely.
</P>
<P>
   The only good news for Welsh is that three of his best players _
Linehan, Maxey, and Mills _ apparently were not involved in the
incident and can play next year.
</P>
<P>
   But with whom? Cole is a senior and would have been gone next
year anyway. Camah has been in trouble before, and sources close to
the program say he will not be missed.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh has three incoming freshmen committed for next season:
forward Marcus Douhit and guards Shieku Kabba and Donnel Allick.
But if the school penalties stick, he will need to attract more
talented players to avoid a second straight losing season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's frustrating to the degree that you see yourself in the
headlines in a negative sense,'' said Welsh. ``All you want to do
is coach the team, do the right thing.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Glory days just a memory
</P>
<P>
   If this were just a blip on the radar screen, a one-time
incident _ just a ``fight,'' as one observer close to the scene
called it _ it would quickly disappear.
</P>
<P>
   But athletic life at Providence College is not like it once was.
The Friars used to be one of the elite college basketball programs
in the East, with a strong tradition that produced such prominent
coaches and players as Joe Mullaney, Dave Gavitt, Rick Pitino, John
Thompson, Lenny Wilkens, and Ernie DiGregorio.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh knew what he was undertaking when he accepted the job in
April 1998.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wasn't coming here unless I got a long-term contract,'' said
Welsh, who signed a seven-year deal. ``I knew all about the great
tradition and expect to get back to that again, but to do it the
right way, it was going to take some time.''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh was pleasantly surprised with the Friars' winning season
his first year. With Connolly and Linehan as his backcourt and a
solid nucleus of players such as Maxey and Wade coming back, he
thought the team could advance a notch.
</P>
<P>
   ``Linehan and Connolly were my staples,'' said Welsh.
</P>
<P>
   But Welsh knew Connolly was a very perishable commodity. When
coach Pete Gillen left Providence for Virginia in the spring of
1998, Connolly decided he'd had enough. Welsh had to do some heavy
bargaining to keep the player from leaving.
</P>
<P>
   ``If Coach Gillen had stayed, I would have stayed, too,'' said
Connolly last week from the basketball offices at Ohio State. ``The
situation there was all right, but I came to play for Coach Gillen,
and when he left, I wanted to leave right away. I gave it a year
and decided I wanted to go somewhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   That decision might have been prompted partly by the atmosphere
around the team when Welsh arrived. Gillen had faced what almost
every PC coach has in recent years: a hard time getting quality
people to come to a school that doesn't offer a lot in social
amenities, especially to black students.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A campus divide
</P>
<P>
   While no one says so publicly, the gap between the student body
and the basketball team has been growing wider for the past several
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime observers of Civic Center home games also noticed a
paucity of students this year that was sometimes embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps it was as simple as a losing season. Maybe it went
deeper than that. The Friars' roster had no white players, wasn't
that good, and had some citizens of questionable character.
</P>
<P>
   Camah, a 6-4 junior from Salem, Mass., was a case in point. In
December, Camah had appeared before the PC judicial board over an
incident involving a reporter at the student paper, The Cowl. The
paper reported that Camah had pleaded no contest to a domestic
disorderly charge involving his girlfriend at a campus dormitory.
</P>
<P>
   When the story appeared, Camah responded by throwing a newspaper
rack in an altercation at the paper's office. He was suspended for
a game against Central Connecticut and required to write an apology
to the newspaper and perform 25 hours of community service.
</P>
<P>
   There has also been some resentment of what many on campus view
as a bottom-line attitude on the part of the administration toward
the school's athletic program. The administration made an unpopular
decision a year ago to drop baseball, one of the more successful
Friars athletic programs, because of Title IX considerations.
</P>
<P>
   ``You would be hard-pressed to go back and find the last time
something was done that was really innovative,'' said one longtime
observer of the athletic program. ``The present administration, as
evidenced by the baseball fiasco of a year ago, is really very
bottom-line oriented.
</P>
<P>
   ``They seem to have lost their soul a little. PC always
succeeded because of the people, whether it was Joe Mullaney or
Dave Gavitt or Rick Pitino. It was always like a family. That's
absent now.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's very frustrating to see them wallowing. They seem to have
lost their passion. They kind of got fat and happy and forgot
whence they came. It's all very sad.''
</P>
<P>
   Athletic director John Marinatto concedes that PC faces some
problems.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do have to be creative,'' said Marinatto, ``because we
can't solve every problem by writing a check. PC is what PC is.
We're a small Catholic school. But one situation is not going to
stop us from its mission.''
</P>
<P>
   But questions linger over how well the basketball program's
mission jibes with the college's. The Friars must compete in the
Big East. But the campus is small. Seventy-four percent of the
school's 3,700 undergraduates come from the Northeast. Women make
up 57 percent of the student body.
</P>
<P>
   The lack of connection with the basketball team, whose players
seem to have very little in common with the student body, is
obvious.
</P>
<P>
   The coaches who have come through the program in recent years
have used PC as a steppingstone. That proved so troublesome to the
administration that it put a buyout penalty in Welsh's contract,
the first time a Friars coach has had one.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Changes take toll
</P>
<P>
   `If you look back at it,'' said Texas coach Rick Barnes, who
coached the Friars from 1988 until 1994 before leaving for Clemson
and then Texas, ``they have had tremendous upheaval in the last few
years. After a long tradition of people like Joe Mullaney and Dave
Gavitt, they had a seven-year period where they had four different
coaches.''
</P>
<P>
   Barnes conceded he took academic chances with some players.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had our battles,'' he said. ``It was never easy because the
talent wasn't in your backyard. You had to go out and sell
Providence, and to do that you had to sell yourself. At a place
like that, if a kid qualifies by NCAA minimum standards, I'm not
sure if you can have any kind of other restriction. If a kid
qualifies by NCAA rules, you had better be able to get him in
school.''
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that kids who can help the team athletically may
have baggage, and that puts even more of a burden on the coach.
</P>
<P>
   In Gillen's final days, the Providence administration endured
what was largely a dysfunctional basketball roster, with players
feuding, sometimes during the course of a game. With the latest
incident, the administration may put pressure on Welsh to bring in
players who are less likely to cause trouble.
</P>
<P>
   But Welsh is restricted there as well, because the type of
players who fit that mold could very easily take a look at
Providence and decide that almost every other school in the Big
East has something better to offer.
</P>
<P>
   Welsh pleads for patience. So do his supporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the biggest thing they need is stability,'' said Big
East commissioner Mike Tranghese, a former Providence sports
information director who knows the program as well as anyone. ``If
people have patience with Tim over the long haul, they can be fine.
The truth of the matter was that when Tim came on board, there
wasn't a lot there. I know they have the right coach, if everybody
has patience.''
</P>
<P>
   Tranghese doesn't buy the theory that you can't win at
Providence.
</P>
<P>
   ``You look around our league at BC, at Seton Hall, at St.
John's, at Villanova,'' he said. ``Everybody in our league has won
at some time. For some schools it's not automatic every year, but
it can be done and has been done.''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh hopes so.
</P>
<P>
   ``This place is similar to Iona,'' said Welsh. ``Same mission,
same type of student-athlete. What upsets me most is the character
issue. Character is important to me in recruiting and once they get
here.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
----- &QC; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Welsh gets tougher
</P>
<P>
   Since the incident, Welsh has had meetings with his players
almost daily.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told them they are going to see me more than they ever
dreamed about,'' he said. ``I told them they learned a lesson in
life. Sometimes you have some great kids who, on the spur of the
moment, will get themselves into a situation. But you can have good
kids and in one 10-minute incident, it can all be erased.''
</P>
<P>
   Welsh said he has heard words of contrition from almost all of
his players. What the players have heard from their coach is a
tough-love speech.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to move on from this, put things back together,''
Welsh said. ``I told them that the chances are they're all going to
live another 50 years, and if they can look back at this as just an
isolated incident in their lives, they will have done pretty well.
But they also have to learn from this. We all do.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
