<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-XFL-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
XFL WILL EXERT WRESTLING HOLD ON FANS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The age of alternative/extreme sports is upon us. They are
making it with their own youthful audience. So why should an
alternative version of football be any different?
</P>
<P>
   Sports fans from age 13 all the way up into their early 30s are
looking at things a little differently than us 40somethings-and-up.
Professional wrestling, love it or hate it, is one of the most
popular entertainment ventures among the younger generation. Vince
McMahon, president and CEO of the World Wrestling Federation, knows
marketing, and somehow, someway, he's going to bring football,
WWF-style, to a national audience.
</P>
<P>
   And the bet here is that one of NBC's highest-rated programs
will be ``Saturday Night XFL'' next winter.
</P>
<P>
   Why? Because America loves football and young America loves
wrestling.
</P>
<P>
   Since the XFL was announced in February, the consensus has been
that it won't make it. But that opinion is coming from
traditionalists and the segment of the population that is not
entirely sure what the league is all about. There have been wild
rumors that the games will be fixed and that coaches will be
hitting players over the head with chairs.
</P>
<P>
   Michael Keller, vice president of football operations for the
eight-team league, wants to make some things clear. The football
will not be a sham. It will not be scripted. It'll just be looser.
The people in the league simply won't take themselves so seriously.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am a football person,'' said Keller, a former executive with
the NFL's Seattle Seahawks, the USFL's Michigan Panthers, and
various World League and NFL Europe teams, plus a former linebacker
at Michigan and with the Dallas Cowboys. ``I've made my living in
football. If this was anything but real football, I would never
have taken the job.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller and his staff will try to rid the game of the ``dumb and
boring plays'' and the silly taboos of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The fair catch is gone. Touchbacks are not allowed. Kickoffs
will be made from the 25-yard line, and even if the kicker has a
strong enough leg to boot it deep into the end zone, the returner
must bring it out.
</P>
<P>
   Keller said there will be rules to protect the quarterback, but
not to the ridiculous extent of the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   The league will allow a player to be in motion heading toward
the line of scrimmage, and as in the college game, a receiver will
need only one foot in bounds to make a catch. On defense, there is
no 5-yard limit on bumping the receiver.
</P>
<P>
   The league, which is scheduled to begin play Feb. 3, 2001, is
toying with the idea of a field goal being worth 4 points from 50
yards and beyond. And extra-point kicks may be abandoned; teams
would have to run or pass it in.
</P>
<P>
   Player salaries? There is a scale even the NFL would love.
</P>
<P>
   Players will receive a base salary of $50,000, with numerous
chances to earn more based on wins and championships. Players on
the winning team will receive $3,000 per game per man. Head coaches
also will be rewarded for victories above their $150,000 salary.
Ties are discouraged; neither team would receive the bonus in that
case. A team that wins the championship will earn $25,000-$30,000
per man.
</P>
<P>
   There will be seven-man practice squads, earning $1,000 per
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a league of opportunity,'' said Keller. ``Winning and
being a starter is rewarded. What I see it as is an upgraded USFL.
Because the league is under one entity, we feel we have a better
chance of being able to control the expenses.''
</P>
<P>
   Where does the WWF come in? Personality, baby.
</P>
<P>
   Players will be allowed _ even encouraged _ to celebrate in the
end zone or after a great play. Teams probably will have their own
dances. Certainly, they'll have unique uniforms, which are
currently being designed. If you've seen some of the WWF wrestlers'
garb, you can only imagine the color schemes and imaginative
nicknames in store.
</P>
<P>
   And if you've seen the women of the WWF, well, you'll probably
see women in the XFL, as well.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a great creative department here,'' said Keller at WWF
headquarters in Stamford, Conn.
</P>
<P>
   This league will encourage players to do interviews, unlike the
NFL, which controls media access. The huddles will be miked, and
the locker rooms will be shown live before and after the game. WWF
stars will attend games and be available for halftime interviews.
There will be a lot of in-game sideline interviews, in fact.
</P>
<P>
   To speed up games, only 35 seconds will be allowed between
plays, and halftime will be shorter than it is in the NFL.
</P>
<P>
   At the wages being offered, it would seem difficult to attract
big-name players and coaches.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have a territorial draft so the players will be known in
those parts of the country where the team plays,'' said Keller,
``but we certainly can't say that a big-name NFL player would
choose to play in our league. That's not going to happen. But with
salary cap issues in the NFL, there are a lot of players who people
recognize who find themselves out of the game. They would certainly
want to resume their careers someplace.''
</P>
<P>
   Keller said there are 20-30 candidates for head coaching jobs,
and fans would recognize some of the ex-NFL coaches who have
applied. He said he's received applications from former college
coaches, former NFL assistants who would love to have a head job on
their resumes, and people from NFL Europe and the Canadian Football
League.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now we're about 30 days from hiring our general managers
and about 60 days from hiring our coaches,'' said Keller.
</P>
<P>
   If the XFL does take off, would it ever consider taking on the
NFL head-to-head? Keller said there are no such plans. The concept
was to devise football for fans to watch after the Super Bowl.
</P>
<P>
   The NFL has always been a little afraid of McMahon. It tried to
buy him out of his Monday night TV time slot a couple of years ago
because his wrestling shows were digging into ``Monday Night
Football'' ratings. So paranoid are some NFL people that they put
out the word at league meetings last month in Palm Beach, Fla., not
to discuss the XFL among themselves or with anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Keller said the league has secured most of the stadiums it will
need _ in places such as Miami, Orlando, Washington, Toronto,
Chicago, and Los Angeles _ but it is making one last scan of other
venues to make sure the best facilities are secured.
</P>
<P>
   He said two more teams will be added, with Boston a candidate,
but as we know there aren't many viable sites in Boston unless
Nickerson Field is revitalized.
</P>
<P>
   We are all skeptical of new leagues, but this one has incredible
juice with McMahon, NBC, and the flavors of wrestling and football.
If McMahon can create The Rock, Stone Cold Steve Austin, Triple H,
the Big Show, etc., he probably can create football personalities
that fans will flock to watch.
</P>
<P>
   The XFL is aiming to make football fun again.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Corner hasn't been sharp
</P>
<P>
   If Bill Belichick can straighten out Antonio Langham, it would
be a major coup. Langham's career has plummeted since he was a
highly touted rookie out of Alabama six years ago. It's not etched
in stone that Langham will beat out Tebucky Jones for a cornerback
job. Patriots fan may recall that when Langham was with the 49ers
in 1998, after signing a five-year, $17 million deal, he allowed
six touchdowns and committed seven penalties in his first six games
before being benched . . . Bruce Armstrong and Zefross Moss may
have been considered too old by the Patriots, but they were also
two of the more respected players on the team. Moss was a tough guy
who played in a lot of pain. Two seasons ago, he missed a week
after Bruce Smith had knocked Armstrong into the back of Moss's
legs. Then Moss attempted to practice with his ankle heavily
wrapped. Two defensive players who were out with injuries came over
to him and asked, ``What do you think you're doing?'' Moss replied,
``I'm trying to practice so I can play.'' The players told Moss,
``Don't come back too soon _ you're making us look bad.''
Armstrong's locker room impact has been well-documented. When
things were going bad, nobody had more of the players' ear than
Armstrong, a man who had been through all the battles and all the
situations and had a knack for putting things in perspective. The
Patriots have lost that (though they still have a chance to get him
back). Good luck to them. While Grant Williams and Lance Scott may
have upside, and Adrian Klemm may eventually be a good player, the
immediate effect could be ugly. Some who watched the Seattle-Miami
playoff game say that Williams had one of the worst games they'd
ever seen by an offensive lineman. Patriots offensive coordinator
Charlie Weis, when asked if offensive line may be the area taking
up most of his time and patience, said, ``I think it's going to be
a position where there'll be some strong competition. We have a
combination of guys who have 4-5 years experience and guys who are
first- and second-year players really getting after it and
competing. I think that can only make us better.'' . . . Not many
football players would go out and get a copy of their offensive
coordinator's biography so they could read up on the guy. Sean
Morey did. The Patriots receiver, playing in NFL Europe for the
Barcelona Dragons, picked up a copy of Sam Rutigliano's book.
Rutigliano, a long-time NFL coach, most notably with the Cleveland
Browns, is assisting former Boston College coach Jack Bicknell in
Barcelona. ``He's an interesting guy,'' said Morey. ``I just wanted
to learn about him. He's an excellent coach. The great thing here
is that I'm getting great coaching and I'm learning all the time.''
He caught 10 passes for 107 yards (including a 19-yard TD) last
week against Berlin after missing four weeks with a high ankle
sprain. ``It was torture just sitting around,'' said Morey, who sat
for most of last season on the practice squad. ``I tried to make
the best of it. Learned everything I could. I watched a lot of film
so I could mimic the tendencies of the receivers we were going to
face for the scout team so I could get Ty (Law) and Steve (Israel)
ready. I also soaked in everything I could from Shawn (Jefferson)
and Terry (Glenn) and Troy (Brown). I watched how they did things,
what they did to get themselves free. I also worked on my speed
with (assistant coach) Mike Morris.'' The Patriots didn't draft a
receiver, so Morey should get more of a look. He met with receivers
coach Ivan Fears before leaving for Europe to get an idea of what
he needed to improve on.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   All the wrong moves
</P>
<P>
   Nice choice, Peter Warrick. Dump a legitimate agent, Michael
George of SFX in New York, for Norm Nixon, a former basketball
player? Some players deserve what they get. A year ago, Ricky
Williams dumped Andrew Brandt of Woolf Associates (now the Green
Bay Packers' contract negotiator) to go to Master P, and signed an
awful contract. This is certainly one of the reasons Brandt and
Patriots negotiator Jack Mula left the agent business; it's getting
dirtier and dirtier, according to industry sources. Agents are able
to steal clients because the NFL agent-player contract is one of
the weakest in sports. Some of the bigger firms have been signing
players to big-time marketing deals, which tend to be more binding.
Boston-based Brad Blank says that some of his more established
clients are solicited ``three or four times a month'' by other
agents. But after making such a switch, most players find that the
grass isn't greener. Agents do get together twice a year, but so
far they are not policing themselves . . . Brandt had a deal with
Sam Adams the night before the draft, but the next morning, Adams
reneged and signed with Baltimore. That's when Brandt flew to Los
Angeles and signed Russell Maryland to a two-year, $3.5 million
deal with a $1.75 million bonus. He got it done in one day . . .
Weis chuckled at a report that he had already scripted 15 plays for
Michael Bishop. ``If you run across a copy of those plays, I'd like
to see them,'' said Weis . . . The Patriots are putting new deals
for Drew Bledsoe and Glenn on the back burner. They are the team's
two best offensive players, and they can't be completely happy
about this. Say this about Glenn: Perhaps he hasn't accomplished
what Marvin Harrison has for the Colts and what Keyshawn Johnson
did for the Jets, but Glenn is arguably more valuable to his team
because the Patriots don't have Edgerrin James or Curtis Martin.
Glenn is the show, and everybody knows it. Especially with Ben
Coates gone . . . Klemm played on Hawaii's 0-12 team in 1998. ``It
was real depressing,'' he said, ``but what I'll always remember is
the celebration last year when we won our first game.'' . . .
Speaking of Klemm, many thought he would go to St. Louis in the
first round, but the Rams passed. Then they traded with Chicago,
moved up 21 spots in the fourth round, and took Klemm's teammate,
tackle Kaulana Noa. Klemm was often overshadowed at Hawaii because
Noa got more publicity as a native Hawaiian . . . Is ``Carl Pickens
wants out of Cincinnati,'' the longest-running and most boring
drama in the NFL? Just get rid of the guy . . . North Andover's Rob
Konrad is being considered at various positions in the Dolphins'
training camp. He has been used at lone setback, fullback, and even
slot receiver.
</P>
</TEXT>
