<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-PATBRADLEY-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY NEARS SUNSET OF SHINING CAREER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   At the twilight of a most spectacular career, there is a sense
of fulfillment, and from where she sits, the view is quite
heartwarming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've made my history,'' said Pat Bradley, the pride of
Westford. ``More than I ever could have imagined when I was 11 and
got into this game.''
</P>
<P>
   The glorious run started in 1974, and a special highlight
remains that first win in 1976, an event called the Girl Talk
Classic, in which she defeated Judy Rankin, Bonnie Lauer, and
Sandra Post in a playoff. There would be 30 more LPGA Tour
victories, including at least one in each of the four major
championships _ the US Women's Open, the LPGA Championship, the
Nabisco Championship, and the du Maurier Classic _ and in 1991 the
hard-to-open doors of the LPGA Hall of Fame swung clear for her
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Really, my career is coming to an end,'' said Bradley.
``There's nothing very surprising about that. That's reality. It's
the cycle of competitive life and it's taking its turn with new
players.''
</P>
<P>
   No surprise, indeed, for Bradley turned 49 last month and since
that Hall-clinching 1991 campaign, in which she won four times,
there has been just one victory. The top 10 finishes, once a given,
have dwindled to just five in the last three years. Players who are
younger and stronger have come along to make things even harder for
Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   Still, there is a renewed passion as she tackles a full schedule
in 2000, a year she envisions as ``the crown jewel to my career.''
Bradley will captain the US Solheim Cup team in the women's
equivalent of the Ryder Cup.
</P>
<P>
   ``It means a great deal to me,'' said Bradley, who played on
three Solheim teams, including the debut edition in 1990. ``It's
kind of like our Olympics, our chance to represent our country.
It's a very special moment for me and for all of our players.''
</P>
<P>
   The Solheim Cup will be played at Loch Lomond in Luss, Scotland,
Oct. 6-8, with the teams determined by a points system.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rock of my team is no surprise,'' said Bradley. ``Juli
Inkster, Meg Mallon, Sherri Steinhauer, Dottie Pepper, and Kelly
Robbins _ it's a great nucleus of experience. But there are
up-and-coming stars like Kelli Kuehne (ninth in the standings) and
new Solheim faces like Nancy Scranton (seventh), and I look forward
to the mix.''
</P>
<P>
   Having returned last week from a promotional visit to Scotland,
Bradley had rave reviews for the Tom Weiskopf-designed Loch Lomond
(``It has a tremendous variety of holes'') and for the way the
event is being welcomed over there (``They'd love to do the Ryder
Cup, possibly in 2009, so we're kind of a steppingstone'').
</P>
<P>
   She also faced questions about a topic that will not fade: the
hard feelings stemming from last September's Ryder Cup at The
Country Club in Brookline. The infamous celebration at the 17th
green is very much a concern for both Bradley and European captain
Dale Reid.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to stifle competitive spirit or spontaneous
emotion,'' said Bradley, ``but we've got to make sure that we
channel them so that the rules of the game and the friendships that
we have worked hard over the years to secure are maintained.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did not take part in the 1998 Solheim Cup at Muirfield
Village in Dublin, Ohio, but she is aware that the competition got
intense and some Europeans took exception to the fiery antics of
some Americans, most notably Pepper. Bradley isn't worried.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dottie bleeds red, white, and blue,'' said Bradley. ``She's a
student of match play. Dottie knows what she can do and what she
can't do. Her spontaneous enthusiasm and competitive fire is what
every team would like to have. I'm just very happy she's on my
team. But I don't foresee that as a problem.''
</P>
<P>
   What could be a problem, said Bradley, is going through 2000
with ``one eye on my game and one eye on the others.'' But it's a
problem she gladly welcomes, and truth be told, she may not even
have one eye on her own game.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you are more concerned with the stock numbers than the
numbers on your own scorecard,'' she said, laughing, ``then things
have definitely changed for you.''
</P>
<P>
   So if this, her 27th year on Tour, is her finale (she said she
might play 10 events next year), then certainly she has been
blessed with a fitting farewell gift. It is something she never
could have envisioned back in the summer of '67, the Impossible
Dream season, when the Red Sox created magic daily. The 16-year-old
Bradley won the New Hampshire Amateur that summer, then repeated
two years later. She won New England Amateur titles in 1972-73,
then set off on a marvelous ride through professional golf.
</P>
<P>
   As the ride nears its end, it is one that should be applauded,
even by those who think golf begins and ends with the PGA Tour.
Ponder for a moment that, in 1986, Bradley won three majors and
finished fifth in the US Women's Open and you get an idea of the
quality of her play.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Circuit clout
</P>
<P>
   Brad Faxon has always been one of the more popular players on
the PGA Tour, a credit to his candor and willingness to give back
to the game. But he said he's become ``a lot more popular (with his
peers) since this event,'' a reference to the CVS Charity Classic,
which debuted in 1999 and will take the stage for a second time
July 9-11 at Rhode Island CC in Barrington. Although weekly pro-am
events are part of the routine for PGA Tour players, there aren't a
lot of chances to play in pro-pro best-ball events, a refreshing
change of pace. Faxon and Billy Andrade have modeled their event
after Peter Jacobsen's Fred Meyer Challenge, and they did such a
good job that their only problem this time was ``how to say no'' to
good friends and colleagues. ``But there were only 20 spots,'' said
Faxon. This time, they used the schedule to their advantage. For
instance, with the British Open July 20-23, some players _ such as
1999 CVS participants Stuart Appleby and Lee Janzen _ will head
over for some golf in Ireland as early as July 10, so they declined
invites. No problem, said Faxon. They went to Justin Leonard and
enticed him by saying how easy it would be to play in their event,
then fly out of Boston on the 11th or 12th for Scotland. Plus, he
would be paired with Davis Love. Leonard signed on. In fact, said
Faxon, the pairings are a selling point, as they were a year ago
when Jack Nicklaus played with his son Gary. This year, Greg Norman
was on the fence until Steve Elkington _ his pal from Australia _
came aboard. Now they can practice for this fall's President's Cup
competition. Jeff Sluman, who teamed with Appleby to win last
year's event, liked the idea of having Hal Sutton as a partner (who
wouldn't?), so two more were locked up. Then there is John Daly,
who can be either a crowd delight or a sponsor's nightmare. But in
recent events, Daly has shown a commitment to hard work and
rediscovering a game that is well worth the price of admission . .
. Tiger Woods, Karrie Webb, and Chad Campbell have streaked into
view with impressive play early in 2000. Chad Campbell? Indeed, as
in the Hooters Tour's Chad Campbell, winner of three straight.
``Everything's kind of falling into place right now,'' said the
Texan, who has not exactly captured the golf world's fancy quite
like Woods (six straight wins) or Webb (four). But the 25-year-old
understands where he is _ or where he isn't: ``It'd be nice to be
playing the PGA Tour or BUY.com tournaments, but it really doesn't
seem like I'm in a position to do that.'' . . . Some readers
inquired as to the whereabouts of former Senior PGA Tour staples
Larry Laoretti and Gay Brewer. You rarely see their names these
days because they have fallen out of the top 70 for career money
among Seniors. Brewer turned 68 last month. Laoretti, 60, will
probably tee it up only in the US Senior Open, which he won in
1992.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Controversial driver
</P>
<P>
   Quite a dilemma seems to be taking shape as the USGA and the
Royal and Ancient see things a bit differently regarding ``hot''
drivers. At the center of the controversy is Callaway's ERC, a
thin-faced driver that has been rejected by the USGA because of its
``springlike effect.'' The R&AMP;A wants to take its time before
deciding whether to follow the USGA, which brings up this
possibility: Colin Montgomerie may have the ERC in his bag at the
British Open in July but not at the PGA Championship in August.
Funny that Montgomerie would be involved in a controversy over a
driver, since that is the one aspect of his game that is never a
worry. The man could split a fairway with a shovel. Now, if he
could only fix his putting . . . The European Tour finally lands in
Europe with a rather important event (the Spanish Open), and where
are marquee names Darren Clarke and Lee Westwood? In Togo, Japan,
of course, playing amid all those Ozakis in the Chunichi Crowns . .
. His caddie is on his honeymoon, so Montgomerie borrowed Peter
Coleman from the vacationing Bernhard Langer for the Spanish Open.
``Bernhard and I have the same game _ I just play it quicker,''
said Montgomerie . . . The New England PGA announced its slate of
major award winners this week, and they included Paul Parajeckas of
Woburn CC as PGA Professional of the Year and Sue Kaffenburgh of
Hyannis GC as Teacher of the Year. Other winners: Wayne Natti of
Bethlehem CC in New Hampshire, Junior Golf Leader Award; Don Lyons
of George Wright GC in Hyde Park, Bill Strausbaugh Club Relations
Award; Bill Safrin of Myopia Hunt Club, Horton Smith Award for
Education; Tom Murphy of Burlington, George S. Wemyss Award for
exemplary promoter of golf in New England; and merchandisers of the
year to Mike Medeiros of Nashawtuc CC in Concord (private), Leigh
Bader of Pine Oaks in Easton (public), and Toby Ahern of Ferncroft
(resorts).
</P>
</TEXT>
