<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-ROSENBLATT-CRAWFORD-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ROSENBLATT LEFT TO PONDER IFS AND BUTTS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOE BURRIS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MASHANTUCKET PEQUOT RESERVATION _ It's the boxing equivalent of
a baseball rainout. You train and prepare, and then misfortune
strikes and the event is over.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, when a boxing match is stopped because of an
accidental head butt, one wonders what might have been done to
prevent it.
</P>
<P>
   Surely Dana Rosenblatt wondered this Friday night, after his
10-round middleweight bout with Jimmy Crawford was stopped with 45
seconds left in the second when the two butted heads and blood
began squirting from Rosenblatt's forehead.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, the Malden, Mass., middleweight spoke about the cuts
suffered in his last six fights, all of which led to trips to the
hospital. He and manager Joe Lake spoke about Lake's warning to him
between rounds about stepping into Crawford head-first.
</P>
<P>
   Rosenblatt also talked about the months of training that went to
waste. Not to mention the plans for a possible summer bout against
Tony Ayala on HBO that were put on hold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know, maybe it's me,'' said Rosenblatt, whose record
is now 36-1-1. ``I'm not sure. Maybe I'm bending in or leaning
forward, I don't know. It happens all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   Crawford, whose previous fight also was stopped after an
accidental head butt, is now 32-2-2.
</P>
<P>
   ``Once I saw the squirt of blood, I knew it was going to be
bad,'' said Rosenblatt.
</P>
<P>
   Each fighter felt he was beginning to assert himself when the
butt occurred. Rosenblatt's plan was to begin with the jab, then go
to the body, and he was doing just that, particularly in the second
round. Crawford, meanwhile, was countering the assault, trying to
catch Rosenblatt coming in with shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hit him with some shots early and he felt them,'' said
Rosenblatt.
</P>
<P>
   The capacity crowd booed when the stoppage was announced, but
clearly Rosenblatt could not have continued.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're seeing the tissue below the skin level,'' said Michael
Schwartz, the ringside physician. ``It was an extremely deep cut.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have never stopped all night. They wouldn't have
been able to close that and the blood in the eyes would have gone
all night and in addition that cut could have become deeper. Then
you get into danger and worried about it being closed effectively
and infection and things like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Both fighters said they would welcome a rematch, but Lake wasn't
so quick to call for one. If HBO officials still want Rosenblatt
for the Ayala fight in the summer, said Lake, he doubts there will
be another bout with Crawford soon.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll have to see what the HBO people say before we come back
here,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Lake also voiced concern about his fighter's propensity for
getting cut in the ring.
</P>
<P>
   Asked at what point it becomes a major issue, Lake said, ``It's
a major issue now.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
