u s BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT &LR;      04-29 0805
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-METS-ROCKIES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PIAZZA SITS AS THE METS PICK UP 23 HITS
</HEADLINE>
  By TYLER KEPNER   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   DENVER _ Mike Piazza was encouraged when he woke up Saturday
morning. He was still injured _ the Mets' cleanup hitter would not
be swinging a bat Saturday _ but Piazza's elbow and wrist felt
better a day after they were battered in a home-plate collision. He
will not need long to recover.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza expects to miss only a few games, meaning he could be
back during the Mets' next series, a four-game visit to Pacific
Bell Park, the new home of the San Francisco Giants. But this is
the Mets' only visit this season to Coors Field, and what a place
for a great hitter to miss.
</P>
<P>
   Piazza, who has hit better than .400 here, could only watch
Saturday as his teammates enjoyed a historic offensive day. The
Mets pounded out 23 hits _ not one of them a homer _ to tie a
26-year-old club record for hits in a nine-inning game. Todd Pratt
and Edgardo Alfonzo had four apiece as the Mets punished the
Colorado Rockies, 13-6.
</P>
<P>
   For Pratt, who is catching in Piazza's place, the four-hit game
was the first in his eight-year career, and it was a fitting way to
begin his latest extended playing stint.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I'm going to play a couple of games in a row and Mike's
going to be out, I take a little bit of pressure off myself because
I know I'm going to be out there tomorrow,'' Pratt said. ``I think
that carried into today's game.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt saw Piazza before the game, and Piazza was upbeat, his
spirits high. It was a different reaction, Pratt noticed, than
Piazza had last April, when his sprained knee worsened the day
after it occurred and forced Piazza onto the disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   ``It feels a lot better than last night,'' Piazza said. ``I feel
it's going to heal quickly. I'm just fortunate it was nothing
major. Minor injuries occur all the time at this position.''
</P>
<P>
   That's why the Mets have Pratt, who played well in Piazza's
absence early last season and in the division series against
Arizona, when he hit the clinching home run in Game 4. He played
down his role in Saturday's victory.
</P>
<P>
   ``Mine's going to just be a three- or four-game stint,'' Pratt
said. ``I'm happy for the guys that are in there every day that we
need to get hot.''
</P>
<P>
   Pratt was referring to Alfonzo, who pulled his average above
.300 for the first time since the season-opening series in Japan,
and Todd Zeile, who had three hits. Derek Bell also contributed
three hits, and Rickey Henderson, Jay Payton and Rey Ordonez had
two apiece. Every Met in the starting lineup, in fact, had a hit by
the fifth inning.
</P>
<P>
   The former Met Masato Yoshii suffered much of the damage,
allowing six runs on nine hits.
</P>
<P>
   Yoshii, who was traded by the Mets in January, lasted only three
and two-thirds innings, and his outing provoked the same kind of
reaction the Mets' Mike Hampton had on Friday night. Then, Hampton
surrendered six runs in an inning and took out his frustrations
with a right hook to the dugout sports-drink cooler. After leaving
in the middle of a six-run inning Saturday, Yoshii pounded
furiously on the coolers in the home dugout.
</P>
<P>
   His anger was understandable. Larry Walker had given the Rockies
a two-run lead with a home run off Rick Reed in the first inning,
and Yoshii gave it away in the second, when three Mets hits tied
the score, 2-2. The six-run fourth, highlighted by a run-scoring
triple by Payton, put the Mets ahead for good.
</P>
<P>
   Payton's triple scored Zeile, and five more runs would scamper
home off Yoshii and reliever Rick Croushore, the last two on
Zeile's second single of the inning.
</P>
<P>
   Payton had gotten two hits Friday, matching his total in 23
at-bats during the Mets' recent homestand. Saturday morning,
however, Payton was still thinking about the double play he had
grounded into with the bases loaded in that game, and he studied
video of himself on a hand-held monitor.
</P>
<P>
   Besides the triple, Payton singled and lined sharply to second
on a ball that was dropped for an error. He now has consecutive
multihit games for the first time this season.
</P>
<P>
   The Mets built a lead of 12-2 in the sixth inning, after Pratt
doubled home Payton, and that was more than enough for Reed, who
improved to 3-0. Pitching for the first time in 10 days after
missing a start with a bruised left hand, Reed worked seven
innings, allowing six runs, all earned, on 10 hits.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you give up six runs here,'' Reed said, ``it's like giving
up three runs anywhere else.''
</P>
<P>
   Reed said his hand was sore from hitting; the pain was most
acute when he swung and missed in the sixth inning, and he said he
probably should not have even tried to swing. But Reed had no plays
in the field, Pratt lobbed his throws back to him, and Reed is not
concerned about making his next scheduled start.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2209EDT &QL; 
