<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-GREECE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHENS IN TROUBLE; ORGANIZERS IN DENIAL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   More troubling than Athens's tragicomic disorganization only
four years before the 2004 Summer Olympics is the Fantasyland
denial by both organizers and the government that there's even a
problem. ``There is no cause for concern,'' the Culture Ministry
insisted after International Olympic Committee president Juan
Antonio Samaranch warned recently that the Games could be taken
away if the Greeks don't make ``drastic changes'' by year's end.
</P>
<P>
   The Lords have never yanked the Olympics from a host city, and
it's unlikely they could find an alternate site on such short
notice. But after watching the organizers dawdle for three years,
Samaranch felt compelled to sound a 1,000-decibel warning.
</P>
<P>
   Athens is months behind in virtually every area of the checklist
_ construction, venues, infrastructure, communications, security,
traffic, and accommodations. It's not just foot-dragging, the IOC
says. It's cluelessness.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our partners do not understand what the Games are,'' says
Jacques Rogge, who heads the IOC's oversight commission.
</P>
<P>
   What the Lords are hoping is that the global embarrassment will
shock the Greek government into taking over and getting
preparations on the fast track. ``It is circulating internationally
that we are a laughingstock,'' groaned the daily newspaper Ta Nea.
Who's cackling loudest? The Romans, who lost the bid to Athens.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Getting in synch
</P>
<P>
   If some noses in the US Olympic family are already out of joint
over the USOC's new corporate emphasis, wait until CEO Norman Blake
starts streamlining the sports governing bodies to get them in line
with their international federations. That would mean one
organization for figure skating and speedskating and one for
swimming, synchronized swimming, diving, and water polo. That may
make flow-chart sense, but it's a political minefield. As it is,
the US skeleton folks want to split from the bobsled people after
the 2002 Winter Games for the usual divorce reasons: irreconcilable
differences . . . Even if Toronto lands the 2008 Summer Games
(which will be awarded next year), the US still will bid for 2012,
even though there's zero chance that the IOC will choose
consecutive North American sites. Since eight cities (New York, Los
Angeles, San Francisco, Dallas, Houston, Tampa, Cincinnati, and
Washington/Baltimore) are already spending money, the USOC feels
compelled to stay the course . . . Tough sell this year to convince
off-duty NHLers to play in the men's world ice hockey
championships, which began this weekend in St. Petersburg, Russia.
The international federation thought it could get more of them to
play by pushing the date three weeks past the end of the regular
season. By now, though, anybody not involved in the playoffs is on
the golf course. And few of them wanted to spend two weeks in
Russia anyway. That's a boost for the Motherland, which hasn't won
the title since 1993 and has been off the award stand for six
years. Dim medal chance for the US, which was sixth last year and
has only 13 NHLers (including Bruins Steve Heinze and Hal Gill) on
the 23-man roster. But with the Swiss and French in their group,
the Yanks at least should make it out of the prelims . . . Home
cookin' could help the US women's ice hockey team break its
six-year run of silver medals behind Canada next year, when the
world championships will be held in Minneapolis. Though the Yanks
won the inaugural Olympic title at Nagano, they've never gone gold
at the global tournament.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Running scared
</P>
<P>
   USA Track and Field types are crossing their fingers and hoping
that the ``right'' person wins the Olympic men's marathon trials in
Pittsburgh a week from Sunday. If the victor hasn't met the A
standard of 2:14 (and only David Morris and Joe LeMay have), the
Americans will get to send only one entrant to the Games for the
first time in history. That's what happened to the women, when
unknown Christine Clark ran (slowly) to daylight in the South
Carolina heat. With Morocco's Khalid Khannouchi, the world
record-holder, unlikely to get citizenship clearance (plus the
signoff from his native country) in time, the odds are more than
decent that the ``wrong'' guy could break the tape . . . Terrific
performance by the US gymnasts at the recent Pacific Alliance meet
in New Zealand. The women, in their first competition since Bela
Karolyi took over as team coordinator, took the title ahead of the
Chinese and Australians, with Elise Ray winning the all-around and
Morgan White sharing third. The men were less than 15 hundredths of
a point behind the world champion Chinese, with Blaine Wilson
winning the all-around . . . It's lucky-loser heaven for the US
boxers. First, lightweight David Jackson got a ticket to the
Olympics after Marshall Martinez quit for personal reasons. Now,
light heavy Olanda Anderson gets one because world champ Michael
Simms Jr. was kicked off the squad for attitude-related issues,
including tardiness, blowing off practice, and missing curfews.
It's the first time that two boxers ended up off the team. The good
news for the beleaguered Yanks, though, is that all 12 survived the
regional qualifiers for the Games . . . The US baseball team that
will face Chinese Taipei in Pawtucket, R.I., in August isn't the
team that will be going to Sydney. It's the usual collection of
college all-stars who barnstorm every summer. The Olympians, who'll
all be minor leaguers from 40-man rosters, won't even be chosen
until Aug. 25 and won't play together until they get to Brisbane,
where they'll train for two weeks before they meet Japan, the
defending silver medalists, in their opener. Former Yankee GM Bob
Watson and former Angels GM Bill Bavasi will co-chair the selection
committee.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Taking flight
</P>
<P>
   Dizzy schedule upcoming for the US Olympic women's soccer team.
After this week's US Cup in Portland, Ore., they head Down Under
for the Pacific Cup in Australia in early June, then back for the
CONCACAF Gold Cup (playing at least once at Foxboro Stadium). Then,
they travel overseas for July tournaments in Germany and Norway,
and back to the States for an exhibition series before leaving for
Sydney. Along the way (probably on May 7 in the US Cup final),
ironwoman midfielder Kristine Lilly will become the first player,
male or female, to earn 200 international caps. The 28-year-old
Lilly, who has played all 90 minutes in 191 of her 198 matches, has
performed against 34 countries. Even so, her mark may not last
long. Teammate Mia Hamm is only 11 matches behind her . . . The US
Olympic women's basketball team, which is done until midsummer,
went 29-2 on its seven-month exhibition odyssey (losing only to
Tennessee and Brazil) and was 11-1 against national teams. The
squad, which still has one player to add, will reconvene after the
WNBA season ends in August and play nine exhibition games on the
way to Sydney . . . After winning only three medals in Atlanta
(none gold), the US Cycling people have abandoned a one-shot
selection for Sydney. Though some team members will come out of
last week's track trials in Texas, most will be chosen in July by
coaches who'll consider reputation, rankings, and recent
performance . . . Why were next month's US Olympic dressage trials
moved from New Jersey to Florida? Because the West Nile horse virus
is still lingering around the Northeast and the US Equestrian Team
is worried that European countries will nix their plans to hold
their final trials overseas during the summer . . . Speedo's new
$300 ``sharksuit,'' which covers the body from neck to ankles, is
causing ripples in the swimming world. The Fastskin suit is legal,
says the international federation, since it has no ``devices'' like
flippers or fins to make swimmers go faster. And Speedo says it'll
make it available to all comers. The sharksuit, which cuts down on
water drag, could do for swimming what the clap skate has done for
speedskating . . . NBA center Vlade Divac and Algerian distance
runner Noureddine Morceli are the most prominent names among the 44
candidates for the eight athletes' spots on the reformed IOC. Also
running is former US volleyball player Bob Ctvrtlik, who was
appointed last year but whose term expires this summer. They'll be
elected by the athletes at the Sydney Games . . . The US Olympic
team will use San Diego's old naval training center as a processing
place for Sydney. With a traveling party of 1,000 (including 600
athletes), the USOC needs a site that has enough space to issue
team gear, take team photos, and do medical checkups. ``We don't
always win the most medals,'' says Greg Harney, the USOC's Games
prep wizard, ``but we have the most baggage.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
