<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBANOTES-EUROPE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG MAN ON CONTINENT IS CLASS OF EUROPEAN DRAFT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chris Wallace, the Celtics' general manager, is barnstorming
through Europe, and this week he will lay eyes on the one player
Over There who is making a case for himself as a lottery pick in
June.
</P>
<P>
   His name is Iakovos Tsakalidis, and he will become a household
name in more than the city of Athens (where he plays) and the
country of Georgia (where he was born) before long. He's 7 feet 2
inches, weighs around 220 pounds, and is either 20 or 22, depending
on whom you talk to.
</P>
<P>
   Wallace will see him Wednesday night in Greece, and he's looking
forward to it. Tsakalidis is projected to be a late lottery pick,
and the Celtics, who are short up front, likely will have a late
lottery pick.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a legitimate lottery talent,'' said Wallace, who has seen
the kid on tape and heard about him through the grapevine.
``There's always a scarcity of big men. But the big question with
him, as with a lot of these guys, is the contract. To quote Stan
Kasten, `International is synonymous with trouble.' He's clearly
lottery material. We'll see what happens when you start peeling
back the pages of the contract.''
</P>
<P>
   A Greek spy reports that Tsakalidis's contract with AEK Athens
expires in 2003 and the team would be disinclined to let him go for
the 2000-01 NBA season. But NBA teams have been known to wait for
Eurotalent; the Bulls waited three years for Toni Kukoc, and
Portland waited nine years for Arvydas Sabonis. Denver is still
waiting for 1996 first-rounder Efthimios Rentzias.
</P>
<P>
   Tsakalidis (also known as Tsakalov in some circles because of
his birthplace) has been tutored overseas by Dusan Ivkovic, who
also worked extensively with Vlade Divac, Kukoc, and the late
Drazen Petrovic. This season, Tsakalidis averaged 9.4 points and
7.2 rebounds while leading his team to the Saporta Cup title. If
his age is determined to be 20, he must apply for the NBA draft;
the deadline for that is May 14.
</P>
<P>
   But Tsakalidis is not alone in whetting the appetites of NBA
talent spotters in Europe. As many as four others could be drafted
in the first round, along with Zeljko Rebraca, probably the best
overall player in Europe, whose rights belong to the Raptors. He's
playing for Panathinaikos.
</P>
<P>
   As Wallace said, ``There's something over there this year.''
</P>
<P>
   Players who, depending on whether they enter the draft, could
warrant first-round status include:
</P>
<P>
   --Josip Sesar, a 6-5 shooting guard from Bosnia-Herzegovina who
played last year in Croatia.
</P>
<P>
   --Olumide Oyededji, a 6-9 native of Nigeria who played for Dirk
Nowitzki's old team in Germany. He was not only named MVP of the
German All-Star Game, he also won the Slam Dunk title. Now 19, he
made an appearance at the Chicago predraft camp last year.
</P>
<P>
   --Marco Jaric, a 6-6 shooting guard who played in Italy.
</P>
<P>
   --Hidayet Turkoglou, a 6-8 swingman who is under a nine-year
deal with Efes Pilsen in Turkey.
</P>
<P>
   You may hear other Europeans announce for the draft, but in many
cases, it is the work of their agents. If the lads go undrafted,
they become free agents, giving them more leverage.
</P>
<P>
   European players may also become more NBA-friendly next season,
when the league moves to make the European game faster by using a
24-second clock and allowing teams to have eight seconds to get the
ball over halfcourt. That will enable many of the teenagers now in
the pipeline to be better acquainted with the NBA game when they
reach draftable age.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   A Net loss
</P>
<P>
   Don Casey saw it coming, knew it was coming, and, well, still
feels it could have waited. But after breakfast last week with
friend and Nets owner Lewis Katz, Casey was told he would not be
back to coach the Nets. New Jersey had until May 10 to move on
Casey's option year, but it was a foregone conclusion he'd be a
goner. Still, he wonders whether anyone else could have done any
more than he did with what he had. ``If you look at the bottom
line, it could fool you one way or another,'' Casey said. ``The
bottom line was not that bad. The problems were the beginning, at
2-15, and the end, when we lost three starters. Everybody forgets
the middle. Everybody points to all the close losses. What did they
want? Would they rather we'd have lost by 20? Getting in position
to win is one thing. Winning is another.'' Casey has been around
long enough to know the drill. The Nets want buzz. They need
someone they can market, even though the Celtics have shown good
coaches can be marketed for only so long. The Nets are locked in
with four huge contracts (Jayson Williams, Keith Van Horn, Stephon
Marbury, and Kerry Kittles). If all the players were healthy, New
Jersey could have a decent team. Casey never had Williams, had a
subpar Kittles most of the year, and spent a good part of the
season trying to get Marbury and Van Horn to work together. The
news that Casey was not coming back was out and about well before
Katz delivered it in person. ``I was hoping that maybe they were
mulling it over and saying, `Let's see what they can do with
everyone back,' '' Casey said. ``But I guess they felt they had us
for one year. And they waited for Passover and Easter to be over.''
Maybe he should have put lamb's blood over his door . . . Casey,
who has been given a three-year gig with Katz's foundation, is
represented by Lonnie Cooper, the Atlanta-based agent who handles
many NBA coaches, including Lenny Wilkens. Cooper said Wilkens will
have ``the option'' of working next season, although it would seem
Washington would not be a good fit for him. (Can you imagine
Wilkens and Rod Strickland?) Wilkens will be 63 when next season
starts and, despite being the winningest coach of all time, has a
rather spotty record where it counts: in the playoffs. He was 17-30
in six playoff appearances with the Hawks and, in seven years in
Cleveland, he managed to win exactly one best-of-seven series
(against the Celtics in 1992). Cooper said he anticipated as many
as eight jobs opening up this summer. As of now, the list includes
Atlanta, New Jersey, Washington, Dallas (although Don Nelson may
stick around), and Indiana. There also could be vacancies in
Detroit, Los Angeles (Clippers), and Vancouver. Throw in Denver
(new ownership) and some team that fails in the playoffs, and you
could have as many as 10 openings . . . One of the rites at Madison
Square Garden this time of year is for John Starks to show up at a
playoff game and have his face shown on the Jumbotron, evoking
cheers from the fans. The same thing happened when the Knicks
hosted Toronto. Starks, a free agent now, said he would love to
return and play in New York. He'll be 35 in August . . . Throwing
out last year's playoff seedings (six games separated teams 1-8),
the Pacers' loss to Milwaukee Thursday night represented only the
third time a No. 1 seed in the East has lost in the first round at
home since 1984. The other two occasions were in 1994, when Atlanta
lost to Miami, and 1995, when Orlando lost to the Celtics. In both
cases, the No. 1 seed rallied to win. The Pacers went into Game 3
against the Bucks with an 18-0 record against teams that had beaten
them in their previous meeting . . . Antoine Walker and Kenny
Anderson were among 27 players who started all 82 games this
season. The Celtics were one of six teams that had two or more
players go wire to wire, led by Vancouver, which had four. (Can you
imagine what would have happened to the Grizzlies had they had any
injury problems?) Eleven teams had no one start 82 games. The Iron
Man of the Year award, however, goes to Chris Gatling. He appeared
in 85 games with Orlando and Denver. The record for games played in
a season is 88, held by Walt Bellamy during the 1968-69 season,
when he spent time with the Knicks and Pistons . . . In case you
missed it, the Celtics lost a coin flip with Denver and will get
the 11th pick in the draft if they don't win the lottery. Both
teams have nine chances out of 1,000 to move into the top three of
the lottery, which will be held May 21 . . . Eddie Jones was asked
by the Charlotte Observer to name the five hardest players to
defend. His first two were Michael Jordan and Allen Iverson. Among
the other three was Paul Pierce. ``I like that kid,'' Jones said.
``He's going to be a player.''
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Bird: bad Pacing
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird thought his team had what it took to win it all two
years ago. He may have thought so last year as well. This year?
Well, it was clear Bird had concerns even before the playoffs
started. Indiana barely squeaked out a win in Game 1 and was
bludgeoned in Game 2 by the Bucks. One thing Bird despises: getting
embarrassed at home. ``I hate it,'' he said. ``I remember when we
would lose at the Garden, I hated the feeling of walking out of
that building. As a player, that's the worst thing that ever
happened to me.'' He also said he thought practice was a good
barometer for a team in the postseason and complained about
listless workouts prior to the Game 2 debacle. ``If they don't
practice well, they don't play well,'' he said. As for Rik Smits,
who is pondering retirement, Bird said, ``I don't talk to Rik about
his injuries. Every time I ask him, he tells me that something's
wrong. So I stopped asking him. The last time I asked him was two
years ago.'' . . . Here's a name to put in your Down The Road
folder: Nate Huffman. He's a 7-1, 215-pound center who spent the
last year playing for Maccabi Tel-Aviv and already is drawing
interest from NBA people in much the same way John Amaechi did.
Huffman played two years for Central Michigan and another year with
the CBA Idaho Stampede. He's been overseas the last two years and
has developed a serviceable game around the basket, especially on
offense. In the just-concluded European Final Four, won by Dino
Radja's old team, Panathinaikos, Huffman averaged 25 points, 7.5
rebounds, and 2 blocks. He reportedly has an option in his deal
with Maccabi to leave for the NBA and has as a tattoo of the NBA
logo on his right arm . . . If Walker is cyber-savvy, he ought to
go to ESPN.com and click on an article by Mike Monroe of the Denver
Post. Monroe talked to Karl Malone about the Mailman's offseason
conditioning program, and the words resonate here. ``You don't
become an All-Star or a great player when the season starts,''
Malone said. ``You just maintain then. All your work is done in the
summer.'' Malone often has criticized up-and-comers for not
preparing properly for play. His summer conditioning program is
legendary. ``You are made into a great player in the summertime,
when it's not so easy to work,'' he said. ``(Non-playoff teams)
have five months off. Well, it's kind of easy to take that first
month off. Then it's, `Aw shoot, I'll take another month off.' Then
it's another two weeks . . . In the summertime, it's easy to get in
your nice Benz, fly here and fly there with five or six of your
buddies. But how many of those buddies are going to say, `Hey,
let's train. Let's get in the weight room'? They don't. They're
saying, `Let's hang out here, let's hang out there.' . . . You've
got a lot of money, a lot of nice, material things. But a lot of
people you hang out with are not going to tell you the stuff you
really need to hear.'' Concludes Malone, ``Commitment is in the
summer, when no one wakes you up, no one sets your alarm clock, no
one gives you an itinerary. You just do it yourself.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
