<SLUG> BC-BBA-REDSOX-INDIANS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SOX GET LOST IN THE SUN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Indians3Red Sox2
</P>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ If it's not raindrops, it's sunspots. And just as
umbrellas were useless to the Red Sox with the Cleveland Indians in
town for last weekend's three-game washout, sunglasses were of no
help to right fielder Darren Lewis here Saturday afternoon under a
high sky in Jacobs Field.
</P>
<P>
   And if the Sox hope to avoid a three-game sweep by the Indians
this weekend, it may take more than sending Pedro Martinez to the
mound this afternoon. They might want to call on weatherman Bruce
Schwoegler for some advice on how to cope with the elements.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox dropped their second straight one-run game to the
Indians Saturday, a taut 3-2 decision that turned on Lewis's
inability to catch Jacob Cruz's fly ball in the fifth inning. Lewis
was charged with an error on the play, but for as much chance as he
had of seeing the ball, Lewis might as well have been wearing a
blindfold.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it when it went up,'' Lewis said. ``It was one of those
that went up in the sun and kind of came straight down in it. I did
everything you're supposed to do to get the ball out of the sun.''
</P>
<P>
   Lewis flipped down his shades. He held his glove high overhead,
trying to shield the sun. He ducked his head, hoping to catch a
glimpse of white on white.
</P>
<P>
   ``I do know,'' said manager Jimy Williams, ``having seen a lot
of day games, that when you see the reflection of the sun on the
glasses, you know it's a tough play.''
</P>
<P>
   It should have been the easiest of plays. Cruz's fly ball was
nothing like Richie Sexson's line single to right or the double
scorched into the left-field corner by Einar Diaz, the two hits
given up by Sox starter Ramon Martinez just before Cruz came to the
plate. Cruz, playing because Kenny Lofton has a strained biceps,
hit a fly ball to medium right field, just a few steps to Lewis's
right.
</P>
<P>
   Lewis looked up. He searched the sky in vain until it was too
late. The ball dropped just behind him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I saw it right at the last second,'' he said. ``But I couldn't
get close enough to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, the center fielder, was close enough to make a
play, and he had a view of the ball.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't call him off,'' Everett said, ``because I thought he
had it. I wasn't sure, and when you're not sure, you don't do
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   While the ball enjoyed its freefall, Sexson scored and Diaz took
third, from where he scored on Omar Vizquel's sacrifice fly to make
it 3-1. Cruz was credited with a sacrifice on his fly ball, too,
and Lewis was saddled with an error by an unsympathetic scorer.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Everett) said he could have caught it,'' Lewis said, ``but
that was one of those in-between plays where you don't have a lot
of time to have a conversation.''
</P>
<P>
   Those runs became the difference when the Sox, who had taken a
1-0 lead on Mike Stanley's home run off Chuck Finley to start the
second inning, scored again in the eighth when Wilton Veras
doubled, took third on Lewis's single, and came home when Jose
Offerman grounded into a force play.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox still had two on and two out when Cruz flagged down
Stanley's deep drive at the wall, crashing awkwardly into the wall.
Earlier, Cruz took away extra bases from Nomar Garciaparra in the
sixth with a lunging catch after making a long run. Garciaparra's
14-game hitting streak expired when he walked in the eighth,
leaving him 0 for 3 on the afternoon.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox, who had seven hits in Friday's 4-3 loss to the Indians,
had just five Saturday, their bats going quiet after last
Wednesday's 21-hit salute in Texas. Leadoff man Offerman remains
buried in his slump, which is now 4 for 34 after an 0 for 3
Saturday. Utility infielder Manny Alexander, Williams's startling
choice to DH against Finley, struck out twice and failed to get the
ball out of the infield in four at-bats.
</P>
<P>
   And the Indians' outfield played good defense for the second
straight game, Cruz's two catches coming in the aftermath of David
Justice's big play the night before on Troy O'Leary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel bad about it,'' Lewis said. ``But what are you going to
do? Plays like that are part of baseball.
</P>
<P>
   ``We had opportunities to win, but they made good plays on the
warning track, and we have two one-run losses.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians are paying Finley $27 million to give them a better
shot against the iron of the AL East, the Sox and Yankees. The
37-year-old lefthander, who is now 3-0 and leads the AL in
strikeouts at least until Martinez makes up a 2-K difference (42 to
40) this afternoon, is now 28-18 lifetime against the Sox and
Bombers.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finley didn't beat us,'' said Everett, who had an infield hit
in four trips and struck out twice, the second time against
reliever Steve Karsay, who has saved each of the last two games.
``I won't give him any credit for that.
</P>
<P>
   ``His pitching didn't beat us. We lost the game in the field,
not because of good pitching.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
