u s BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS     04-29 0933
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBA-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INDIANS ARE SAFER WITH FINLEY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.2000 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ They are the four richest families in the
neighborhood known as the American League. They reside in an
exclusive baseball cul-de-sac, and spend most of their time
figuring out how they can be better than each other.
</P>
<P>
   The Yankees and Indians are old-money residents. They've been in
the wealthy 'hood since '95, playoff participants for five
consecutive seasons. The Red Sox and Rangers are the nouveau riche.
They have three postseason appearances since '95. Any other folks
who sneak into the gated playoff community (the Orioles and
Mariners have done it twice) are tagged with a ``Just Visiting''
label.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday at Jacobs Field, more than 42,000 people got a chance
to see how the AL rich live. No way was this just another game
between the Indians and Sox. These were two nosy neighbors
investigating each other, trying to peer over the fence to see if
one had reason to be jealous of the other.
</P>
<P>
   The last two games _ both Cleveland wins _ were the first since
last fall in which the Indians have seen the Sox with Carl Everett.
This was also the first the Sox have seen of Chuck Finley as an
Indian.
</P>
<P>
   There is no way I would trade the 28-year-old Everett for the
37-year-old Finley. But who could blame the Sox for also wanting
what the Indians have? The Sox' want is certainly not one of
excess; they certainly could use a lefthander whose career epitaph
will read: He Always Handled The Yankees (16-9 in his career).
</P>
<P>
   ``People are always going to give you a label,'' Finley said
after his 7 2/3-inning, seven-strikeout performance Saturday.
``It's better to have that label than for someone to say, `He Can't
Do It.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Couple Finley's work with Saturday's 3-2 Indians win and what
you have is a neighborhood power statement. We can all fool
ourselves if we want and pretend that the White Sox can win the AL
Central. We can worry about the Blue Jays and Orioles in the East.
We can continue to say nice things about the A's and Angels. But
when October arrives, don't expect the neighborhood to change too
much. If the Sox return to the playoffs, the Indians and Yankees
will be there with them.
</P>
<P>
   It is not too early to ask if the Sox are better-equipped to win
the pennant than they were last season. It is obvious that they are
better with Everett as the starting center fielder and Darren Lewis
as an outfield rover. But it's difficult to resist playing chess
with the Indians. They added Finley to a rotation of Bartolo Colon,
Jaret Wright, Charles Nagy, and Dave Burba. This is no longer a
Looks Good on Paper argument; if the Indians can do Sunday what
they never have done _ beat Pedro Martinez _ they will sweep the
series.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's only April. Yes, they have been one-run games that
could have been won by the Sox. No, a sweep would not cause the Sox
to panic. But I am sure the current Indians have inspired Boston GM
Dan Duquette to think about tinkering with his team.
</P>
<P>
   You remember the Indians from October, right? Does this look
like the same team? I don't think so. The biggest difference is
Finley. The pitcher is married to actress Tawny Kitaen, who said
she became intrigued when she first saw Finley's ankles (she says
they are the sexiest she's ever seen). Kitaen used to be married to
David Coverdale, the former lead singer of a Led Zeppelin ripoff
rock group named Whitesnake (how's that for subtle commentary?).
She has said it's no coincidence that the group fell apart when she
left Coverdale.
</P>
<P>
   The Indians, who haven't won a World Series since 1948, don't
care about Finley's ankles. They don't listen to Whitesnake. They
are in love with their new pitcher's left arm, and if other members
of the cul-de-sac are honest, they will tell you that they are hot
for Finley's arm, too. Last winter, the Sox, Yankees, and Orioles
all tried to sign the former Angel. Boston lost out, Finley said,
because he thinks the Indians have the best chance of winning.
</P>
<P>
   ``My heart and soul is with this team,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   While everyone in baseball knows Finley has had success against
the rich-boy Yankees, few know he also has dominated Nomar
Garciaparra in his career. Garciaparra, who had his 14-game hit
streak broken Saturday, is 1 for 14 vs. Finley. The pitcher was
asked if he knew about those numbers. He shook his head.
</P>
<P>
   ``No, I'm just having trouble remembering where I put my keys,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Across the room, teammate David Justice was saying that he has
always respected pitchers such as Martinez.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, he's like Sandy Koufax and Bob Gibson,'' Justice
said.
</P>
<P>
   He also threw in a playful dig at Kenny Lofton, who is not
expected to face Martinez Sunday.
</P>
<P>
   ``When Kenny gets over his Pedro-itis,'' Justice said, ``he'll
be back.''
</P>
<P>
   But Justice also respects pitchers such as Finley, guys who
aren't stars but who know how to pitch. ``Basically, pitchers who
have game,'' the outfielder explained. Finley has game. He joins a
few other Indians who have game, too.
</P>
<P>
   What does this mean for the Sox? Well, we know that they will
continue to live among the baseball elite. But when they look
outside their windows, they see three World Series flags flapping
outside the recent Yankee estate. They also see the Indians
surrounding the pinstriped home, trying to see how they can win a
flag of their own. If the Sox are swept in this series _ the
calendar be damned _ they will know that they need an upgrade or
two.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2214EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
