<HEADLINE>
WILL IT BE 10 FOR 10 AT NAPA 500?
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ There have been nine different winners in nine
NASCAR Winston Cup races this season.
</P>
<P>
   Will today's NAPA Auto Parts 500 at California Speedway produce
the 10th?
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd sure like to be the 10th,'' said Ontario, Calif., native
Mike Skinner, who will start from the pole in search of his first
Winston Cup victory. ``But it's tough. I think the guy (starting)
42nd, if he gets his setup right, is going to be the guy to beat.
</P>
<P>
   ``Track position is very, very important. But if a guy back
there in 35th place gets his car hooked up and you have a long
green-flag run, before long he's going to have track position
because he's faster then everybody else.''
</P>
<P>
   That's been the case in the three previous Winston Cup events at
California Speedway, which has seen Jeff Gordon produce runaway
victories in 1997 and 1999 and Mark Martin win in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Most wouldn't be surprised if the same scenario repeated itself
today.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's a possibility (again),'' said Ricky Rudd, who
starts third in his Texaco Ford Taurus. ``You want to sit here and
talk about how exciting it's gonna be and it very well may be the
greatest race we've ever seen here at California, but this type of
racetrack has that potential. If you hit a really good chassis
setup you can check up on the competition.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is what Gordon did when he beat teammate Terry Labonte in
the inaugural event in 1997 and repeated in finishing ahead of Jeff
Burton last year.
</P>
<P>
   ``If a guy gets going and gets his car balanced, then he'll run
away,'' said Tony Stewart, who starts a disappointing 32nd.
``That's just the characteristic of this kind of track. It's fast,
it's flat, and momentum is so important here. If a guy is off just
a little, he's off a lot.''
</P>
<P>
   That might give the edge to Skinner. The former Winston Cup
Rookie of the Year, who finished a career-best second at Talladega,
Ala., two weeks ago, was near the top of the practice results
before taking the pole with an 186.061-mph lap on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   ``The main thing is to get the car handling real well and the
rest of it takes care of itself,'' Skinner said. ``If you've got to
lift off the gas when you get behind a car coming off a corner, you
can't pass that car. You've got to be able to make a run at 'em,
make your move and go on. If you're pushing (moving up the race
track), you ain't going to make it.''
</P>
<P>
   And you are also not going to make it unless you can average 50
laps between pit stops, which Martin found out in 1997 when he was
forced to pit from the lead with 10 laps remaining in the 250-lap
race.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's what they keep telling me,'' said rookie Scott Pruett,
who starts sixth. ``You have to make it to 50 (laps) on fuel.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think it's just how fast the race goes and how many long
green-lap runs we have. You have to make the right amount of stops
to put you in those fuel windows to be able to cut (a stop) down,
rather then add one.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2221EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0232 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 22:23 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1377 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-CAR-EARNHARDT-FONTANA     04-29 0644
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAR-EARNHARDT-FONTANA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
`INTIMIDATOR' A CONTENDER AGAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By STEVE RAMIREZ  
 c.2000 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FONTANA, Calif. _ What comes around, goes around.
</P>
<P>
   Nobody in NASCAR Winston Cup understands that more then Dale
Earnhardt, who after nearly three subpar seasons in the late 1990s
appears to have recaptured his championship form.
</P>
<P>
   Since finishing a disappointing 21st at the season-opening
Daytona 500 in February, Earnhardt has one victory and seven top-10
finishes in eight races. He comes into today's NAPA Auto Parts 500
fourth in points.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a race team right now that every man on it, they're
pumped to win,'' said Earnhardt, who has his best chance at winning
a Winston Cup championship since 1995. ``They're coming to the race
track pumped to win. They're excited. You don't have to do
something exciting to excite them. They're ready to go.''
</P>
<P>
   Which is a far cry from where Earnhardt the `Intimidator' was
just a couple of seasons ago.
</P>
<P>
   After winning 70 races and seven Winston Cup championships
between 1979 and 1994, he dropped into the mainstream. Earnhardt,
who was recently voted ESPN Driver of the Decade, won just once in
97 races between March 1996 and February 1998, including going
winless in 1997.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know where I was at,'' Earnhardt said. ``Everybody
talked about me being gone or whatever. I've been (here). I just
kept working and the guys kept working and we didn't give up on
each other.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither did team owner Richard Childress, who realized early in
1999 that he hadn't provided Earnhardt with the best possible
equipment during those lean years. The former Winston Cup regular
rebuilt his two-team operation, adding aerodynamic specialist Louis
Duncan.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of the critics said it would never work because of the
personalities, you know, with me and Dale involved,'' Childress
said. ``It hasn't been nothing but positive. If anything, our
working relationship has been stronger. I think it makes mine and
his personal relationship stronger because we got a common thing
we're all working at.''
</P>
<P>
   But Earnhardt's slump wasn't just mechanical. His 49-year-old
body had taken its toll following three major crashes between 1996
and '98, including rolling his Monte Carlo at Talladega in 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Earnhardt addressed that issue by having surgery this past
December to repair a ruptured disc.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel better than I have in a long time after getting my neck
worked on back in December,'' said Earnhardt, who won three times
last year. ``It took a lot of strain and stress off me, so I'm in
better shape. I think what happened to me happened in '96 at
Talladega and it was something that didn't really get aggravated
until March of last year when I wrecked in Atlanta. Last year, I
was racing pretty much with a lot of pain and stuff.''
</P>
<P>
   And the improved feeling has shown on the race track this
season. Earnhardt finished second at Rockingham, won at Atlanta,
and was a close third at Talladega. He's suddenly a contender
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``The rebuilding process was a long hard thing,'' Earnhardt
said. ``To put it into perspective that's what we did, we just
rebuilt. We were ready this year. I think we're more ready this
year, team-wise, than we've been in a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   And it has the team thinking about that eighth Winston Cup
championship.
</P>
<P>
   ``All of us want to see Dale win that eighth championship,''
Childress said. ``I think it would mean a lot to the sport,
(Richard Childress Racing) and for Dale to win that eighth title
and down the line.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something I think about every day.''
</P>
<P>
   So does Earnhardt.
</P>
<P>
   ``I feel good,'' Earnhardt said. ``I've mellowed as I've gone on
and got smarter. I still drive the race car pretty good. I'm just
enjoying it.''
</P>
<P>
   So are his fans. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2223EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
