r s BC-FBC-UCLA-SPRING-LADN     04-29 0546
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-UCLA-SPRING-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WEATHER NICE, BUT UCLA SCRIMMAGE NOT SO GOOD
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JON WILNER  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ UCLA concluded its injury-marred spring practice
with a short scrimmage Saturday under a brilliant sky at remodeled
Drake Stadium, but its performance didn't match the weather. The
offense sputtered and the defense dominated as 20 ailing players
watched from the sideline.
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Ryan McCann completed 3-of-6 passes for 18 yards and
an interception during the 30-minute scrimmage. He also fumbled
twice and fell once while retreating from center.
</P>
<P>
   Reserve quarterback Scott McEwan was 4 of 7 for 18 yards and
struggled with the basics, as well. A makeshift offense line
contributed to the woes, as did the absence of top receivers
Freddie Mitchell (baseball) and Brian Poli-Dixon (hamstring).
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm a little disappointed with some performances of the
quarterbacks,'' coach Bob Toledo said. ``We looked like the
Keystone Kops out there ... (but) we're missing 20 players, and
it's hard to have any continuity or consistency.''
</P>
<P>
   Quarterback Cory Paus, competing with McCann for the starting
job, did not participate in the scrimmage because of offseason
shoulder surgery, but he was sharp in the non-contact drills. Paus,
who started seven games last year, was the most consistent passer
throughout the spring.
</P>
<P>
   Toledo won't name a starter until training camp.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm very pleased with the way I played this spring considering
I couldn't throw the ball for four months in the offseason,'' Paus
said.
</P>
<P>
   Starting tailback DeShaun Foster (sprained knee) didn't play,
and second-stringer Jermaine Lewis played sparingly. That created
an opportunity for third-stringer Akil Harris, a redshirt freshman
from Monrovia. He scored the only touchdown and had nine carries
for 53 yards, including a 40-yard burst that was the afternoon's
lone offensive highlight.
</P>
<P>
   ``He did a great job,'' Toledo said. ``He's going to be an
excellent back.''
</P>
<P>
   LOOKING GOOD: Despite a month of injuries, the coaches had time
to evaluate several underclassmen who redshirted last year. Four
made lasting impressions: defensive tackle Rodney Leisle, defensive
ends Dave and Mat Ball, and guard Shane Lehmann.
</P>
<P>
   Leisle is the projected starter at one of the tackle spots
(alongside Ken Kocher) after outplaying junior Anthony Fletcher.
</P>
<P>
   INJURY UPDATE: None of the spring injuries are expected to
linger until training camp. However, reserve linebacker Billy
Pieper's career is in jeopardy because of a neck problem that is
partly congenital and partly related to football, a school official
said. The Bruins will consult with specialists before making a
final decision.
</P>
<P>
   BARNES UPDATE: Basketball player Matt Barnes attended Saturday's
scrimmage and expects to join the football team for training camp
as a receiver. For now, basketball is secondary.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to work with the quarterbacks and receivers in the
summer and report in August,'' Barnes said. ``I'm going to stick
with football until it ends and then go play basketball.''
</P>
<P>
   Before his decision to play football, Barnes was projected to
start at power forward in place of NBA-bound Jerome Moiso. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
