<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUT-TROUT-OPENER-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OPENING DAY IN EASTERN SIERRA IS ABOUT MEMORIES
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By MICHAEL A. ANASTASI  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MAMMOTH LAKES, Calif. _ Very early Saturday morning, George
Rozuk caught a fish.
</P>
<P>
   Then, as his wife had told him to do, he opened the package
shehad wrapped. Inside was a framed photo of George Rozuk Jr., age
10. Theboy in the photo beamed, showing three fingers and holding a
large trout from a long-ago opener, his first opener and the first
of many to comewith Dad. Georgie was proud because his three trout
came before anyone else had any.
</P>
<P>
   His father looked at that old photo Saturday morning, as the
orange light of dawn slowly revealed Crowley Lake and the thousands
of anglers who had come here, and he cried.
</P>
<P>
   George Rozuk Jr., 24, died in an automobile accident on April
15.
</P>
<P>
   They were to come here together on Saturday, George Sr. and
George Jr., as they always had. Instead, George Sr. came with a
sign on hisRV. ``Crowley bound in memory of my son.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I told my family I was going to God's country,'' said Rozuk,
who is from Covina. ``God took my son, and I feel deeply in my
heart this is where my son wanted me to be.''
</P>
<P>
   Down the shoreline from Rozuk stood Jeff Cox of Boron and his
son, exactly in the same spot they stood last year and exactly in
the same spot they stood the year before that. Fishing was slow,
and they were cold, and it didn't matter.
</P>
<P>
   A half-mile away, Reggie Rodriguez of Canyon Country fished
theWhiskey Creek Inlet. Across the way his wife Bea fished. They
were married on the opening day of trout season 21 years ago.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie's been fishing up here for 30 years, ever since his
father brought him.
</P>
<P>
   ``The guys I first fished with, they were in their 60s then,''
Rodriguez said. ``They're all gone now. I come out here now and
think about them. I think about the things they did, the things
they said.''
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's trout opener in the Eastern Sierra was like that.
Itwas not about fish, who caught them and how big they were _
although that's what people talked about. What mattered was love
and family, the past and the future, connecting and reconnecting.
</P>
<P>
   George Flores of Sylmar looked at the two small fish on his
stringer and a pole that hadn't been hit in a while. A dozen
buddies from the Valley fished all around him. ``I think,'' he
said, ``this is beautiful.''
</P>
<P>
   Bea Rodriguez hadn't fished before she met her husband-to-be.
But, Reggie told her, she'd better learn.
</P>
<P>
   ``How I love being here and watching him catch his fish,'' she
said.
</P>
<P>
   One year, not too long after they had gotten together, Bea and
Reggie fished Owens River. She wore waders for the first time and
figured one of her feet grew increasingly uncomfortable because
that's just the way waders were. Finally, her foot hurt just too
much.
</P>
<P>
   She took the boot off.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hey,'' she said, ``I didn't know these were fur-lined.''
</P>
<P>
   ``They're not,'' Reggie said.
</P>
<P>
   She turned the boot upside down, and out came a mouse.
</P>
<P>
   Bea screamed, chucked the boot into the river, and ran. Then a
gull swooped before her, Hitchcock-style, and squaked. Bea,
hysterical, turned and sprinted.
</P>
<P>
   Reggie retrieved the boot and then retrieved his wife.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whoever you come out here with, you bond,'' Reggie said.
``When you get back to the city, you see that individual and things
are different. Something has changed between you, and it never goes
away.''
</P>
<P>
   George Rozuk stands alone on the shore, an eye on his pole and
his mind on his son.
</P>
<P>
   More than 600 people came to the funeral, George said.
</P>
<P>
   He smiled.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would say,'' he said, ``two hundred of them were his
girlfriends.''
</P>
<P>
   A respectful distance away, George Sr.'s friend Armando Angulo
milled about.
</P>
<P>
   ``He needs some time alone,'' Angulo said, nodding toward the
boat a short distance offshore in which George's brother Charlie
and his good friend Dan Sanchez fished.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're here for his support,'' Angulo said. ``George hasn't
really broken down yet. I'm trying to keep myself together, but
it's hard. I still hear it in his throat, the cry for his son.''
</P>
<P>
   George and Armando display the photo of 10-year-old George Jr.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm out here for my boy. I hope you guys understand it,''
George Sr. said. ``My boy, he would have wanted it. He loved
everybody. He was always helping people.
</P>
<P>
   ``My boy went everywhere and did everything with me. He did a
lot more than what most kids do with their dads,'' George said. ``I
used to tell him, `Mijo, every day is a special day.'''
</P>
<P>
   Fred Weatherly of Mammoth Lakes and his son Walker, 12, are
heading home. They trolled Crowley and limited out in an hour and a
half.
</P>
<P>
   Walker proudly shows off a large cutthroat he caught, the
day'sprize of an impressive stringer.
</P>
<P>
   Fred's the preacher for the High Sierra Christian Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``Fishing is all about memories,'' he said. ``One of these days,
we'll sit around and remember. Remember the day we caught all those
fish? Remember the day we caught that old cutthroat? Remember how
cold it was that day?
</P>
<P>
   ``Remember,'' he said, ``how much fun we had?''
</P>
<P>
   Remember. And never forget. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2301EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
