<HEADLINE>
SHARKS CONFIDENT DESPITE GAME 1 DEBACLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ San Jose winger Jeff Friesen skated off the Reunion
Arena ice after yesterday's optional skate, looked at a group of
reporters and said, ``The sun came up today.''
</P>
<P>
   One day removed from a 4-0 loss in Game 1 against the Stars, the
Sharks remained composed and confident. They didn't get bogged down
with talk about turning the series into a war of attrition. They
stressed improving the penalty kill, raising their intensity,
taking advantage of scoring opportunities and, most important,
getting their forecheck in gear.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have to play with more emotion and we will,'' defenseman
Jeff Norton said. ``How we do it is we get back to dropping the
puck in properly, get bodies on guys, obviously, we can't take bad
penalties against these guys.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks depend on a strong forecheck. They dump the puck into
the zone and use their forecheck to gain puck possession. The
Stars, with a big assist from the return of Sergei Zubov, cleared
their own zone swiftly and took the Sharks out of their game.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we had success against St. Louis was to get our
forechecking going,'' center Vincent Damphousse said.
\Nsubheds:Line changes Sharks coach Darryl Sutter said line changes
might be coming.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't like any of the matchups,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Sutter said the Stars surprised him by matching their No. 1 line
of Mike Modano, Brett Hull and Brenden Morrow against his top line
of Vincent Damphousse, Owen Nolan and Dave Lowry. Sutter expected
Stars coach Ken Hitchcock to attack that line with checkers Guy
Carbonneau, Mike Keane and Blake Sloan.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't know what the matchups were going to be,'' Sutter
said. ``Who did they want against Vinny? I think it was different
than what we thought it would be. We probably have to make some
adjustments.''The Sharks realize their best games come when they
play disciplined and positionally strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``The games we lost \Rto St. Louis\S we were undisciplined,''
Jeff Friesen said. ``The three games they beat us, they beat us
5-3, 5-3, 6-2. It shows you, you give up four goals to Dallas, with
\REd\S Belfour in net, you're not going to win any games.''
</P>
<P>
   On the flip side, in the Sharks' four victories over the Blues,
they allowed a total of six goals.] \Nsubheds:Briefly The Sharks
remain confident goalie Steve Shields can rebound again from a poor
outing. ``We don't worry about Shields at all,'' Mike Ricci said.
``He's a great competitor. He is going to be there. We just have to
make sure we're there in front of him.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked how he will raise his intensity level for Game 2, the
long-haired Ricci said, ``Maybe I'll shave my head.''
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
