<HEADLINE>
SHARKS CAPTAIN OWEN NOLAN FEELING PLENTY OF PAIN
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JEFF CAPLAN 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   DALLAS _ Owen Nolan is hurting. Apparently so much that his
status for today's Game 2 is shaky.
</P>
<P>
   But don't tell Nolan.
</P>
<P>
   ``Without a doubt,'' Nolan said, ``I'll be playing in Game 2.''
</P>
<P>
   More is ailing the Sharks' captain than his bruised left foot
that blocked St. Louis defenseman Al MacInnis' slap shot in Game 7
of their first-round series. In the final weeks of the season,
Nolan suffered a concussion and a shoulder injury, forcing him out
of four crucial games.
</P>
<P>
   The shoulder was still bothering him against St. Louis, but in
keeping with the hockey code this time of year, he kept that topic
to himself and played through the pain.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to get into specifics,'' said Nolan, who had six
goals and eight points against the Blues. ``The second I start
telling you guys, they \R the Stars\S start coming after it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am sore and kind of hampered a little bit.But, it's just
something you've got to battle through. I'm sure a lot of guys are
going through that.''
</P>
<P>
   The Stars didn't need to know his medical history to target him.
The Stars came after him early and often in the 4-0 victory in Game
1. Nolan didn't seem able to find his typical burst to the puck and
lacked the punch he usually brings.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you ask Nolan what's wrong, you never know,'' teammate
Jeff Friesen said. ``He takes it personally. It's hard to get close
to Nolan when he's hurt. If he needs time to rest, everyone has to
pick up the slack.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks' regular-season leader in goals (44), hits (209),
takeaways (70) and minutes (21:07) per game, Nolan registered no
hits on Friday and had four shots. Stars goalie Ed Belfour made a
sliding save on Nolan's one golden scoring chance.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took it to the net once really strong, but there were a
couple of times he'd have a grimace on his face,'' Stars winger
Brenden Morrow said. ``We noticed he wasn't 100 percent, but he's
still dangerous.''
</P>
<P>
   The Sharks need him. He has scored nearly a third of their
playoff goals and is the greatest scoring threat on a team not
blessed with a roster full of gunslingers. The Sharks win by
throwing the puck at the net and banging it home, something they
say they must do more of in Game 2 _ with or without their captain.
</P>
<P>
   ``If he can't play, it's because he's hurt,'' Sharks coach
Darryl Sutter said.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
