r s BC-RAC-DERBY-PEGASUS-TEX     04-29 0760
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RAC-DERBY-PEGASUS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUSAICHI PEGASUS FACING SCRUTINY AS DERBY NEARS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By TIM PRICE 
c.2000 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
 
 
 
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   When the 126th running of the Kentucky Derby is conducted
Saturday at Churchill Downs in Louisville, Ky., the world will find
out if a goofball can win horse racing's biggest event.
</P>
<P>
   Horses regarded as goofballs don't have a good record in the
Derby. Fusaichi Pegasus acts like a goofball. He tossed his rider
and flipped over onto his back Thursday after what was supposed to
be a routine gallop. Nothing seems routine for Fusaichi Pegasus,
yet he certainly might be favored to win the Derby.
</P>
<P>
   If he is, it's because almost everything Fusaichi Pegasus does
between the lines _ from starting gate to the wire in horse racing
_ is win. Although he lost his career debut in December by a neck,
he's put together a winning streak of four races.
</P>
<P>
   His previous race, in the Wood Memorial Stakes in New York, is
thought to be his best. He sat behind a quick pace of 464/5 seconds
through the opening half mile, getting mud kicked into his face for
the first time in his career. Not deterred, he passed the leaders
and drew off to win by four lengths in a final eighth of a mile in
122/5 seconds.
</P>
<P>
   He sandwiched that performance by holding up the start of the
race when he refused to budge from the top of the stretch, his
attention diverted to the parking lot where buses were moving,
according to jockey Kent Desormeaux.
</P>
<P>
   Once past the finish line, he put on the brakes again. It took a
pair of handlers from trainer Neil Drysdale's barn to go and walk
him back.
</P>
<P>
   Then he was caught on national television highlight reels
Thursday during his flipping episode. If Drysdale is worried, he's
not showing it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know the press has to make a do about something because it's
your job,'' Drysdale said. ``But in my mind, this colt isn't that
bad. I've had a lot worse.
</P>
<P>
   ``Has anybody been watching him? He's fine. \RThursday\S was the
first time he's done anything wrong since he's been here.''
</P>
<P>
   Horses who become their own worst enemies have trouble at the
Derby. There are four examples from the 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   General Challenge came into Kentucky last year off a big victory
in the Santa Anita Derby. Along with entrymate Excellent Meeting,
General Challenge was the Derby favorite.
</P>
<P>
   But he sweated profusely during a schooling session in the
paddock the week of the Derby. He ended up running 11th.
</P>
<P>
   Pulpit was the morning-line favorite in 1997. Because he was
close to losing his composure in the post parade in front of
140,000 people at Churchill, he was excused and allowed to be by
himself on the backstretch. He ran fourth and later had a knee
injury.
</P>
<P>
   Unbridled's Song was the betting favorite in '96, and he also
was excused from the post parade. He wore a bar shoe designed to
help a slight hoof injury, and he faded to fifth.
</P>
<P>
   In '92, Arazi was the heaviest betting favorite since Easy Goer
in 1989. Arazi tossed a rider during morning exercise hours in the
week leading up to the Derby, and he finished eighth.
</P>
<P>
   There might be one more thing that Fusaichi Pegasus will have to
overcome to win the Derby. The colt wears wraps on his front
ankles, which sometimes is a sign of unsoundness. Fusaichi Pegasus,
however, has been wearing the wraps for every career start.
Drysdale said he uses them for support of the ankles because
Fusaichi Pegasus is a big horse.
</P>
<P>
   A research of ``Daily Racing Form'' charts and winner's circle
photos shows that a Derby winner hasn't worn front wraps during the
race since Tomy Lee in 1959.
</P>
<P>
   Drysdale said the front wraps _ or what's under them _ aren't
the reason Fusaichi Pegasus sometimes balks.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he's a horse with a mind of his own,'' Drysdale said.
``But he doesn't get excited or nervous.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a bit of a rascal. He wants to be in charge, so we go
along with it because he's bigger and stronger.''
</P>
<P>
   People seeking a more controlled horse will look at The Deputy.
He won the Santa Anita Derby and is being ridden by two-time Derby
winning jockey Chris McCarron.
</P>
<P>
   ``On paper, he looks like the `livest' Derby horse I've been
on,'' McCarron said. ``He's professional. And the more professional
the horse is, the better chance they have to overcome misfortune.''
</P>
<P>
   In their only meeting, Fusaichi Pegasus beat The Deputy by
three-quarters of a length in the San Felipe Stakes. The Deputy
rallied from about six lengths behind, but Desormeaux never used
his whip in the stretch.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2311EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
