<HEADLINE>
HERGES KNOWS HIS TIME MAY COME
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RICH HAMMOND  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Matt Herges realizes his scoreless innings streak,
along with his Dodger career, could end at any time, so he's not
about to take any success for granted.
</P>
<P>
   Herges, a 30-year-old reliever who has spent parts of eight
seasons in the Dodgers' minor-league system, has started the season
by pitching 15 consecutive scoreless innings through Saturday's
game against Florida.
</P>
<P>
   His spot in the bullpen is tenuous, however, because the team
remains uncertain of what it will do when Gregg Olson, out with a
strain to his left forearm, returns from the disabled list in the
next week or two.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know I'm the only guy down here whose job isn't secure,''
Herges said. ``I have other options as far as what the team can do
with me, and I just don't know what they are going to do. Gregg
obviously belongs up here, there's no question, so something is
going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Herges started the season as the 12th man in a 12-man bullpen,
on the roster mostly because outfielder Geronimo Berroa was on the
disabled list.
</P>
<P>
   The challenge for Herges is to continue pitching well enough to
make it difficult for the Dodgers to get rid of him.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know a run is going to come eventually,'' Herges said. ``I'm
not going to pitch good all the time, so once I do allow a couple
runs in a game, I'll have to come back and prove to people that I'm
a good pitcher.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now, every pitch I throw is important, because I have to
prove to (manager Davey Johnson) that I belong here. Maybe that
would (bother) some other guys, but not guys who have been in the
minors for eight years. This is all just gravy for me.''
</P>
<P>
   SHORT REST: Second baseman Mark Grudzielanek returned to the
starting lineup after a one-game absence. Grudzielanek, who is
making a transition after spending most of his career at shortstop,
came into the game hitting .198, but hit a two-run home run in the
first inning, his second of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never been a real big believer in streaks, I thought it
always had more to do with luck, but I don't think I've ever been
through a stretch this bad before,'' Grudzielanek said. ``It's been
weird, because during this little stretch I've picked it up, got my
stroke back a little, and then I lost it again.
</P>
<P>
   ``I know it will come back for good soon enough though.''
</P>
<P>
   Grudzielanek, one of the Dodgers' top fielders in 1999, has made
only one error this season before Saturday but said that learning a
new position is an ongoing and sometimes difficult process.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just try to ask a lot of questions about things I'm supposed
to do,'' Grudzielanek. ``It's coming along, and I feel a little
more comfortable every day.''
</P>
<P>
   GOLDEN BOY: The Dodgers gt one of their first glimpses Friday of
why right fielder Shawn Green won a Gold Glove with Toronto last
season.
</P>
<P>
   Green hit a two-run double to give the Dodgers their winning
margin, but his biggest play may have come in the second inning.
</P>
<P>
   The Marlins had a 2-0 lead against Carlos Perez, and had runners
on the corners with one out. Mark Kotsay hit a fly ball to right,
and Green made the catch and threw to the glove of catcher Todd
Hundley, who tagged out Dave Berg. It was Green's second outfield
assist of the season.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest thing is to just get behind the ball and make a
good throw,'' Green said. ``You don't ever want to short-hop it,
that's the worst thing you can do, and you want to keep the throw
low so the first baseman can grab it if he needs to.''
</P>
<P>
   SHORT HOPS: Sheffield's multihomer game was the 16th of his
career. ... Johnson isn't sure when Olson would be activated, but
he said the reliever should begin throwing in the next few days.
... Orel Hershiser is back in the bullpen, but Johnson said he will
remain an important part of the pitching staff. ``I didn't bring
him here to mop up games,'' Johnson said. ``I expect him to be a
big part of our success.'' ... Johnson did some minor lineup
adjusting, switching Sheffield and Green to No.3 and No.4 and
Adrian Beltre and Todd Hundley to No.6 and No.7. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
