<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-KINGS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS BENCH OUTPLAYING `BENCH MOB'
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.2000 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   EL SEGUNDO, Calif. _ Give the Lakers a little more time, a few
more playoff wins, and perhaps, finally, someone will slap a clever
nickname on the reserves. Or at the least, recognize their
contributions.
</P>
<P>
   If you outplay one of the league's most celebrated and
coolest-named benches, certainly you've earned an identity. With
defense, rebounding and some timely scoring, that's what the
Lakers' anonymous second unit has done in this first-round playoff
series against the Sacramento Kings, and their vaunted ``Bench
Mob.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers, up 2-0 in the best-of-five series, go for the sweep
this afternoon at Arco Arena, and the benches should figure
prominently.
</P>
<P>
   The Bench Mob has played like a group stripped of its ``Tommy''
guns and pinstripes.
</P>
<P>
   Peja Stojakovic burned the Lakers for 20-plus points per game in
the regular season, but is averaging 3.0 points in the series,
making 2 of 12 shots. Jon Barry is averaging 5.5 points. Of the
Kings' reserves, only Tony Delk has scored in double figures 17
points in Game 1 and the last 10 points came in garbage time.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Lakers' unheralded reserves are quietly playing
solid defense and playing the Bench Mob to a virtual draw.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every time we've gotten to that point, our bench has really
stepped in and played well, and we've had some real good efforts
from them,'' coach Phil Jackson said. ``Even though they're not the
group that takes shots a lot of times, they come in and play
defense and do the things we ask them
</P>
<P>
   get the ball to Shaquille (O'Neal) or whatever. They've done a
fine job and I'm very pleased with what they've done.''
</P>
<P>
   Because of the firepower brought by O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Glen
Rice, offense from the bench is a luxury, not a necessity. They've
provided it where needed _ 11 points from Rick Fox in Game 2, 8
points from Robert Horry in Game 1. The reserves have also
accounted for 20 of the Lakers' 49 assists in the series.
</P>
<P>
   Yet Jackson expects the balance could quickly shift to the Kings
today at Arco Arena. Bench players, he has observed, tend to play
better at home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think our bench might have trouble with their bench on the
home court,'' he said. ``They'll have more liberties, they'll be
more comfortable. Barry got a couple shots last game, he's starting
to look like he's coming off that (back) injury and downspell that
he had a little bit. Stojakovic had one 3-pointer (in Game 2).
Delk, we were able to contain a little bit the last game, but he's
been a problem for us. And basically (Lawrence) Funderburke has
been eliminated by (Chris) Webber's great play.
</P>
<P>
   ``But those are the guys that hurt us in past games. I wouldn't
be surprised if Rick (Adelman, the Kings' coach) went to his bench
a little bit earlier and a little bit longer than he has in the
first two games.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether it's Webber and Jason Williams or Delk and Barry, the
Lakers expect a feisty Kings attack today as Sacramento faces
elimination. The Kings went 30-11 at Arco Arena this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to be tough,'' said Ron Harper, ``because we know
when their crowd gets in there and they start shooting them wild
shots and they start to hit some that we need to take the ball back
inside ... that's a really tough place to play. That's really a
great place to play. I mean, the fans are right there on the
floor.''
</P>
<P>
   But if the Lakers' bench can outplay the Bench Mob once more,
that crowd will fall silent, and then someone can get back to
finding them a nickname.
</P>
<P>
   ``You can call it being overshadowed by an MVP season (by
O'Neal) and great play by Kobe and Glen,'' said Fox, ``but we've in
a lot of ways just accepted the fact that we're fill-ins to a
triangle offense that's going to make Glen, Shaq and Kobe have
great opportunities for themselves. As a whole, we're not asked to
be big-time scorers. But we're all capable of feeding off of those
guys and as for recognition, I think it will come a lot more once
we're able to follow through with the game plan here and win out
and win a championship.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
