<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-LEAFS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS BEAT MAPLE LEAFS, 1-0 
</HEADLINE>
   By JOE LAPOINTE   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ Most hockey teams will settle for a split of two games
on the road to open a Stanley Cup playoff series. The Devils might
have deserved better than that here with the Toronto Maple Leafs in
the Air Canada Center.
</P>
<P>
   But they could have gotten worse against this opportunistic and
resourceful team, which they outplayed twice.
</P>
<P>
   So the Devils will take Saturday night's 1-0 victory home for a
1-1 deadlock in the four-of-seven-game Eastern Conference
semifinals.
</P>
<P>
   Colin White, a rookie defenseman, scored for the Devils early in
the game, and goalie Martin Brodeur made it stand up.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the third period, with Toronto applying pressure,
the Devils' Jason Arnott received a double minor for high-sticking
Garry Valk at 8 minutes 20 seconds. With the capacity crowd
roaring, Toronto directed intense pressure at Brodeur early in the
man advantage.
</P>
<P>
   But as the Maple Leafs' second power play ticked away, the
Devils' penalty killers took control and worked the puck down the
other end. Helping in this effort was Brodeur, one of the league's
better puck-handling goalies, who cleared the puck the length of
the ice.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs' failure to score on this opportunity left them 2 for
33 on the power play in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   In the final minute, Toronto pulled goalie Curtis Joseph for an
extra attacker and earned a face-off in the Devils' end after an
icing with 40 seconds remaining.
</P>
<P>
   Although Toronto's Mats Sundin won the face-off, the Leafs could
not control the puck and it left the zone. They never got another
shot on goal and the Devils ended the game with a 33-20 edge in
that department.
</P>
<P>
   Games 3 and 4 of this series will be at Continental Arena on
Monday and Wednesday nights. The winner of the series will meet
either Pittsburgh or Philadelphia in the Eastern Conference finals.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils dominated the first two periods but led by only a
goal thanks to White, who scored on a slap shot at 6:41 of the
first period. Arnott assisted on the goal, which came at the end of
a good shift of forechecking.
</P>
<P>
   It was not the only instance of this tactic, which the Devils
used to dominate long stretches of play. Devils Coach Larry
Robinson used all four of his forward lines, which kept the Toronto
defensemen busy around the net of Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   Alexander Mogilny of the Devils had prime chances in the first
two periods. On the first, he and Patrik Elias blitzed Joseph for
three or four shots in succession. On the second, Elias fed Mogilny
on a two-on-one, and Mogilny's hard shot was turned away by Joseph.
</P>
<P>
   But the Leafs also had their moments. An early one came when
Wendel Clark, the veteran and fan favorite, split the Devils'
defense.
</P>
<P>
   His shot was stopped by Brodeur, who also took a penalty on the
play for roughing Clark after the whistle.
</P>
<P>
   The Leafs also hit a goal post midway through the second period
after Tomas Kaberle fired from long range _ a shot that may have
been tipped by Kevyn Adams as it moved toward the net. Adams got
the rebound but put the puck on Brodeur's pads.
</P>
<P>
   Toronto, a team at its best when it is skating freely, picked up
the pace in the second half of the second period with its captain,
Sundin, creating chances with aggressive skating. Sundin was
double-shifted by Pat Quinn, the Toronto coach.
</P>
<P>
   On one of his best chances, near the end of the period, Sundin
intercepted a Bobby Holik pass and stickhandled through several
Devils, forcing White to take a penalty for holding the stick.
</P>
<P>
   The Devils killed the power play, but the score remained cause
for concern.
</P>
<P>
   In Game 1, a 2-1 Toronto victory, the Devils also outplayed
Toronto, but the opportunistic Leafs won that one in the third
period. Another Toronto trait is to win despite being outshot.
</P>
<P>
   After two periods, Elias and Petr Sykora each had three shots,
tied for the lead on the Devils. Mogilny also had three.
</P>
<P>
   His coaches have been urging him to shoot more _ he had no shots
in Game 1.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
