<HEADER>
A1405 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NUKE-FLAWS-NYT &LR;      04-29 0520
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NUKE-FLAWS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FORMER ENERGY DEPT. ADVISER CITES FLAWS IN NUCLEAR COMPLEX 
</HEADLINE>
   By WILLIAM J. BROAD   
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   In 1996, a truck carrying nuclear warheads skidded off an icy
road in Nebraska and crashed. For half a day, no one in government,
including the president and his cabinet, knew the degree of danger,
or if any nuclear material had escaped into the environment,
because radiation monitors on the government's fleet of weapons
trucks had been removed after complaints from drivers.
</P>
<P>
   The drivers had said the monitors showed that they were facing
potential health risks from their cargoes.
</P>
<P>
   These accusations have been made by Robert Alvarez, who from
1993 to 1999 was a policy adviser in the Department of Energy,
which runs the nation's nuclear complex. Before that, as a Senate
aide, he specialized in helping oversee the department.
</P>
<P>
   In an article for a journal, Alvarez calls problems with the
atomic fleet ``emblematic of the department's inept and often
arrogant management culture.'' The mind-set has become so backward,
he says, that the complex is now basically a ticking time bomb
waiting to go off in a serious accident or an inadvertent nuclear
blast.
</P>
<P>
   His 12-page analysis appears in the May/June issue of The
Bulletin of the Atomic Scientists, which was posted over the
weekend on the group's Web site, www.thebulletin.org.
</P>
<P>
   In interviews, Energy Department officials said that although
the department's handling of weapons had problems, Alvarez was
blowing them out of proportion.
</P>
<P>
   In his article, Alvarez said the uncertainty in the Nebraska
incident was cleared up after a federal crisis team arrived and
found no danger. But the underlying woes persisted. Today, he said,
the drivers are still disgruntled and the trucks still have no
radiation monitors. Until their salaries were raised recently, he
added, atomic truckers were paid less than those who haul
vegetables.
</P>
<P>
   Energy officials and outside experts agree that the department
has serious problems, with roots in the vast responsibilities and
liabilities incurred during the Cold War in making 70,000 nuclear
arms. The challenges now lie in old age and downsizing. The
department owns more than 20,700 facilities and buildings,
including 89 nuclear reactors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Major elements of Energy's complex are closing down,'' Alvarez
said in the article, ``leaving a huge unfunded and dangerous
mess.''
</P>
<P>
   Reacting to Alvarez's overall accusations, Ellen Livingston, the
department's senior adviser for environmental affairs, said,
``We've gone to great lengths to develop safety and training
programs to limit the hazards because we recognize the handling of
nuclear materials is a risky business.''
</P>
<P>
   Alvarez, who is now a consultant to antinuclear groups, said the
department was wrong in playing down his charges but right in
calling him an antagonist.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not like I was their golden boy and they booted me out
and now it's sour grapes,'' he said in an interview. ``They used me
as an internal critic. If I've got an ax, it's one I've been
grinding for 25 years.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-04-29-00 2356EDT &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT20000429.0252 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 2000-04-29 23:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A1407 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     04-29 1030
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV07-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, May 7)  
 c.2000 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; THE WONDERS OF THE INVISIBLE WORLD: Stories &LR;  By David Gates.
Vintage Contemporaries, $12. These mordant tales are filled with
aging male hipsters whose ironic detachment and heightened
self-awareness leave them unable to connect with the real world.
``Gates can be very funny,'' Gerald Marzorati wrote in The New York
Times Book Review last year, but mostly he ``is concerned with
creating characters you haven't met in fiction before, getting just
right the words they use to disengagedly engage their women and
their friends and even their inner selves.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Clear Springs: A Family Story &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Bobbie Ann Mason. HarperPerennial, $14.
</P>
<P>
   The author revisits her old Kentucky home, and in recounting the
details and Southern traditions of her upbringing sheds light on
the inspiration for much of her fiction. ``Mason gets to the heart
of a whole generation,'' Josephine Humphreys wrote here last year.
``She can write the hard truth about home, love, loss and the
terrifying passage of time.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Italian Fever &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Valerie Martin. Vintage Contemporaries, $12.
</P>
<P>
   The author's sixth novel, about a young divorcee who travels to
Tuscany to settle the affairs of an American writer who has died
and left behind the manuscript of his final book, has more to do
with the development of consciousness than plot. The heroine's
adventures among the locals, particularly her sexual awakening at
the hands of her charming cicerone, make this ``a study of the
complications of lovemaking and its effects on women,'' Craig
Seligman wrote here in 1999. ``Martin's sureness of phrasing is one
of the great pleasures of her recent fiction. ... Her cool, remote
voice has mellowed, and her competence has kindled into
brilliance.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; In September, the Light Changes: Stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Andrew Holleran. Plume, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   These carefully built tales are steeped in the cadences,
vocabulary and concerns of gay life in the late 20th century, and
reveal an obsessive awareness of the loss of friends, health and
youth. The result is a ``beautifully observed'' collection that is
``unflinching, provocative, witty and shrewd,'' Peter Parker said
here in 1999.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Diary of Vaslav Nijinsky: Unexpurgated Edition &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Edited by Joan Acocella. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $15.
</P>
<P>
   The legendary Russian dancer's diary, originally published by
his wife in a sanitized, scaled-back version in 1936, chronicles
his long, anguished struggle with insanity. ``In displaying its
author in all his terrifying particularity, it allows us to glimpse
in his madness, not the apotheosis, but at least the ruins, of his
genius,`` William Deresiewicz wrote here in 1999.  &UR; No
IntermissionS: The Life of Agnes de Mille &LR; , by Carol Easton (Da
Capo, $18), is a portrait of the combative American dancer,
choreographer, author and lecturer who labored mightily to be taken
seriously in the male-dominated genre of musical comedy. ``Easton
tracks de Mille's struggles with the limits of her gift,'' Joan
Acocella said here in 1996. ``De Mille fans will want to read the
book.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; A Journey to the End of the Millennium: A Novel of the Middle
Ages &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By A.B. Yehoshua. Harvest/Harcourt, $14.
</P>
<P>
   This novel about a North African Jewish merchant who travels to
Europe with his two wives and his Muslim partner in the year 999
explores the gaps between Jews and Christians, Jews and Muslims and
men and women. ``Yehoshua is so graceful and eloquent that his
work's timeliness also succeeds, paradoxically, in making it
timeless,'' James E. Young wrote here last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Someone to Watch Over Me: Stories &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Richard Bausch. HarperPerennial, $13.
</P>
<P>
   These tales eavesdrop on couples bantering in bars, in
restaurants and in bed, and examine the human desire for solicitude
and tenderness. ``Bausch hovers over his characters like the
guardian angel they all seek,'' Lisa Zeidner wrote here in 1999.
``His stories illuminate the charged stillness in which emotional
changes happen.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Weird and Tragic Shores: The Story of Charles Francis Hall,
Explorer &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Chauncey C. Loomis. Modern Library, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   In 1968, the author exhumed the body of Charles Francis Hall, a
19th-century amateur explorer who made three Arctic voyages in
search of survivors of Sir John Franklin's disastrous expedition of
1845, and he discovered traces of arsenic. This biography
``suggests who may have killed him,'' Edmund Carpenter wrote here
in 1971. ``It is both a first-rate detective story and a very
scholarly work.'' Modern Library has also reissued  &UR; The Brendan
Voyage &LR; , by Tim Severin ($14.95), a chronicle of Severin's trip
across the North Atlantic in a small oxhide boat like the ones
reputed to have been used by Irish monks on their way to the New
World in the sixth century. ``His account of the adventure is a
sailor's delight,'' one critic said in 1978. In  &UR; Voyaging:
Southward From the Strait of Magellan &LR; , by Rockwell Kent (Wesleyan
University, $16.95), the artist recounts in rousing fashion his
journey to Tierra del Fuego in a small sailboat. ``The strength and
menace and majesty of the Cape Horn region proved admirable
material for Kent's black-and-white drawings,'' the Book Review
said in 1924.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; The Tree of Life &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Hugh Nissenson. Paul Dry, $14.95.
</P>
<P>
   In this novel as pioneer journal, a former minister abandons New
England for a rugged life on the Ohio frontier in 1811. The book
contains ``numerous small glories,'' Ivan Doig said here in 1985,
and the author ``toils like a stump farmer to create
verisimilitude.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; Geographies of Home &LR;
</P>
<P>
   By Loida Maritza Perez. Penguin, $12.95.
</P>
<P>
   The heroine of this first novel is torn between memories of her
lush homeland in the Dominican Republic and concern for her
impoverished family, which is losing its strength and identity in
Brooklyn. ``The result is a deluge of intense imagery where the
magical and the real occupy the same awful and sometimes sensual
space,'' Erica Sanders said here last year.
</P>
</TEXT>
